<SLUG> BC-BBO-BRAVES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SECOND JONES HOMER SAVES GAME FOR MADDU
</HEADLINE>
   (ko) 
 By JACK CURRY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service     
<TEXT>
<P>
   There were 50,469 fans at a raucous and cammy Yankee Stadium
Friday night, and Andruw Jones acted as if he had heard each one.
Every time the fans booed, Jones listened. He let the sounds drift
through his ears and motivate him. He wanted to quiet these rowdy
fans.
</P>
<P>
   So when Jones batted with the score tied and two runners on base
in the ninth inning, he finally had his chance to silence Yankee
Stadium. And he did. Mariano Rivera tried to throw a high inside
fastball past Jones, who blasted it over the left field fence to
vault the Braves to a wild 10-7 victory.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to beat them so bad because of their fans,'' said
Jones. ``They think they're putting pressure on us. We know they're
a good team too. There's nothing wrong with thinking we could play
them in the post-season, too.''
</P>
<P>
   On a back-and-forth night when Greg Maddux was bounced from the
game in the fourth inning and Orlando Hernandez left in the fifth,
the Braves rallied for four runs in the ninth off the struggling
Rivera. Jones climaxed the nifty comeback with his second homer of
the game, duplicating what he accomplished against the Yankees as a
19-year-old in Game 1 of the 1996 World Series.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those things are in the past,'' said Jones. ``Maybe when I
retire, they'll show it and my kids will see it. I'll tell them,
`That's what your dad did. He hit two homers in the World Series.'
''
</P>
<P>
   Maddux was relieved that Jones saved the Braves. With the sweat
dripping off his face, his eyes focused on his cleats and his
tongue probably wanting to bark objections to umpire Jim Evans,
Maddux trudged off the mound in the fourth because his brief and
ugly night was over. Maddux heard a thunderous mixture of boos and
sarcastic cheers as the fans serenaded the precise pitcher who was
very imprecise.
</P>
<P>
   There was some suspense about whether Maddux would say something
to Evans, but he never even glanced at him. Maybe Maddux was too
exasperated or simply had nothing to utter. It was a disastrous
night for the 33-year old pitcher who said on Thursday that Yankee
Stadium was a cool and fun place to play. After Maddux was blitzed
for five earned runs on nine hits in three and a third innings, his
shortest outing in almost three years, he was not feeling cool
because he had had no fun.
</P>
<P>
   The most frustrating part of Maddux's start occurred with one
out and the bases loaded in the fourth. Maddux uncorked a 1-2
fastball to Scott Brosius that missed the outside corner by a few
inches. Maddux obviously thought it was close enough to be a
strike, he complained to himself about the pitch, and Evans walked
toward him and waved his finger at the four-time Cy Young Award
winner.
</P>
<P>
   While manager Bobby Cox asked Evans why he confronted the
pitcher, Maddux wiped the sweat off his forehead and later said
that he did not even notice that Evans had pointed at him. On the
next pitch, Brosius chopped a ball off a leaping Maddux's glove
that narrowly slithered into center field to score two runs and put
the Yankees in front, 4-3. Maddux was perturbed and mumbled
something near Evans after backing up the play. ``That's a ball
that just missed,'' said Maddux. ``That's what's frustrating. The
strike zone was all right. It was a lot more me than him.''
</P>
<P>
   While Maddux struggled with the new strike zone earlier this
season, he was 5-1 with a 0.86 earned run average in his last six
starts and had seemingly made the proper adjustments. That
impressive streak ended abruptly in the fourth when Derek Jeter's
run-scoring single boosted New York's lead to 5-3 and sent Maddux
searching for soap and shampoo.
</P>
<P>
   The forgettable 3 1/3 innings was Maddux's shortest outing since
the Braves removed him after two innings against the Expos on Sept.
28, 1996 to set up their post-season rotation. The last time Maddux
was knocked out of a contest this early because of shoddy pitching
was on June 7, 1996, when he gave up 7 runs and 11 hits to
Colorado. But Maddux got to stand in a victorious clubhouse because
Jones went deep and quieted more than 50,000 fans.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was a big win for us,'' said Maddux. ``We beat a really
good closer. I'm happy for Andruw. That was a good hit.''
</P>
</TEXT>
