<HEADER>
A3638 &Cx1f; tth-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RACE-HATRED-SPI &LR;      07-17 1382
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RACE-HATRED-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOE OF HATE GROUPS SAYS LACK OF HELP FORCED HER INTO HIDING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By MIKE BARBER  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ A year ago, Bonnie Jouhari was battling hate groups in
Pennsylvania, working for fair housing and involved in an
unprecedented state lawsuit that banned a hate group from the
Internet.
</P>
<P>
   Today, the 42-year-old single mom and her 17-year-old daughter
are living in limbo _ hiding in the Seattle area and hoping to
escape continued harassment from those who see her as ``a race
traitor.''
</P>
<P>
   While she's lost everything, Jouhari said, she's most troubled
by what she considers foot-dragging by the Justice Department, a
one-time ally that has left her feeling vulnerable and betrayed for
the past 18 months.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know if the government is really serious about civil
rights,'' said Jouhari. ``If they were, they would file the case
they took over in Pennsylvania last year that we were involved in.
Since they haven't, we can't qualify for protection to help us get
our lives together.
</P>
<P>
   ``Overall, it just sends the wrong message'' to hate groups, and
to people who stand up against racism, she said.
</P>
<P>
   Jouhari said she wanted to stay out of the public spotlight in
Washington state for her daughter's sake. But frustrated with the
government, she phoned the Post-Intelligencer for help after the
harassment started here last month.
</P>
<P>
   Federal officials declined to comment on the case, other than to
say the investigation is still active.
</P>
<P>
   But Bill Wassmuth, head of the Northwest Coalition Against
Malicious Harassment, said he is familiar with Jouhari's case and
his group is ``going to try to help her in any we can.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is an example of the kind of intrusion into people's
lives that'' that white supremacists are committing, he said. ``We
in government and in society need to do a better job of standing
together with those who are victimized.''
</P>
<P>
   Pennsylvania is home to more organized hate groups than any
other state, Penn State professors Colin Flint and Lorraine Dowler
recently reported as part of a long-term research project for the
state's Human Relations Commission.
</P>
<P>
   Jouhari, a Navy veteran with a degree in criminal psychology,
was a fair housing specialist for the Reading-Berks County Human
Relations Council in eastern Pennsylvania when her troubles began.
</P>
<P>
   Active and outspoken, she organized a workshop on how the
Internet was being used to recruit members of hate groups and to
intimidate enemies. Then she found herself a target.
</P>
<P>
   After she appeared on a local television program about hate
groups in Berks County in early 1998, Jouhari's picture appeared on
the web site of a Philadelphia-based white supremacist group called
Alpha HQ, according to court documents. Alpha HQ describes itself
as ``the racial, political/paramilitary arm of the Aryan people.''
</P>
<P>
   A caption next to Jouhari's picture on the website said she had
``received warnings in the mail that she is a race traitor and
should beware. Traitors like this should beware, for in our day,
they will be hung from the neck from the nearest tree or
lamppost.''
</P>
<P>
   The website also pictured the Human Relations Council building
as though it were being blown up.
</P>
<P>
   ``Over the next eight months, we endured hell,'' Jouhari said.
Dead flowers were sprinkled over her car. Flyers branding her a
race traitor were left at her door. Anonymous callers told her to
write a will. The head of the local KKK hung around her office,
taking her picture.
</P>
<P>
   ``It annoyed me but didn't scare me,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   But when members of the hate group learned that Jouhari's
daughter, Dani, is bi-racial, ``they had a field day,'' Jouhari
said.
</P>
<P>
   She said she decided to move when her daughter received a call
warning that ``they could get to both of us whenever they wanted
to.''
</P>
<P>
   As Jouhari prepared to leave the state, Pennsylvania Attorney
General Mike Fisher filed an unprecedented civil suit against Alpha
HQ, accusing the group of publishing terroristic threats, ethnic
intimidation and harassing messages.
</P>
<P>
   The state won by default in December when the defendants failed
to show up in court, but Jouhari wasn't around to celebrate _ she
and Dani were living quietly in Silverdale, Wash.
</P>
<P>
   A CBS-TV cameraman from Washington had recommended the Kitsap
County suburb when the two met during taping of a ``48 Hours''
program about her that aired last October.
</P>
<P>
   Jouhari and Dani could have been eligible for Pennsylvania's
victim and witness protection program some months ago, but they are
now caught in a Catch 22: The state cannot help because federal
authorities have taken over the case, and federal officials say
they can't do anything to shield her until the investigation is
complete and charges are filed.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Jouhari is stuck: She'd like to rent a place under an
assumed name to escape the harassment, but no landlords would allow
it.
</P>
<P>
   And she'd like to work, but she can't fill out applications
without giving an address that could be traced.
</P>
<P>
   Pennsylvania authorities have done what they can, ruling that
fleeing from hate groups is a valid reason to leave a job. Calling
her decision to quit ``based on factors which were real,
substantial, and reasonable,'' Pennsylvania awarded her
unemployment benefits.
</P>
<P>
   Jouhari, who said she has turned down offers of pay to appear on
tabloid TV shows, said she'd doesn't want publicity or money.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just want to work and do what other people do. I want to
find a way to get an apartment without using my name, and to get a
job. This is about safety,'' she said. ``And when Dani is grown and
away in college, I want to get back into fighting racism.''
</P>
<P>
   The federal Housing and Urban Development administration where
Jouhari worked was making its own case against hate groups last
year, based on threats Jouhari received at her home. The case
seemed to be percolating along until the Justice Department took
over, Jouhari said.
</P>
<P>
   Representatives of the Justice Department, FBI and U.S.
Marshal's office in Washington, D.C., referred questions to one
another Friday.
</P>
<P>
   A Justice Department spokeswoman in Washington said Jouhari's
case is still being developed. Local offices in Seattle can't help,
however, because the case is being handled in Philadelphia, where
no one was available for comment Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Some of Jouhari's local friends, meanwhile, are trying to get
high ranking elected officials involved. Tova Ravitz, spokeswoman
for Sen. Patty Murray, D-Wash., said the senator was unaware of the
case but ``would love to be helpful.''
</P>
<P>
   For now, Jouhari said she feels secure in the fellowship of a
local church that has provided her with a place to live, but prays
someone in authority helps her soon. She and her daughter moved
from Silverdale late last month after the threats found them again
_ hangup phone calls and cryptic messages, a dead rabbit left on
their stoop.
</P>
<P>
   A reporter from her hometown newspaper apparently let slip to a
local Klansman where Jouhari had gone, she said. A former reporter
from the newspaper confirmed that account.
</P>
<P>
   It hasn't been easy for her 17-year-old daughter. A gifted
student, Dani had been involved in student council and volleyball
at her high school. She said she left behind a boyfriend, a nice
job and ``all our little treasures,'' during the quick move in late
November from Pennsylvania.
</P>
<P>
   ``At first I didn't want to come here,'' Dani said. ``We had no
money even for a tree at Christmas. I missed 45 days of school last
year and didn't take my SAT exams.
</P>
<P>
   ``We gave up everything. Now it's a big treat for us to go to
the store to get food.''
</P>
<P>
   But Dani said she's proud of her mom, although the move created
some tension.
</P>
<P>
   ``I blamed my mom at one point but she's not the one who is at
fault,'' said Dani. ``The racists and hate groups aggravate me, but
I feel sympathy because they are sick people who need God. I blame
the government, ultimately, for failing us.
</P>
<P>
   ``My mom had a quote on her old office door: `Evil wins when
good men do nothing.' What will it take to help us _ something
catastrophic? We can send thousands of troops to Kosovo, but my mom
has to hide in her own country.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
