<SLUG> BC-EDIT-BOSTON-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: A CHANGE OF COURSE IN BOSTON 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial for Saturday, July 17:
</P>
<P>
   Desegregation policies that assign children to public schools
based on race, sometimes busing them to achieve integration, have
lost ground steadily since they were introduced in the 1960s and
'70s. Some policies have been swept away in court challenges while
others were rendered moot when whites withdrew to the suburbs,
making racial balance impossible to achieve. Both factors came to
bear this week in Boston, which responded to white flight _ and a
lawsuit challenging desegregation policies _ by eliminating race as
a factor in deciding where children attend school.
</P>
<P>
   This was a reasonable decision given the demographics, the legal
climate and the fact that both blacks and whites support a plan
that focuses less on race and more on improving the quality of
education. But Boston's minority children will suffer, as will the
city's future, if Boston does not keep its pledge to build new
schools in crowded minority districts and raise the level of
instruction throughout the city.
</P>
<P>
   The desegregation plan was developed 25 years ago because black
students had been deliberately confined to cramped, underfinanced
schools with little possibility of a first-rate education. When the
Boston School Committee declined to remedy the problem, U.S.
District Judge W. Arthur Garrity Jr. forced the issue with a busing
and desegregation plan that led to a near civil war in the white
communities of South Boston and Charlestown. The struggle over
busing, documented in J. Anthony Lukas' ``Common Ground,'' was one
of the most poisonous of that era. But some whites who opposed
desegregation in the 1970s have changed their minds. One is Lisa
McGoff Collins, whose family fought the plan but who told school
officials this week that busing had made her ``a better person'' by
exposing her to another culture. ``We feared other cultures,'' she
said, ``and that was wrong.''
</P>
<P>
   Racial integration is unquestionably a social good. But the
desegregation plans of the 1970s aimed to do more than put black
and white students into the same classroom. The ultimate aim was to
force municipalities to spend the same effort and resources on
educating black and white children _ and to give both groups equal
access to successful schools.
</P>
<P>
   This seemed fine in the abstract, until violence erupted in
Boston's streets and whites either fled the city or placed their
children in non-public schools. The racial balance that had seemed
a plausible goal in 1974, when Boston's schools were slightly more
than half white, began to seem more and more remote as white
representation fell to its present level of about 15 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The danger for Boston's future is that a mainly white civic
leadership will withdraw support, turning its back on the blacks
and Latinos who fill the schools. To avoid that outcome, school
officials will have to make it clear that everyone has a stake in
the system, showing the public that all of the system's children
can learn.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
