<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POPULATION-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FUTURE'S UPON US: WORLD POPULATION TO TOP 6 BILLION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By JON KAMMAN  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Any moment now, there will be 6 billion of us. Human beings,
sharing planet Earth.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. Census Bureau, which keeps odometerlike counters
running on its Web site to offer its best estimates of the nation's
and world's expanding population, says the milestone, frightful to
many, but little cause for alarm to others, will occur Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   The United Nations, the only other body that attempts a world
count, calculates that the 6 billion mark will be reached in
October. A number of environmental and population-control
organizations will observe the event Oct. 12.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever the date, the numbers tracked by both organizations
portray staggering growth since the dawn of the Industrial
Revolution.
</P>
<P>
   It took all of human history up to 1804 for the human race to
achieve a world population of 1 billion. It took only 12 years to
leap from 5 billion to 6 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Since 1960, the Earth's population has doubled. The world is
gaining more than 77 million people annually, roughly the
equivalent of adding a new France, Greece and Sweden each year, or
a city the size of Phoenix every six days.
</P>
<P>
   And though fertility rates are declining, the United Nation
projects the world population will swell by an additional 3 billion
by 2054.
</P>
<P>
   The question is, are we breeding ourselves out of existence?
</P>
<P>
   ``Fundamentally, I think it's fairly scary,'' George L. Cowgill,
an Arizona State University anthropology professor, says of the 6
billion mark. ``It's not something that should cause people to
panic, though.''
</P>
<P>
   Cowgill contemplates the perils of overpopulation as a sideline
to his study of settlements in central Mexico dating back 2,000
years. (Earth's population was an estimated 300 million to 500
million.)
</P>
<P>
   ``I think there are limits to how many people the Earth can
support, but anybody who tries to put a number on it is just
guessing,'' Cowgill says.
</P>
<P>
   Groups such as ZPG, for zero population growth, founded in the
1960s by Stanford University Professor Paul Ehrlich and activists
inspired by his watershed book ``The Population Bomb,'' react with
greater alarm to what is known as Y6B, the year of 6 billion.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every 20 minutes, the world adds another 3,500 human lives but
loses one or more entire species of animal or plant life, at least
27,000 species per year,'' ZPG writes. ``This is a rate and scale
of extinction that has not occurred in 65 million years.''
</P>
<P>
   The World Conservation Union published a survey in 1996
estimating that one-fourth of mammals and amphibians, one-fifth of
reptiles, more than one-third of fish and 11 percent of birds are
in danger of extinction.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, ``inch for inch, in human-manipulated environments
there still is enormous biodiversity,'' says Professor Charles
Redman, director of ASU's Center for Environmental Studies.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are eliminating things, and that is deplorable, but we're
also introducing other things, both exotics and greater quantities
of native species, just as fast,'' says Redman, a professor of
anthropology who is heading a long-term study of the biological
health of Phoenix and central Arizona.
</P>
<P>
   Redman cites several grounds for optimism: the remarkable
adaptability of various life forms, human ingenuity and ample
evidence that people can and do regulate themselves.
</P>
<P>
   ``No matter what has happened . . . here we are. . . . We've
overcome all the difficulties,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   Cowgill points to the youthfulness, and therefore fertility, of
today's population as a big concern. The United Nations estimates
the world has 1 billion teenagers.
</P>
<P>
   Sandra Fan, who headed the now-inactive Metro Phoenix Chapter of
ZPG, asks, ``How in the world do you stop 6 billion people from
continuing to multiply?''
</P>
<P>
   The litany of worries about overpopulation extends from food
shortages to global warming; economic paralysis to warfare over
resource shortages; pollution of water supplies and the oceans to
denuding of forests; befoulment of air to decline in soil quality;
greater traffic congestion to fewer educational opportunities.
</P>
<P>
   The biggest issue of late is the unequal distribution and
consumption of resources between developed and undeveloped
countries.
</P>
<P>
   ``The richest fifth (of the world's people) consumes 86 percent
of all goods and services and produces 53 percent of all carbon
dioxide emissions,'' says ZPG, while the figures for the poorest
fifth are 1.3 percent and 3 percent.
</P>
<P>
   For many, the most comforting signs are declining fertility
rates, the number of children born per woman during her fertile
years.
</P>
<P>
   Annual world population growth appears to have peaked at 86
million in 1989. Average global fertility has been halved, from a
high of about six children per woman in the 1950s to 2.9 today.
</P>
<P>
   No single industrialized nation in the world has a fertility
rate above replacement level, which is about 2.06 children per
woman. The United States, with 2.03 children per woman, has the
highest fertility rate in the developed world.
</P>
<P>
   The average fertility rate for European countries is 1.4. In
Japan, it's also 1.4.
</P>
<P>
   In the Third World, where 98 percent of population growth is
expected to take place, there have also been dramatic declines.
Since 1985, the fertility rate for developing countries has fallen
from 4.7 to 3.1.
</P>
<P>
   ``Demographers have been repeatedly amazed at how rapidly
fertility rates have come down in a matter of a few decades,'' said
Brian Halweil of the Worldwatch Institute, a non-profit
organization that analyzes global trends.
</P>
<P>
   However, slower growth is a long way from no growth.
</P>
<P>
   In Africa, the Middle East and southern Asia, fertility rates
remain high. In 40 African nations, women still average six
children. Niger leads the world with 7.5 children per woman. And
Latin America is still growing, albeit more slowly.
</P>
<P>
   Religion also is criticized as deterring attempts to curtail
population, specifically the Roman Catholic Church.
</P>
<P>
   But Monsignor Edward Ryle of Phoenix, executive director of the
Arizona Catholic Conference, points out that from the time of Pope
John XXIII in the early 1960s, the Catholic Church has considered
limiting population an acceptable means for the faithful to achieve
economic, social and political enlightenment. &QL; 
Scripps Howard contributed to this article. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
