<SLUG> BC-EDIT-GRIDLOCK-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: GRIDLOCK CITY  
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial for Saturday, July 17:
</P>
<P>
   Manhattan's hottest piece of real estate, Times Square, has
gotten so crowded lately that pedestrians often have to wait in
line to cross the street. The newest arrival, Conde Nast
Publications, plans to hold court in its icy tower by mid-August.
ABC's ``Good Morning America'' will settle nearby in September. The
human gridlock can only get worse in November, when the World
Wrestling Federation hunkers down in the Paramount Building to open
a theme restaurant. The real theater this fall will unfold on
Broadway, the street.
</P>
<P>
   As New Yorkers and tourists converge on already crowded
sidewalks, the question of what to do about pedestrian congestion
is unavoidable. Proposals are circulating to improve sidewalk
conditions, but the Department of Transportation confirms only
plans to resurface streets and make crosswalk signals more
internationally recognizable.
</P>
<P>
   Times Square already includes some of the city's more hazardous
intersections. Drivers career up the side streets to escape
construction, making jaywalking and even legal crossings more
perilous. The islands near the bow tie of Seventh Avenue and
Broadway are clogged with visitors waiting for lower-cost theater
tickets. Across the street, teen-agers gather under MTV's
street-front studio screaming for a wave from VJ Carson Daly. The
arrival of ``Good Morning America,'' with its celebrity guests,
could entice even bigger crowds.
</P>
<P>
   Business leaders advocate the use of mid-block passageways
through Shubert Alley and the Marriott Marquis Hotel to avoid the
growing sidewalk scramble. The city should also consider widening
sidewalks, adjusting stoplights to give pedestrians more time to
cross and strictly enforcing driving regulations.
</P>
<P>
   As entertaining as it might be to watch wrestling stars like
Hulk Hogan vying with Vogue editors for the next light, it would be
better to give pedestrians a little more elbow room.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
