<HEADLINE>
DON'T SOCK IT TO ME: THE SOCKS ALREADY HAVE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MONICA FRAZIER ANDERSON 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Socks &AMP; Things
</P>
<P>
   I had a thought, a simple thought.
</P>
<P>
   I threw it in the fire.
</P>
<P>
   There it grew large,
</P>
<P>
   'til it was forged
</P>
<P>
   And thus became desire.
</P>
<P>
   I did not want it,
</P>
<P>
   Did not need it
</P>
<P>
   Among my mind's possessions.
</P>
<P>
   Still it grew
</P>
<P>
   Until like new
</P>
<P>
   And it became Obsession.
</P>
<P>
   I've been thinking. I haven't done a lot of thinking, just a
little thinking so that I don't get overwhelmed and start to feel
the need to actually do something productive.
</P>
<P>
   I just kind of like to talk about the thoughts.
</P>
<P>
   Anyway, I've been thinking about that sock issue again. It's
just so very puzzling to me. I know we've discussed it ad nauseum,
and there's nothing we can do about the sock disposal hidden in the
dryer.
</P>
<P>
   However, yesterday, I counted 18 single socks in my youngest
son's drawer. Eighteen, for goodness sakes! Where the heck are the
socks going?
</P>
<P>
   I have visions of a little old lady somewhere knitting a giant
quilt made out of athletic socks. It's so big that it can cover the
entire state of Missouri. Or maybe there's a big sailboat on the
lake, and it's shaped like a shoe. Its sails are made of thousands
of socks. It cruises, and sometimes it smells like a locker room.
</P>
<P>
   I don't know. I just want the socks back.
</P>
<P>
   Why can't you go to the pawnshop and buy single socks? They have
everything else.
</P>
<P>
   In lieu of a sock recycling center, which probably isn't very
practical, I propose that we simply dispense with the apparel
etiquette regarding feet. Why do the socks have to match anyway?
</P>
<P>
   We're wearing polka-dot shorts with striped shirts now. Men wear
ties that have absolutely nothing on them to complement their
suits. Women have been given freedom by the fashion industry to mix
gold and silver jewelry. As far as I can tell, many models don't
comb their hair or shave anymore.
</P>
<P>
   Why all the angst about the socks matching, especially under a
pant leg?
</P>
<P>
   Let's free ourselves of all these restrictions and conventions.
Socks cost too much to toss them just because one goes on the lam.
Let's not even roll them up into those little balls anymore; just
throw them in the drawer and pick out any two, randomly, when
needed. Don't we have enough stress in our lives already?
</P>
<P>
   I made this suggestion to my loved ones, and they just looked at
me with a mixture of sympathy and disbelief. They can't embrace the
vision. If we can only get Ricky Martin or Cher to do it, it will
quickly become the rage. Of course, we could just pin the sock
pairs together before we wash and dry them. Nah, what's the fun in
that?
</P>
<P>
   Oh, I have to go; my family is getting that straitjacket out
again. I have to act normal now. I'll go put on a pair of matching
socks, if I can find one. That fools them every time.
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-17-99 0035EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
