<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 
The Arizona Republic plans to move the following stories for use by
clients of the NYTimes News Service for Saturday, July 17. If you
have any questions, please call the Republic News Desk at (602)
444-8286.
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
DE VITA-MUSIC (Phoenix) - It probably isn't a coincidence that
``Nada Es Igual,'' the title of Franco De Vita's seventh studio
album, means ``nothing is the same.'' The 45-year-old troubadour
seems determined to shake things up this time around. By RANDY
CORDOVA. Story moved in the ``E'' category. &QL; 
GUNS (Washington) _ Presidential candidates, like calculating poker
players, once believed they had more to lose than gain by
mentioning guns. But a rash of shootings by teenagers and young
adults has some in the 2000 campaign gambling that the time is
right to speak out about gun control. By JEFF BARKER. Story will
move in the ``A'' category.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
POPULATION (Undated) - Any moment now, there will be 6 billion of
us. Human beings, sharing planet Earth. The U.S. Census Bureau,
which keeps odometerlike counters running on its Web site to offer
its best estimates of the nation's and world's expanding
population, says the milestone, frightful to many, but little cause
for alarm to others, will occur this Sunday. The United Nations,
the only other body that attempts a world count, calculates that
the 6 billion mark will be reached in October. A number of
environmental and population-control organizations will observe the
event Oct. 12. By JON KAMMAN. Story will move in the ``A''
category.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
YUGOFRAUD (Phoenix) - Law enforcement officials from Kosovo to
Arizona are investigating an Arizona state legislator who
apparently conned U.S. Rep. J.D. Hayworth, R-Ariz., out of a trip
to the Balkan conflict in May by posing as a Naval reservist
desperately trying to join his unit. Hayworth said the FBI and the
Navy are conducting a fraud investigation. Hayworth also called for
state lawmakers to conduct an ethics inquiry. By CHRIS MOESER.
Story will move in the ``A'' category. &QL; 
 &QL; 
AUTO-REVIEW (Phoenix) - With its all-new Sonata, Hyundai has
arrived. Finally. Best-known for selling inexpensive cars with
short life spans, the Korean automaker takes a major leap forward
with the redesigned Sonata. With a new V-6 engine, an attractive
new body design, fairly roomy interior and a sub-$20,000 price tag
fully loaded with luxury features, the Sonata presents a formidible
entry in the broad, competitive class of mid-size sedans. By BOB
GOLFEN. Story moved in the ``L'' category. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
