<HEADLINE>
A 6,000 - SEAT STADIUM OPENS IN NEWARK 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (CORRECTS spelling of Lehigh in 5th graf; ADDS score of game in
last graf.) (ART ADV: A photo is being sent. Non-subscribers can make
individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
 By RONALD SMOTHERS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service     
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEWARK _ This city, which has been furiously reimagining itself
in recent years as performing arts center and a transportation hub,
donned a baseball uniform Friday with the opening of Riverfront
Park stadium and the return of minor-league baseball to Newark
after a 50-year absence.
</P>
<P>
   The new 6,000 seat, $34 million stadium, financed by the city
and Essex County, will be the home of the Newark Bears. The name is
drawn from the Triple-A New York Yankees farm team that won two
dozen divisional and league championships and three minor-league
equivalents of the World Series. The Yankees imagery dominated
Friday as the Bears' owner, Rick Cerone, a former Yankees catcher
who grew up in Newark, brought in the legendary Yankees Yogi Berra
and Phil Rizzuto for the opening ceremonies.
</P>
<P>
   Calling the stadium the ``House That Rick Built,'' the master of
ceremonies had county and city elected officials lined up along the
first base line. Clowns, a costumed stilt walker, bagpipers and
some Bears players circulated among the soldout crowd. A video
about the old Newark Bears and the city's Newark Eagles of the
Negro leagues played on a giant scoreboard screen.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a carnival atmosphere and that's what it should be,''
said Cerone, speaking to reporters before the game while
self-consciously twisting the huge World Series ring on his left
hand.
</P>
<P>
   The Bears _ in violet shirts, white pants and white and violet
caps _ took the field for the first time to the pulsing beat of
rock music, ready to face the Lehigh Valley Black Diamonds.
</P>
<P>
   The emotions in the stands ran the gamut.
</P>
<P>
   Larry Goldman, the president of the nearby New Jersey Performing
Arts Center whose opening 18 months ago heralded an important
beginning to the city's revitalization, said that ``arts and
sports, sports and arts would prove to be the leading edge of
change in urban areas.'' He went on to cite examples in Pittsburgh,
Dallas, Cleveland and Baltimore.
</P>
<P>
   For Diana Hawks, a longtime Newark resident it was ``someplace
to take the grandchildren.''
</P>
<P>
   Isaias Vasquez, 10, attending his first baseball game, was in
search of similar memories. Looking around the stadium and
pronouncing it ``beautiful,'' he said: ``I just want to get hit by
a ball.''
</P>
<P>
   Situated on seven acres near the Passaic River that once housed
iron foundries, carriage works and a dairy, Riverfront is the
stadium that almost wasn't built.
</P>
<P>
   Two years ago, just two weeks before city and county officials
were to break ground on county parkland about a mile away,
neighborhood opponents of the plan obtained landmarks designation
for the park and blocked construction.
</P>
<P>
   The Essex County Improvement Authority, the designated builder,
had to shift gears, revise the financing plans, find a new site,
negotiate to buy land from private owners and deal with new
construction realities. The changes pushed the costs 50 percent
over initial estimates.
</P>
<P>
   Even as work started, there remained skepticism, Cerone said.
From January to June, Cerone said the team got no calls from
advertisers seeking space on the scoreboard or outfield fences or
takers for their luxury skyboxes. Most thought work would never be
finished by Friday, he said, adding: ``But once the light towers
went up last month and the sod went down, they started calling. Now
we have a waiting list for everything including promotions for our
36 home games.''
</P>
<P>
   All last winter and spring the contractor has been playing
``beat the clock,'' said Harris Levy, the construction manager for
the project with Prismatic Development Corp.. Friday, still looking
much like a construction site with trailers clogging dusty flats,
and some cement walkways cordoned off and still drying, the stadium
was pronounced ``fan-ready'' by Levy.
</P>
<P>
   As part of the six-team, independent Atlantic League, the Newark
Bears are part of a boom in minor league baseball that experts say
is being fed by the same promise of economic development that comes
with having a major league team and stadium. Currently there are
five independent leagues, which are not affiliated with
major-league teams or their farm systems, with a total of 48 teams.
</P>
<P>
   Alan Simpson, editor of Baseball Today, the trade publication
that focuses on minor league baseball, the teams of the Atlantic
League are an ``aggressive'' bunch who are paying more than some
other leagues in an effort to get good players and who seem to have
a flair for the marketing necessary to build fan interest and
profits.
</P>
<P>
   Last year in their first year of operations and when they played
home games at Bridgeport and Skylands Park in far west Sussex
County, the Bears came in last with a record of 17-33.
</P>
<P>
   Team manager Tom O'Malley said that ``feeling like nomads'' with
no place to call home may have accounted for that dismal record.
After an equally dismal first half of the season, the team has
started the second half with a 1-2 record.
</P>
<P>
   But Friday night, the Bears gave the fans a thriller, winning
9-8 in 10 innings.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
