<SLUG> BC-EDITORIAL-MONTENEGRO-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMMON CAUSE WITH MONTENEGRO 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   As in a Sophoclean tragedy that bestows calamities on every
member of an accursed family, the curtain is now rising on
Montenegro, the last Yugoslav republic to remain yoked to the
Serbian regime of Slobodan Milosevic.
</P>
<P>
   Montenegro, under the democratic leadership of President Milo
Djukanovic, has witnessed the brutal blundering of Milosevic in
Kosovo and decided it must have either political parity in a
restructured Yugoslav Federation or independence.
</P>
<P>
   The Montenegrin predicament merits tactful understanding from
the Western democracies. The leadership in Montenegro was as
horrified as the NATO allies at Milosevic's recidivist crimes in
Kosovo, yet Montenegrins suffered under NATO bombs and now must
face the economic consequences of NATO's air war against
Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   The pro-Western Djukanovic, whose administration entered crucial
negotiations this week with Milosevic's representatives, would
prefer a change of regime in Belgrade to secession from Yugoslavia.
But there is no assurance that Milosevic will step down or be
removed any time soon. And as long as he remains in power,
Milosevic will have powerful incentives to prevent Montenegro from
seceding from Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   The moment Montenegro leaves the federation, Yugoslavia will
cease to exist, and Milosevic will cease to be its president.
Moreover, a Serbia that is no longer federated with Montenegro in a
Yugoslav state would become not only a pariah among nations but a
landlocked pariah. Hence Milosevic can be counted on to do
everything in his power to keep Montenegro within Yugoslavia. The
fate of Milosevic cannot be separated from the outcome of
Montenegro's challenge.
</P>
<P>
   Montenegro is asking not only for equal political representation
in Yugoslav institutions but for free and fair elections and
integration into Europe. These are demands Milosevic can hardly
satisfy.
</P>
<P>
   Djukanovic deserves unflinching support in the coming showdown
with Milosevic so that the peoples of the region may recover from
the calamities wrought by Milosevic.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-17-99 0059EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990717.0017 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-17 01:01 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3689 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EDITORIAL-SENATE-BOS &LR;      07-17 0357
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDITORIAL-SENATE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHY LOSERS WIN ON CAPITOL HILL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Stalemates solve nothing and often tarnish the participants. Yet
Congress is often oblivious to the damage caused by its legislative
games.
</P>
<P>
   Senators Trent Lott and Mitch McConnell are trying to have an
associate law professor, Bradley A. Smith of Capital University in
Columbus, Ohio, appointed to the Federal Election Commission.
</P>
<P>
   Smith opposes the law that the FEC enforces. ``Campaign finance
reform has turned out to be bad policy,'' he has written. ``The
most sensible reform is a simple one: repeal of the Federal
Elections Campaign Act.''
</P>
<P>
   Smith's writings on the subject make him a fine advocate. And he
points out that reformers want to change the law, too. Still, his
opposition to the thrust of the law would make him a poor
commissioner. President Clinton is correct in refusing to appoint
him. Clinton would do well to end the practice of filling FEC jobs
on the basis of congressional recommendations. At a minimum, he
should ask Lott for a more fitting choice.
</P>
<P>
   Lott and McConnell, however, have stubbornly resorted to a
time-tested strategy: legislative blackmail. They are holding up
Clinton's nomination of Richard Holbrooke to be UN ambassador.
Holbrooke, though prickly, is an accomplished diplomat whose
qualifications are manifest. Even Lott admits that he will likely
be confirmed in the end. The stalemate, he implied, is to get
Clinton's attention. ``We need to get an understanding of how this
(FEC appointment) is going to work,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   All this game-playing is a way of life in Washington but a
mystery outside the Beltway.
</P>
<P>
   Forcing the United States to shuffle along at the United Nations
for months without a permanent ambassador is an embarrassment,
especially when the obvious candidate is at hand. Muscling Clinton
to make an FEC appointment singularly unsuited to the job is
stranger still.
</P>
<P>
   Most bizarre is the cynicism involved in linking the two so that
stalemate will guarantee no action. Congress should think better of
itself.
</P>
</TEXT>
