<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-17 01:01 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3690 &Cx1f; tth-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBA-VECSEY-COLUMN-SPI     07-17 0872
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-VECSEY-COLUMN-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
M'S FUTURE AT STAKE IN UPCOMING WEEKS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By LAURA VECSEY  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ Minutes before the All-Star break and a few days
before the Mariners moved into their wonderful new ballpark, Jay
Buhner took a moment to remind his teammates of the serious
business ahead.
</P>
<P>
   As a veteran and a leader and a 12-year Mariner who has been
abundantly committed to the team and the community, Buhner said he
was not going to let go unsaid that a lot was at stake between July
15 and July 31, the trading deadline for major league baseball.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are a lot of young guys here, and I just told them this
(stuff) is serious. If we're not in it, the 1st of August could
roll around and a lot of lives could be changed,'' Buhner said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told them to go and have a good few days off but get ready
to come back and kick some butt. There's a lot riding on this.
There are a lot of free agents on this team, and a lot of things
could happen.''
</P>
<P>
   Buhner is right. The Mariners are up against it.
</P>
<P>
   No one wants to rain on the Mariners' parade, except maybe the
Northwest weather, which is why the roof at Safeco Field was closed
Friday night.
</P>
<P>
   No one wants to be constantly suspicious of just where the
Mariners are heading, especially now, with the aisles at Safeco
Field barely sticky from spilled soda.
</P>
<P>
   Friday was Day 2 of the New Outdoor Era. It dawned gray and
drizzly _ and that was even before the area's rabid sports talkers
embarked on a day-long rant about what the heck the Mariners are
going to do improve their pitching.
</P>
<P>
   See, all the deserved pomp, circumstance and hoopla about the
Mariners' truly splendid new ballpark has had some early
competition.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of being awash in dreamy reverence for all that $517
million can build _ and it's quite a lot, especially when you add
up all those rest rooms _ the equally predominant theme du jour has
been overwrought concern about the bullpen, John Halama's ability
to keep up the good work and Jeff Fassero's capacity for turning
around his first-half yips.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe it is not fair that the glory of Safeco's opening day was
riddled with derision about ``New Ballpark, Same Old Mariners.''
</P>
<P>
   But when closer Jose Mesa bombed in a ninth-inning demonstration
on how not to throw strikes, walking four of the five batters he
faced and losing the game, the onslaught of catcalls was
inevitable.
</P>
<P>
   You don't watch the home team lose its sixth straight and lapse
into last place in the ultra-weak American League West, which is
what happened after Mesa's meltdown, and not stop to think that
perhaps this is a sure sign of a team on the slide.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought (opening night) was a great game, well played, great
pitching between (Jamie) Moyer and (Andy) Ashby. It's just too bad
we came out on the short end of the stick,'' Alex Rodriguez said.
</P>
<P>
   Rodriguez said he never once thought about whether Mesa should
have been pulled.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's been the best closer we've had in five years. What's his
ratio, 18 saves in 20 attempts? What better numbers can you have? I
think he's earned the right to be out there,'' Rodriguez said.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you're going to sit around and feel sorry for yourself,
you're going to be in a lot of trouble. We have to keep going. We
have to fight.''
</P>
<P>
   The Mariners under Lou Piniella have always been good
second-half battlers. It was that way in 1994, just before the
strike that ended the season. It was that way in '95 when they won
the West and in '96 when they were in it until the last weekend of
the season, and again in '97.
</P>
<P>
   But everyone's patience is running thin. The credibility of the
team has suffered since last season, when Randy Johnson's trade
turned into a nine-month drain on everyone _ fans, team, manager
and Johnson.
</P>
<P>
   Then, in the offseason, not enough of that credibility was
restored when the M's could have gone shopping for one pitching
ace, edged above the self-imposed salary cap and bought the
Mariners a ton of the benevolence that the front office, manager
and owners now feel is in serious short supply.
</P>
<P>
   Nothing was quite so sad and ugly as watching what should have
been the start of a fresh new era start off on such a sour note.
Nothing is quite so uncomfortable as the home team booing one of
its own players on what should have been one of the best nights in
team history.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, the opening days of Safeco Field feel as if they
are coinciding with the potential start to the undoing of a dream
team that never quite filled its potential.
</P>
<P>
   Buhner is right. The next two weeks are crucial.
</P>
<P>
   ``This has been an organization that has always gone out and
gotten help (if the team was in contention at the trading
deadline),'' Buhner said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've come too far, we have too much fun as a group to let
July 31 come and be one of the teams other people are coming to to
take our players.''
</P>
<P>
   And as much as we all want to come out and luxuriate in
Seattle's prize ballpark, it would make it so much easier if there
were fewer questions about whether this team is on the verge of
surging or dumping.
</P>
<P>
   Laura Vecsey is a P-I columnist
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
