<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDITORIAL-Y2K-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
APOCALYPSE? NOT NOW 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For release Sunday, July 18, 1999)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Y2K bug is a problem, not a monster. But man's fears of the
unknown are pumping the thing into apocalyptic proportions in some
quarters. Like the end-of-the world visions and religious
pilgrimages that ushered in ``Y1K'' a thousand years ago, wild
millennial imaginings of modern man reduce him to a primitive and
create what the history books might dub the Panic of 1999.
</P>
<P>
   There's nothing wrong with being prepared or upgrading
computers, as business and government offices are doing or have
done. The Federal Emergency Management Agency recommends that
people look at the flip of the calendar to the year 2000 the way
they might view an approaching storm _ have the flashlights,
batteries, radios, canned goods, jugged water, and enough cash on
hand for a long weekend in case the microchips blow, but don't
anticipate Armageddon.
</P>
<P>
   Some people insist on doing just that as they build bunkers,
stake out caves, or plan to sail off on boats with their cash and
stock portfolios in the hold. Retailers also report a run on
generators, with some suppliers back-ordered to the year 2001.
</P>
<P>
   ``Experts'' at Y2K survival sites on the Internet advise people
to build solar stills for storing water, to become familiar with
the barter economy, to know advanced first aid, to expect martial
law or a military invasion, to have guns ready with 200 rounds of
ammunition, to have cash for two months, and to buy a three-month
supply of groceries, including 20 pounds of wheat and corn per
person _ don't forget the hand-cranked grain mill.
</P>
<P>
   Anyone ``caught without a mill,'' notes one Web site, should put
an inch of grain into a can, hold the can on the ground between his
or her feet, and then pound the grain with a pipe.
</P>
<P>
   These people should get a grip _ on a lot more than their grain
pipes. The world as we know it is not about to disappear. It may
have a case of hiccups or a bad cold on Dec. 31, but with so many
technological wizards focused on the problem, the bug is not likely
to turn into Godzilla. Public calm will help minimize any trouble.
The bunker mentality and hoarding will only make it worse.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-17-99 0102EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990717.0020 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-17 01:07 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3693 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WVA-AGED-ART-2NDTAKE-     07-17 0500
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WVA-AGED-ART-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 DUNBAR: poll-tailored evasions. 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``God will be setting my term limit,'' says Hechler rather
nonchalantly. ``But I don't want to be known as the candidate of
the seniors,'' he insists. As a native New Yorker, he moved here in
the 1950s, fresh from working in the idealistic campaigns of Adlai
Stevenson, to teach political science at Marshall College and try
to engender fresh interest in politics among the young.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a legend,'' said Bill Walker, a 24-year-old political
science student from Marshall working the picnic crowd at Hechler's
side as a summer intern. ``Just to someday look back and say I
learned politics from Hechler is a great honor,'' said the student.
He exuded the dedication of one of the young interns in the special
state program in which elderly mountaineers have been reinstilling
the art of fiddle playing lost by earlier generations who had to
emigrate for work.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll tell you, people my age are soured on politics lately,''
said Walker, who is determined to run for political office at the
earliest opportunity.
</P>
<P>
   As the elderly come to the fore, state politics are shifting to
consider issues like how the revenue base will hold up as more
retirees claim special tax abatements. ``Most studies show incoming
retirees are actually increasing the economic base,'' said Dudley
of state senior services. ``They bring in an average of $250,000 in
liquid assets, and they're a tremendous resource in volunteer work,
politics and civics.''
</P>
<P>
   Like all the states, West Virginia faces the potential trauma
from the retirement of a wide swath of talent when the baby boomer
generation hits 65. ``We'll feel it a little quicker,'' said
Dudley. But he noted there are all sorts of variables, including a
slow but promising downturn from the state's traditional loss of
young workers, plus a redefinition of retirement itself.
</P>
<P>
   ``Close to half of the governor's Cabinet came out of retirement
to serve,'' noted Dudley, who is busy preparing for Underwood's
regional conference in September on the problems and opportunities
of the elderly. Next year, West Virginia will play a principle role
in the United Nation's International Year of the Older Person when
it hosts the conference on rural health.
</P>
<P>
   Hechler appreciates those issues but puts more passion into
railing against mechanized mountain-top coal mining and its effects
on the environment, citizenry and general attractiveness of West
Virginia now that all the retirees are flocking in. He has been
hiking the state on this issue, just as he has been hiking
nationally for campaign finance reform, a buoyant old New Dealer
come round one more time.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh, that's Ken Hechler,'' an elderly woman told her friend as
the candidate confronted them at the picnic. ``You ought to know
him _ he's been around 100 years.''
</P>
<P>
   Hechler, a whippet on the hustings, instantly responded: ``One
hundred years! Whoopee!'' And he asked if he might give the woman a
hug.
</P>
</TEXT>
