<HEADER>
A3697 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBA-REEVES-COLUMN-TEX     07-17 0859
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-REEVES-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TRADE GUESSING GAME A TOUGH CASE TO CRACK
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JIM REEVES 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ARLINGTON, Texas _ We ambushed Doug Melvin on his way to dinner
last night at The BallPark in Arlington. It was a cheap trick, but
all's fair in baseball when the trading deadline is fast
approaching.
</P>
<P>
   It was the classic strike favored by the Zulus, the flanks
spreading forward to each side like the horns of the African
buffalo, luring the victim into the center, where the real assault
can take place.
</P>
<P>
   In other words, Rangers beat writer Johnny Paul and I
double-teamed the general manager. He had no where to run.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, that's when our well-planned sneak attack began
to fizzle.
</P>
<P>
   I've squeezed more information out of dead men.
</P>
<P>
   Navy Seals threatened with going to bed without their supper are
more loose-lipped than a general manager two weeks from the July 31
drop-dead date.
</P>
<P>
   We played good cop-bad cop. We played good cop-good cop. We
played bad cop-bad cop. We played cops and robbers. We played ...
well, you don't think we're going to reveal all our trade secrets
here, do you?
</P>
<P>
   We even told Melvin if he didn't talk, he'd have to clean his
plate, which shook him up more than anything else we'd said. But he
still wouldn't come clean.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nobody's called me offering pitching in two days,'' was the
GM's opening gambit.
</P>
<P>
   Sure, Doug, and I suppose you really expect us to believe that?
</P>
<P>
   ``No, really,'' Melvin insisted. ``I've never seen it so quiet
this close to trading deadline.''
</P>
<P>
   Four scouts, two from Minnesota, laughed and joked a few tables
away. What about them, we asked Melvin. Guess they're just here for
the press box cuisine at eight bucks a pop, huh?
</P>
<P>
   Melvin shrugged and clamped his walrus mustache over his lips.
I've seen tough cookies before, but this guy takes the cake.
</P>
<P>
   It's not like Melvin wouldn't like to make a deal. His team
could use another positive bump in the rotation. But this is like
picking through a bin of used golf balls: You know darn well if
there is a Titleist in there, it's going to have an ugly scuff mark
or two on it.
</P>
<P>
   You've heard the names of all the usual suspects by now. The
Twins may have two scouts here, but they keep insisting they're not
going to dump Brad Radke. Ditto for the Phillies and Curt
Schilling, who apparently doesn't want to come to Texas anyway.
</P>
<P>
   ``If he doesn't want to come here,'' second baseman Mark
McLemore said before last night's 9-8 victory over the
Diamondbacks, ``then we don't want him. Let him stay in
Philadelphia and keep losing.''
</P>
<P>
   Players are funny that way. They'd love to see the Rangers get
some help, as long as they're not the ones involved in the trade.
</P>
<P>
   ``Personally, I'd like to see them give up every second baseman
they have in the minors,'' McLemore said laughing. ``I know Doug's
trying to do something, but there are no guarantees out there. I
know we can't afford to give up any of our frontline players but if
we could get another starter who can keep us in the game, it would
help.''
</P>
<P>
   Nobody _ and I mean nobody _ wants to give up Ruben Mateo.
</P>
<P>
   Which takes us back to the suspect list.
</P>
<P>
   The A's say they won't trade Kenny Rogers as long as they're
still in the race. Juan Guzman is available but he's about as
erratic as they come. Keep him in mind.
</P>
<P>
   The Orioles are also hoping someone _ anyone _ will take Scott
Erickson, his 6-plus ERA and his ridiculously exorbitant contract.
It won't be the Rangers.
</P>
<P>
   The best starter out there might be the Dodgers' Ismael Valdez,
but LA is offering a package deal: Whoever takes Valdez also has to
take nonproductive, overpaid first baseman Eric Karros. That's a
total of $9 million, plus the players and prospects you have to
give up, to get a pitcher you want and a first baseman you can't
use. Besides, the Dodgers are desperate for left-handed hitting and
you-know-who _ the redhead _ ain't going nowhere. Forget it.
</P>
<P>
   Oh yeah, there's Darryl Kile from Colorado, but he's in the
second-year of a $24 million contract that included a $5 million
signing bonus. Seems $3 million of that bonus, along with Kile's
base pay of $8 million, are due next season, making him an $11
million player. That's not happening here.
</P>
<P>
   It's not as if Melvin hasn't pulled the trigger on these
deadline deals before. Last year he brought in Todd Stottlemyre,
Todd Zeile and Royce Clayton. In '96 he added John Burkett after
the deadline but in time to help during the Rangers' stretch run.
</P>
<P>
   What this team needs _ a bonafide ace who can help get them
beyond the first round of the playoffs _ just isn't out there or
isn't available. Not yet anyway. But there are lesser veterans who
could help if the price isn't too high.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't worry about the playoffs,'' said Melvin, still playing
the tough guy. ``I worry about getting there first. Cleveland might
be the only team with the luxury of not worrying about getting
there.
</P>
<P>
   ``Believe me, I'd do something if I thought it made sense.''
</P>
<P>
   A likely story. What, you think we haven't heard that alibi
before?
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-17-99 0114EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
