</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-RANGERS-D'BACKS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OFFENSE SAVES RANGERS AGAIN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOHNNY PAUL 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ARLINGTON, Texas _ The Rangers ask much of their offense.
</P>
<P>
   Their rotation and defense require it.
</P>
<P>
   The recurring storyline appeared again last night in the
Rangers' 9-8 victory against the Arizona Diamondbacks at The
Ballpark in Arlington.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers staged their second ninth-inning victory in as many
evenings when third baseman Todd Zeile drew a bases-loaded walk
from Dan Plesac to force left fielder Rusty Greer across the plate
with the winning run.
</P>
<P>
   ``We feel confident that we're going to get that one run,''
Zeile said. ``Anybody in this lineup can beat you with one swing.''
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers' offense overcame:
</P>
<P>
   closer John Wetteland, who blew a save opportunity of the fourth
time in seven chances;
</P>
<P>
   a shaky performance from reliever Mike Venafro, who surrendered
two seventh-inning runs;
</P>
<P>
   and Zeile's fourth-inning throwing error that opened the way for
two unearned runs.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we can just stay close, this offense can do a lot,'' said
dugout coach Bucky Dent, who managed the Rangers in the absence of
Johnny Oates, who attended his son's college graduation.
</P>
<P>
   Greer and Juan Gonzalez served as the Rangers' ninth-inning
catalysts by collecting consecutive singles against Arizona's Bobby
Chouinard (2-1). The Diamondbacks opted to walk Rafael Palmeiro
after a passed ball moved Greer Gonzalez into scoring position.
Zeile then drew a five-pitch walk.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers appeared to have this game wrapped up a half-inning
earlier, but Arizona's Matt Williams delivered a two-out,
run-scoring single against Wetteland (3-3). Williams' four-hop
ground ball evaded shortstop Royce Clayton and rolled into center
field to score Tony Womack with the tying run.
</P>
<P>
   Arizona took an early 2-0 lead after the Rangers were hurt by
their defense, again. Zeile's errant, fourth-inning throw resulted
in two unearned runs against Aaron Sele, who surrendered two hits
and recorded eight strikeouts before stepping to the mound for the
seventh inning.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel bad for Aaron Sele,'' Zeile said. ``He didn't deserve
to give up a couple of those runs.''
</P>
<P>
   Zeile's error gave the Rangers six in the past four games and 13
in their past 10 contests. The Rangers began play yesterday ranked
12th among the American League's 14 teams in fielding percentage.
</P>
<P>
   All appeared well, though, after the offense cranked out a
seven-run fifth inning, sending 11 men to the plate. Consecutive
run-scoring singles by second baseman Mark McLemore and catcher
Ivan Rodriguez tied the score, and a two-run double by left fielder
Rusty Greer produced the Rangers' first lead.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers continued to pound right-hander Armando Reynoso,
whose evening would be complete after surrendering the inning's
fifth hit _ a run-scoring single to Zeile that gave the Rangers a
5-2 lead.
</P>
<P>
   Left-hander Greg Swindell replaced Reynoso and retired first
baseman Lee Stevens for the inning's second out, but center fielder
Ruben Mateo delivered a two-run triple before the former University
of Texas pitcher got out of the inning.
</P>
<P>
   Sele had given up only two hits before Arizona's Steve Finley
deposited Sele's second pitch of the seventh inning into The
Ballpark's upper-deck home run porch in right field, and David
Dellucci and Travis Lee followed with consecutive singles, ending
Sele's night.
</P>
<P>
   Dent summoned Venafro from the bullpen, but the usually reliable
rookie surrendered consecutive run-scoring singles to the
Diamondbacks' Nos. 8 and 9 hitters, Bernard Gilkey and Kelly
Stinnett.
</P>
<P>
   Right-hander Jeff Zimmerman entered the fray with Gilkey and
Stinnett in scoring position after a sacrifice bunt, but the
All-Star reliever could not protect the Rangers' 7-5 lead. Second
baseman Jay Bell produced a sacrifice fly that scored Gilkey, and
designated hitter Luis Gonzalez delivered a two-out single that
scored Stinnett with the tying run.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
