u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EDIT-YUGOSLAVIA-NYT &LR;      07-17 0257
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-YUGOSLAVIA-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: BELGRADE'S  ` CARE ' CAPTIVES  
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial for Saturday, July 17:
</P>
<P>
   This week in Belgrade a panel of military judges heard the
appeal of three employees of the humanitarian group CARE, who in
May were convicted of espionage and given long prison terms _ one
of them 12 years. The appeal provides an opportunity for Slobodan
Milosevic to free these men, and end an apparently baseless
prosecution that opens all humanitarian workers to the threat of
arrest.
</P>
<P>
   Steve Pratt and Peter Wallace, both Australians, and their
Serbian colleague Branko Jelen were charged with running a spy
ring. When he read the verdict, the judge threw that charge out,
but then declared the three guilty of passing secret information to
a foreign government or agency. The defense had not known of the
charge, and the judge provided no details.
</P>
<P>
   The information the workers held, CARE officials maintain, was
the same publicly available data on humanitarian problems collected
by all aid organizations. Ironically, they had been mainly helping
Serbian refugees from Croatia and Bosnia.
</P>
<P>
   Nelson Mandela, Kofi Annan and others have appealed for the CARE
employees' freedom. But Milosevic has so far been unmoved, even
though the arrest has driven CARE away from Serbia when
humanitarian help is most needed. He has also used espionage laws
to arrest Serbian reporters who covered anti-government protests.
He should free the three men.  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
