<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990717.0028 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-17 01:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3707 &Cx1f; tic-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-YUGOFRAUD-AZR &LR;      07-17 1306
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-YUGOFRAUD-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LAWMAKER FOCUS OF INQUIRY; TRIED TO SERVE IN BALKANS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By CHRIS MOESER  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Law-enforcement officials from Kosovo to Kayenta are
investigating an Arionza state lawmaker who apparently conned U.S.
Rep. J.D. Hayworth, R-Ariz., out of a trip to the Balkan conflict
in May by posing as a Naval reservist desperately trying to join
his unit.
</P>
<P>
   State Rep. Tom Gordon, who was working part time for Hayworth,
wasn't even an active Naval reservist at the time, according to
Hayworth's office. But with many of his state House colleagues,
there to see him off in May, Gordon hopped on a National Guard
flight at Phoenix's Sky Harbor International Airport that would
eventually take him to Bosnia-Herzegovina.
</P>
<P>
   Hayworth has fired Gordon. And on Friday, Hayworth announced the
FBI and the Navy are conducting a fraud investigation. Hayworth
called for state lawmakers to conduct an ethics inquiry.
</P>
<P>
   Gordon said late Friday that he would explain everything
eventually, but not until he spent time with his family. He said he
will meet with federal officials as early as Monday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've just come back from serving overseas and basically going
through six months of hell,'' Gordon said. ``Lots of things need to
be explained, and in due course, they will be.
</P>
<P>
   ``The only thing I'm going to do right now is spend time with my
family.''
</P>
<P>
   Gordon was reached on mobile phone and would not elaborate on
where he was other than to say he was back in Arizona.
</P>
<P>
   Ed Hall, an FBI spokesman, confirmed the bureau was in the
initial stages of an investigation, but he provided no other
details.
</P>
<P>
   The bizarre case stunned lawmakers, who described Gordon as a
bright, friendly man.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is so strange, it's a bad B movie, James Bond-style,''
said Rep. Marilyn Jarrett, chairwoman of the House Ethics
Committee.
</P>
<P>
   Hayworth, was unavailable for comment. But in letters to Arizona
House Speaker Jeff Groscost and Jarrett, he expressed outrage at
Gordon's actions.
</P>
<P>
   ``Rep. Gordon lied to me and my staff and has acted in a manner
that I believe is inconsistent with the high ethical standards
people expect of their elected representatives,'' Hayworth said in
a statement.
</P>
<P>
   The mess began in late April, when Gordon, 41, told House
colleagues he had been called up by his Naval Reserve unit for
action in the Balkans. On his House biography, Gordon lists service
in the U.S. Navy from 1984 to 1987 and duty in the Naval Reserves
since 1987.
</P>
<P>
   Several local units reported for duty around May 1.
</P>
<P>
   Many colleagues, including Groscost, believed Gordon was a Navy
SEAL.
</P>
<P>
   Gordon said he was a Naval officer with SEAL Unit 1 primarily
dealing with intelligence, but clarified he was not a SEAL.
</P>
<P>
   Joe Eule, a Hayworth spokesman, said Gordon contacted Hayworth's
office and said he was having trouble joining his unit in Bosnia
and needed help catching a National Guard flight.
</P>
<P>
   Hayworth gave Gordon a congressional travel order, which Eule
said was not unusual. He explained that members of Congress have
the ability to issue such orders, as if they were military
officials.
</P>
<P>
   Eule said the office didn't request to see Gordon's military
orders, adding that there was no reason to suspect anything
unusual. At the time, Gordon was working part time for Hayworth,
providing constituent services in northern Arizona.
</P>
<P>
   According to Eule, Gordon used bogus travel documents ``obtained
under false pretenses'' to go to the Balkans.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had no reason to doubt he wasn't a Naval reservist,'' Eule
said. ``Sure, we believed him.''
</P>
<P>
   As he left Phoenix around May 1, Groscost and other House
colleagues paid tribute to him on the House floor and went to the
airport to see him off. Rep. Wes Marsh put a yellow ribbon on his
desk on the House floor.
</P>
<P>
   What happened next is unclear. Gordon flew to Virginia and then
to Europe, spending time, apparently, in both Germany and Italy
before ultimately arriving in Bosnia. Once he got there, he
apparently approached several units and tried to persuade them to
activate him.
</P>
<P>
   In early to mid-June, an Army official called Hayworth's office
to inquire about Gordon. Eule said it was then that Hayworth
discovered Gordon had never been called into service and a search
began for Gordon.
</P>
<P>
   The official told Hayworth that Gordon was involved in
``unauthorized and disruptive activities in the region.''
</P>
<P>
   Numerous efforts to contact Gordon in Europe failed, Eule said.
When he left, Gordon was placed on furlough, which means he wasn't
being paid by Congress. He was fired June 22.
</P>
<P>
   The military couldn't locate him until last week, when he was
detained at a base in Sarajevo.
</P>
<P>
   It's unclear what Gordon was doing from the time he arrived
until last week, Eule said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a tragic situation, and it's extremely bizarre,'' Eule
said. ``He took advantage of a lot of us.''
</P>
<P>
   Gordon's colleagues at the state House were floored by the
allegations. He was encouraged by Groscost to run in the heavily
Democratic district, winning a seat when Democrats failed to
qualify a candidate for the ballot. The district covers much of
northeastern Arizona, including the Navajo Nation.
</P>
<P>
   House members considered Gordon an intelligent colleague with a
bright political future, a belief backed up by credentials he lists
on his resume.
</P>
<P>
   Brigham Young University officials confirmed that Gordon
graduated with a degree in political science in 1982. He also lists
a graduate degree from Harvard in 1992.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Steve Huffman, a fellow freshman who sat next to Gordon,
said he never doubted his military background. Huffman is a Naval
reservist and said the two talked often about his impending
deployment.
</P>
<P>
   ``He told me he had his orders, that he had been in contact with
his unit and that he was trying to delay it so he could finish the
legislative session,'' Huffman said.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Ken Cheuvront, who also sat near Gordon on the floor, said
Gordon had talked about being stationed in Beirut and in Berlin
before the Berlin Wall came down in 1989. Many members thought he
was doing intelligence work.
</P>
<P>
   ``All of us assumed he was working for the CIA or the FBI,''
Cheuvront said. ``None of us questioned anything because of his
military background. He was a very bright guy.''
</P>
<P>
   Gordon is fluent in several languages, including Navajo. He
worked for Sen. John McCain's Washington office, handling Native
American issues from March 1997 until January of 1998. But Nancy
Ives, a McCain spokeswoman, said Gordon was ``let go,'' adding she
didn't know the circumstances.
</P>
<P>
   Gordon said that he returned to Arizona ``for personal
reasons,'' and that he didn't like living in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   Cheuvront added that he believed Gordon was having marital
problems. He missed a lot of votes toward the end of the session,
Cheuvront said, and told colleagues he had to be at home to take
care of eight children.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Sylvia Laughter has known Gordon since the two were
students at BYU together. She said Gordon's wife contacted her,
saying she was concerned that she had not heard from Gordon for six
weeks. Some of his belongings had been mailed home.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tom contacted her,'' Laughter said. ``From what she had heard,
he had been kidnapped or caught by the Serbs, detained and
beaten.''
</P>
<P>
   Camille Gordon could not be reached for comment. Laughter said
she was baffled by the charges.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't have any reason to believe what he shared with us
isn't true,'' she said. ``I'm not even going to question it until I
hear it from him.''
</P>
<P>
   Groscost was traveling and could not be reached for comment. His
spokesman, Paul Senseman, called the allegations serious.
</P>
<P>
   ``We would look for Mr. Gordon's resignation if they are in fact
true,'' he said. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
