<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOX-REID-KELLY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REID'S TALENT IS ENOUGH TO RETAIN WBA TITLE
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Colo, Pa.)   (rk) 
 By TIMOTHY W. SMITH   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTIC CITY, N.J. _ It looked like an ominous sign when Kevin
Kelly entered the ring Friday night and the Australian flag one of
his cornermen was carrying was mounted on the pole upside down, an
international signal for distress. Kelly was an unknown quantity
going against David Reid, a well-trained Olympic gold medalist who
had won a world championship in just 12 professional fights.
</P>
<P>
   But as the match wore on at the Boardwalk Convention Center
ballroom, it was Reid who looked as if he was in the fight of his
life against Kelly, a longshoreman and former rugby player from New
South Wales, Australia, who moonlights as a boxer.
</P>
<P>
   In the end the prodigy prevailed, as Reid (13-0) scored a
unanimous decision over Kelly (25-5-3) before a crowd of 1,967 and
kept his WBA super welterweight title. Judges John Stewart and
Vargas Marcial both scored it 116-111 and Henk Meijers scored it
115-112, all for Reid.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was very game in the ring,'' Reid said. ``He was very
tricky. He took a lot of good shots. But I had the tools to win. I
thought it was close, but I thought I won.''
</P>
<P>
   Reid's victory came on the strength of sheer talent. And if
Fernando Vargas, Reid's Olympic teammate and 154-pound nemesis, was
watching Friday night, he liked what he saw, because Reid was very
hittable. Kelly did not have enough of an arsenal to take Reid out;
Vargas does.
</P>
<P>
   ``He never hit me,'' Kelly said. ``My strategy was to give him
lots of angles. It was close, but I thought I won the fight.''
</P>
<P>
   This was Reid's first defense of his title, which he won with a
12-round decision against Laurent Boudouani on March 6. Between
fights, Reid had more surgery on his drooping left eyelid, moved
his training camp from Philadelphia to Denver and signed a new
contract with HBO.
</P>
<P>
   HBO did not deem his title defense against Kelly, the WBA's No.
1 contender, worthy of broadcast, however. The bout was shown on
the FX cable network, which has an agreement with Reid's promoter,
America Presents.
</P>
<P>
   Kelly, 29, had vowed to put on a performance that would make HBO
executives eat their Nielsen ratings sheets. It was a tall order
for a boxer who did not turn pro until he was 22 and spent the
first couple of years of his career learning how to box. But he did
not embarrass himself.
</P>
<P>
   Kelly spent much of the first three rounds fighting while
backing up. He did not seem inclined to test Reid's speed or power.
When the 25-year-old Reid managed to catch Kelly, he stunned him
with some sharp punches under the chin. But Reid seemed reluctant
to put together combinations or work off his jab _ the things that
his trainer, Al Mitchell, has been preaching to him since he was an
amateur fighting for Olympic gold.
</P>
<P>
   As the fight went on, Kelly's confidence grew. In the fourth
round, he grabbed Reid's attention with a blistering
right-left-right combination. In the fifth round, Kelly dropped
Reid to the canvas with a looping left that caught Reid on the
chin. Reid sprang up immediately and did not appear to be hurt.
</P>
<P>
   In the next round Reid picked up the pace. But by the seventh
round his drooping left eyelid was completely closed, and it
appeared that he had just a sliver of vision from it.
</P>
<P>
   Kelly was trying to become the second aborigine world champion
from Australia. The first was bantamweight Lionel Rose in 1968. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-17-99 0204EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
