<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990717.0042 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-17 02:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3745 &Cx1f; tth-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBA-MARINERS-SPI &LR;      07-17 0839
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-MARINERS-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MARINERS MISPLACE BATS IN MOVE TO SAFECO 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By TYLER KEPNER  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ It's not Safeco Field's fault. The Mariners offense, a
well-oiled machine for so many years, was sputtering in the
breakdown lane before moving to its new home.
</P>
<P>
   But the early _ OK, (begin ital) very (end ital) early _ returns
are in on the ballpark, and it's just what so many people thought
it would be. There have been no home runs so far, but Mariner
pitchers have allowed only five runs in the first two games here.
The problem is, the offense has scored only three.
</P>
<P>
   Friday night's result was a 2-1 loss to the San Diego Padres and
Sterling Hitchcock. The loss was the seventh in a row for the
Mariners, who remain in last place. The rest of the American League
West won Friday, and Seattle fell to eight games out of first.
</P>
<P>
   The Mariners offense continued to struggle. The M's have scored
seven runs in their last five games, and have not exceeded three
runs since last Monday.
</P>
<P>
   ``It seems like we go through these three or four times every
year,'' said third baseman Russ Davis. ``You knock on wood and hope
things pan out. I know they will. I can't see it lasting a long
period of time. It happens to the best of teams. This is a great
ball team and everybody knows it.''
</P>
<P>
   Especially Hitchcock, who played for the M's in 1996 before
being traded to the Padres for long-gone right-hander Scott
Sanders. Hitchcock worked seven shutout innings, outdueling Jeff
Fassero for his first win ever against Seattle.
</P>
<P>
   ``It doesn't matter who it's against,'' Hitchcock said. ``It's
not like I felt jerked around or felt I was treated unfairly when I
was here. I've got friends in that clubhouse.''
</P>
<P>
   Those friends were not happy Friday, although Fassero was
encouraged about Safeco Field.
</P>
<P>
   ``It doesn't seem like the ball's going to carry that well,'' he
said. ``... It's a lot easier to pitch here. You get to challenge
guys on 2-0, 2-1, throw it to the outer half of the plate and not
have them hitting it to the short right-field fence. It's nice.''
</P>
<P>
   Fassero pointed to an at-bat against Quilvio Veras. He fell
behind, 2-0, and Veras took an outside fastball to the right-field
warning track for a fly out.
</P>
<P>
   ``Over in that park,'' Fassero said, referring to the Kingdome,
``it's a home run.''
</P>
<P>
   There were two major differences between Fassero and Hitchcock
Friday night. One was control. The other was center fielder Ruben
Rivera _ who, alas, plays for Hitchcock's team.
</P>
<P>
   Fassero walked six Padres, while Hitchcock walked no Mariners.
Rivera went 2-for-3 and snuffed a Mariners rally with a sprinting
catch.
</P>
<P>
   Hitchcock issued four singles _ just two leaving the infield _
and doubles to Alex Rodriguez and Davis. Davis' came with two outs
in the seventh, and was followed by a Dan Wilson blast to right
center.
</P>
<P>
   Rivera sprinted after it and grabbed it on the run, ending the
inning. His night over, Hitchcock waited for Rivera to come in from
center, congratulating him before taking a seat.
</P>
<P>
   ``I looked for the ball to fall in behind him. When it didn't, I
just went, `Wow,''' Hitchcock said. ``He's been doing that all
year.''
</P>
<P>
   Friday night was the fifth time in his last seven outings that
Hitchcock has lasted seven, and the difference has been control.
After walking 16 over a three-start stretch, Hitchcock has walked
just 10 in his last seven starts _ and none Friday.
</P>
<P>
   ``Take away a few early starts, he probably would have gone to
Boston (for the All-Star Game), too,'' said Padres manager Bruce
Bochy.
</P>
<P>
   Donne Wall came in for the eighth, and the M's seemed to welcome
the change. David Bell ripped a single up the middle, and David
Segui rifled a ball to first. It caromed off first baseman Wally
Joyner and right to second baseman Veras, who flipped to second for
the force.
</P>
<P>
   Ken Griffey Jr. followed with a smash down the first-base line,
but it hit the bag, going for a single and holding Segui at second.
After a fly out by Rodriguez, Edgar Martinez singled to bring in
Segui, cut the Padres' lead to 2-1 _ and bring in closer Trevor
Hoffman.
</P>
<P>
   Hoffman struck out Jay Buhner to end the inning, and earned his
22nd save the next inning.
</P>
<P>
   Fassero (4-10) walked six batters, matching a season high, and
by the time he left the game had thrown more pitches _ 134 _ than
any M's starter this year. Fassero was fresh, having thrown only 73
pitches in a three-inning start last Sunday in Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll be happy to go out the rest of the season and have more
starts like I did tonight,'' Fassero said. ``You win more than you
lose this way.''
</P>
<P>
   But the offense has to come around.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jeff pitched a great game,'' Davis said. ``I wish we could
have given him a win. I'm sure Jeff's happy with his performance,
and he should be. ...
</P>
<P>
   ``We're getting good pitching and not good hitting, or good
hitting and not good pitching. We need to be more consistent.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
