 AM-NYT-BUDGET  
(th) 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; FOR SUNDAY AMs &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Here are today's top news stories from The New York Times News
Service for AMs of Sunday, July 18:
</P>
<P>
   &UR; INTERNATIONAL &LR;  (Moving in ``i'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-DEATH-TOLL (Pristina, Yugoslavia) _ At least 10,000
people were slaughtered by Serbian forces during their three-month
campaign to drive the Albanians from Kosovo, according to war
crimes investigators, NATO peacekeeping troops and humanitarian
agencies struggling to keep up with fresh reports each day of newly
discovered bodies and graves. By John Kifner. (With map.)
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA-CHURCH-SCHISM (Yekaterinburg, Russia) _ Set on the Ural
mountain divide between Europe and Asia, this city has long been at
the crossroads of Russian history. Russia's last czar was executed
in Yekaterinburg. President Boris Yeltsin began his political
career here as a Communist Party boss. And the local military still
boasts of its cold war role in shooting down Gary Powers' U-2 spy
plane. But Yekaterinburg is best known these days for the protest
that has rocked the nation's most trusted institution: the Russian
Orthodox Church. By Michael R. Gordon. (With photo, map.)
</P>
<P>
   ISRAEL-SYRIA-ASSESS (Washington) _ Three years after being
pushed to the back burner of Middle East peace negotiations, Syria
is back in the picture. By Jane Perlez.
</P>
<P>
   IRAN-STUDENTS (Tehran, Iran) _ Student leaders on Saturday
announced a temporary ban on pro-reform demonstrations, but pressed
the Islamic government on a long list of demands, including the
resignation of the country's chief of police. By Elaine Sciolino.
</P>
<P>
   INDIA-TV-WAR (Mokhra, India) _ India has fought three larger
wars with Pakistan, in 1947, 1965 and 1971, but the last two months
of fighting in the Himalayan land of Kashmir that lies between them
has produced India's first televised war. In 1971, fewer than 1 in
200 of India's households had TV's. Now, it's more than 1 in 3. By
Celia W. Dugger. (With photo, graphic.)
</P>
<P>
   COLOMBIA-CRISIS (Bogota, Colombia) _ On Monday, the government
of President Andres Pastrana and the Revolutionary Armed Forces of
Colombia, the Marxist guerrilla group known to Colombians as FARC,
are scheduled to begin formal peace negotiations aimed at ending 35
years of civil conflict. But a rapidly deteriorating political and
economic situation has weakened Pastrana's hand going into the
talks, undermining prospects for peace and emboldening the rebels.
By Larry Rohter.
</P>
<P>
   SAFRICA-TORTURER (Pretoria, South Africa) _ In his drab denim
shirts and army-style green sweaters, Eugene de Kock answers
questions for hours, rarely showing any signs of emotion. His face
is lineless, his eyes small behind thick glasses that make him look
more like the class nerd than South Africa's most notorious
apartheid-era henchman. De Kock's amnesty application, listing his
misdeeds, is more than 4,000 pages long. By Suzanne Daley.
</P>
<P>
   URUGUAY-LEFTIST (Reboledo, Uruguay) _ From Monday through
Wednesday, Tabare Vazquez fights cancer as one of Uruguay's leading
oncologists. From Thursday through Saturday, he runs for president
_ and along the campaign trail he wags his finger at smokers urging
them to ``lay off the poison.'' By Clifford Krauss. (With map.)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL &LR;  (Moving in ``a'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   KENNEDY-MISSING-PLANE (New York) _ A small plane carrying John
F. Kennedy Jr. to a wedding on Martha's Vineyard was reported
missing early Saturday, and a search was under way off the coast of
New York's Long Island, officials said. The plane took off at 8:45
p.m. Friday and was believed to be carrying Kennedy, his wife
Carolyn Bessette, and her sister, who were heading to the Cape
Cod-Martha's Vineyard area where the Kennedy family was gathering
for a wedding, a source told The Associated Press.
</P>
<P>
   (EDS: For first edition, we are planning one main story. Among
the sidebars that are being considered is one out of Washington on
the FAA angle. Obituaries are also being prepared, should that
become necessary.)
</P>
<P>
   _____
</P>
<P>
   APOLLO-REFLECTIONS _ Over dinner a few weeks ago, a former
astronaut who walked on the Moon and one of the Apollo flight
directors got to skylarking about the good old days, something
people do when they think of their past receding and a big
anniversary approaching, in this case the 30th anniversary of the
Apollo 11 lunar landing on July 20, 1969. But without prompting,
they wondered in sadness and perplexity what had happened to the
good old days. Such were the bittersweet thoughts among some of
those of the Apollo generation as they began celebrating the time
when human beings first (and last) set foot on another world. By
John Noble Wilford.
</P>
<P>
   NAVAJO-MINE-DISPUTE _ John W. Fritz, an Interior Department
official during the Reagan administration, has long wondered why
his decision to increase the coal mining fees paid to the Navajo
Indians by hundreds of millions of dollars was blocked. He may now
have his answer. By Barry Meier. (With photo.)
</P>
<P>
   NY-SUMMER-SCHOOL (New York) _ Outside, summer beckons, with
bikes to be ridden, video games to be played, cartoons to be
watched, Barbies to be pampered for hours on end. But the third
graders in a Brooklyn classroom must set those pleasures aside for
now, ignore the teasing afternoon breeze wafting through the
windows and focus on the task at hand: to draw a picture from one
of three stories they have studied today and write a few sentences
about why they liked it. By Randal C. Archibold. (With photo.)
</P>
<P>
   ALA-MAYOR-RETIRE (Birmingham, Ala.) _ For the last 20 years,
each time he walked into the City Hall he transformed, Mayor
Richard Arrington Jr. has passed by the name T. Eugene Connor
carved into the building's cornerstone. But the sense of distance
between the snarling dogs of Bull Connor, the former police
commissioner who became the symbol of intolerance in the days of
the civil rights movement, and the placid, prosperous Birmingham of
today is due in significant part to two decades of quiet work by
Arrington, who will retire on Monday at age 64. By David Firestone.
</P>
<P>
   COLO-DNC-FUNDRAISER (Aspen, Colo.) _ Some Aspenites are upset
that the town government is absorbing the costs of a major
Democratic Party event next weekend that will include a visit by
President Clinton and his wife, Hillary Rodham Clinton. While
presidential trips are fairly routine in their security
requirements and the demands they place on the local venue,
Aspenites assert that someone else _ the Secret Service, the White
House, the Democratic Party _ should pay for what is essentially a
political event. By Michael Janofsky.
</P>
<P>
   IRS-TAXPRO-WORRIES _ The IRS, operating under a new law and led
by a commissioner who calls taxpayers ``customers,'' radically cut
back on its traditional collection techniques: garnishing wages,
tapping bank accounts, placing liens on property so the government
gets paid first when the property is sold, and seizing businesses
and homes. Tax professionals say they are worried about lax
enforcement. By David Cay Johnston.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WASHINGTON &LR;  (Moving in ``w'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   HEALTH-HOUSE-REBELS (Washington) _ A group of rebellious House
Republicans, in defiance of their leaders, are trying to pass much
tougher regulation of managed-care plans than the Senate adopted
last week and say they can win if they can force a vote. By Adam
Clymer.
</P>
<P>
   POWER-OUTAGE-INQUIRY (Washington) _ Energy Secretary Bill
Richardson will propose six steps to reduce electricity disruptions
in severe weather in a speech on Monday, including federal
investigations of power blackouts like the ones that plagued New
York and other cities this month, department officials say. By
Matthew L. Wald.
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-REPUBS-TAXES (Washington) _ Stepping up his attack on
Republican tax-cutting proposals, President Clinton said Saturday
that the cost of the tax bill moving through the House would rise
to ``unimaginable'' levels and threaten the nation's ability to
deal with its most pressing long-term problems. By Richard W.
Stevenson.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; COLUMNS &LR;  (Moving in ``k'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   HERBERT-COLUMN _ On wrongfully imprisoned people. By Bob
Herbert.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MOVING LATER:  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   AM-FRONTPAGE-NYT _ A description of the front page layout of the
first edition of The New York Times will move by noon ET.
</P>
