<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-17 11:08 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3775 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-APOLLO-REFLECTIONS-55     07-17 0595
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-APOLLO-REFLECTIONS-550(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPACE EXPLORERS REFLECT ON MOONWALKING NOSTALGIA 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By JOHN NOBLE WILFORD    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Over dinner a few weeks ago, a former astronaut who walked on
the moon and one of the Apollo flight directors got to skylarking
about the good old days, something people do when they think of
their past receding and a big anniversary approaching, in this case
the 30th anniversary of the Apollo 11 lunar landing on July 20,
1969.
</P>
<P>
   They laughed almost to tears telling cherished stories, one
trying to top the other, about the time men flew to the moon.
</P>
<P>
   Then a cloud seemed to pass over their faces. Without prompting,
they wondered in sadness and perplexity what had happened to the
good old days.
</P>
<P>
   Where were the astronauts on Mars? The permanent lunar bases or
the giant space stations wheeling through orbit? This was the
future that should have arrived by now, as prophesied in the heady
atmosphere of the Apollo 11 triumph. Both men _ the astronaut
Charles ``Pete'' Conrad Jr., who was soon to die after a motorcycle
accident on July 8, and the flight director Gerald Griffin _
worried that the United States had lost the old can-do spirit and
the will to carry out ambitious, expensive space endeavors.
</P>
<P>
   Such were the bittersweet thoughts among some of those of the
Apollo generation as they began celebrating the time when human
beings first (and last) set foot on another world. On Friday, the
anniversary of the day they rocketed off to the moon, the first
moonwalkers, Neil A. Armstrong, now 68 years old, and Buzz Aldrin,
69, visited the Kennedy Space Center in Florida for a reunion with
many who had worked on their mission. Michael Collins, 69, who had
piloted the Apollo command module in lunar orbit while the other
two astronauts landed on the moon, was invited but did not attend.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, they had some post-Apollo regrets. ``I guess all of us
would like to see more things going on in terms of space
exploration,'' Armstrong told reporters.
</P>
<P>
   He paused and grinned. ``The regret on our side is, they used to
say years ago, we are reading about you in science class,''
Armstrong said. ``Now they say, we are reading about you in history
class.''
</P>
<P>
   NASA officials, scientists and others involved in current space
projects have mixed feelings about such celebrations that dwell on
the past.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we spend so much time celebrating history, trying to
replicate history, we may never get a chance to make new history,''
Daniel S. Goldin, the head of the National Aeronautics and Space
Administration, said in an interview last week.
</P>
<P>
   The concern is that Apollo, though worthy of tribute, should not
be held up as a model for planning space exploration for the long
haul. The project was not really about science or space
exploration, but the Cold War confrontation between the United
States and the Soviet Union. It was a crash program and too
expensive to be sustained once the immediate goal was achieved.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Apollo program is not replicable,'' Dr. John M. Logsdon,
director of the Space Policy Institute at George Washington
University, wrote in the current issue of Space News, a trade
weekly. ``It was a product of a specific time in history, as the
Soviet Union and the United States were using space firsts as a
surrogate battlefield for their global geopolitical competition. It
was definitely not part of a societal commitment to space
exploration and development.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   As Logsdon recalled, in April 1961 President John F. Kennedy had
asked his advisers to identify a ``space program which promises
dramatic results in which we could win.'' The answer was a race to
send men to the moon before the end of the 1960s.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is hard to conceive a similar question, 30 years later, for
which the answer is to send people to Mars _ or any other
Apollo-like space undertaking,'' Logsdon concluded.
</P>
<P>
   So many other things have changed between the time of Apollo 11
and now. Americans seem to have lost their taste for grand
adventures if they require longterm commitments of money and
expanded government power.
</P>
<P>
   With the end of the Cold War, the Russians have gone from being
adversaries, whose early space triumphs provoked the moon race, to
allies. Indeed, they are partners in a $100-billion international
project to assemble and operate an Earth-orbiting space station,
though the financially strapped Russians often have troubles paying
their bills and meeting schedules. Other partners are the
Europeans, Japan and Canada. Major programs of human space flight
are becoming unaffordable, except through multinational
collaborations.
</P>
<P>
   Goldin conceded that Russian participation has added what he
called a ``Perils of Pauline'' element to the space station
project, now scheduled to be completely assembled in orbit in 2004.
The NASA administrator said he would be meeting with Russian space
officials this week to assess the implications of a recent Proton
rocket failure on Russia's ability to launch the Russian service
module for the space station on Nov. 12. Under current plans, no
further U.S. space shuttle missions can be launched to the station
until the Russian service module is in place.
</P>
<P>
   Even when the much-delayed station is operating with
international crews, human flight will still be confined to
circling Earth. No one has flown to the moon since December 1972,
or is likely to for years to come. On the 20th anniversary of
Apollo 11, in 1989, President George Bush called for a national
commitment to return astronauts to the moon and send them to Mars
by 2019, the 50th anniversary. His Space Exploration Initiative has
come to nothing fast.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, the Clinton administration issued a space policy
declaration giving highest priority to the space station and
restricting NASA from beginning any preliminary work on human
flights to the moon or Mars until after the station is in full
operation.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Alex Roland, a historian of technology at Duke University,
said that human space flight was still in its ``barnstorming
period,'' comparable to aviation before the 1930s. The development
of larger, sturdier airframes ushered in commercial passenger
flight. And military strategists began to conceive of the airplane
as an effective weapon of war. Human space flight, he said, has yet
to find an indispensable place for itself.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview, Roland suggested three changes that could bring
that about, none of which is likely to occur in the immediate
future. One would be a large-scale commercial exploitation of
space, like huge solar-power arrays that require people to maintain
them, similar to workers on offshore oil rigs. Fossil fuels would
have to be running low before that becomes likely, he said. Other
possibilities would be finding some military use _ farfetched at
the moment _ or developing much less expensive launching systems,
which could open up opportunities for commercial, scientific or
even tourist flights.
</P>
<P>
   Goldin agreed that launching rocketry is stalled with 1960s
technology _ ``middle age has set in'' _ and is a crucial area in
need of investments in new ideas and research. Logsdon said a
number of launch failures in the last year put renewed pressure on
NASA and the Defense Department to look at new investments in
rocketry.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the brightest stars in the post-Apollo space program
have been robotic spacecraft. They have scouted out all the planets
except for Pluto, rendezvoused with comets and asteroids and probed
the far horizons of the cosmos. They have landed and looked for
life on Mars, and will do so again several times over the next
decade. One is orbiting Jupiter and its large moons right now, and
another is on its way to orbit distant Saturn. The moon has been
revisited twice in this decade by modest spacecraft, which may have
found evidence of water ice at the lunar poles. At the end of this
month, after 18 months of circling the moon, Lunar Prospector is to
be crashed into the lunar surface to look for more definitive
evidence.
</P>
<P>
   Early Tuesday morning, the anniversary of the Apollo 11 Moon
walk, a space shuttle is scheduled to lift off on a mission to
deliver the Chandra X-ray Observatory to orbit, opening one more
window on the universe that had been closed before telescopes could
be placed above Earth's atmosphere.
</P>
<P>
   One more important difference from the Apollo days: the shuttle
Columbia will be commanded by Col. Eileen Collins of the Air Force,
the first woman to lead a shuttle mission.
</P>
<P>
   As the celebrations began, Neil Armstrong was asked what he
thought the lasting legacy of Apollo would be. It was, he said, ``a
demonstration that man was not chained to this planet.''
</P>
<P>
   At the time of Apollo, the historian Arthur Schlesinger Jr.
predicted that in 500 years, the 20th century would probably be
remembered in history mainly for its pioneering space flights,
humanity's first venture beyond its native planet. He repeated this
assessment recently at a retrospective symposium on the vibrant,
tempestuous 1960s.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-17-99 1108EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990717.0061 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-17 11:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3777 &Cx1f; var-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EMBASSY-CLOSINGS-REVI     07-17 0912
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EMBASSY-CLOSINGS-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A YEAR AFTER BOMBINGS, A CASE OF DIPLO-JITTERS 
</HEADLINE>
  (The Week in Review) 
(NOTE TO INTERNATIONAL CLIENTS: For use by special arrangement
only. Asian and European points: Call Karl Horwitz in Paris for
details and prices, phone: 47 42 17 11; fax: 47-42-80-44). Latin
American points: Call Olivia Vasquez in Los Angeles, phone:
310-996-0075; fax: 310-996-0089). 
(jt) 
 By PHILIP SHENON    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The U.S. Embassy in Madagascar, a coffee-growing
island nation hundreds of miles off the east coast of Africa, might
not seem a likely target for terrorists from the faraway Middle
East.
</P>
<P>
   But the State Department and the Central Intelligence Agency are
worried that followers of Osama bin Laden, the Saudi-born terrorist
suspect, have had the U.S. compound under surveillance in
preparation for an attack this summer. As a result, the embassy has
been shuttered for most of the last month.
</P>
<P>
   The closing of U.S. embassies, those flag-flying symbols of U.S.
power and influence, was once about as common as a snowstorm on the
palm-shaded beaches of Madagascar.
</P>
<P>
   But in the year since terrorist bombs destroyed U.S. embassies
in Kenya and Tanzania and killed 224 people, 67 U.S. embassies and
consulates have been closed for some period of time for security
reasons. In June alone, six U.S. embassies in Africa were shut down
because of terrorist threats.
</P>
<P>
   The State Department has no comparable figure for the prior
12-month period. But it says the number of closings in the year
since the August explosions in East Africa, which the United States
has blamed on bin Laden, dwarfs that for the previous year.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think some of the swagger around here has disappeared,''
said a senior department official who has served at large embassies
in Europe and Asia. ``Once you treated the threat of terrorism as
the price of being a diplomat. You didn't demand resources for
embassy security. Now you do.''
</P>
<P>
   The embassy closings reflect both a heightened awareness of
security _ diplomats say they are much more likely to report
suspicious people loitering near an embassy _ and intelligence
reports suggesting that bin Laden's followers are about to strike
again.
</P>
<P>
   State Department officials say the bombings in East Africa left
some U.S. ambassadors frantic about the vulnerability of their
embassies, and a number have flooded the department with requests
for better security or new buildings.
</P>
<P>
   Many U.S. diplomats were startled to learn after the embassy
bombing in Nairobi, Kenya, that the U.S. ambassador there, Prudence
Bushnell, had been pleading to the State Department for months for
money to build a safer compound; her requests had been turned down
for lack of money.
</P>
<P>
   A recent survey by the department found that 80 percent of U.S.
embassies and other diplomatic offices did not meet security
standards set in the 1980s requiring that the buildings be at least
100 feet away from the street to protect against car bombs.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wouldn't say that panic is the word, but there's a
tremendous amount of concern,'' said another senior department
official. ``We know these 2,000-pound truck bombs are a new,
ominous threat.''
</P>
<P>
   Some diplomats, angered by bureaucratic delay in Washington,
have sought help from private security companies in the aftermath
of the Africa bombings. Bechtel, the giant San Francisco-based
construction company, says it has spoken with diplomats in Croatia
about improving security at the highly exposed U.S. embassy in
Zagreb, the capital.
</P>
<P>
   Terrorism is also taken seriously at the State Department's
headquarters in Washington, which has recently been ringed with
concrete barricades like those that surround the White House. The
department is considering closing the airy, glass-enclosed main
entrance, fearing it may present a tempting target.
</P>
<P>
   In seeking to improve embassy security, the department's biggest
problem is, as always, money.
</P>
<P>
   The department received an emergency $1.4 billion from Congress
last fall to beef up embassy security, and the money has been used
for enhancements like alarms, closed-circuit television systems and
metal detectors, as well as for an extra 4,000 local guards to work
along the perimeter of embassy compounds.
</P>
<P>
   But virtually every security consultant who has studied the
problem for the government agrees that U.S. diplomats will remain
in danger until scores of old, vulnerable embassies are replaced
with new buildings, a project that will cost billions of dollars.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are many embassy buildings that can't be secured,'' said
Jane C. Loeffler, author of ``The Architecture of Diplomacy''
(Princeton Architectural Press, 1998). ``Some are right on the
sidewalk. They have no setback, they're old, their walls aren't
strong enough.''
</P>
<P>
   This year, a State Department panel recommended a $14 billion
budget to improve embassy security over the next decade. But
Congress and the Office of Management and Budget have resisted a
commitment to anything approaching that amount because of budget
caps that the Clinton administration and Capitol Hill have vowed to
enforce.
</P>
<P>
   State Department officials acknowledge that it will be years
before some of its most vulnerable diplomatic buildings are
replaced. Until then, Americans traveling abroad seeking help from
the local U.S. embassy had better get used to seeing a sign hanging
from a locked front gate: ``Closed.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-17-99 1111EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990717.0062 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-17 11:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5627 &Cx1f; var-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EMBASSY-CLOSINGS-REVI     07-17 0912
