<HEADER>
A3780 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-SUMMER-SCHOOL-ART-     07-17 0802
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-SUMMER-SCHOOL-ART-800(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN SEASON TO PLAY, DAUNTING STRUGGLE TO LEARN 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Nonsubscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(jt) 
 By RANDAL C. ARCHIBOLD    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Outside, summer beckons, with bikes to be ridden,
video games to be played, cartoons to be watched, Barbies to be
pampered for hours on end.
</P>
<P>
   But the third-graders in a Brooklyn classroom must set those
pleasures aside for now, ignore the teasing afternoon breeze
wafting through the windows and focus on the task at hand: to draw
a picture from one of three stories they have studied today and
write a few sentences about why they liked it.
</P>
<P>
   Their teacher, Shawn Hunt, is not pleased with the results. Some
have scribbled a few words. Thomas Johnson has written a fragment
of a sentence, without a period or comma in sight.
</P>
<P>
   ``Do you know what a sentence is?'' Mrs. Hunt asks, a note of
dismay in her voice. ``That's a part of a sentence.''
</P>
<P>
   Thomas stares down at his paper in frustration, the same
feeling, he later says, that washed over him in April as he
struggled through the citywide English exam _ the beast that landed
him here, in mandatory summer school at Public School 41 in
Brooklyn.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Hunt senses dejection, and calm returns to her voice as she
once again realizes how far behind these children really are _ how
far they have to go to pass the test that is their ticket to the
fourth grade.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is nothing wrong with you not knowing what a sentence
is,'' she says. ``I'm going to help you understand what a sentence
is.''
</P>
<P>
   After all, she says, driving the point home, ``you guys know
writing is part of the test, and when they ask you to write a
letter or a response on it, you can't just write one sentence.''
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Hunt and her 8- and 9-year-old students have just completed
the first two weeks of mandatory summer school, the keystone of
Schools Chancellor Rudy Crew's program to end the practice of
sending students on to the next grade whether or not they are
ready.
</P>
<P>
   This year, in the most ambitious and structured mandatory
program since the 1980s, 58,000 third-, sixth- and eighth-graders
are back in class for extra reading and writing, and to a lesser
extent mathematics, to prepare them for the promotion test in early
August.
</P>
<P>
   Mandatory summer school is expected to grow much larger next
year. Crew has proposed ending social promotion in grades 3 through
12, setting benchmarks on standardized tests, class work and
attendance that students must meet during the year if they want to
avoid summer school.
</P>
<P>
   The mandatory programs this year vary among the 32 community
school districts, but cannot exceed 10 students per class, and most
run five or six weeks.
</P>
<P>
   And so it is that at 9 every morning, Mrs. Hunt escorts her
seven students from the cafeteria, where some get free breakfasts,
to Room 224. The summer program, which began on July 1 and ends on
Aug. 5, offers a five-and-a-half-hour day to students drawn from
several nearby schools in this district of working-class and poor
families in housing projects and row houses.
</P>
<P>
   She reads to them in a loud, slow voice, and they read too,
haltingly and stiffly, deciphering vocabulary words like
``polish,'' ``scissors'' and ``ornaments.'' Then they often write
their impressions, since expository writing is a major part of both
the test they must pass next month and the statewide reading and
writing test they will face in fourth grade.
</P>
<P>
   She sings a ``good morning to you'' song, usually at Jose's
request. She scolds them for rudeness, for kicking one another
under their desks and for speaking out of turn.
</P>
<P>
   But she also seizes any opportunity to lift their spirits,
pointing out that she is from Brownsville too, went to public
schools here and made it to Howard University. (Mrs. Hunt, 30, has
taught fourth grade for seven years in Brooklyn, where her mother
teaches in the first grade.)
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't want you to think you can't go to college,'' she tells
them one afternoon after reading a story that deals in part with
gifts of money for education. ``You can do it.''
</P>
<P>
   Now and then, she asks about their lives and dreams, finding a
way to relate them to the work at hand.
</P>
<P>
   What do you want to be when you grow up? she asked the other
morning. ``An astronaut!'' Thomas replied. ``An artist!'' said
Ozlen Adams. ``A wrestler!'' said Tommy Carmona.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now, Tommy,'' Mrs. Hunt said, ``you said you wanted to be
wrestler, and that's OK. But I want you to know you are going to
have to be able to read a contract if you do that, and that's what
you are here for.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Hunt has not yet received their individual records, and so
is not exactly sure how far behind each child is; any student who
scored below the 15th percentile on the citywide exam last spring
was ordered to summer school. Based on their reading and class work
so far, she figures they are about a year behind.
</P>
<P>
   She is following a tightly structured lesson plan developed by
District 23, where this school sits and where summer school is of
particular importance. The district is ranked 25th out of 32 in the
city and contends with some of New York's highest poverty and
lowest literacy rates.
</P>
<P>
   The lesson plan, based in part on guidelines from the
chancellor, is closely linked to the city's reading and math tests.
It dictates which books to read _ an assortment of multicultural
works intended to make reading more interesting for these students,
who are mostly black or Hispanic _ and when to read them and even
what is written on the chalkboard. Mrs. Hunt learned the other day
that she must add ``mandatory'' to ``summer school, Class 3-224''
to remind students of the importance of being there.
</P>
<P>
   The children study these things during the year, of course, but
seldom in such a concentrated and focused way. Mrs. Hunt has to
pack a lot in, and she constantly watches the clock. There is no
scheduled recess. Mrs. Hunt has injected some fun into the lessons
by having the students do arts and crafts related to the stories
they have read; their colorful posters hang from the overhead
lights and enliven the drab room, with its pale aqua walls and
scuffed linoleum.
</P>
<P>
   Another important difference is the size of the class. Mrs. Hunt
has seven pupils now but may get closer to the maximum of 10 as the
district continues to track down parents who have not registered
children ordered to school. During the year, the average elementary
school class has 24 students, and Mrs. Hunt wonders how many of
these seven would be here if they had received the close attention
she can give them in summer school.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes, some just get lost and fall behind in a big
group,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Not that summer school has been free of problems. At first, Mrs.
Hunt had to bring in her own reading books because supplies had not
yet arrived; it was only last Monday that she received the final
batch of materials, including pivotal practice booklets for the
August promotion test. District and Board of Education officials
acknowledge that it has been a strain to mount such abroad program
days after the end of regular classes.
</P>
<P>
   Then there is the weather. When the heat wave in early July
turned the classroom into a furnace, Mrs. Hunt brought a fan and a
water cooler from home. Still, flies buzzed, heads sank to desks
and eyelids drooped. (The Board of Education has begun putting fans
in all classrooms. Only a fifth of classrooms in the system are
air-conditioned.)
</P>
<P>
   But the constant and overbearing presence is that of the
end-of-summer test. Mrs. Hunt says that she and the pupils worry
about it but that she wants summer school to be about more than
passing the test.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really want you guys to do well,'' she told them. ``But I
don't want you to say you went to summer school to prepare for the
test. I want you to say you learned new authors, we colored, we
learned about genres. We learned a lot, we read, we did math and
also concentrated on our test skills.''
</P>
<P>
   Later, in an interview, Mrs. Hunt said she would consider it a
significant accomplishment if her pupils could write a paragraph of
three to five sentences, with proper punctuation and spelling,
related to a story's theme. She is confident they will make
progress, but acknowledges they have a way to go.
</P>
<P>
   Here, for example, is one of her students' written responses to
``The Quilt Story,'' by Tony Johnston, about a homemade quilt that
comforts a pioneer girl and then, generations later, another lonely
girl:
</P>
<P>
   ``I enjoy the story because the girl liked her quilt, Because
her mother made it. When the girl in the story got sick the quilt
made her Better when she move she stell hade it and The end of the
story she still have it.''
</P>
<P>
   On the first day of summer school, Mrs. Hunt had her students
write down their feelings about it and put the responses on a
poster tacked to the bulletin board.
</P>
<P>
   Jose: ``I am happy and excited because I will learn new
things.''
</P>
<P>
   Tommy: ``I like summer school because if were home I would just
be playing.''
</P>
<P>
   Colin: ``I have a big smile because I have another chance to go
to the fourth grade.''
</P>
<P>
   After two weeks, they still say they do not mind summer school.
Their parents say they appreciate the extra lessons, though some
acknowledge they were surprised to learn their children were
failing.
</P>
<P>
   Maria Guzman, Jose's mother, said he generally took home good
grades. Mrs. Guzman said that she sometimes reads to Jose, and that
her 12-year-old daughter plays teacher to him.
</P>
<P>
   All the pupils said they had done a lot of reading in school,
and some at home.
</P>
<P>
   One day, Mrs. Hunt asked how many had library cards. Only two
hands went up, and when asked in interviews later what they did
most recently at the library, the two students said they had mainly
looked up the Web sites for MTV and the Backstreet Boys.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, there are signs of improvement. Colin Bunbury, who
at first hardly spoke and seemed on the verge of tears when pressed
to participate, now jumps in gleefully. Ozlen, too, has perked up.
</P>
<P>
   Thomas, the boy who had struggled with a sentence, surprised
Mrs. Hunt the other day on another assignment. ``Wow, a complete
sentence!'' she said, looking over his work.
</P>
<P>
   Thomas beamed.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
