<SLUG> BC-FRONTPAGE-NYT </SLUG>
  
(th) 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Here are the stories New York Times editors are planning for
Sunday, JULY 18, Page 1. The N.Y. Times News Service Weekend Editor
is Tim Hilchey; phone: (888) 346-9867; e-mail:
hilchey(at)nytimes.com.
</P>
<P>
   TOP
</P>
<P>
   Lead story:
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-DEATH-TOLL (Pristina, Yugoslavia) _ At least 10,000
people were slaughtered by Serbian forces during their three-month
campaign to drive the Albanians from Kosovo, according to war
crimes investigators, NATO peacekeeping troops and humanitarian
agencies struggling to keep up with fresh reports each day of newly
discovered bodies and graves. By John Kifner.
</P>
<P>
   (We plan to move the story by noon ET in ``i'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: A map is being sent to NYT graphics clients.
Nonsubscribers can make individual purchase by calling
1-888-603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.)
</P>
<P>
   Top center story:
</P>
<P>
   KENNEDY-MISSING-PLANE (New York) _ A small plane carrying John
F. Kennedy Jr. to a wedding on Martha's Vineyard was reported
missing early Saturday, and a search was under way off the coast of
New York's Long Island, officials said. The plane took off at 8:45
p.m. Friday and was believed to be carrying Kennedy, his wife
Carolyn Bessette, and her sister, who were heading to the Cape
Cod-Martha's Vineyard area where the Kennedy family was gathering
for a wedding, a source told The Associated Press.
</P>
<P>
   (We plan to move the story by 1 p.m. ET in ``a'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   (EDS: For first edition, we are planning one main story. Among
the sidebars that are being considered for later in the day is one
out of Washington on the FAA angle. Obituaries are also being
prepared, should that become necessary.)
</P>
<P>
   Off-lead story:
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA-CHURCH-SCHISM (Yekaterinburg, Russia) _ Set on the Ural
mountain divide between Europe and Asia, this city has long been at
the crossroads of Russian history. Russia's last czar was executed
in Yekaterinburg. President Boris Yeltsin began his political
career here as a Communist Party boss. And the local military still
boasts of its cold war role in shooting down Gary Powers' U-2 spy
plane. But Yekaterinburg is best known these days for the protest
that has rocked the nation's most trusted institution: the Russian
Orthodox Church. By Michael R. Gordon.
</P>
<P>
   (We plan to move the story by 12:30 p.m. ET in ``i'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Graphic is
being sent to NYT graphics clients. Nonsubscribers can make
individual purchase by calling 1-888-603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.)
</P>
<P>
   FOLD
</P>
<P>
   APOLLO-REFLECTIONS _ Over dinner a few weeks ago, a former
astronaut who walked on the Moon and one of the Apollo flight
directors got to skylarking about the good old days, something
people do when they think of their past receding and a big
anniversary approaching, in this case the 30th anniversary of the
Apollo 11 lunar landing on July 20, 1969. But without prompting,
they wondered in sadness and perplexity what had happened to the
good old days. Such were the bittersweet thoughts among some of
those of the Apollo generation as they began celebrating the time
when human beings first (and last) set foot on another world. By
John Noble Wilford.
</P>
<P>
   (Story has moved in ``a'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   BOTTOM
</P>
<P>
   NAVAJO-MINE-DISPUTE _ John W. Fritz, an Interior Department
official during the Reagan administration, has long wondered why
his decision to increase the coal mining fees paid to the Navajo
Indians by hundreds of millions of dollars was blocked. He may now
have his answer. By Barry Meier.
</P>
<P>
   (We plan to move the story by noon ET in ``a'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients.)
</P>
<P>
   NY-SUMMER-SCHOOL (New York) _ Outside, summer beckons, with
bikes to be ridden, video games to be played, cartoons to be
watched, Barbies to be pampered for hours on end. But the third
graders in a Brooklyn classroom must set those pleasures aside for
now, ignore the teasing afternoon breeze wafting through the
windows and focus on the task at hand: to draw a picture from one
of three stories they have studied today and write a few sentences
about why they liked it. By Randal C. Archibold.
</P>
<P>
   (Story has moved in ``a'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients.)
</P>
