<DOCTYPE> MISCELLANEOUS TEXT (slug-filter) </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-17 12:03 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3800 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-THISWEEK-REVIEW-NYT     07-17 2069
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-THISWEEK-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
(JT)
</HEADLINE>
 
(Week in Review summary of events in the headlines last week)   c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Race-Based Busing Ends in Boston
</P>
<P>
   Twenty-five years ago, riots and rocks and beatings turned
Boston into the epicenter of national turmoil over busing ordered
by the courts to speed school desegregation. Now the Boston School
Committee has ended the last vestiges of that era by voting, 5-2,
to drop race as a factor in deciding which school a pupil would
attend.
</P>
<P>
   School officials, who have been examining the Boston school
assignment system for years, said they had to act quickly and
decisively because of a pending lawsuit by parents who say the
system discriminates against white children by giving them less
choice of which school to attend.
</P>
<P>
   But that did not keep some two dozen parents and advocates at
the committee's meeting from protesting that Boston was still far
from desegregated. Supporters of the move countered that they
wanted to focus less on race and more on improving education for
all.
</P>
<P>
   _ CAREY GOLDBERG
</P>
<P>
   A Doctor Is Forced To Heal Herself
</P>
<P>
   An Air Force jet flew an emergency mission over the South Pole
last Sunday to drop medical supplies for a member of a research
team who discovered a lump in her breast. But the case is more
difficult than government researchers revealed: the patient will
have to treat herself, because she is the only doctor on the
41-member team at the isolated Antarctic base. Her diagnosis has
not been disclosed. Because of harsh winter conditions, she cannot
be flown out until October or November.
</P>
<P>
   _ DENISE GRADY
</P>
<P>
   Cruise Line Discloses Sexual Assault Cases
</P>
<P>
   Carnival, the world's biggest cruise company, disclosed in court
papers that its crew members had been accused of sexually
assaulting passengers and fellow workers 62 times in a five-year
period that ended last August. Though details on the incidents were
sparse, it was the first time anyone in the cruise industry had
disclosed statistics on shipboard crime.
</P>
<P>
   A company lawyer said the figures demonstrated that Carnival
ships are relatively safe. But lawyers for the people who claimed
to be victims, along with Sen. John McCain, R-Ariz., and chairman
of the Commerce Committee, disagreed with that interpretation and
called on the industry to make a fuller disclosure of crimes.
</P>
<P>
   _ DOUGLAS FRANTZ
</P>
<P>
   U.S. Sues Toyota
</P>
<P>
   The Justice Department sued Toyota on Monday, accusing it of
violating the Clean Air Act and seeking fines that could, in
theory, approach $60 billion, although any actual verdict or
settlement would almost certainly be far less.
</P>
<P>
   The government contends that Toyota did not properly program the
``check engine'' light on the dashboards of most 1996 to 1998 model
Toyota and Lexus automobiles.
</P>
<P>
   The lights would illuminate during regulators' laboratory tests,
but would not turn on during street driving even if traces of
gasoline vapor were leaking from fuel lines and the gas cap, the
lawsuit said. Toyota said that regulations only required the lights
to work during lab tests.
</P>
<P>
   _ KEITH BRADSHER
</P>
<P>
   A Vaccine Is Halted
</P>
<P>
   A year ago, health workers were elated when the first vaccine
against rotavirus, the most common cause of severe diarrhea in
infants and young children, was licensed and recommended for all
infants in this country. But the joy has now been muted; federal
health officials called for immediate suspension of the vaccine
because post-marketing monitoring suggested a link between it and
20 non-fatal cases of a painful blockage of the bowel called
intussusception.
</P>
<P>
   _ LAWRENCE K. ALTMAN
</P>
<P>
   British Beef Readmitted To the World's Markets
</P>
<P>
   The European Commission lifted the worldwide ban on British beef
exports that it imposed three years ago after an epidemic of a
brain malady in cattle known as mad cow disease (bovine spongiform
encephalopathy) was found to be responsible for transmitting a
related brain-wasting disorder (new variant Creutzfeldt-Jakob
disease) to humans.
</P>
<P>
   Regulated feed, new standards for slaughterhouse hygiene and
computer tracking of herds are now in place to restore the good
name of a signature product in Britain. The country, after all, was
once so associated with red meat in Europe that Britons were known
in French as ``les rosbifs.''
</P>
<P>
   _ WARREN HOGE
</P>
<P>
   A New Regimen To Fight AIDS in Newborns
</P>
<P>
   Developing countries have long sought a simple, affordable way
to prevent mother-to-child transmission of the AIDS virus. A study
reported from Uganda last week suggested that it may be a drug,
nevirapine, that has been marketed in the United States since 1996.
Both mother and newborn take nevirapine once _ the mother during
labor and the baby by the third day of life. The total cost is $4.
</P>
<P>
   Because AIDS prevention also requires testing and counseling,
which are scarce in the Third World, experts urged pilot studies of
such combinations before widespread use of nevirapine.
</P>
<P>
   The advance comes at a time when African leaders, mostly silent
for nearly two decades, have begun to speak out against AIDS.
Meanwhile, AIDS has become Africa's leading killer.
</P>
<P>
   _ LAWRENCE K. ALTMAN
</P>
<P>
   Refugees Say Goodbye to an Army Post
</P>
<P>
   With the last refugees from Kosovo expected to leave in the
coming days, Fort Dix prepared to end its brief life as a gateway
for victims of ethnic cleansing, and go back to being a training
camp for military rservists.
</P>
<P>
   More than 4,000 Albanian Kosovars came through Fort Dix starting
in early May; immigration, health and police authorities used the
post to screen the newcomers before resettling them in 40 states.
Another 5,000 refugees, some with relatives already in the United
States, came in through Kennedy Airport.
</P>
<P>
   The plight of the Kosovar refugees touched ordinary Americans,
who stepped forward in great numbers with donations and offers to
take in families, while communities vied to sponsor them, according
to resettlement workers. Though the United States pledged to take
in 20,000 Kosovars, the war's swift end has let it close down
resettlement efforts at less than half that number.
</P>
<P>
   _ DIANA JEAN SCHEMO
</P>
<P>
   A Fugitive Is Found
</P>
<P>
   After months of eluding the authorities, who had linked him with
eight brutal killings in Texas, Illinois and Kentucky, Angel
Maturino Resendez, a Mexican drifter with a fondness for aliases,
disguises and travel by freight train gave himself up in El Paso,
Texas, after his sister negotiated his surrender with a Texas
Ranger.
</P>
<P>
   While Maturino Resendez, who had been known to his pursuers as
Rafael Resendez Ramirez, was being arraigned in a Houston court,
officials said evidence had surfaced that could connect him with a
ninth murder.
</P>
<P>
   _ MICHAEL JANOFSKY
</P>
<P>
   Bush Forgoes Federal Funds to Avoid Spending Limit
</P>
<P>
   Politicians these days are raking in huge gobs of campaign cash,
more than ever before. So when a presidential candidate turns down
$16.5 million, there can only be one explanation: It's not enough.
</P>
<P>
   Gov. George W. Bush of Texas announced he would not accept
federal money to finance his campaign for the Republican
nomination. That's because he wants to cut the strings attached to
the federal gift: restrictions on the amount he can spend.
</P>
<P>
   Candidates who accept federal money can't spend more than $40
million. But Bush has already collected $37 million _ seven months
shy of the first primary.
</P>
<P>
   Bush said avoiding spending limits would allow him to respond to
attacks by a wealthy Republican rival. That would seem to be Steve
Forbes, the multimillionaire publisher, who has already announced
he would not accept matching funds for the 2000 primary season.
</P>
<P>
   The Other Prime Minister's Visit
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ On the Israeli prime minister's visit to Washington
last week, everything went swimmingly.
</P>
<P>
   Of course. Foreign leaders don't just show up at the White
House; these visits are painstakingly planned so there are no
unpleasant surprises. Ever.
</P>
<P>
   Except where there are.
</P>
<P>
   Another prime minister also dropped in on President Clinton last
week and things didn't work out quite so well.
</P>
<P>
   He was John Howard of Australia and his notion was to score a
few points back home by celebrating the friendship between
Washington and Canberra.
</P>
<P>
   It didn't work.
</P>
<P>
   Several days before he was due to arrive, the White House
announced that a 9 percent tariff would be slapped on Australian
lamb imports, and any imports above the current level would receive
an additional 40 percent tariff.
</P>
<P>
   There are few things closer to the Australian heart than a
roasted leg of lamb. More important, lamb is a major export, and
farmers remain a symbol of the Australian way of life. They are
also among the noisiest constituents an Australian politician can
face.
</P>
<P>
   So why did the president act just before the visit?
</P>
<P>
   Australian lamb, it turns out, has been doing so well on the
American market that sheep ranchers had begun to complain. More
than 30 senators, including Sen. Max S. Baucus, D-Mont., who
represents ranchers, wrote to the president asking him to decide in
favor of new tariffs. And he did.
</P>
<P>
   Howard, caught unawares, declared he was appalled and outraged.
</P>
<P>
   The Australian press was downright apoplectic.
</P>
<P>
   ``Damn Ewe!'' screamed The Daily Telegraph in Sydney. A
photograph of a sheep with Clinton's head superimposed accompanied
the article.
</P>
<P>
   Then the newspaper's New York correspondent was ordered to
Washington to find a live sheep. The reporter found a pet lamb and,
at his editor's request, tethered the animal to the White House
fence with a protest sign attached. The animal was duly
photographed.
</P>
<P>
   The next day at the White House, Howard's 20-minute audience
with Clinton was dominated not by discussion of friendship and new
defense arrangements, but by talk of meat.
</P>
<P>
   _ JANE PERLEZ
</P>
<P>
   Thinking Small. Real Small.
</P>
<P>
   As remarkable as today's supercomputers are, they may seem like
Model-T's in less than a decade. Scientists say they have taken the
first tentative steps into a world of computing that would be far
smaller and faster than today's silicon-based machines.
</P>
<P>
   By shrinking computer switches into the Lilliputian world of
individual molecules and atoms, researchers have raised the
possibility of building machines so small that they could navigate
human blood vessels hunting for diseases or create supercomputers
so powerful that they might be 100 billion times faster than
today's machines.
</P>
<P>
   A team of researchers from Hewlett Packard and the University of
California at Los Angeles reported in Science magazine that they
have succeeded in building tiny electronic switches no wider than a
single molecule.
</P>
<P>
   The researchers said there is still much experimentation needed
to create complete computers from the tiny new switches.
</P>
<P>
   For example, they have yet to figure out how to hook the
switches together into vast arrays. And there are still skeptics
who believe that building machines from individual molecules will
always remain a science fiction tale.
</P>
<P>
   But the new molecular switches are a promising first step. If
nothing else, they suggest that if there are limits in the world of
microelectronics that may one day slow the advance in computing
power, they may not be reached for many decades.
</P>
<P>
   _ JOHN MARKOFF
</P>
<P>
   No Fishing
</P>
<P>
   Church and state, forever separate _ that's American bedrock. No
city would dare, say, depict Jesus on a town hall banner. But as
with any self-respecting issue, vast gray areas emerge. If two
lines cross in a town logo, some will see a Christian symbol;
others, well, two lines crossing.
</P>
<P>
   Republic, Mo., has a fish symbol in its official seal. Is this
fish just a fish? Apparently not. The seal's designer said the
symbol represented all religion. But some saw an ancient Christian
symbol and demanded its removal, prompting a bizarre legal battle.
Backers of the fish, even as they acknowledged its religious
overtones, tried to prove it predated Christianity. And local
manicurists painted fish on customers' nails _ presumably with
their permission.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, the American Civil Liberties Union, representing a
local believer in witchcraft, won the day, as a federal judge ruled
that it was indeed a ``Christian fish'' and had to go.
</P>
<P>
   _ HUBERT B. HERRING
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
