<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-17 12:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3817 &Cx1f; taf-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-REPUBS-TAXES-     07-17 1067
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-REPUBS-TAXES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON WARNS AGAINST REPUBLICAN TAX CUTS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Texas)  (mk) 
 By RICHARD W. STEVENSON    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Stepping up his attack on Republican tax-cutting
proposals, President Clinton said Saturday that the cost of the tax
bill moving through the House would rise to ``unimaginable'' levels
and threaten the nation's ability to deal with its most pressing
long-term problems.
</P>
<P>
   Citing a new estimate by the Treasury Department that the cost
of the House tax bill would ``explode'' from $864 billion over the
first decade to $3 trillion in the 10-year period starting in 2010,
Clinton said the country could not afford to allocate anywhere near
that much money to tax cuts without first shoring up Social
Security and Medicare, both of which will come under severe
financial strain in the next few decades as the baby boom
generation retires and life expectancies increase.
</P>
<P>
   The Republican plan would also crimp the government's ability to
use projected federal budget surpluses to pay down the national
debt, and could eventually send the country back into a spiral of
budget deficits and rising debt reminiscent of the 1980s, Clinton
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``At the very time the nation will be confronting the
demographic challenge of the baby boom,'' Clinton said in his
weekly radio address, ``the Republican plan will blow a $3 trillion
hole in the federal budget, threatening our ability to secure
Social Security and Medicare for the next generation and risking
return to the era of deficits with high interest rates and economic
stagnation.''
</P>
<P>
   Tax cuts of the size contemplated by the Republicans, Clinton
said in his weekly national radio address, ``quite simply are bad
economic policy.''
</P>
<P>
   Republicans defended their plan as prudent, and said Clinton was
straining to come up with a justification for why Washington should
not return to taxpayers the growing pile of excess federal revenue.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats predicted dire consequences for the economy each time
taxes have been cut in the past few decades, most recently in 1997,
Republicans said. But each time, they said, the economy has been
strengthened, propelling the United States to new levels of
prosperity.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is an elaborate smoke screen to hide the fact that
Democrats don't want to cut taxes,'' said Trent Duffy, the
spokesman for Rep. Bill Archer, R-Texas, who is chairman of the
Ways and Means Committee and the author of the House plan. ``All
their predictions about tax cuts have been wrong.''
</P>
<P>
   Archer's $864 billion plan, which uses virtually all the surplus
over the next decade except for the portion that goes to Social
Security, was approved by the committee along party lines on
Wednesday, and is scheduled to go to the full House later this
month. In the Senate, the Finance Committee will take up a $792
billion 10-year tax cut on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Although Clinton has threatened to veto both bills or any
blended version of them, he has signaled his willingness to
negotiate a compromise.
</P>
<P>
   Neither side, however, is quite ready to strike a deal.
Republicans are intent on passing their bills, even in the face of
a veto threat, to draw a clear distinction about their differences
with Clinton and his party as the 2000 election approaches.
</P>
<P>
   For his part, Clinton is happy to wait a few months, because
White House officials believe Republicans are stumbling into a
budget trap of their own making that will weaken their negotiating
position.
</P>
<P>
   Administration officials said Republicans will be unable to pass
all the necessary appropriations bills this year without violating
strict spending caps that both parties have pledged to honor.
</P>
<P>
   Only after the Republicans' budget bind becomes clear _ probably
around or just after the end of the government's fiscal year on
Sept. 30 _ is Clinton likely to judge the time right for serious
talks on tax and spending issues, Democrats said.
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, as Clinton's statements Saturday suggest, both
parties are staking out positions and testing out new arguments to
keep the pressure on the other side.
</P>
<P>
   Congress limits its long-term tax and spending projections to 10
years, judging that to be the longest horizon over which economists
and budget analysts can make halfway credible estimates.
</P>
<P>
   Concern about the long-term cost of the current House Republican
proposal has been particularly acute among Democrats because of the
way the plan works. Rather than putting the entire package of tax
cuts into effect immediately, the plan phases them in gradually
over the next 10 years to match the expected growth of the budget
surplus.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, it is not until the cuts are are fully phased in,
in 2009, that their full cost in foregone revenues is realized. For
the House plan, the cuts start out at $4.6 billion next year and
reach $203.4 billion in 2009.
</P>
<P>
   While clearly somewhat speculative if not outright guesswork
given the long-time horizon, the Treasury study cited by Clinton on
Saturday tries to project the costs starting in 2009, and to look
in particular at some of the provisions whose costs could be
expected to continue increasing at the fastest pace.
</P>
<P>
   Among them is the proposed repeal of the inheritance tax on
large estates. The lost revenue would be just $3 million next year,
growing to $15.2 billion by 2009, according to Congress' Joint
Committee on Taxation, for a total of $75.3 billion over the first
decade.
</P>
<P>
   But according to the Treasury estimates, the cost in 2009 would
be considerably higher _ $46 billion _ and would grow to an average
of $57 billion a year for the following decade, benefiting just a
tiny handful of wealthy taxpayers and their heirs, said Gene
Sperling, the White House economic adviser.
</P>
<P>
   The central feature of the House tax plan, its 10 percent
reduction in all income tax rates, would likewise show a steep cost
increase, Sperling said, growing from just over $400 billion in the
first decade to $1.5 trillion in the second 10 years.
</P>
<P>
   ``The reason why this is such a threat to our long-term fiscal
health and our ability to preserve Medicare and Social Security is
that this is exactly the period _ between 2010 and 2020 _ when
Medicare becomes insolvent, when Social Security first comes under
strain, and when we first see the challenges of the baby-boom
retirement,'' Sperling said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
