<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-17 12:28 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3823 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KENNEDY-MISSING-PLANE     07-17 1142
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KENNEDY-MISSING-PLANE-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KENNEDY PLANE IS MISSING 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Map is being sent to NYT graphic clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036.) 
(lh) 
 By DAVID BARSTOW    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ A small plane carrying John F. Kennedy Jr., his wife,
Carolyn Bessette Kennedy, and her sister was reported missing on
Friday, and a huge search was under way Saturday off Long Island,
N.Y., and Cape Cod, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   Kennedy was flying to the wedding of a cousin, Rory, daughter of
the late Sen. Robert F. Kennedy, in Hyannisport, Mass. She was to
be married Saturday before 275 guests in a private ceremony. The
wedding was canceled.
</P>
<P>
   Lt. Martha LaGuardia, a Coast Guard spokeswoman, said the plane,
a Piper 32 Saratoga, left from Fairfield, N.J., at 8:38 p.m. on
Friday and was scheduled to land on Martha's Vineyard, Mass., about
10 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   According to the Coast Guard, the last contact between the plane
and aviation authorities was at 9:39 p.m. on Friday.
</P>
<P>
   When the plane did not arrive, the Kennedy family notified the
Federal Aviation Administration, which began trying to track the
plane, a staff member for Sen. Edward M. Kennedy said.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. LaGuardia said she did not know who was piloting the plane.
Some news reports said Kennedy, who obtained his pilot's license
last year, was at the controls. Other reports said a flight
instructor was on board.
</P>
<P>
   At the Kennedy compound in Hyannisport, a white tent stood by
the sea, and a flag at full staff billowed in the breeze. A Mass
began on the porch of the house of Rory's mother, Ethel Kennedy,
with about 50 family members and three priests praying ``for the
safety of the loved ones, as well as for Rory'' and her fiance,
Mark Bailey, said a family spokesman, Brian O'Connor.
</P>
<P>
   Christina Rivers of Hyannis was to dress the hair of the bridal
party before attending the wedding as a guest. Friday night, she
designed Rory's hair for the rehearsal dinner.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was just wonderful over there last night, just exciting,''
Ms. Rivers said as she sat by her telephone Saturday. ``It's just
not fair. I don't know what it is, but it's not fair.''
</P>
<P>
   Inside the compound were the bride; her uncle, Edward M.
Kennedy; her mother, Ethel Kennedy, and numerous friends and
members of the wedding party.
</P>
<P>
   Kennedy, 38, is the only surviving son of John F. Kennedy, the
35th president. He was born within weeks of his father's 1960
election and was known to the nation as ``John-John,'' a childhood
nickname.
</P>
<P>
   On Nov. 22, 1963, his father was assassinated, and the enduring
image from the funeral came when Kennedy, then a little boy in a
blue coat and shorts, saluted his father's casket outside St.
Matthew's Cathedral.
</P>
<P>
   It was his third birthday.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton was informed early Saturday, and the White
House said search efforts were being coordinated by the Coast
Guard, the U.S. Department of Transportation and the Department of
Defense.
</P>
<P>
   The Air Force Rescue Coordination Center out of Langley Air
Force Base was leading the search, with help from Coast Guard
vessels dispatched from Cape Cod and Montauk, N.Y.
</P>
<P>
   The search was being conducted along the presumed flight path of
Kennedy's plane.
</P>
<P>
   The Coast Guard said that in addition to a number of vessels, it
had launched an H-60, or Jayhawk, helicopter, a Falcon fixed-wing
jet, and a C-130 from the Air National Guard. They were searching
Block Island Sound, Long Island Sound, and the South Shore of Long
Island.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've set up search areas that would cover any possible area
the plane would have flown over,'' Ms. LaGuardia said. ``We would
hope that if there was a distress signal we would be able to pick
up on it.'' But, she said, ``I have not been able to confirm any
kind of signal.'' Other agencies joined the search.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have three marine boats searching the North Shore area,
from Huntington out east,'' said Officer Robert Harris of the
Suffolk County (N.Y.) Police Department. ``It's an Air Force and
Coast Guard search. We are assisting as we can.''
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman for the National Transportation Safety Board, Ted
Lopatkiewicz, said his agency, which investigates all plane
crashes, was standing by. ``We wouldn't know where to go at this
stage,'' he said. The Safety Board got the report of an overdue
plane at about 5 a.m., he said.
</P>
<P>
   The National Transportation Safety Board early Saturday morning
sent investigators to the airport in Caldwell to gather records and
speak to ground personnel, according to a person answering the
phone at the airport operations center. The Safety Board's regional
office is nearby, in Parsippany, N.J.
</P>
<P>
   Aircraft such as the Piper do not carry flight data recorders or
cockpit voice recorders, the ``black boxes'' that investigators use
to piece together the details of airliner crashes.
</P>
<P>
   The plane was flying under visual flight rules, meaning that the
pilot took responsibility for picking his route and avoiding other
traffic, rather than relying on air traffic controllers.
</P>
<P>
   Thus the FAA's air traffic control system did not assign it a
specific beacon code; it would have showed up on controllers' radar
screens with a generic symbol denoting general aviation.
</P>
<P>
   Investigators could pick it out, though, if they knew its hour
of departure and general route. That might help locate the wreckage
and could give a clue as to whether the plane broke up in flight,
officials said.
</P>
<P>
   Though wind conditions were mild on Friday night, visibility in
the area was poor, pilots said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was very hazy, and it was very dark, and it was very hard
to see the horizon,'' said Michael C. Bard, a private pilot, who
left Martha's Vineyard about 9:15 p.m. on Friday and flew back to
his home in Danbury, Conn.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you're not instrument rated, it could be difficult
maintaining the airplane in an upright condition.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't believe that something like this could happen _ again
_ to the Kennedy family,'' said Mayor Rudolph Giuliani of New York,
speaking at the city's Office of Emergency Management on the 23rd
floor of the World Trade Center. ``Let's hope and pray that it's a
successful effort,'' he said of the search.
</P>
<P>
   New York Police Commissioner Howard Safir said the Police
Department, acting on a request from the Kennedy family early
Saturday, had dispatched officers to Kennedy's Manhattan apartment
to make sure he was not there.
</P>
<P>
   The family also asked the police to make sure Kennedy's car was
at the airport.
</P>
<P>
   After graduating from Brown University, Kennedy went to law
school and joined the Manhattan district attorney's office.
</P>
<P>
   In 1995 he started the magazine George _ subtitled ``not just
politics as usual.'' A year later, Kennedy _ once dubbed ``the
sexiest man alive'' by People magazine _ married Ms. Bessette.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-17-99 1228EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
