<SLUG> BC-SAFRICA-TORTURER-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SOUTH AFRICA HEARING UGLY TALE IN RIVETING DETAIL 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 By SUZANNE DALEY    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   PRETORIA, South Africa _ In his drab denim shirts and army-style
green sweaters, Eugene de Kock answers questions for hours, rarely
showing any signs of emotion. His face is lineless, his eyes small
behind thick glasses that make him look more like the class nerd
than South Africa's most notorious apartheid-era henchman.
</P>
<P>
   De Kock's amnesty application, listing his misdeeds, is more
than 4,000 pages long. It is by far the largest one received by
this country's Truth and Reconciliation Commission. Already he has
been on the stand more than six weeks. Getting through his
application is expected to take 16 weeks. No one else comes close.
</P>
<P>
   The other day he was describing the killing of Japie Maponya, a
small town security guard, who had done nothing at all except that
his brother was an antiapartheid guerrilla. First, Maponya was
tortured (he divulged nothing), then taken to a forest to be
killed.
</P>
<P>
   There is some dispute, however, about what followed. For no
apparent reason, one of the security officers with de Kock slammed
Maponya on the side of the head with the silencer-equipped gun that
was to be used in Maponya's execution. This caused the gun to jam,
and another gun had to be used.
</P>
<P>
   But the question occupying the commission was did de Kock smash
a shovel through Maponya's skull before or after he was finally
shot?
</P>
<P>
   De Kock insisted it was after. ``It was standard practice to
make sure people were dead after they had been shot,'' said de
Kock, who has a way of making brutality sound like regulation.
</P>
<P>
   But others who were there say differently. They say that when
the gun jammed, de Kock did not hesitate to pick up the shovel and
hit the kneeling, handcuffed Maponya with the sharp edge. Only
afterward, they say, because he still showed signs of life, was
Maponya shot in the head.
</P>
<P>
   Inside an ordinary conference room here the grisly details of
the more than 100 instances of torture and killings to which de
Kock has confessed are gone over and over again _ illustrating
perhaps more than any other testimony the ugliness of the former
government's efforts to stay in power.
</P>
<P>
   Yet despite de Kock's voluminous confessions many people believe
that he has still not told the whole truth, that he is holding back
details, trying to make himself look more like a soldier than a
monster.
</P>
<P>
   To get amnesty, the commission, which is investigating human
rights abuses during the apartheid-era, must find that de Kock has
told the whole truth and that his acts were politically motivated.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are still discrepancies,'' said Linda Lockhat, who was
questioning de Kock for the Commission last week. ``He still does
not want to admit some things. He wants to clean it up, to make it
look like he was a precision man, an army man in a war.''
</P>
<P>
   De Kock, a highly decorated former colonel in South Africa's
police force, was in charge of the Vlakplaas counterterrorism unit
from 1985 to 1993. But he is currently in jail serving two life
terms plus 212 years for a range of charges, including six murders,
one attempted murder and 66 acts of fraud. He has written a book on
his life, lashing out at the generals who he says abandoned him
after he had finished their dirty work.
</P>
<P>
   It is unclear whether he will be granted amnesty and for which
acts.
</P>
<P>
   The Truth Commission, which is supposed to help South Africa put
its apartheid past to rest, issued 3,500 pages of its final report
last fall and is winding down its work, with only about 800 of its
6,400 amnesty applications still pending.
</P>
<P>
   The commission has already granted amnesty in some of South
Africa's most memorable cases of human rights violations, like the
killing of Amy Biehl, an American aid worker who was stoned to
death in a township outside of Cape Town because she was white.
</P>
<P>
   But in recent months the commission has also denied amnesty in
several prominent cases, including those involved in the deaths of
the activist Chris Hani and the leader of the Black Consciousness
movement, Steve Biko.
</P>
<P>
   Experts say that the range of de Kock's offenses is so large it
is unlikely he will get out of jail anytime soon. Some of his acts
_ killing a diamond dealer because he was not satisfied with the
quality of the diamonds he was sold _ appear to have little to do
with politics.
</P>
<P>
   De Kock himself routinely acknowledges that his misdeeds are so
many that he has trouble remembering them himself.
</P>
<P>
   ``I spent 10 years as the head of an incredibly active unit,''
de Kock told the commission just last week when he was being
questioned about who had witnessed Maponya's murder. ``It is
difficult to keep track of every detail.''
</P>
</TEXT>
