u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-POWER-OUTAGE-INQUIRY-     07-17 0677
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POWER-OUTAGE-INQUIRY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ENERGY DEPTARTMENT PLANS ACTION ON BLACKOUTS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Md., N.J., Del., Pa., N.Y.)  (lh) 
 By MATTHEW L. WALD    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Energy Secretary Bill Richardson will propose six
steps to reduce electricity disruptions in severe weather in a
speech on Monday, including federal investigations of power
blackouts like the ones that plagued New York and other cities this
month, department officials say.
</P>
<P>
   Richardson's speech is scheduled for a convention in San
Francisco of the National Association of Regulatory Utility
Commissioners, whose members serve on state public service
commissions.
</P>
<P>
   In remarks prepared for delivery, Richardson says: ``Clearly, we
need to be concerned. Customers should not have to wonder whether
the lights will go out the next time the thermometer hits 90
degrees.''
</P>
<P>
   Richardson will form a team of experts from within the Energy
Department to investigate ``major power outages,'' a department
official said. These would be disruptions resulting from
insufficient generation or transmission problems, but not
distribution problems, like the ones that blacked out a
neighborhood in northern Manhattan in sustained extreme heat two
weeks ago. There is no routine federal investigation of blackouts,
although some states look into some of them, department officials
say.
</P>
<P>
   Richardson will also call for a ``regional summit'' of
governors, state public service commissioners and other state
officials in the Northeast to discuss new transmission lines that
can ease supply problems, overcoming local objections to high
voltage lines when they serve regional needs.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's an increasingly difficult issue,'' one department
official said. ``These things need to be looked at on a regional
basis.''
</P>
<P>
   In another step, the department will try to equip the federal
government, which is the nation's largest electricity consumer, to
be more helpful in times of tight supply.
</P>
<P>
   On July 6, the day after the long Fourth of July weekend, when
power was stretched tight during a heat wave, the power pool
serving the District of Columbia _ along with Maryland, New Jersey,
Delaware and most of Pennsylvania _ called big employers to ask for
emergency help in cutting consumption.
</P>
<P>
   In the Energy Department's own headquarters, technicians shut
down some escalators and elevators, and many office workers with
windows turned off their lights. But when a deputy secretary of
energy called the General Services Administration, which is the
federal government's property management agency, and asked that
other agencies be told to do likewise, he learned that there were
no provisions for doing so.
</P>
<P>
   ``We really didn't have a governmentwide plan for how to deal
with these things,'' one official said on Friday.
</P>
<P>
   The department already had plans to issue a new rule in April
2001, requiring central air conditioners for houses to be up to 20
percent more efficient, but Richardson will announce an effort to
get the rule out six months earlier. The effective date would also
be six months earlier, although that might be years away.
</P>
<P>
   The electric supply question is more complicated, experts say,
because of deregulation by the states, which means that many of the
utilities that deliver electricity to customers no longer generate
it, but buy it from competitive producers.
</P>
<P>
   Richardson's prepared remarks say uncertainty about what changes
the federal government will make in electricity rules has led some
companies to delay building power plants. His remarks say Congress
should act on an administration proposal made in April, to reduce
this uncertainty.
</P>
<P>
   That proposal would also increase money available for
conservation efforts sponsored by utilities, which have been
sharply reduced as utilities have begun to compete with each other.
But Congress for the last several years has been unable to agree on
what steps the federal government should take to encourage
deregulation, and the result has been a state-by-state patchwork.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
