<P>
   Here are the top Times Express stories planned for Sunday, July
18. The N.Y. Times News Service Supervisor is Tim Hilchey; phone:
(888) 346-9867; e-mail: tihilc(at)nytimes.com.
</P>
<P>
   EXP-KOSOVO-DEATH-TOLL (Pristina, Yugoslavia) _ At least 10,000
people were slaughtered by Serbian forces during their three-month
campaign to drive the Albanians from Kosovo, according to war
crimes investigators, NATO peacekeeping troops and humanitarian
agencies struggling to keep up with fresh reports each day of newly
discovered bodies and graves. By John Kifner.
</P>
<P>
   EXP-RUSSIA-CHURCH-SCHISM (Yekaterinburg, Russia) _ Set on the
Ural mountain divide between Europe and Asia, this city has long
been at the crossroads of Russian history. Russia's last czar was
executed in Yekaterinburg. President Boris Yeltsin began his
political career here as a Communist Party boss. And the local
military still boasts of its cold war role in shooting down Gary
Powers' U-2 spy plane. But Yekaterinburg is best known these days
for the protest that has rocked the nation's most trusted
institution: the Russian Orthodox Church. By Michael R. Gordon.
</P>
<P>
   EXP-IRAN-STUDENTS (Tehran, Iran) _ Student leaders on Saturday
announced a temporary ban on pro-reform demonstrations, but pressed
the Islamic government on a long list of demands, including the
resignation of the country's chief of police. By Elaine Sciolino.
</P>
<P>
   EXP-INDIA-TV-WAR (Mokhra, India) _ India has fought three larger
wars with Pakistan, in 1947, 1965 and 1971, but the last two months
of fighting in the Himalayan land of Kashmir that lies between them
has produced India's first televised war. In 1971, fewer than 1 in
200 of India's households had TV's. Now, it's more than 1 in 3. By
Celia W. Dugger.
</P>
<P>
   EXP-COLOMBIA-CRISIS (Bogota, Colombia) _ On Monday, the
government of President Andres Pastrana and the Revolutionary Armed
Forces of Colombia, the Marxist guerrilla group known to Colombians
as FARC, are scheduled to begin formal peace negotiations aimed at
ending 35 years of civil conflict. But a rapidly deteriorating
political and economic situation has weakened Pastrana's hand going
into the talks, undermining prospects for peace and emboldening the
rebels. By Larry Rohter.
</P>
<P>
   EXP-SAFRICA-TORTURER (Pretoria, South Africa) _ In his drab
denim shirts and army-style green sweaters, Eugene de Kock answers
questions for hours, rarely showing any signs of emotion. His face
is lineless, his eyes small behind thick glasses that make him look
more like the class nerd than South Africa's most notorious
apartheid-era henchman. De Kock's amnesty application, listing his
misdeeds, is more than 4,000 pages long. By Suzanne Daley.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL &LR;  (Moving in ``a'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   EXP-KENNEDY-MISSING-PLANE (New York) _ A small plane carrying
John F. Kennedy Jr. to a wedding on Martha's Vineyard was reported
missing early Saturday, and a search was under way off the coast of
New York's Long Island, officials said. The plane took off at 8:45
p.m. Friday and was believed to be carrying Kennedy, his wife
Carolyn Bessette, and her sister, who were heading to the Cape
Cod-Martha's Vineyard area where the Kennedy family was gathering
for a wedding, a source told The Associated Press.
</P>
<P>
   EXP-APOLLO-REFLECTIONS _ Over dinner a few weeks ago, a former
astronaut who walked on the Moon and one of the Apollo flight
directors got to skylarking about the good old days, something
people do when they think of their past receding and a big
anniversary approaching, in this case the 30th anniversary of the
Apollo 11 lunar landing on July 20, 1969. But without prompting,
they wondered in sadness and perplexity what had happened to the
good old days. Such were the bittersweet thoughts among some of
those of the Apollo generation as they began celebrating the time
when human beings first (and last) set foot on another world. By
John Noble Wilford.
</P>
<P>
   EXP-NAVAJO-MINE-DISPUTE _ John W. Fritz, an Interior Department
official during the Reagan administration, has long wondered why
his decision to increase the coal mining fees paid to the Navajo
Indians by hundreds of millions of dollars was blocked. He may now
have his answer. By Barry Meier.
</P>
<P>
   EXP-HEALTH-HOUSE-REBELS (Washington) _ A group of rebellious
House Republicans, in defiance of their leaders, are trying to pass
much tougher regulation of managed-care plans than the Senate
adopted last week and say they can win if they can force a vote. By
Adam Clymer.
</P>
<P>
   EXP-CLINTON-REPUBS-TAXES (Washington) _ Stepping up his attack
on Republican tax-cutting proposals, President Clinton said
Saturday that the cost of the tax bill moving through the House
would rise to ``unimaginable'' levels and threaten the nation's
ability to deal with its most pressing long-term problems. By
Richard W. Stevenson.
</P>
