<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ALA-MAYOR-RETIRE-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MAYOR IMPROVES CITY'S IMAGE BUT NOT ITS RACIAL SPLIT 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(lb) 
 By DAVID FIRESTONE    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   BIRMINGHAM, Ala. _ For the last 20 years, each time he walked
into the City Hall he transformed, Mayor Richard Arrington Jr. has
passed by the name T. Eugene Connor carved into the building's
cornerstone.
</P>
<P>
   It is just a name now, one of a list of men now dead who voted
to erect the building, and most people do not even notice it. Even
if it had included Connor's better-known nickname, Bull, the
carving would still seem as out of place among Birmingham's new
skyscrapers and polished corporate headquarters as a hieroglyph
telling an ancient story of conflict.
</P>
<P>
   That sense of distance between the snarling dogs of Bull Connor,
the former police commissioner who became the symbol of intolerance
in the days of the civil rights movement, and the placid,
prosperous Birmingham of today is a result in significant part of
two decades of quiet work by Arrington, who will retire on Monday
at age 64.
</P>
<P>
   When Arrington took office in 1979 as the city's first black
mayor, Birmingham was still struggling to shed its national
reputation as ``Bombingham,'' the city where racial divisions
became explosive in the 1960s and where any police shooting
threatened to turn into a confrontation. One of Arrington's first
efforts was to integrate and tame the Police Department, and the
effect was immediate.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Bernard Kincaid, a black member of the City Council who is
usually one of Arrington's sharpest critics, said: ``At the time he
became mayor, if you were an African-American who was stopped by
the police, you didn't know if you were going to be shot and a gun
dropped beside you. Arrington stopped that dead in its tracks. The
outright fear, that shook you down to your boots, is gone.''
</P>
<P>
   The city's economy, crumbling in 1979 after Birmingham's giant
steel plants began to close, has been renewed by a carefully
managed shift toward health care, biotechnology and banking.
</P>
<P>
   The unemployment rate, which soared above 20 percent during the
recession of the early 1980s, is now 4.3 percent, and new
businesses continue to move into 80 square miles of largely vacant
land that Arrington annexed for the city's growth. Many of those
businesses are taking advantage of substantial tax incentives that
he has offered in consultation with a tight circle of local
executives.
</P>
<P>
   But for all that he has accomplished in the region, the mayor
remains a divisive figure in Birmingham. The son of sharecroppers,
a former zoology professor whose political savvy cannot conceal a
quiet, scholarly core, Arrington was never as forceful or
confrontational as the other ``first black mayors'' who dominated
their cities for 20 years, figures like Tom Bradley of Los Angeles,
Coleman Young of Detroit and Richard Hatcher of Gary, Ind.
</P>
<P>
   Yet like so many other black mayors, Arrington never attracted
more than a small fraction of the white vote in his five terms, or
established lasting biracial coalitions with other politicians or
white suburbs.
</P>
<P>
   Tens of thousands of white residents moved to the suburbs during
his tenure, leaving the city with a 70 percent black majority and
shrinking the population by 11 percent, to 252,997 last year from
284,413 in 1980.
</P>
<P>
   An undercurrent of racial tension continues to define the
region's politics, even at the smallest level. Recently, after the
Arrington allies who control the City Council voted to rename a
major street in his honor, white members of the County Commission
grumbled that the new name would require merchants on the street to
get new stationery.
</P>
<P>
   ``It has been good for Birmingham's image to have someone like
Arrington, who is obviously smart and thoughtful, and provided
steady leadership,'' said Robert Norrell, a historian of the civil
rights movement at the University of Tennessee who lived in
Birmingham for many years and worked for Arrington's first mayoral
campaign. ``But since the 1950s, Birmingham has been deeply and
angrily divided over race, and he hasn't been able to overcome
that. Of course, it's hard to imagine anyone who could.''
</P>
<P>
   Sitting in his office last week while aides scooped hundreds of
honorary plaques off the walls and into packing boxes, Arrington
was unapologetic about the exclusively black nature of his
political organization, the Jefferson County Citizens Coalition,
which became the main vehicle for black enfranchisement in
Birmingham, often at the expense of biracial unity.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, we never said whites couldn't come, but it was a black
organization and we'd like to keep that in place,'' the mayor said.
``Political power was something blacks didn't have in this town
until the 1980s, so we said, `Let's organize, let's bloc-vote,
let's mobilize.' Now people say we've got a political machine, and
they resent it. But that's a cop out. You can't blame everything
wrong in Birmingham on Bull Connor and Richard Arrington.''
</P>
<P>
   Though it may have proved annoying to many white residents, his
effective marshaling of black political power in a state long
famous for its absence has made him an iconic figure to his
supporters.
</P>
<P>
   ``From the first time I met him, I was in awe of him,'' said
Norman Davis Jr., a black investment banker in Birmingham who
recently was appointed Alabama's superintendent of banks. ``This
was a man with incredible vision, who knew what he had to do to
keep the city strong despite white flight and the death of the
steel industry. To many blacks, he'll always be a hero, but
unfortunately, a lot of whites never gave him a chance.''
</P>
<P>
   Many white voters and elected officials were put off by what
they saw as cronyism in the awarding of contracts and the hiring of
key personnel, a sense that was only enhanced when the federal
government began looking into those issues in a series of
investigations in the 1980s and '90s. Arrington always said the
inquiries were racially motivated, and in 1992 he spent a day in
jail rather than turn over documents to the U.S. attorney.
</P>
<P>
   Two former allies were found guilty of fraud in connection with
the construction of the Civil Rights Institute, a museum of the
struggle for equality that is a tourist attraction. Arrington was
named an unindicted co-conspirator in a kickback scheme, but the
Justice Department later withdrew that designation.
</P>
<P>
   ``He has taken care of his friends, but the only white people he
cares about are the corporate leaders,'' said Craig Sanderson, who
is white and the president of the Crestwood Community Association,
which represents a mostly white neighborhood on the east side. ``I
think there are some good things that he did, but I wish he hadn't
played the race card so often.''
</P>
<P>
   The city's physical face is also showing signs of wear in some
places. Many roads, school buildings and low-income neighborhoods
seem forgotten. Birmingham's symbol, a 56-foot iron statue of
Vulcan that overlooks the city from Red Mountain, has deteriorated
so badly that the council voted recently to spend $1 million to
take it down before it falls. Private donors plan to raise an
estimated $10 million to repair and restore it.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Arrington acknowledges that the most serious criticism from his
opponents _ his neglect of the school system _ is legitimate.
Birmingham's schools now rank 109th out of the state's 128 school
districts in achievement test scores, according to a recent study
by The Birmingham News.
</P>
<P>
   The ranking actually represents a recent improvement. The mayor
does not have direct control over the school system. But the City
Council, which Arrington controls, appoints the school board.
</P>
<P>
   ``What I regret most of all is, I didn't know the schools were
in quite as bad a shape as they were,'' said Arrington, who has
eight children, most of whom attended public schools. ``I just did
not deal much with the schools, because I had a zillion other
problems to deal with. I felt I had less authority and clout there
than I did in other areas.''
</P>
<P>
   He is stepping down now, he said, because he has done all he can
do and believes the city needs new leadership. But even his method
of departure has caused a stir. Because he is leaving three months
before his term is up, his close ally William Bell, the City
Council president, will become interim mayor and have a leg up in
his campaign to succeed Arrington in the Oct. 12 election.
</P>
<P>
   Other candidates, including Kincaid, have complained that the
move is a high-handed attempt to preserve the mayor's dynasty.
</P>
<P>
   ``He cannot anoint his own successor,'' Kincaid said.
</P>
<P>
   But unless the black vote begins to splinter badly, most of
Arrington's successors are likely to be black, thanks to an
assertion of power by the once powerless that seemed unimaginable
before he took office. Arrington is explicit in hoping that his
successors will use the political tools he provided to create an
eventual racial reconciliation that he could not achieve.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I was first elected, a lot of people expected this town
to go to pot, and I think we surprised them,'' he said. ``That's
going to continue. And the next mayor won't have to fight a lot of
the battles that I fought.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
