<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LIPSYTE-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: OK, SPORTS ISN'T SOLELY ABOUT SEX 
</HEADLINE>
  (jt) 
 By ROBERT LIPSYTE    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Equating sex and sports last week was a mistake for which I have
been taken to task and for which I now apologize. There is far more
to sports than sex. There is also drugs and violence. And they seem
to be fun, too.
</P>
<P>
   Drugs must be even more fun than sex because athletes are
getting so righteous about their right to use. Nearly half the
riders in the Tour de France were de-biked last year for testing
positive for illegal substances, which many of them decried as a
ridiculous witch hunt. Mais oui. I would need to get stoned just to
get on a bike in France the way they drive, so imagine if you had
to also race up and down hills.
</P>
<P>
   Is it irony or what that the current hero of the Tour is Lance
Armstrong of the U.S. Postal Team, who has probably had more drugs
pumped through his body than any other rider in history _
life-saving chemotherapy drugs for testicular cancer that invaded
his lungs and brain. No wonder he is an outspoken critic of mere
performance-enhancing drugs.
</P>
<P>
   And then there are the rivers of androstenedione that run
through our games. These days, who would even dream of entering a
potato race without a pill or two? Andro, which is banned by the
colleges, the Olympics and pro football, has been a big hit in
baseball, especially after Mark McGwire hit his 70 home runs last
season. He acknowledged a boost from the legal supplement that so
stimulates natural testosterone production that some doctors
consider it a steroid. Baseball has not banned andro, many experts
believe, because it would cast a pall on the home-run record.
</P>
<P>
   Obviously, McGwire was legally within his rights to use andro,
and expose himself to possible negative long-term side-effects. But
should he have kept it to himself? As a proud daddy who purports to
understand his role as a model, why did he lead a million kids into
the health-food stores? Unless, of course, he had a higher
obligation to truth and his endorsement contracts. He has since
said that andro does more for his sex life than his baseball
scoring.
</P>
<P>
   And inquiring minds want to know just what was going on when
three past and present Jets, Jumbo Elliott, Matt O'Dwyer and Jason
Fabini, were arrested last weekend for going postal (we should
retire that in deference to Armstrong and his merry mailmen) in a
bar in Long Beach, N.Y. Although there is no evidence of drug use,
these are the 'roid rage dog days, the time of year when pro
football players complete their steroid cycles so the quicker
picker-uppers are out of their systems by the time they are tested.
</P>
<P>
   Let's not forget that performance-enhancing drugs are addictive
in their way. A former Division I lineman, Al Brown, now an
Emmy-award-winning TV cameraman, told me recently about the
``pleasurable fascination'' he felt as his body grew larger and
stronger. He had started taking steroids to compete against bigger
linemen; the resulting sense of omnipotence off the field was as
satisfying. He quit while still in college after his 4-year-old
nephew inadvertently kicked him in the kidney. Brown collapsed.
</P>
<P>
   Although it apparently helps, you don't need drugs to be
violent. Here comes Lawrence Phillips again, bad actor at Nebraska
and at several National Football League teams before he stayed out
of jail in Barcelona this spring.
</P>
<P>
   While playing in NFL Europe, he rushed for a record 1,021 yards,
was the league's most valuable player on offense and drew interest
from several more pro teams. Have the shrinks cleared him for
takeoff or are there now 1,021 reasons why he is an acceptable risk
again? The NFL announced last week it would not suspend Phillips
for past infractions if he returned, merely fine him.
</P>
<P>
   The best pro football players, said a very good one, the New
England lineman Brian Holloway, are able to disengage their ``moral
delay,'' that little brake that keeps most of us from responding
immediately and violently to the slightest affront, be it an
oncoming jersey or a sign of disrespect on the street. Some players
can turn it on and off, others wear a permanent game face.
</P>
<P>
   Football is a violent game, and coaches look for violent
players; why do we keep insisting on athletes with split
personalities? These guys give us so much entertainment, they
deserve some slack, a town-sized All-Star Cafe they can trash at
will, rubber walls to cut down injuries, breakaway windows, bowls
of drugs on the bar.
</P>
<P>
   As the Women's World Cup champions continue to sell the
beautiful game with endearing photo ops of goodness, friendship and
nonthreatening sexuality, the more traditional joys of Jumbo seem
increasingly gross and pathetic. Are the bad boys of summer over?
Will the Cup babes reform sports along the way? Jumbo poses nude.
Lawrence admits his chronic thug syndrome and works through it with
Dr. Ruth on ESPN. The estrogenie is out of the bottle.
</P>
<P>
   Or, does the old jock culture win. Brandi gets randy, they bulk
up on andro, disengage their moral delays and start swaggering
through SportsWorld, pony-tails whipping, showing a new generation
of 10-year-old girls how to take back the schoolyard.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
