<SLUG> BC-BKN-NOTEBOOK-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NBA NOTES AND NEWS 
</HEADLINE>
  (jt) 
 By CHRIS BROUSSARD    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Knicks' Coach Is Back, but for How Long?
</P>
<P>
   First, the precarious nature of Coach Jeff Van Gundy's job
status was supposed to end when Allan Houston's jump shot propelled
the Knicks past the despised Miami Heat in the first round of the
playoffs. When that did not happen, it was assumed that Van Gundy
would be granted his desired security as a result of subsequent
victories over the Atlanta Hawks and the powerful Indiana Pacers
and the Knicks' gallant effort against the San Antonio Spurs in the
NBA finals.
</P>
<P>
   But even though those achievements assured Van Gundy of another
season at the helm, they may not have delivered what many presumed
they would: a long-term contract extension for the embattled coach,
who has two years left on his existing deal.
</P>
<P>
   While preparing for this week's mini-camp and next week's
rookie/free-agent summer league in Boston, Van Gundy waited _
perhaps in vain _ for Dave Checketts, the Madison Square Garden
president, to call and initiate discussions on a contract
extension. Van Gundy said he was not concerned, but he realizes
that the lack of a contract extension could lead to another season
of uncertainty and unwanted, behind-the-scenes suspense.
</P>
<P>
   ``Dave's been busy with some other things,'' Van Gundy said.
``I'm sure everything's going to be fine, but we haven't done
anything.''
</P>
<P>
   On the surface, nothing seems necessary since Van Gundy will be
paid $2 million this season and $3.5 million the next. But without
long-term security, the upcoming season becomes little more than a
probationary period for Van Gundy. If the Knicks do well, he will
very likely have his contract extended beyond the 2000-1 season. If
they fail to meet Checketts' standards, the Knicks could easily
choose to replace Van Gundy and take a relatively small $3.5
million hit for buying out his final year.
</P>
<P>
   That being the case, Van Gundy will have to maneuver smoothly
through a minefield of potential eruptions on his club, the most
predominant issues being Patrick Ewing's role, Latrell Sprewell's
place in the lineup and the use of Marcus Camby.
</P>
<P>
   While the debate about whether the Knicks are better with Ewing
or without him continues, there is little question that the future
Hall of Famer must accept a diminished role in the offense. Last
season, Van Gundy proved unwilling to take the ball away from
Ewing, who has been the coach's greatest supporter within the
organization. The result was that a team stacked with thoroughbreds
was confined to a plodding half-court offense and played beneath
expectations during the regular season.
</P>
<P>
   It was not until injuries limited Ewing to the role of defender,
rebounder and mere component of the offense _ as opposed to its
main feature _ that Sprewell, Camby and the rest of the Knicks took
off. But Ewing plans to be healthy next season and shortly after
the finals made it clear that he expects to play the same role he
always has _ the focal point. That puts the onus on Van Gundy to
keep his center happy while at the same time limiting his role.
</P>
<P>
   Before injuries forced his hand, Van Gundy had Sprewell coming
off the bench, which irritated the former All-Star guard. After his
outstanding performance in the playoffs, Sprewell will not want to
return to being the sixth man, and, like it or not, Van Gundy has
little choice but to start him. Sprewell is in the last season of
his contract, and if displeased with Van Gundy, he will have the
option of leaving as a free agent _ with the Knicks getting nothing
in return. That would not increase Van Gundy's popularity with the
fans or the front office.
</P>
<P>
   The situation surrounding Camby is not as volatile since he will
accept coming off the bench. But he must play a lot of meaningful
minutes, and the Knicks must play a style that takes advantage of
his tremendous ability. Camby expressed dismay last season with
what he viewed as Van Gundy's biased treatment of him because of
the coach's fondness for Charles Oakley and, after his excellence
in the playoffs, he now has the stature to affect Van Gundy's
future.
</P>
<P>
   In the past Van Gundy sometimes catered to Ewing and ignored the
wishes of Sprewell and Camby, but without a contract extension, he
will not have the security to do so this season.
</P>
<P>
   Timberwolves Surviving
</P>
<P>
   The Minnesota Timberwolves lost two All-Star caliber players in
Tom Gugliotta and Stephon Marbury within one year, which would
crush most teams. But the Timberwolves are not far from where they
were when Gugliotta, Marbury and Kevin Garnett formed what appeared
to be the nucleus of the future in the Western Conference.
</P>
<P>
   After Gugliotta left Minnesota in free agency to play for
Phoenix last season, the Timberwolves were fortunate to land Joe
Smith, the former No. 1 National Basketball Association draft pick
who soon could be as good as Gugliotta. Then, when Marbury forced
them to trade him to the Nets, they acquired Terrell Brandon, a
two-time All-Star point guard who is just a notch below Marbury.
</P>
<P>
   Not long ago, the Timberwolves feared losing both Smith and
Brandon to free agency, but it appears that both will return to
Minnesota to keep the team on the heels of the Western Conference
elite. Both are near certainties to sign with the club in August.
They should team with Garnett and the newcomer Wally Szczerbiak to
give the Timberwolves a solid and talented core.
</P>
<P>
   Brandon is meeting with the Timberwolves' owner, Glen Taylor,
tomorrow, and Bill Duffy, Brandon's agent, expects an agreement to
be reached in principle soon thereafter.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're inclined to sign,'' Duffy said. ``They want Terrell
back, and I believe he wants to be back. We're just going to hope
that we're on the same page.''
</P>
<P>
   Actually, the parties may be a few pages apart, but the divide
should be closed quickly. The Timberwolves would like to get
Brandon for about $7 million a season and cite his history of
injuries _ he has missed 46 games the past two seasons _ as the
reason for the relatively low figure. While Duffy refused to
discuss his client's salary desires, Brandon, 29, is believed to be
looking for a six-year deal that averages $10 million or $11
million a season.
</P>
<P>
   The negotiations should be cordial since Duffy is a longtime
friend of the Timberwolves general manager Kevin McHale. In fact,
when it became apparent that Marbury intended to leave Minnesota,
Duffy actively helped to deliver Brandon as his replacement, a
gesture the agent is sure to bring up during negotiations. Brandon
went on to average 19.3 points, 7 assists and 7.5 rebounds as the
Timberwolves gave San Antonio its toughest test of the playoffs
before losing, three games to one.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Timberwolves are just a couple of players away,'' Duffy
said. ``And I'd like to take some credit for that because we were
involved with getting Terrell there.''
</P>
<P>
   It's Good to Have a Shooter
</P>
<P>
   While Cleveland has been roundly criticized for selecting Trajan
Langdon, a 6-foot-3-inch jump shooter from Duke, with the 11th pick
of the draft, Wayne Embry, who recently resigned as general manager
of the Cavaliers but remains as the club's president, defended the
decision.
</P>
<P>
   ``Would you rather have a guy who can make a shot off your
offense or transition, or would you rather have a guy who can
create but can't make a shot?'' Embry asked, denouncing the idea
that Langdon's inability to slash to the basket makes him a
liability. ``When you've got a strong inside game, you have to
protect your big men, and we've always tried to do that. You've got
to guard shooters, so that opens up the middle.''
</P>
<P>
   In Langdon, his fellow draft pick Andre Miller (No. 8 overall),
Brevin Knight, Derek Anderson, Bob Sura and Wesley Person, the
Cavaliers have one of the deepest backcourts in the league, one
that should allow them to play the up-tempo style that the new
coach, Randy Wittman, is espousing. To free up the logjam, Person,
an excellent shooter, will play lots of small forward.
</P>
<P>
   If center Zydrunas Ilgauskas, who missed most of last season
with a broken left foot, is healthy, the Cavaliers, led by the
All-Star power forward Shawn Kemp, could be one of the best teams
in the wide-open Eastern Conference.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
