<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-UMPIRES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THREATENING UMPIRES ARE TAKING A HUGE GAMBLE 
</HEADLINE>
  (jt) 
 By MURRAY CHASS    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Said a man with great insight into the way the real world works:
``You never ask for something you might get.''
</P>
<P>
   He was applying this cautionary wisdom to the umpires' announced
intention to resign Sept. 2, leaving the last month of the season
and the playoffs and World Series to less experienced and skilled
officials.
</P>
<P>
   Although Commissioner Bud Selig and other high-ranking officials
have carefully avoided making public comments about the umpires'
negotiating ploy, they are portrayed by people who have spoken with
them as outraged and intent on letting the umpires walk.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're making a mistake if they think they're going to resign
and still umpire,'' said an official privy to Selig's thinking. He
added that barring a change in that thinking, Selig will accept the
resignations and wish the umpires well in their future careers.
</P>
<P>
   The umpires have certainly won no friends with their surprising
declaration, not that they had many to begin with, which is sort of
their point in taking such a severe step. But their attempt to gain
respect could turn their resignation hammer into an unemployment
boomerang.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking of Richie Phillips, the umpires' union leader and chief
strategist, a lawyer with links to baseball management said:
``Richie is looking for something he's not going to get. Bud and
the owners will see this as a chance to get rid of Richie and break
the union.''
</P>
<P>
   Phillips is counting on baseball's experience with replacement
umpires to prompt Selig and Sandy Alderson, who has been the point
man in umpiring matters, to negotiate a deal by Sept. 2. In
previous work stoppages, everyone, including fans, has clamored for
the return of the regular umpires once the replacements missed a
few calls.
</P>
<P>
   For now, though, officials are buoyed in their resolve to hold
firm by the reaction of fans and news media critics. Fans at
major-league parks have booed the umpires, and columnists have
blistered the umpires in virtually unanimous fashion.
</P>
<P>
   Club owners, who have been described as ``enraged,'' are urging
Selig to adopt a hard-line stance. The umpires will find no
supporters in the players. ``Whatever happens, the game will go on,
and the players will deal with it,'' said the Yankees' David Cone,
the union's American League player representative.
</P>
<P>
   The umpires will be alone as they march toward Sept. 2, their
letters of resignation perhaps serving as death warrants. Phillips
is betting otherwise, but this is by far his biggest gamble.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
