A3892 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-CAMPS-NYT &LR;      07-17 0916
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-CAMPS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE LANDSCAPE CHANGES FOR LAST SEASON'S TOP 4 
</HEADLINE>
  (jt) 
 By MIKE FREEMAN    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   When we last left the National Football League's final foursome
_ Denver, the New York Jets, Minnesota and Atlanta _ each team was
vowing it would return to at least the conference championships. It
is easy to understand why.
</P>
<P>
   John Elway was still hinting he might come back to the Broncos'
corral. Jets players, at a postseason party soon after arriving
home from the conference championship loss to Denver, said they
were going to be the team to beat. The Vikings were in a state of
depression but eagerly looked forward to proving their season was
no fluke, while the Falcons took up residence on cloud nine.
</P>
<P>
   Things change quickly. Elway retired and was replaced at
quarterback by Bubby Brister. Two Jets players were arrested this
past week after getting into a fracas in a Long Island, N.Y., bar.
The Falcons and their star running back, Jamal Anderson, are in a
bitter contract dispute.
</P>
<P>
   And Minnesota? Despite the bitter loss to Atlanta, Vikings
players are mentally strong.
</P>
<P>
   Training camps across the league open this week, and certainly
the status of the top four from last season is among the flashier
story lines, but in fact almost each franchise has something
interesting going on.
</P>
<P>
   One good example is the expansion Cleveland Browns. The rookies,
who include quarterback Tim Couch, the No. 1 draft pick overall,
report on Wednesday. At some point Coach Chris Palmer plans on
showing a tape to the team about the history of the Browns'
franchise.
</P>
<P>
   Giants' rookies and veterans are scheduled to report July 29 in
Albany. One day later, the Jets' camp begins at Hofstra University
in Hempstead on Long Island.
</P>
<P>
   As for the rest of the league, everything begins with the
Broncos, who will be without Elway for the first time in 16 years.
Opposing coaches and players have doubts that Brister can lead
Denver to another Super Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   Because of that, the Jets are considered the favorite to win the
American Football Conference, though that could depend on the
status of offensive linemen Jumbo Elliott and Jason Fabini. Those
two were involved in a scuffle at a bar last weekend that resulted
in the arrest of Elliott, Fabini, and the Cincinnati Bengal lineman
Matt O'Dwyer, formerly a Jet. Originally, it was thought that
Elliott, who was accused of punching a woman during the incident,
might face a suspension under the league's violent-crime policy.
</P>
<P>
   But the league's decision about Lawrence Phillips, who pleaded
no contest to an assault against a woman in Miami last year, might
have been a break for Elliott. The league announced that if
Phillips rejoins the league after playing in NFL Europe this
spring, he will receive a substantial fine, but not a suspension,
after he signs a contract.
</P>
<P>
   In the National Football Conference, the Falcons are a different
team from the one that upset the Vikings. Wide receiver Tony
Martin, accused by the federal government of laundering drug money,
left for Miami. Linebacker Cornelius Bennett and safety William
White, both leaders on defense, are gone, too.
</P>
<P>
   The Falcons may have made a mistake in alienating Anderson, who
wants a deal in the vicinity of what Denver's Terrell Davis earns,
which is $56 million over nine years. The Falcons are balking, and
during the April draft they explored trading Anderson, who could
miss the start of camp July 28 over his contract dispute. Some
Falcon players are angry at the way the team is treating Anderson.
</P>
<P>
   The Vikings are the only team of the four that seems in perfect
harmony. Minnesota lost no major free agents, wide receiver Randy
Moss has stayed out of trouble, and there was an extra sense of
urgency at Cris Carter's annual training camp. Minnesota, for now,
is focused.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're looking forward to this season,'' Coach Denny Green
said. ``I don't think you'll see this team take a step back.''
</P>
<P>
   Training camp is a time when every team is optimistic. Right
now, around the league, coaches are returning from their vacations
and dreaming of a championship. Here's how the divisions should
actually shake down in December:
</P>
<P>
   AFC EAST: Buffalo, behind quarterback Doug Flutie, should win at
least nine games. Indianapolis is not ready to challenge for the
division title. New England needs a proven running back. Miami made
some interesting moves this off-season _ possibly dangerous ones _
by picking up Martin and drafting the troubled running back Cecil
Collins.
</P>
<P>
   AFC CENTRAL: The Baltimore Ravens could surprise some teams
thanks to the offense of their new coach, Brian Billick. The
Bengals are the Bengals. In Pittsburgh, quarterback Kordell Stewart
has a new contract. The Tennessee Titans, formerly the Oilers, seem
poised to make a playoff run. The team to watch in this division is
Jacksonville; the Jaguars are capable of getting to the Super Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   AFC WEST: Even if Brister is so-so for the Broncos, the
defending Super Bowl champions still have enough firepower to win
11 games.
</P>
<P>
   NFC EAST: The Giants, if their quarterback situation settles
down, will probably fight Arizona for the division title.
</P>
<P>
   NFC CENTRAL: The Vikings should win the division, but Green Bay
and Tampa Bay will be only a half-step behind. The Lions are still
panicking about Barry Sanders, who isn't answering their calls.
</P>
<P>
   NFC WEST: It's a two-team race between the Falcons and the
49ers.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-17-99 1355EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990717.0113 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> MISCELLANEOUS TEXT (slug-filter) </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-17 14:04 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3895 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBO-NOTEBOOK-NYT &LR;      07-17 1251
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-NOTEBOOK-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHECKING IN WITH A WORKHORSE 
</HEADLINE>
  (jt) 
 By MURRAY CHASS    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   They don't make them like Warren Spahn anymore.
</P>
<P>
   In a 17-season span from 1947 through 1963, he averaged 35
starts, 21 complete games, 278 innings and 20 victories a season.
He was a 20-game winner 13 times and led the National League in
victories eight times, including in five successive seasons. He
pitched a no-hitter in 1960 at age 39, then pitched another in 1961
five days after his 40th birthday. Pitching at age 42, he matched
his career high in victories with 23 in 1963.
</P>
<P>
   Spahn, the No. 1 left-handed winner in history with 363
victories, follows baseball closely and, not surprisingly, he
doesn't like the pitching developments he has seen.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's what baseball does today,'' he replied on the day of the
All-Star Game in Boston, where he was asked for his views on
pitching circa 1999. ``They count pitches. They pitch once a week.
I don't approve of those things. I don't agree, but that's baseball
today.''
</P>
<P>
   Did all of that pitching he did, starting every fourth day,
sometimes every third, have any ill effects on him?
</P>
<P>
   ``No,'' he said, dismissing the notion as absurd. ``One of the
things I dislike about baseball today is we've made nonathletes out
of pitchers. They pitch once a week. They count the pitches. They
don't hit. they don't run the bases. That's not my kind of
baseball.''
</P>
<P>
   And one more thing. ``Everybody in baseball is crying about
pitching and they've got 10 guys sitting there that aren't
pitching,'' Spahn said. ``Why? I don't know.''
</P>
<P>
   Are the pitch count and the radar gun the two worst things that
have happened to pitching? ``I think so,'' he said. ``That's my
opinion. Today's baseball came up with the gun and everybody's
impressed if you throw 98 miles an hour, but nobody talks about
what the ball does.''
</P>
<P>
   Spahn, whose victory total is fifth highest in the history of
baseball and the most since Grover Cleveland Alexander, who retired
in 1930 with 373, is a spry 78-year-old Hall of Famer who sees
little to like when he looks at pitching in the major leagues.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Atlanta Braves are probably a throwback to what we were,''
he said, standing outside so he could smoke. ``They have their
pitchers throw every day, they pitch in a regular rotation and they
have been successful. Look at the guys they've come up with.''
</P>
<P>
   And look at their pitching coach. There is a link between Spahn
and that coach, Leo Mazzone. His name is Johnny Sain, as in ``Spahn
and Sain and pray for rain.'' Later, when Sain was a pitching coach
in the Atlanta organization, Mazzone became a disciple.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know,'' Spahn said when the connection was mentioned. ``I
was in Atlanta, and Leo wanted to pick my brain about pitching.
He's smart. He'll listen. He wants information, and he'll use that
information, so that makes him a good coach. You look around the
league and see who the pitching coaches are, and what did they ever
accomplish to be the one to say this is what you should do, young
man?''
</P>
<P>
   Mazzone, who as the Braves' pitching coach has supervised the
best starting rotation of the 1990s, first encountered Sain in West
Palm Beach, Fla., in 1979. Sain was in charge of pitching in the
Braves' minor-league system, and Mazzone was a 30-year-old Class A
pitching coach.
</P>
<P>
   ``He took me under his wing,'' Mazzone said. ``Every night he'd
invite me to his trailer and barbecue. He'd make me some beans and
cornbread and we talked pitching every night that entire spring. I
realized that he had something to offer that nobody else I had come
into contact with had.''
</P>
<P>
   Mazzone listened to Spahn's former pitching partner and learned.
Contrary to the method that prevails now, Sain taught that pitchers
should throw in some manner every day. That's what Mazzone's
pitchers do.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of things you see with our pitching comes from Johnny
Sain and what they used to do in the '60s,'' Mazzone said.
</P>
<P>
   It's no surprise, then, that Spahn should like the Braves and
have no use for those newfangled pitching practices.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you're going to be stronger with rest, why aren't pitchers
strong at the beginning of the year?'' Spahn asked. ``But you got
to get your arm in shape. I think under the present system they
never get their arm in shape, and that's probably why they have the
injuries they have.''
</P>
<P>
   Jewish Players Are Catching On
</P>
<P>
   Even before the All-Star Game began, it had a record: most
Jewish players on the All-Star teams. Outfielder Shawn Green of
Toronto and catcher Brad Ausmus of Detroit were American League
reserves; catcher Mike Lieberthal of Philadelphia was a National
League reserve.
</P>
<P>
   Asked why the number of Jewish players in the major leagues has
``proliferated,'' Green said: ``I think Jewish parents are so
focused on education and studying that there wasn't much emphasis
on sports. I think now maybe kids are getting a little more
involved and playing a little more and getting out there as much as
anybody is.''
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this year it was pointed out to Lieberthal that he,
Ausmus and Jesse Levis, who not long ago played for the Milwaukee
Brewers, were all catchers and that Jewish kids were thought to be
too smart to subject themselves to the rigors of that position.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are smart,'' Lieberthal countered with a smile. ``You don't
have to hit to catch. We don't have to hit 40 homers. We don't have
to run. We don't have to steal bases. All you have to do is catch,
and you'll be in this league forever. We get beat up a little bit,
but it's the quickest way to the major leagues.''
</P>
<P>
   Tough Luck in Arizona
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a bit comical in some light,'' Randy Johnson said, ``but
it's a bit scary, like a Stephen King book.'' And that was before
Johnson left a game against Texas with a 2-0 lead, only to have
Arizona's new closer, Matt Mantei, give up three runs in the ninth
inning.
</P>
<P>
   Finding his fortunes had not changed after the All-Star Game
break, Johnson suffered yet another lost night. At least he wasn't
charged with the loss. But in his last five starts, Johnson has won
not once while allowing 5 earned runs (6 total) and 25 hits and
striking out 62 in 40 innings. The Diamondbacks have scored a total
of two runs and collected 13 hits. His record is 9-7; it
could-should _ be 14-3.
</P>
<P>
   Weary of talking about his hard luck, Johnson revealed that he
could have signed with Anaheim if the Angels' ownership had been
more responsive to his questions.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were in meetings with the Angels and extremely close to
going with them,'' Johnson said. ``It was a matter of getting some
answers. When we needed some answers from ownership, we were
getting them right away from Jerry Colangelo. The Disney people
that own the Angels took a little bit longer.''
</P>
<P>
   What was his rush? ``I didn't relish being in this position,''
he said. ``It was kind of stressful. I wanted to get it over with
so I would know where I was going to be.''
</P>
<P>
   Among the questions Johnson sought answers to: ``I wanted to
know if ownership would be willing to go out and get somebody in
July when the team was a player away.''
</P>
<P>
   No answer was forthcoming from the Angels. Colangelo, the
Diamondbacks' managing partner, replied promptly. ``He said he had
no problem doing that,'' Johnson said. ``I think what he has done
for this team speaks for itself.''
</P>
<P>
   Even with the torturous streak, Johnson said, ``I don't regret
any decision I made.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
