<HEADLINE>
WEATHER 
</HEADLINE>
  (Editors: The following text accompanies the weather map for
Sunday, July 18, sent to computer graphics clients of The New York
Times News Service. For information call: 888-603-1036.) 
(js) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NATIONAL FORECAST
</P>
<P>
   The second heat wave of the summer along the Atlantic Seaboard
will pass its peak Sunday as a push of sultry air from the South
precedes a weakening cool front. With hazy sunshine, readings will
rise from values near 80 degrees at sunrise to the middle 90s in
many sections from southern New England to the Carolinas. Sultry
breezes will gust over 20 miles per hour in the Northeast.
</P>
<P>
   Thunderstorms will form over the Appalachians around midday and
may organize into a squall line as they move toward the Northeast
coast. Strong winds and small hail could accompany many of the
storms, perhaps leading to spotty power outages.
</P>
<P>
   Clouds and thundershowers will cling to the Southeast coast,
with the most numerous storms in the eastern parts of the
Carolinas. The uneven heating of the Smokey Mountains will promote
a few storms. Florida will notice thunderstorms along both coasts.
</P>
<P>
   A stream of very humid air moving northward through the
Mississippi Valley will encounter a jet stream disturbance along a
stalled front in Iowa. This will lead to a complex of thunderstorms
in the Middle West. As sultry air rises over more comfortable air
in the northeast Plains, more thundershowers will develop.
</P>
<P>
   There will be a concentration of thunderstorms in the Four
Corners region, with some storms moving east into the central
Plains. Low pressure in the Northwest will keep conditions cool and
dull in Washington. Much of the Southwest will be bright and warm. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Focus: Hazy Skies
</P>
<P>
   The heat and humidity in the East this weekend would not be
complete without the mention of haze. Haze is not just pollution,
as it occurs even in the cleanest environments of the polar
regions. Most often, haze is found in the middle latitudes during
the summer season when the winds aloft become very light. The weak
winds allow for considerable vertical mixing in the lower
atmosphere. As a result, dust, pollen and pollutants are carried
higher into the atmosphere than usual. The presence of humid air
can also produce numerous water droplets that adhere to the tiny
solid particles.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
