<P>
   HURRICANE-BIGONE _ NEW ORLEANS _They call it the Big One, the
dreaded hurricane that would hit New Orleans in just the right
place and with just the right force to turn this city into a giant
lake.The Big One hasn't hit in modern times, but last September, it
came so close, you could almost smell it. That close call, combined
with predictions of a busy 1999 hurricane season, has given many
residents the jitters. (Konigsmark, Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
25.
</P>
<P>
   HOSPITAL-WASTE _ DAYTON, Ohio _ During a routine inspection of a
truck hauling trash this month, workers at BFI's recycling transfer
station outside of Cincinnati discovered what looked like blood
coming from one of the bags. They found that some of the bags
contained hazardous medical wastes _ bloody gauze, surgical gowns
and other operating room equipment. When on July 8 biomedical
wastes were found a second time, it prompted a review by the Ohio
Environmental Protection Agency and the Middletown Health
Department of the Middletown hospital's waste handling, a crucial
procedure that a recent study says needs to be improved at many
hospitals around the country. (Dempsey/Mong, Dayton Daily News)
MOVED
</P>
<P>
   BORDER-PROTECTORS _ MATAMOROS, Tamaulipas _ In a narrow ravine
on the Mexican side of the Rio Grande, four would-be illegal
immigrants huddled together, waiting for opportunity. That's when
the flashlight beam from above found them. ``Come on out,
muchachos, don't be scared,'' said the man in the faded jeans with
the pistol on his hip. After the group reluctantly climbed up into
the warm night air, Erazmo Antonio Alaniz tried to ease their
fears. Alaniz, a 27-year-old Matamoros police officer, is part of
Mexico's own small but growing border patrol, a collection of
police and immigration officers assigned to protect the hundreds of
thousands of migrants who cross the border into the United States
every year. (Harmon, Austin American-Statesman) MOVED
</P>
