<SLUG> BC-FBN-NOTEBOOK-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MODELL AND CLEVELAND BOTH STILL BITTER 
</HEADLINE>
  (jt) 
 By MIKE FREEMAN    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Two years after Art Modell moved his team from Cleveland to
Baltimore, one of the most controversial acts in the history of the
National Football League, he was asked if he felt his chances of
being elected to the Hall of Fame had evaporated. ``I think that
ship has sailed,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Modell left Cleveland in 1995, a move that left the city furious
with Modell and Modell angry with Cleveland. The city feels he
violated its trust and toyed with one of the league's beloved
franchises. Modell believes politicians and civic leaders lied to
him.
</P>
<P>
   Even now the city and Modell remain angry at each other. Modell
has not been back to Cleveland since the move to Baltimore, and he
vows never to return. When the Ravens' vice president for player
personnel, Ozzie Newsome, a former Browns receiver and a close
friend of Modell's, is inducted into the Hall of Fame next month,
Modell will not attend the ceremony in Canton, Ohio, just 49 miles
from Cleveland. He says he does not want to be a distraction.
</P>
<P>
   ``I will never go back to Cleveland, ever,'' Modell said, ``and
the fact I cannot see my good friend Ozzie inducted really hurts
me.''
</P>
<P>
   The decision Modell made to move the team has unfortunately
overshadowed more than three decades of outstanding service to pro
football. There are some fans, members of the news media and
politicians who maintain that Modell's move of the Browns, and
especially the manner in which he did it, should keep him out of
the hall.
</P>
<P>
   That would be a travesty. Modell could certainly have handled
the move better. He should have given the city an ultimatum: help
build a new stadium or else. Instead, he negotiated secretly with
Baltimore and then sprang the devastating news on Cleveland.
</P>
<P>
   Yet Modell's move now seems more benign, with Cleveland having a
new Browns expansion franchise and the act of relocating a team
having become as common as the cold. The Oakland owner Al Davis is
in the hall, though he has moved the Raiders twice. Bob Kraft has
been accused of using the state of Connecticut to get a better deal
from Massachusetts for his New England Patriots. And the Arizona
Cardinals are always threatening to move a second time.
</P>
<P>
   Few owners in league history have contributed as much as Modell.
He spent 32 years on the television committee and, with the former
commissioner Pete Rozelle, helped marry television to the NFL. The
billions of dollars the league now receives from the networks can
be traced in significant measure to Modell's efforts.
</P>
<P>
   Modell has served on the league's management council and various
labor committees, and he is the former chairman of the commissioner
selection committee. He realized the potential power of preseason
football and pushed for the NFL to promote it on television.
</P>
<P>
   Modell has not won a Super Bowl championship but neither did the
New Orleans general manager Jim Finks or the Los Angeles Rams owner
Dan Reeves, and both are enshrined in Canton.
</P>
<P>
   The Modell name in Cleveland is associated with treachery. But
that is simplistic. Fearing that estate taxes might force the sale
of the team after his death, Modell moved for financial reasons,
mainly so he could leave something for his family.
</P>
<P>
   Cleveland again has a team, and Modell is happy in Baltimore.
Both parties need to put what happened behind them, and Modell
should be remembered not solely for what happened in Cleveland. He
has been too influential in pro football to be judged on that act
alone.
</P>
<P>
   `Arliss' at Work
</P>
<P>
   Every year it's the same silly song. General managers complain
that agents impede negotiations with rookies chosen in the draft
simply because they want to break the bank. Agents respond by
claiming general managers are trying to low-ball their clients.
Isn't there a rule about whining in football?
</P>
<P>
   This year, however, the general managers may have legitimate
complaints. Draft pick signings have been extremely slow. With two
weeks to go until training camps begin in full force, only five
first-round picks have been signed. It's worse with
second-rounders; just four have contracts.
</P>
<P>
   No one keeps records on this sort of thing, but these numbers
are among the lowest in the '90s for this time of year, team
executives and agents agree. And the agents are probably to blame.
</P>
<P>
   In their increasingly competitive world, there are fights for
clients that resemble small wars. Each day in the agent business is
like an episode from ``Arliss.''
</P>
<P>
   Because of the competition, agents are making more and more
promises to clients, some legitimate and others outrageous. One of
the more bogus ones is the following.
</P>
<P>
   The agent claims to a prospective client that he can beat the
strict pay system set up by the NFL for rookies. Each salary is
slotted under the system, so that the pay for the 14th pick in the
third round, for example, is predetermined by a complicated salary
cap. There isn't much leeway unless there are highly unusual
circumstances.
</P>
<P>
   When agents say during the hotly contested recruiting battles
that they can beat the system, some players, highly gullible,
believe it and sign on.
</P>
<P>
   Now comes the month of July. The team wants to get a deal done,
but the agent resists, asking for a salary above the slotted
amount, knowing he probably will not get it. But he can't give in
too quickly because his rookie client might suspect that the
promise was a sham. So the agent waits. And waits. And waits. He
delays as long as possible, then goes back to the client, saying it
is time to sign because he has fought the team as long as possible
and the team is not giving in.
</P>
<P>
   For these and other reasons, the delays in the signing process
continue. Although they are not a recent phenomenon, it does seem
to be an increasing problem.
</P>
<P>
   Moore Waits for Sanders
</P>
<P>
   The Lions would like to sign the Pro Bowler Herman Moore to a
new deal that would possibly make him one of the highest-paid wide
receivers, earning in the $5 million-a-year range. There is a Hall
of Fame impediment to the signing, however: his name is Barry
Sanders.
</P>
<P>
   Sanders remains out of contact with the Lions, not returning
telephone calls from team executives and members of the coaching
staff. In fact, he has not spoken to the team since the end of last
season. His status remains questionable, and there is a
possibility, albeit remote, that he might sit out the year.
</P>
<P>
   Sanders, who has won just one playoff game in his 11-year
career, wants to join a winning team.
</P>
<P>
   There remain persistent rumors that the Lions are attempting to
trade Sanders, something the team strongly denies.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
