<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990717.0119 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-17 14:27 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3903 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-APOLLO-18-COX     07-17 1338
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-APOLLO-18-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Prospecting for water on the moon
 &HT;    By Timothy R. Gaffney
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ Thirty years since the first humans blasted off
for the moon, America is about to land on the moon again _ hard.
</P>
<P>
   On July 31, a 354-pound spacecraft named Lunar Prospector will
dive into a crater at the moon's south pole with the force of a
four-ton car moving at 1,100 miles per hour.
</P>
<P>
   In the last dramatic act of a successful mission, the little
spacecraft will destroy itself for the sake of science.
</P>
<P>
   It's a brute-force way of returning to the moon, but Alan
Binder, the man who conceived Lunar Prospector and the program's
lead scientist, hopes the impact will kick up a bit more evidence _
namely, water _ to support arguments in favor of returning to the
moon.
</P>
<P>
   Since January 1998, the drum-shaped spacecraft has been circling
the moon in an orbit that passes over both poles. Its five sensors
have mapped elements in the moon's ancient crust, including dense
areas of hydrogen atoms. Binder says it's strong evidence _ though
not proof _ that billions of tons of water lie frozen in the
permanently shadowed bottoms of deep craters at the moon's poles.
</P>
<P>
   Large water deposits could help supply a moon base, and Binder,
a longtime lunar scientist, hopes Lunar Prospector's findings will
help revive public interest in the idea.
</P>
<P>
   He also hopes Lunar Prospector's shoestring budget _ just $63
million, including the rocket that launched it _ show that lunar
exploration can be affordable.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's where I think man will start his first extraterrestrial
base and colony, and it's a stepping stone for the rest of the
solar system,'' he said last month from from the National
Aeronautics and Space Administration's Ames Research Center in
California, where he directs the mission.
</P>
<P>
   America was moonstruck early in the space age. In 1961,
President Kennedy challenged the nation to put a man on the moon
and return him safely to earth by the end of the decade. Just eight
years later, on July 20, 1969, Apollo 11 astronauts Neil Armstrong
and Buzz Aldrin became the first humans to walk on the moon.
</P>
<P>
   But Americans quickly lost interest after meeting Kennedy's
challenge. The last of six Apollo moon landings took place in
December 1972.
</P>
<P>
   In 1994, the 25th anniversary year of Apollo 11, a Defense
Department satellite dubbed Clementine orbited the moon for about
three months as part of a technology demonstration. Radio waves it
bounced off the bottoms of craters at the moon's poles showed
tantalizing signs of ice.
</P>
<P>
   Clementine's well-timed findings stirred new interest in the
moon, and the news media followed Lunar Prospector's launch on Jan.
6, 1998. Five days later, it became the first dedicated U.S. moon
mission to enter lunar orbit since Apollo.
</P>
<P>
   After completing its one-year primary mission, the hardy
spacecraft was still running strong, so Binder lowered its orbit to
continue its mapping in greater detail. Now the spacecraft whips
around the moon just 15 to 19 miles above its dusty mountains and
plains.
</P>
<P>
   Lunar Prospector was doomed to crash eventually, because the
moon's uneven gravitational field upsets its orbit. Binder said it
has always been his goal to use its remaining rocket fuel to
``smash the spacecraft into something interesting.''
</P>
<P>
   It's a long shot, Binder cautioned, but with luck Lunar
Prospector will hit a bed of ice suspected to lie at the bottom of
a deep crater. With more luck, the crash will throw up a plume of
water molecules just big enough for telescopes on earth to detect
it.
</P>
<P>
   A spurt of water molecules from the crash would prove the
existence of water on the moon.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't know if it's water. We believe it is but we have no
real proof,'' Binder said. ``This is a way to use the spacecraft to
get the last drop of science out of it.''
</P>
<P>
   Some scientists have long believed craters at the poles, where
the sun barely peeks above the horizon, could trap water as ice in
their permanently shadowed depths. Prior to Clementine, lunar
missions only explored a narrow band along the moon's equator.
</P>
<P>
   Lunar Prospector's data indicates some six billion of tons of
water may lie in frozen pools or mixed with soil. The findings
excite some space advocates who say it could cut the cost of space
exploration by providing a source for water, air and rocket fuel
(water can be split into oxygen and hydrogen.)
</P>
<P>
   Exploring the moon is what Binder, a lunar scientist since the
1960s, thinks humans should do next in space. Not surprisingly, he
thinks President Nixon was wrong to terminate the Apollo program
and cancel its last two scheduled missions.
</P>
<P>
   ``(Apollo) should never have ended in my opinion, and if it
hadn't we'd already be on the moon permanently,'' Binder asserted.
</P>
<P>
   Binder has been trying to restart the earth's exploration of the
moon almost since it ended with Luna 24, a Soviet robot lander that
scooped up soil samples in 1976.
</P>
<P>
   Teaching in Germany, he advised the European Space Agency on its
plans for a lunar orbiter and later developed a proposal for a
joint U.S.-German program to study the moon with a series of robot
landers.
</P>
<P>
   Returning to the U.S. in 1983, Binder said he was struck by the
ponderous pace and astronomical expense of NASA's space science
programs. He proposed Lunar Prospector as a model for cheap, simple
space missions.
</P>
<P>
   In the 1990s, NASA Administrator Dan Goldin began pushing the
concept of ``faster, better, cheaper'' space science missions.
Lunar Prospector became the first mission under its no-frills
Discovery program.
</P>
<P>
   Binder said Lunar Prospector operates more like a commercial
operation than typical NASA missions. NASA funded the program, but
Binder said he's operating the spacecraft for NASA as an
independent contractor.
</P>
<P>
   ``What I deliver to NASA is simply the data,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Ultimately, Binder wants to find private investors to fund lunar
exploration as a commercial enterprise. Instead of funding the
operation up front, NASA would pay for the scientific results as
they were produced.
</P>
<P>
   Binder envisions a series of unmanned moon landers and rovers
that would lead to the establishment of a manned lunar base.
</P>
<P>
   ``We know how to build a lunar base. We've known that for years
and years and years, but it's a matter of taking all the studies
that have been done and actually doing it,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   And doing it more efficiently than NASA has done other programs,
such as the long-overdue International Space Station.
</P>
<P>
   Binder claims a base could be built using off-the-shelf hardware
for about $10 billion - less than half the cost of the space
station, although the moon base would get part of its cost savings
by using hardware developed for the space station.
</P>
<P>
   Binder believes it's time to get back to the moon, and the
sooner the better.
</P>
<P>
   ``We would hope this would all culminate in a lunar base, in
say, 2010, which would really be the beginnings of the colonization
of the moon,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But in the meantime, Binder admits he's having a lot of fun with
Lunar Prospector.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm flying a live spacecraft around the moon,'' he marveled.
``This is great fun. As I keep telling everybody, I have the best
computer game in the world.''
</P>
<P>
   On the Net
</P>
<P>
   _ Lunar Prospector Home Page
</P>
<P>
   http://lunar.arc.nasa.gov/
</P>
<P>
   _ NASA's Apollo 11 Anniversary home page
</P>
<P>
   http://www.hq.nasa.gov/office/pao/History/ap11ann/eagle.html
</P>
<P>
   _ Lunar Prospector
</P>
<P>
   BUILDER: Lockheed Martin Corp. Missiles and Space Division
</P>
<P>
   PRINCIPAL INVESTIGATOR: Alan Binder
</P>
<P>
   DESCRIPTION: Low cost lunar satellite built from off-the-shelf
parts
</P>
<P>
   MISSION: Map the elemental composition of the moon's crust and
search for evidence of water
</P>
<P>
   HEIGHT: 4 feet 3 inches
</P>
<P>
   WIDTH: 4 feet six inches
</P>
<P>
   WEIGHT: 650 fueled, 354 pounds at mission end.
</P>
<P>
   LAUNCH DATE: Jan. 6, 1998
</P>
<P>
   IMPACT DATE: July 31, 1999
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
