<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-17 14:27 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3904 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-APOLLO-LANDING18-COX     07-17 0949
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-APOLLO-LANDING18-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    A safe landing off Sea of Tranquility
 &HT;    By Timothy R. Gaffney
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Editor's note: This account is based on an annotated NASA
transcript of Apollo 11 communications.
</P>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ In the infinite vastness of deep space, two
gleaming spacecraft drew apart as they sailed 69 miles above the
gray, forbidding landscape of the moon.
</P>
<P>
   A quarter-million miles from earth, Michael Collins watched in
Apollo 11's command module Columbia as Wapakoneta native Neil
Armstrong and Edwin ``Buz'' Aldrin slid away in the lunar module
Eagle.
</P>
<P>
   Eagle was a boxy-looking spaceship with four spiderlike landing
legs. Inside, it was so small and Spartan it didn't even have
seats. Armstrong and Aldrin flew in a standing position, clad in
their white moonsuits.
</P>
<P>
   Four days earlier, on July 16, 1969, they had blasted off from
Florida on a Saturn 5 rocket to make the first human landing on the
moon.
</P>
<P>
   Now it was time.
</P>
<P>
   ``See you later,'' Armstrong radioed Collins.
</P>
<P>
   As they looped behind the moon, Armstrong and Aldrin fired
Eagle's descent engine to drop it into a 69-by-10 mile orbit. If
everything went well, the engine would fire again when they reached
the low point, and this time it would keep firing in a powered
descent all the way to the lunar surface.
</P>
<P>
   But problems cropped up from the moment Eagle came back around
the moon and made radio contact with Mission Control in Houston,
Texas. Its radio signal _ the astronauts' voices and the vital data
from Eagle's systems _ kept cutting in and out. They had to keep
turning the lander or switch antennas to regain contact.
</P>
<P>
   Mission controllers got enough data to see that Eagle was in
good shape. Back in Houston, fellow astronaut Charlie Duke manned
the radio: ``Eagle, Houston. If you read, you're go for powered
descent.''
</P>
<P>
   Collins had to relay the news to his crewmates while they worked
to re-establish contact with Houston. But the rest of the countdown
went smoothly and the descent engine fired right on schedule.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ignition,'' Armstrong and Aldrin chorused.
</P>
<P>
   With the engine braking its speed, Eagle fell in a long arc
towards the Sea of Tranquility _ a dark, flat plain on the near
side of the moon.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everything is looking good here,'' Duke radioed.
</P>
<P>
   Eagle was traveling tail first with its windows facing the
cratered lunar surface. Timing landmarks as they went by, Armstrong
realized Eagle was farther downrange than it was supposed to be.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're long,'' he said to Aldrin.
</P>
<P>
   Following the schedule, Armstrong rolled Eagle on its back to
point its landing radar toward the surface. The radar came to life;
steering jets fired, jolting the astronauts as it made corrections.
</P>
<P>
   But the radar's data was flooding Eagle's tiny computer memory.
An alarm buzzed loudly.
</P>
<P>
   ``Program alarm,'' Armstrong called out. ``It's a 1202.''
</P>
<P>
   This was an alarm neither he nor Aldrin recognized from
simulations. For all they knew, they might have to abort the
landing at any second _ a disappointing and dangerous procedure.
</P>
<P>
   But Houston quickly analyzed the situation and decided the
computer was OK.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're go on that alarm,'' Duke said. The alarm kept sounding,
but each time Houston judged it OK.
</P>
<P>
   At 7,500 feet above the moon, Eagle began pitching over into
landing position. Armstrong looked out his window across the
cratered Sea of Tranquility. He was trying to judge their touchdown
point, but the computer kept triggering alarms, each time raising
the possibility of an abort. Houston continued to tell them ``go,''
but the constant alarms distracted Armstrong.
</P>
<P>
   Now they were just 1,000 feet up, and Eagle was taking them
right towards a crater littered with boulders the size of cars.
</P>
<P>
   ``Pretty rocky area,'' Armstrong said.
</P>
<P>
   He took control of the lunar module to slow its descent and flew
past the crater. The ground coming up was still thick with
dangerous boulders. Armstrong slowed the craft again while he
scanned the ground for a clear spot.
</P>
<P>
   Eagle dropped below 300 feet, and Armstrong spotted a likely
site.
</P>
<P>
   ``OK. Here's a ... Looks like a good area here,'' he said, but a
moment later he decided it wasn't safe. He flew on while precious
fuel, altitude and time dwindled.
</P>
<P>
   A light came on, indicating only a minute's worth of fuel
remained.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sixty seconds,'' Duke warned.
</P>
<P>
   But Armstrong had found a landing spot, and he was easing Eagle
down and forward towards it.
</P>
<P>
   Aldrin chanted the altitude and rate of descent: ``Forty feet,
down 2 1/2. Picking up some dust.''
</P>
<P>
   The rocket's exhaust gases reached the surface. Dust streaked
out in all directions through the airless void, obscuring
Armstrong's view of the ground. He brought Eagle down gently,
fighting its sudden tendency to drift.
</P>
<P>
   ``Thirty seconds,'' Duke warned. Their fuel was all but gone.
</P>
<P>
   Ten-foot-long landing probes sticking down from three of Eagle's
landing pads touched the moon.
</P>
<P>
   ``Contact light,'' Aldrin said.
</P>
<P>
   Armstrong was supposed to cut the engine and let the lunar
module drop the last few feet, because engineers feared the
rocket's exhaust so close to the ground could bounce back into the
engine and blow it up.
</P>
<P>
   But Armstrong was completely focused on the landing; he touched
down so gently that neither man felt a bump.
</P>
<P>
   ``Shutdown,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The astronauts quickly went through their post-landing
checklist. Then they turned to each other, grinned through their
bubble helmets, and shook hands.
</P>
<P>
   ``Houston, Tranquility base here,'' Armstrong radioed. ``The
Eagle has landed.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-17-99 1427EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990717.0121 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-17 14:27 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3905 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BORDER-PROTECTORS18-C     07-17 1529
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BORDER-PROTECTORS18-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Little known Mexican police group protects immigrants trekking
to U.S.
 &HT;    By Dave Harmon
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   MATAMOROS, Tamaulipas _ In a narrow ravine on the Mexican side
of the Rio Grande, hidden from the U.S. Border Patrol's floodlights
and night-vision scopes, four would-be illegal immigrants huddled
together, waiting for opportunity.
</P>
<P>
   That's when the flashlight beam from above found them.
</P>
<P>
   ``Come on out, muchachos, don't be scared,'' said the man in the
faded jeans with the pistol on his hip. They hesitated. He could
have been one of the river bandits who prey on those preparing to
sneak into the United States. Or a crooked cop trying to shake them
down for cash. He could have been anybody.
</P>
<P>
   After the group reluctantly climbed up into the warm night air,
Erazmo Antonio Alaniz tried to ease their fears.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm with Grupo Beta,'' he told them. ``My job is to help you,
protect you, and make sure nobody harms you.''
</P>
<P>
   Alaniz, a 27-year-old Matamoros police officer, is part of
Mexico's own small but growing border patrol, a collection of
police and immigration officers assigned to protect the hundreds of
thousands of migrants who cross the border into the United States
every year.
</P>
<P>
   Their mission is to arrest the bandits, narcotics traffickers
and immigrant smugglers who operate on the border, Alaniz said.
They do not interfere with people trying to cross into the United
States, which is not a crime in Mexico. Instead, they emphasize the
dangers of the journey: pamphlets they hand out have titles such
as, ``Migrant woman: sexual violence is a real problem. Let us help
you!''
</P>
<P>
   The Mexican government launched the first Grupo Beta _
literally, Group B _ eight years ago in Tijuana, Baja California,
to crack down on border bandits who routinely robbed, raped, and
murdered migrants in the canyons south of San Diego. Since then,
five more units have formed in cities along the U.S.-Mexico border.
Two additional units patrol Mexico's border with Guatemala, the
main route for Central Americans heading to the United States.
</P>
<P>
   ``(The criminals) take everything from them _ their money, their
pants, even their shoes,'' said Gregorio Gerardo Montalvo, a state
police officer assigned to Grupo Beta in Matamoros.
</P>
<P>
   Four years after the Matamoros unit became the first and only
Beta team on the Texas-Mexico border, its agents have formed close
ties with the U.S. Border Patrol. Despite their different missions,
the two agencies stay in constant contact via radio, advising each
other about possible criminal activity near the Rio Grande.
</P>
<P>
   ``If there's any problem along the river, Grupo Beta is there to
respond to it,'' said Ernesto Castillo, the patrol agent in charge
of the Border Patrol's Brownsville station. ``They don't alert us
when anyone is crossing, they don't have to _ we're there. Their
job is to make sure that anyone on that riverbank is safe.''
</P>
<P>
   Border Patrol supervisor Jaime Salazar said his agents recently
came upon a group of smugglers hauling bundles of marijuana across
the river. When the smugglers spotted the agents and swam back into
Mexico, Salazar said, they summoned Grupo Beta members, who made
the arrest.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're currently serving time in the Mexican judicial
system,'' Salazar said. ``Whereas in the past, that probably
wouldn't happen _ we would have had the marijuana, but these guys
would have gone scot free.''
</P>
<P>
   ``In the past, the river used to belong to the criminal
organizations. I mean we had all kinds of rapes and murders and
aggravated assaults,'' said Carlos Quevedo, a Brownsville Border
Patrol supervisor who acts as the agency's main liaison with Grupo
Beta. ``Sometimes they would rape women in front of their
children.''
</P>
<P>
   Since the Border Patrol launched Operation Rio Grande in
Brownsville almost two years ago, flooding the riverbank with
agents and high-tech equipment, the criminals have largely
abandoned the Brownsville area and retreated to the Mexican side of
the river.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. agents talk proudly about how they haven't had a single
violent crime reported on their side of the border since the
operation began. It's easy to see why: The Border Patrol has 335
agents in the Brownsville area. Grupo Beta has 18 on their side.
</P>
<P>
   The disparity is the same across the U.S.-Mexico border. In
Nogales, Arizona, Mexican consul Roberto Rodriguez said his office
has urged the Mexican government to send more help to a Grupo Beta
unit in Nogales, Sonora, that has only eight agents, compared to
about 280 Border Patrol agents who are stationed across the border
in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   In Brownsville, Quevedo sees signs of improvement. He parked his
Ford Expedition next to the river and pointed to a neighborhood on
the Mexican side.
</P>
<P>
   ``You see how many people are walking along the river? And guess
why? Because it's safe now,'' he said. ``It's safe because Border
Patrol and Grupo Beta, we're all trying to achieve the same goal,
to make this the safest border in the world.''
</P>
<P>
   They haven't achieved their goal yet. At Brownsville's Ozanam
Center for the Homeless, where many immigrants seek food and
shelter during their journey north, Catholic nun and social worker
Fatima Santiago said the immigrants who pass through still talk
about being robbed by men with guns or knives.
</P>
<P>
   Grupo Beta's statistics also show bandits are still active in
the area: Since January, they say they have interrupted 21 assaults
near the Rio Grande. In some of those cases, they were the intended
assault victims, Alaniz said. They sometimes pose as migrants,
disguised behind dirty clothes, three-day beards, and bags slung
over their shoulders.
</P>
<P>
   In the past year, the agencies have held two joint operations,
with Border Patrol and Grupo Beta agents sweeping their respective
sides of the river on foot, trying to flush out bandits and drug
smugglers.
</P>
<P>
   Both agencies say the Border Patrol's night-vision capabilities
have helped reduce crime on the river. Agents with heat-detecting
cameras scan both sides of the river and call Grupo Beta if they
see suspicious activity on the Mexican side.
</P>
<P>
   One night a few months ago, Alaniz said, Border Patrol agents
guided his Beta team to an assault in progress. They arrested three
men beating a pair of Central American immigrants, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Omeheira Lopez, director of the Reynosa-based Center for Border
Studies and Promotion of Human Rights, remains skeptical of Grupo
Beta and a similar migrant-protection group that operates under a
different name in Reynosa, across the river from McAllen.
</P>
<P>
   ``We haven't heard of any abuses by the new police forces,'' she
said, but added that they haven't heard of the units helping
migrants either.
</P>
<P>
   ``There have been cases where they have detained groups of
migrants, but the smugglers disappear,'' she said. ``It looks like
there's an arrangement.'' On the Mexican side of the international
bridge linking Brownsville and Matamoros, Grupo Beta's offices are
stark and hot. The plaster walls are water-stained. There is no air
conditioning, little furniture other than worn desks, and agents
peck out their paperwork on an old manual typewriter.
</P>
<P>
   On an office window, families have taped handmade posters with
the photocopied pictures of migrants who have disappeared. One face
belongs to a 15-year-old from Veracruz. Another, a 13-year-old from
Matamoros, vanished May 26.
</P>
<P>
   Alaniz, who has been a member of Grupo Beta for more than two
years, shook his head.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're from every part of this country, and lot of other
countries,'' he said. ``There are a lot who live here and go to
Brownsville to cut yards or clean houses and cross every day.''
</P>
<P>
   Alaniz understands the draw of the United States. His wife is
from Brownsville, and most of his family now lives in Brownsville
and Los Angeles. Like his Beta colleagues, he draws extra pay for
serving on the unit and considers himself lucky to have a good job
in Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   ``Many times, it's necessary for a Mexican to leave his family,
sell what he has, and go to the United States,'' he said, steering
a black pickup truck _ one of Beta's few vehicles _ over rough dirt
trails as Montalvo aimed a hand-held spotlight from the truck bed.
</P>
<P>
   The three young men Alaniz had flushed from the ravine earlier
in the evening were typical. Two came from Tampico, a third caught
a bus from the neighboring state of Nuevo Leon. All talked about
hard times back home; they wanted to find work in the United
States.
</P>
<P>
   The fourth person, a middle-aged woman who said her name was
Antonia, had come from Saltillo to work as a maid in Brownsville,
hoping to earn enough money to pay for a lawyer back home. Sobbing,
she had told Alaniz her son-in-law had killed her granddaughter,
and she wanted justice.
</P>
<P>
   With Border Patrol agents watching from just across the river,
the group had shuffled away. The young man from Nuevo Leon said he
would find another place to cross the river.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't bring any money,'' he said. ``How can I get back
home?
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
