A3909 &Cx1f; tad-z
u p &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BUSH-MILITARY18-COX     07-17 2103
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSH-MILITARY18-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Military service issues continues to dog Bush
 &HT;    By Mike Ward and Ken Herman
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ At a time when the Tet Offensive was
dramatically increasing the number of young Americans in combat in
Vietnam, George W. Bush, then a congressman's kid, found a way to
put on a uniform yet stay relatively safe during the unpopular war.
</P>
<P>
   How he managed to do that is a question that has dogged Bush
since he made his first run for public office six years ago, and it
continues as he pursues a front-runner's campaign for the GOP
presidential nomination. Critics have suggested that because he has
a father with position and influence, strings were pulled to help
him get into the National Guard and avoid the draft, though so far
there is no evidence to prove it. Still, records and comments by
Guard officials suggest that Bush wasn't hurt by his pedigree,
either.
</P>
<P>
   Whether that will hurt him with voters come Election Day remains
to be seen.
</P>
<P>
   In the Texas governor's favor is a field of candidates not
well-positioned to assail his military record. The GOP side
includes two other former guardsmen, five who never served, a woman
who had no obligation to serve _ and a decorated ex-POW.
</P>
<P>
   ``Here is a fellow that went and flew airplanes and learned to
be a pilot and was prepared to go if he had to,'' said Utah Sen.
Orrin Hatch, a recent entry in the presidential field and a
candidate with no military service. ``That is a lot. You know, I
don't see how anybody can find fault with that.''
</P>
<P>
   Arizona Sen. John McCain, the only GOP presidential contender
with active-duty military service, has not made a big issue of
Bush's military service. McCain, however, has joked that he slept
more soundly as a prisoner of war in North Vietnam knowing that
Bush was defending Texas from invasion.
</P>
<P>
   Also working for Bush is an electorate seemingly beyond
fascination with war-hero presidents. Bill Clinton, who used
student deferments to avoid military service in a war he did not
support, defeated two World War II veterans, George Bush and Bob
Dole.
</P>
<P>
   But working against Bush is a national press corps that has
drawn a big target on him. Rolling Stone magazine is out this week
with an article that concludes Bush ``skirted the draft with help
from his father.'' The proof? A quote from an unnamed Democratic
Party insider who heard it from someone else. The article is the
latest in a series of national media stories in recent weeks to
focus on Bush's military record.
</P>
<P>
   Questions about Bush's military record have surfaced in
surprising places. Last week, two Dallas lawyers tried to make it
an issue in a civil lawsuit filed by a former Texas Lottery
director. Although the issue of whether Bush got preferential
treatment in the Guard played to no conclusion, the line of
questioning quickly became grist for the Austin political rumor
mill.
</P>
<P>
   In deposing Austin lobbyist Nick Kralj, lawyers for Larry
Littwin, who was removed as lottery chief in October 1997, pressed
for information about former Lt. Gov. Ben Barnes, who was lottery
company Gtech's top lobbyist in Texas until the company bought out
his contract in February 1997. Littwin's lawyers asked whether
Barnes had interceded in 1968 to get Bush into the Texas Air
National Guard. Kralj worked as Barnes' top aide in 1968.
</P>
<P>
   Attorneys for Litwin, who is suing the Lottery Commission over
his firing, said they were trying to gauge how much political clout
Democrat Barnes might have had with Republican Bush, whose
appointees made up a majority of the Lottery Commission.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are attempting to chase down all the rabbit trails for how
Gtech might have had some influence'' over the commission, said
Rich Aubin, one of Littwin's lawyers. ``Certainly if Ben Barnes had
done a favor for George Bush 30 years ago, that might provide some
potential influence.'' Aubin said Kralj ``confirmed there was a
practice wherein he would be given a list of names'' by Barnes to
be forwarded to the late Brig. Gen. James M. Rose, head of the
Texas Air National Guard when Bush served. ``And then one way or
another those people would end up in the Guard,'' Aubin said Kralj
testified.
</P>
<P>
   But Kralj also testified he did not remember any names on the
lists, the attorneys said. Barnes has since told The Associated
Press that he did not intercede for Bush. For his part, Bush has
defended his six years in the Air National Guard as earned and
honorable _ the same thing he's been doing since it first surfaced
as an issue in his 1994 gubernatorial campaign.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not suggesting I was any great war hero,'' Bush said
during that campaign. ``But I want you to know that flying F-102
fighters, putting the thing in afterburner at the end of a runway,
was something other than not being a part of the military.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wouldn't necessarily call it risky duty, but we lost a
couple of guys in our unit. I'm not the least bit ashamed of what I
did.''
</P>
<P>
   AN ATTRACTIVE OPTION
</P>
<P>
   Bush's military career began in 1968, as he finished his final
semester at Yale University.
</P>
<P>
   With his deferments ending and the Vietnam War escalating as the
North Vietnamese launched the bloody Tet Offensive, Bush, like most
other draft-age American men, faced the prospect of going to
Vietnam.
</P>
<P>
   The Guard offered an appealing alternative: Fulfill your
military service obligation, probably stateside. Nationally, the
waiting lists contained more than 100,000 names.
</P>
<P>
   But the Texas Air National Guard, in which Bush enlisted in May
1968, had openings _ 156 among its authorized staffing level of
925.
</P>
<P>
   Bush said his choice was motivated more by career interest than
avoidance. ``I knew I was going into the military and would have
liked to come out with a skill,'' Bush said recently. ``Your
options were either to avoid the draft or sign up, and I signed
up.''
</P>
<P>
   Guard records show that soon after Bush met in Houston with Col.
Walter ``Buck'' Staudt, then the commander of the Texas Air
National Guard, he was immediately accepted as a pilot trainee. He
had passed a screening exam to be a military pilot several months
earlier at a recruiting office near the Yale campus. With no
aviation background or schooling, he might have seemed like an
unlikely candidate _ his Guard application form listed jobs such as
messenger, ranch hand, oilfield roustabout, Sears sporting goods
salesman and bookkeeper. Asked for ``background qualifications of
value to the Air Force,'' Bush wrote, ``None.''
</P>
<P>
   But he scored in the top 5 percent in the ``officer quality''
section of his enlistment test _ a section designed to measure
intangible things such as leadership. His score in the pilot
aptitude section was much lower, in the 25th percentile, the lowest
allowed for wannabe fliers, records show.
</P>
<P>
   He was physically and educationally qualified and was willing to
undergo the lengthy and rigorous pilot training _ something some
enlistees were not.
</P>
<P>
   ``A quiet, intelligent young man who has the interest,
motivation and knowledge necessary to become a commissioned
officer,'' Staudt wrote in a report on his first meeting with Bush.
</P>
<P>
   By early June, he was a member of the 147th Fighter Interceptor
Group, part of the so-called ``Ace in the Hole'' squadron based at
Ellington Air Force Base outside Houston, Bush's hometown. The unit
flew F-102s, an older model of jet that was being phased out of the
regular Air Force but was still seeing duty in Vietnam.
</P>
<P>
   DRIVEN BY POLITICS
</P>
<P>
   Would Bush have advanced in rank so quickly, would he have been
able to land a coveted pilot's job, if not for his name? Guard
records give no indication of that, though official press releases
frequently played up Bush's famous father, whose adventures as a
Navy pilot in World War II made him a war hero.
</P>
<P>
   Five or six pilot jobs were open at the time, and Bush got one
because he was qualified, Guard officials have said. Indeed, his
performance reports gave glowing evaluations of his work, which
consisted of flying ``alerts'' over the Gulf of Mexico _ military
jargon for guarding the border against enemy attack.
</P>
<P>
   When Bush was promoted to first lieutenant in November 1970, his
Guard review called him ``a natural leader whom his contemporaries
look to for leadership. Lt. Bush is also a good follower with
outstanding disciplinary traits and an impeccable military bearing.
. . . (He) possesses vast potential and should be promoted well
ahead of his contemporaries.''
</P>
<P>
   Just as his family had been driven by politics, so was Bush's
military career. In late 1972, he asked for _ and received _ a
three-month transfer to the Alabama Air Guard so he could work on a
Republican candidate's Senate campaign _ even though the Alabama
unit was being phased out.
</P>
<P>
   Guard officials said such a transfer was not unusual, and the
Bush campaign says it was for the same flying job he held in Texas
_ but it gave him the opportunity to pursue his civilian job of
political work. A May 1973 job evaluation, however, reported he had
been ``performing equivalent training in a non-flying status.''
</P>
<P>
   Though Bush was required to serve in the Guard until May 1974,
he was allowed to leave in October 1973 to attend Harvard Business
School.
</P>
<P>
   Nothing unusual, Guard officials have said, since his unit was
changing planes at the time _ from single-seat F-102 jets to the
dual-seat F-101s. With just eight months of service left, they
said, it made little sense to retrain Bush.
</P>
<P>
   NOT YET A PUBLIC ISSUE
</P>
<P>
   So far, if Bush's military record has drawn media attention, it
is the only candidate's record to do so. Political observers say
the public has shown little interest so far.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think it's a very big issue. Obviously, the farther
away we get from Vietnam the more the issue fades,'' said Stephen
Hess, a longtime presidential politics analyst at the
Washington-based Brookings Institution. ``I think it would be
somewhat mitigated by the fact that the man became a fighter pilot.
It's not as if he was sitting at a typewriter at Fort Leonard Wood.
It just doesn't strike me that this one is going to stick to the
ribs.''
</P>
<P>
   For his part, Dan Quayle, 52, has said questions raised during
the 1988 presidential campaign about his service in the Indiana
National Guard may spare Bush the same intense media scrutiny this
time around. ``The bottom line is this: Were any rules broken, was
there favoritism?'' Quayle said earlier this month. ``If there was
favoritism, then that's wrong. If there was special treatment,
that's wrong. If there were rules that were violated, then that's
clearly wrong.''
</P>
<P>
   Paul Begala, a former adviser to President Clinton, said Friday
that few people will believe Bush didn't get a family nudge into
the Guard.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm willing to accept his argument that neither he nor his
father pulled any strings,'' said Begala, a Gore backer. ``What I
have a hard time believing is when he says he didn't receive . . .
preferential treatment. He was a Bush and a son of a Bush. And he
was jumped ahead of everyone else on the waiting list.''
</P>
<P>
   Begala said he doesn't perceive any voter animosity to
politicians who served in the Guard rather than active-duty
military. He said the only way the issue could hurt Bush is if
voters believe he is not being straight with them.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why doesn't he just say, `It sure looks like they gave me a
chance to serve ahead of others. I couldn't control that and I
didn't ask for that,'?'' Begala said.
</P>
<P>
   Pollsters in recent years have mostly ignored the issue of
presidential candidates' military service. But when asked about it
in 1988, 63 percent of Americans did not have a less favorable view
of a candidate with no military service, while 32 percent did,
according to the Pew Research Center in Washington, a source of
independent polling data.
</P>
<P>
   Marvin Kalb, a longtime TV network correspondent who directs
Harvard University's Joan Shorenstein Center on the Press, Politics
and Public Policy, sees a simmering issue that could hit the
campaign-trail boiling point down the line.
</P>
<P>
   ``There isn't fire in the electorate right now for presidential
politics,'' he said. ``But the merits of this issue will have long
legs, and undoubtedly the issue will come up again when people are
more focused on the presidential race.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think people will think he got a break and that he got a
break because he was the son of a congressman from the area,'' he
said. ``And I think they think unkindly about that.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
