<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOSPITAL-WASTE18-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Poor handling of hazardous hospital waste worries officials
 &HT;    By Dale Dempsey and Cathy Mong
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ During a routine inspection of a truck hauling
trash this month, workers at BFI's recycling transfer station
outside of Cincinnati discovered what looked like blood coming from
one of the bags.
</P>
<P>
   They found that some of the bags contained hazardous medical
wastes _ bloody gauze, surgical gowns and other operating room
equipment _ from Middletown Regional Hospital. Such hazardous
material is prohibited by federal environmental laws from mixing
with ordinary waste.
</P>
<P>
   When on July 8 biomedical wastes were found a second time, it
prompted a review by the Ohio Environmental Protection Agency and
the Middletown Health Department of the Middletown hospital's waste
handling, a crucial procedure that a recent study says needs to be
improved at many hospitals around the country.
</P>
<P>
   Middletown hospital responded quickly to clean up the hazardous
waste, but the incidents raised concerns among environmental
officials because hospitals use a wide range of materials that can
contaminate the environment. In addition to potentially infectious
materials, there are pollutants such as mercury in thermometers and
blood pressure devices, and polyvinyl chloride plastic in IV drip
bags.
</P>
<P>
   ``They definitely did good work at the transfer station in
spotting this stuff,'' said Lynne Barst of the Ohio EPA.
</P>
<P>
   Hazardous medical wastes are required to be placed in special
red bags that carry a warning and disposed of in special landfills
or by incineration. Some of the waste found at BFI was in ordinary
bags. Disposing of ``red bag'' waste can cost two to three times
more than regular waste.
</P>
<P>
   Middletown hospital is opening and inspecting all of the trash
that leaves the building and is reviewing its systems and
procedures, according to Larry James, vice-president of marketing
at the hospital. The Miamisburg health department also made a
partial inspection.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a very, very serious incident for us,'' James said.
``We're doing everything to make sure that it doesn't happen
again.''
</P>
<P>
   Staff education about proper disposal is also ``going on with
even greater emphasis,'' James said.
</P>
<P>
   Education is also one of the key recommendations of a survey of
50 major U.S. hospitals conducted last year by the Environmental
Working Group in Washington, D.C.
</P>
<P>
   The report said that lack of basic environmental practices at
hospitals is resulting in serious pollution problems.
</P>
<P>
   Among its findings were:
</P>
<P>
   _ The average hospital is recycling only approximately one-third
of the readily recyclable items. Some hospitals recycle none.
</P>
<P>
   _ Only 20 percent of the hospitals surveyed had programs to
reduce purchases of polyvinyl chloride plastic. PVC plastic is a
major factor in emissions of the carcinogen dioxin when waste is
incinerated.
</P>
<P>
   _ While 80 percent of the hospitals have mercury reduction
programs, the programs are not particularly effective.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
