<SLUG> BC-AMERICA'S-CUP-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOLLOWING MONEY FOR THE AMERICA'S CUP 
</HEADLINE>
  (jt) 
 By BARBARA LLOYD    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   In 1992, shortly after winning the right to challenge the United
States for the America's Cup, Italy could not get enough of the
American Paul Cayard. But now the Italians have a new focus, new
money and a new skipper. And no one knows that better than Cayard,
a mostly forgotten yachtsman in Italy these days.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's probably truthful that whoever is going to win the cup
this next time is the team with the most money to optimize boat
design,'' Cayard said in a recent telephone interview from San
Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the Italians who have that money. It's a worry, because
they will be the ones who can afford the incremental tidbits that
can make the difference.''
</P>
<P>
   Cayard has organized his own America's Cup campaign for the
1999-2000 event under the aegis of the St. Francis Yacht Club in
San Francisco. The team was preparing last week to christen the
first of its two new 75-foot sailboats. The ceremony was scheduled
for Saturday at the group's summer training base in San Pedro,
Calif. Both yachts, designed by Bruce Nelson of San Diego, will be
shipped to New Zealand by the end of August.
</P>
<P>
   Cayard's group, America One, has probably as good a chance as
any of the five U.S. teams to win the America's Cup from New
Zealand. But first there are the Italians. Their yachting syndicate
is organized by Prada, the Italian apparel designer and
manufacturer. Petrizio Bertelli, Prada's director, is chairman of
the yachting syndicate.
</P>
<P>
   Flush with financial support from Prada, the group has hired top
sailors and designers, including two Olympic champions, Francesco
de Angelis, the Italian helmsman, and Torben Grael of Brazil,
tactician. Other insiders include Laurent Esquier and Steve
Erickson, both important members of Cayard's boat-building team
until the Italians lured them away with bigger salaries.
</P>
<P>
   The 40-year-old Cayard tends to be far more philosophical since
sailing for an Italian group that made it to the America's Cup
finals in 1992. He competed that year as yacht skipper for Italy's
Il Moro di Venezia syndicate.
</P>
<P>
   Money flowed into the America's Cup effort with the help of the
late Raul Gardini, who was syndicate chairman. The financier, a
prominent Italian businessman, spent somewhere between $60 and $100
million _ reports varied widely _ in his effort to win the cup.
</P>
<P>
   But that wasn't enough to thwart the equally determined and
comparably wealthy Bill Koch, the America3 financier, who
eventually prevailed against the Gardini-Cayard bid. After losing
to Koch, Gardini went back to Italy where he faced potential
government bribery charges. In the midst of the political turmoil,
Gardini shot himself.
</P>
<P>
   For Cayard, who had seen Gardini as a father-figure, it was a
personal tragedy. Aimless as he faced a five-year wait for the next
scheduled America's Cup regatta, Cayard immersed himself in a
victorious Swedish-backed campaign in the 1997-98 Whitbread Round
the World Race.
</P>
<P>
   Gardini's death marked the end of a gilded era in yacht racing
for Cayard. But the Whitbread provided a chance for personal
triumph on his own terms. His team included mostly hand-picked
sailors from his cup years, and they learned on the job about the
humility, tenacity, terror and the conquest of sailing a 60-foot
yacht round the world. For Cayard, it was a crash course in
self-reliance.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had the benefit of Gardini, but that was not really
reality,'' Cayard said about the 1992 cup year. ``Reality is
earning your keep, and making this thing valuable to others,
especially corporate sponsors. From a time standpoint _ and the
fact that the America's Cup is a hard sell _ it adds a lot of
pressure to being skipper. It is a very first-person thing, and
very time-consuming.''
</P>
<P>
   Cayard's America One budget is a hefty $32 million. But he has
significant financial backers already in place _ including
Hewlett-Packard, Ford Motor Co. and Science Applications
International Corp., a technology firm based in California. He
needs $8 million more.
</P>
<P>
   It is difficult to strike a balance between fund raising and
racing, and no one knows that better than Dennis Conner. The
veteran cup helmsman increasingly finds other sailors to steer his
boat while he is raising money. He has named Ken Read, a two-time
Rolex Yachtsman of the Year, to steer for the 1999 challenger
trials.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a battle out there trying to sell the America's Cup,''
said Bill Trenkle, project manager for Conner. ``You're competing
with every other sport out there. Paul has a new appreciation for
what it takes.''
</P>
</TEXT>
