<HEADER>
A3913 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-POLITICAL-BRIEFS-NYT &LR;      07-17 1290
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POLITICAL-BRIEFS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RETAIL POLITICS  
 STATE-SPECIFIC POLL RESULTS  
 DEMOCRATS EYE KASICH DISTRICT 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: N.H., Iowa, Minn., Ariz., Tenn., Ohio)  (mk) 
 By B. DRUMMOND AYRES JR.    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Retail politics.
</P>
<P>
   That's the first thing New Hampshirites mention when they argue
that their state, more than any other, deserves the right to hold
the nation's first presidential primary. And the same is true of
Iowans when they contend that their state should always hold the
first presidential caucuses.
</P>
<P>
   By ``retail,'' these proud New Englanders and Midwesterners mean
old-fashioned politicking in which candidates get down on the
ground and meet and greet voters personally in their homes, in
coffee shops and at small rallies. The impersonal ``air game'' of
flashy television advertising that dominates campaigns in most
other states, the argument goes, does not work in compact, folksy,
down-to-earth New Hampshire and Iowa. Politicking in those two
states, it is said, is like politicking used to be _ and still
should be.
</P>
<P>
   So far, most candidates buy that argument, or at least go along
with it.
</P>
<P>
   But is retail really retail?
</P>
<P>
   The answer seems to be yes and yes _ that is, retail politics in
a political sense really does bring unusually large numbers of
candidates and voters face to face, as in clerk and customer; and
in the classic retail sense, or business sense, in that it pumps
money, big money, into the economy.
</P>
<P>
   A survey commissioned by the Library and Archives of New
Hampshire's Political Tradition found that in the 1996 presidential
campaign, retail politicking resulted in one of every five New
Hampshire voters personally meeting at least one candidate, and
often more. By contrast, in a state like California, the average
voter can go the better part of a lifetime, if not an entire
lifetime, without meeting a candidate.
</P>
<P>
   Further, the study found that all the running around, eating,
advertising and renting of rooms, cars, auditoriums and workspace
by candidates, political consultants and reporters, created 1,500
temporary jobs and pumped over $210 million into the New Hampshire
economy.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's our answer for why New Hampshire works,'' former Gov.
Hugh Gregg, the chairman of the Library and Archives organization,
said in releasing the study.
</P>
<P>
   The study, based on a survey of travel, business, tax and
Federal Election Commission data, along with interviews with
campaign workers and media specialists, also concluded that the New
Hampshire primary offered the state a huge opportunity to promote
itself at no cost because of the press coverage given the
quadrennial event. The state received over 20,000 media mentions in
1996, the study said, going on to estimate that they were read,
heard or seen by upwards of 150 million people around the country.
</P>
<P>
   But if the promotion opportunity is to be fully exploited, the
study added, the state needs to impress visiting reporters that
more New Hampshirites hold high-technology jobs these days than
milk cows and wear flannel shirts.
</P>
<P>
   In a Swift Campaign, Some Fast Polls, Too
</P>
<P>
   It is still early in the Election 2000 nominating game, but in
the for-what-it's-worth department, here are the results of some
polls taken in various states in recent days.
</P>
<P>
   Minnesota: According to a survey conducted last weekend by the
independent Mason-Dixon polling organization of Maryland, four of
every five voters do not want Gov. Jesse Ventura to run for
president.
</P>
<P>
   The governor, whose surprise victory in last fall's election
made him the most successful Reform Party candidate ever, has said
repeatedly that he has no designs on the White House. And, in fact,
he is urging former Gov. Lowell Weicker of Connecticut, a
Republican-turned-independent, to run for the Reform nomination.
</P>
<P>
   But because Ventura is also calling for reform of the Reform
Party _ he asserts that Ross Perot's time has passed _ there is a
steady undercurrent of talk that ultimately, whatever the wishes of
Minnesota voters, he intends to seek the nomination for himself.
</P>
<P>
   So when the Reform Party holds its annual convention in
Dearborn, Mich., next weekend, there could be a tussle worth
watching between the governor, a strutting former professional
wrestler, and the bantam billionaire Texan, one of the richest and
fastest tongues in the West.
</P>
<P>
   New Hampshire: Good news for Sen. John McCain, R-Ariz. Because
he is the only Republican candidate not competing in Iowa's straw
poll on Aug. 14, perhaps the biggest political event of 1999, and
because he has indicated that he will not compete next year in
Iowa's pivotal first-in-the-nation caucuses, New Hampshire's
first-in-the-nation primary looms as the first big test for him.
And he is working the state hard.
</P>
<P>
   How's he doing?
</P>
<P>
   For months he was bumping along near the bottom in most polls,
badly trailing both Gov. George W. Bush of Texas, the runaway
leader, and the No. 2 contender, Elizabeth Dole, the former Red
Cross president. Now comes a new poll conducted by an independent
New Hampshire polling company, the American Research Group.
</P>
<P>
   Bush is still the runaway leader, still ahead of the
second-place finisher by almost 3-1. But that second-place finisher
is now McCain.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Dole has slipped to fourth, behind Patrick Buchanan, the
commentator and winner of the 1996 New Hampshire primary.
</P>
<P>
   Arizona: Bad news for McCain in the latest poll from his home
state, which also holds an early primary, one in which he obviously
must shine.
</P>
<P>
   Bush, who trailed McCain in earlier Arizona polls, has now
pulled ahead and leads the senator almost 2-1, according to a
survey conducted last weekend by an independent polling group, the
Rocky Mountain Behavior Research Center of Phoenix.
</P>
<P>
   Tennessee: Really bad news in the latest poll from the home
state of another Republican contender, former Gov. Lamar Alexander.
</P>
<P>
   He is already on the political ropes, down to just $90,000 in
campaign cash and betting everything on next month's straw poll in
Iowa.
</P>
<P>
   And now comes news that when the West Knoxville Republican Club
held a straw poll last Monday (members say it was not announced in
advance), he drew just one of the 64 votes cast, the political
equivalent of drawing the last straw, given that Bush got 51 votes
and West Knoxville lies just 20 miles north of Alexander's
hometown, Maryville.
</P>
<P>
   A `Safe' GOP Seat? Democrats Lining Up
</P>
<P>
   When Rep. John Kasich, R-Ohio, abandoned his quest for the
Republican presidential nomination last week, he made life easier
for all those Republican leaders who are promoting George W. Bush
as the party's best hope in Election 2000. But Kasich left them
with a problem when he also announced that after nine terms, he
planned to give up representing Ohio's 12th District in Congress.
</P>
<P>
   Add another ``safe'' Republican seat to the ``open seat'' list,
the category for seats most vulnerable to takeover by the other
party.
</P>
<P>
   Having controlled the 12th, which covers major parts of
Columbus, for 17 years, Republicans probably still have a better
shot at it than Democrats in Election 2000. But President Clinton
carried it in 1996 and only barely lost it in 1992, and so
Democrats see the district as one that, with a bit of luck, could
help them narrow the six-seat edge Republicans currently hold in
the House.
</P>
<P>
   Two Republicans, state Sen. Eugene Watts and state Rep. Pat
Tiberi, a former Kasich aide, have announced and are out raising
money. On the Democratic side, at least half a dozen party figures
have expressed interest in running, among them a local county
chairman, several state legislators, a city attorney and a member
of the city council.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
