<SLUG> BC-EDIT-TAXCUTS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GO SLOW ON TAX CUTS 
</HEADLINE>
  (jt) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial for Sunday, July 18:
</P>
<P>
   Cutting taxes always sounds good in Washington, and it may be
inevitable that Congress will pass a tax cut before next year's
election. But if that is to happen, the grandiose cutting plans
proposed by the chairmen of the congressional tax-writing
committees need to be scaled back substantially.
</P>
<P>
   Economically, this is an inappropriate time for any tax
decrease. With the economy booming and the Federal Reserve raising
interest rates in an effort to slow growth and prevent inflation, a
fiscal stimulus package would have the opposite effect, and could
persuade the Federal Reserve that it will need to raise interest
rates more than would otherwise be necessary.
</P>
<P>
   But the most important defect of the plans by Rep. Bill Archer,
the chairman of the Ways and Means Committee, and Sen. William
Roth, the chairman of the Finance Committee, lies in their sheer
scope. Rather than simply pass a tax cut that would take effect in
the next year or two, both Republican bills call for major cuts to
be made well into the next decade. The Archer bill even has cuts to
take effect in 2009, three presidential elections from now.
</P>
<P>
   Archer's bill, as passed by his committee on a party-line vote,
is expected to cut government revenue by $864 billion over the next
10 years, and by much more in years after that as some major
provisions _ including a repeal of all estate taxes, even for
billionaires _ are phased in. The Roth bill calls for cuts of $792
billion over the 10 years. A more moderate plan from Senate
Democrats led by Sen. Daniel Patrick Moynihan proposes cuts of $295
billion, still more than the $250 billion President Clinton has
suggested.
</P>
<P>
   The Republican proposals are based on estimates that the
government will otherwise run huge surpluses in coming years. But
those estimates are inherently questionable, and the surpluses
could vanish if the economy were to weaken. In addition, the
surplus figures are based on the assumption that spending will be
held down in accord with previous budget compromises, even though
it appears likely that this Congress will be unable to abide by the
harsh spending cuts required to meet those targets. Congress should
first pass its spending bills and only then turn to the issue of
taxes.
</P>
<P>
   If there are to be tax cuts, they should be targeted at middle-
and lower-income taxpayers. While some adjustments to estate taxes
may be in order, Archer's plan to eliminate the tax is a giveaway
to the wealthy that would severely damage the government's finances
after it took effect in 2009. Similarly, there is no reason to
further cut capital gains taxes, as Archer proposes.
</P>
<P>
   Any bill that is passed should target the abusive tax shelters
used by some companies to avoid paying taxes. The Republicans say
they are still studying Clinton administration proposals.
</P>
<P>
   Most important, a tax bill should not have provisions that would
decimate government revenues five or 10 years from now. If the
present optimistic economic forecasts prove to be accurate, there
will be more than enough time for a future Congress to consider
those reductions.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
