<HEADER>
A3917 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SMALL-TOWN-WRESTLING-     07-17 0805
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SMALL-TOWN-WRESTLING-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SMALL-TOWN WRESTLING DRAWS BLOOD AND FANS 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(jt) 
 By ALAN FEUER    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   BAYONNE, N.J. _ As the crowd of hundreds chanted ``Make them
bleed! Make them bleed!'' Frank Iadavaia raised the metal garbage
can above his head and heaved it into the ring.
</P>
<P>
   It bounced on the canvas, spilling crutches, wooden canes and
frying pans provided by the fans in the furtherance of mayhem,
across the mat. Then Iadavaia led a dozen wrestlers over the ropes
and started whacking anything, and anyone, that moved.
</P>
<P>
   The battle might have seemed like a sporting event gone horribly
wrong. But as evenings go for Jersey All-Pro Wrestling, one of the
scores of independent wrestling federations that have blossomed
across the country in the last five years, it was run of the mill.
</P>
<P>
   Steeped in blood, these tiny leagues have seized upon a hunger
among their fans for increased realism and violence in professional
wrestling _ for a real-life urgency that their larger counterparts,
the World Wrestling Federation and World Championship Wrestling,
cannot supply.
</P>
<P>
   But is it fake? Well, sort of. It has long been one of
professional wrestling's canards that matches are scripted, lacking
even the slightest spontaneous move. While that is mostly true for
the larger leagues, which plan everything for television and do not
pretend that the pain they portray is real, the smaller leagues,
which operate outside the media's eye, are somewhat looser when it
comes to blood.
</P>
<P>
   Though wrestlers at Jersey All-Pro Wrestling and other, similar,
leagues do plan most of their matches in advance, the techniques
they use are more dangerous than those in the big leagues, and are
designed to meet an expectation in the crowd that actual beatings
will occur. Some of the pain and blood is fake. Some is quite real.
</P>
<P>
   Which, of course, is the point.
</P>
<P>
   No one knows for sure how many independent leagues like Jersey
All-Pro Wrestling exist throughout the country. The small outfits,
which are often no more than a promoter and his stable of
wrestlers, have no governing body, and promoters and newsletter
writers who follow the sport say there are so many new federations
popping up each month that it would be impossible to count them
all.
</P>
<P>
   Jersey All-Pro, which began in this blue-collar enclave, is a
typical example of an independent league, and Iadavaia, a Bayonne
native who wrestles under the name Lightning Lou Diamond, embodies
the passions that characterize it.
</P>
<P>
   A thick-waisted, ebullient man of 26, he founded Jersey All-Pro
in 1995 while working as an administrative clerk by day and manager
of an auto body shop at night. Though he said his first shows were
depressing failures _ no more than a dozen fans showed up _ he
found what he needed to draw in the fans when he discovered
violence.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was doing all kinds of things back then to bring in the
fans,'' he said. ``I put chairs by the ropes and did 360s into the
crowd. Then I happened to pick up a chair and whacked somebody with
it and the roof blew off the place. Right there is where I decided.
I just told everyone, `Let's go out and bleed.'''
</P>
<P>
   Jersey All-Pro is one of the bloodier independent leagues. Its
wrestlers grapple inside wire cages or on mats strewn with tacks.
It is also one of the more sexually provocative leagues,
occasionally promoting matches in which women wrestle wearing only
string bikinis.
</P>
<P>
   A regular feature is what Iadavaia calls a ``weapons match.'' As
the spectators paid their $10 and filed into Charity Hall, they
brought along a staggering array of clubs and bludgeons and put
them in the ring for the fighters to use once they entered: hockey
sticks, baseball bats, even a kitchen sink.
</P>
<P>
   Most of Jersey All-Pro's wrestlers are local men, guys from
Bayonne and the nearby communities who think of match night as a
chance to perform in front of neighbors and friends. While they say
there is a certain pleasure in getting paid to swing a frying pan _
most make $40 to $100 a night _ many say the bouts are a way to
rise above their workaday lives and bask in acclaim they would
never otherwise enjoy.
</P>
<P>
   With its motto, ``Blood is better,'' and the occasional but very
real injuries that occur in the ring, Jersey All-Pro walks a line
between the mainstream wrestling leagues and ``ultimate'' or
``extreme fighting'' events, the no-holds-barred competitions
blending martial arts, wrestling and common street brawling.
</P>
<P>
   While Jersey All-Pro's wrestlers have suffered an array of
bumps, cuts, bruises and broken bones over the years, none of them
have been killed or seriously injured _ yet.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
