<HEADLINE>
WAY WEST ON 14TH STREET: CHANGING FROM A PLACE FOR MEAT TO A PLACE
TO MEET 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By JOHN HOLUSHA    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The contrast could hardly be more stark. There in the
city's traditional meat-packing district on 14th Street between
Ninth and Tenth avenues, art galleries, trendy restaurants and
stores are mingling with men in bloody aprons.
</P>
<P>
   The contrast signals that another industrial neighborhood in
Manhattan is in the process of being transformed by the inexorable
spread of white-collar businesses, just as the printers of Hudson
Square are being ousted by new media companies and warehouses on
the West Side are becoming offices and residences.
</P>
<P>
   ``Many of the meat-packing companies will be moving to the Hunts
Point area over the next few years,'' said David Gmach, executive
director of the 14th Street-Union Square Business Improvement
District and Local Development Corp., who noted that much of
Manhattan's fish market was headed toward the same location.
</P>
<P>
   In all, Gmach said, a total of about 10 galleries have moved
into the area, which has among its advantages a proximity to the
Hudson River and the prospect that a riverside park will be built
at some point in the future.
</P>
<P>
   The street also has an outpost of the Little Pie Co. and Dizzy
Izzy's, which one resident described as ``a bagel place and
cultural center.''
</P>
<P>
   Many of the new commercial tenants said they were attracted by
more affordable space and the willingness of their customers to
travel to parts of city once considered off limits to middle-class
shoppers. ``Collectors like that kind of thing, digging around in
odd parts of the city,'' said Susan B. Anthony, a broker with her
own agency that specializes in gallery relocations.
</P>
<P>
   The other reason for the increase in activity is that there was
almost no other place to go in Manhattan. ``We really have had a
hard time finding space in Chelsea,'' she said. ``We had to look
elsewhere.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I was on 57th Street along with Bugs Bunny,'' said Stephen
Long, the owner of Long Fine Art, referring to the Warner Brothers
Studio Store that occupies a Fifth Avenue corner on that street. He
moved to a converted meat storage building in February 1998 to save
on rent and to stand out a bit more with ground-floor space than
was possible on an upstairs floor of a building in midtown.
</P>
<P>
   ``The first summer I was here was a little frightening,'' he
said. ``All my veggie friends said they would do business by
phone.'' But he said customers have followed him to the new
location and special events like the Meat Market Crawl, when
galleries stay open late one night a month, have drawn in shoppers
not familiar with the area.
</P>
<P>
   One advantage of the area, he said, was that the low-rise
buildings nearby provided plenty of natural light for the gallery.
And he said the schedule of the meat business actually helped to
make the area more secure than might be expected.
</P>
<P>
   ``The meat packers start about midnight and work through the
morning, which makes this a 24-hour neighborhood,'' Long said.
``Artists who live in the area say it is very secure.''
</P>
<P>
   The development of West 14th Street appears to echo what
happened previously in the western part of Chelsea in the 20s,
where gallery owners being driven out of SoHo by rising rents paid
by retailers eager to set up shop in a heavily trafficked area
converted old garage buildings that had formerly served the garment
district into galleries.
</P>
<P>
   One SoHo refugee is Hal Katzen of the Katzen-Stein gallery a few
doors east of Long's establishment. ``My space in SoHo on West
Broadway was sold, so I had to find a new space.'' He said he has
been in his 14th Street space for a year and finds it satisfactory
``There is a rawness to the area, but my clients are making their
way over here,'' he said. ``It reminds me of the old SoHo in the
1970s.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Just about everyone concedes that the traffic on the congested
cobblestoned street is a problem, with huge tractor-trailer trucks
attempting to maneuver in spaces laid out when the biggest vehicle
was a horse-drawn wagon. Most trucks cannot back directly up to the
places where they are making deliveries, but must position
themselves at an angle to the building, restricting traffic.
</P>
<P>
   The general hope among the newer tenants in the area is that as
the meat industry relocates, the big trucks will follow.
</P>
<P>
   Farther to the west, in an old warehouse next to Moishe's Mini
Storage, a new, 12,000-square-foot retail store, to be called
Jeffrey, is under construction.
</P>
<P>
   The proprietor, Jeffrey Kalinsky, plans to open the store on
August 2, on his 37th birthday, which seemed like an ambitious goal
given the state of construction just a few weeks before that date.
The store is expected to be stocked with clothing and shoes with
brand names like Gucci, Helmut Lang, Jil Sander and Prada.
</P>
<P>
   Kalinsky, who was formerly the women's shoe buyer for Barneys,
said he thinks the location is a good one for a store selling
upscale products, despite its distance from the main shopping
districts on Madison and Fifth avenues, 57th Street and SoHo.
</P>
<P>
   ``I love this neighborhood and the structure is beautiful,''
said Kalinsky, who operates three stores in Atlanta but who has not
tested the New York market on his own before.
</P>
<P>
   One of the advantages of the area is low rent, which brokers put
in the $23 to $26-a-square-foot-a-year range, compared to hundreds
of dollars a square foot in some of the more established retail
areas.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jeffrey made his deal eight months ago and already it's
undervalued due to growing attention to the neighborhood,'' said
Caroline Banker, a broker with New Spectrum Realty Services.
``Landlords in the area are already asking $35 a foot for
ground-floor space.''
</P>
<P>
   She said residential development in the area and the decision by
a retailer like Comme des Garcons to open a store on 22nd Street
between 10th and 11th avenues would help make the area a
destination for shoppers.
</P>
<P>
   Kalinsky expects to expand his operation as the ministorage
winds down _ he and his broker, Ms. Anthony, say that the
mini-storage operation is expected to be converted to retail use _
and is planning to eventually occupy 92,000 square feet, said Ms.
Banker, who noted that the store's proximity to the West Side
Highway may make it attractive to suburban shoppers as well.
</P>
<P>
   But others were more skeptical about the location. ``It is out
of the way, and who has time to shop anyway,'' said Faith H.
Consolo, a senior managing director of Garrick-Aug Associates,
another brokerage specializing in retail leasing. ``He's going to
have to cater to the `ladies who lunch' and hope they will go
there.''
</P>
<P>
   One place those hungry ladies will be able to stop in at is
Markt, a restaurant at 14th Street and Ninth Avenue.
</P>
<P>
   Peter Michaels, who opened the restaurant about six months ago,
said he was ``lucky on the timing.
</P>
<P>
   ``I live in the neighborhood and I saw Chelsea moving down and
the West Village moving up and meeting here.'' He said other
restaurants were open or planning to open in the area, including Le
Gans on Gansevoort Street and Balthazar on West 12th Street. In
addition, he said it is widely believed in the neighborhood that a
hotel will be built on a parking lot a few blocks to the south.
</P>
<P>
   Certainly people are moving to the area and paying hefty prices
to do so. Several old industrial buildings at 345 W. 13th Street
have been converted into 46 luxury condominiums. Recently a
two-bedroom loft sold for over $2 million and the largest unit is
expected to fetch close to $3 million.
</P>
<P>
   Just to the east, on the southwest corner of 14th Street and
Eighth Avenue, a landmarked former bank and an adjoining structure
are also being converted into upscale housing.
</P>
<P>
   Some residents fear that the area may go the way of SoHo, with
early pioneers being driven out as national retailers rush in and
offer higher rents to be in a fashionable area.
</P>
<P>
   ``If Jeffrey is successful, you know other retailers will try to
move in here, just as they have done in other parts of Manhattan,''
Michaels said. ``If a Gap opens up nearby, I'm going to put the
restaurant up for sale.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
