</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KENNEDY-NY-SCENE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REPORTERS DESCEND ON KENNEDY'S NEW YORK NEIGHBORHOOD 
</HEADLINE>
   (With KENNEDY-MISSING-PLANE)  
(lh) 
 By PAUL ZIELBAUER    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The normally quiet TriBeCa neighborhood that is home
to John F. Kennedy Jr. and his wife, Carolyn Bessette Kennedy,
turned into a media jungle Saturday afternoon, as police guarded
the building where the couple live and reporters stationed
themselves outside, searching for people who knew the Kennedys.
</P>
<P>
   Behind the blue police sawhorses, two bouquets of flowers lay on
the gray iron steps leading to the doorway of the apartment
building at 20 North Moore St., a gritty 10-floor industrial
structure whose top floor is occupied by the Kennedys.
</P>
<P>
   Kennedy is a popular and oft-noticed personality in the
neighborhood, a celebrity who makes frequent stops at his favorite
breakfast place, Bubby's, and the magazine shop and grocery store
around the corner.
</P>
<P>
   At least twice a week, Kennedy, 38, orders his usual breakfast
of oatmeal and cafe latte at Bubby's, a restaurant on the corner of
Hudson and North Moore streets that lures more than its share of
celebrity regulars, including actors Robert DeNiro and Harvey
Keitel.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was always asking questions about the kids or how the
business was going,'' said Seth Price, 35, a co-owner of Bubby's
who became friends with Kennedy over the course of nine years. ``He
was born into this family that is like royalty in the United
States, but he was really a human being. You meet a lot of
celebrities in this business,'' Price said, ``and many of them
believe in their own hype. John wasn't like that at all.''
</P>
<P>
   During his days as a Manhattan assistant district attorney,
Kennedy would often show up for breakfast in business suits, Price
said. Other days, he would show up in shorts and tennis shoes
during a break in a day of errands.
</P>
<P>
   One block away, at the Hudson Market, owner Talsun Yi said
Kennedy was always running in to buy coffee, a newspaper or some
fruit. ``He always bought the 50-cent coffee,'' Mrs. Yi, 70, said.
``He was such a nice man. He always came in looking like he was
jogging, wearing clothes that were not so nice. Shoes were not
new,'' she said. ``I always said, John F. Kennedy, he's so rich,
but he always acted the same as you or me.''
</P>
<P>
   Kennedy attended the New York Yankees' game at Yankee Stadium on
Thursday night, sitting near the home dugout, and it did not escape
the notice of the players that Kennedy stayed to watch the entire
game. Some players, David Cone among them, greeted Kennedy briefly,
and after the game, Kennedy departed the stands through the tunnels
of Yankee Stadium, escorted by security.
</P>
<P>
   Manager Joe Torre had noticed all the attention focused on a
nearby fan during the game, but hadn't realized until later who the
fan was.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't see him,'' Torre said. ``After the game, my niece
said, `Wow, it was neat seeing him,' and I was like, `Oh, that's
who that was.' What a tragedy. If that doesn't tell you to enjoy
every day, I don't know what does.''
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees asked for silence before Saturday's game, with the
announcer Bob Sheppard mentioning the uncertainty of Kennedy's
whereabouts, and asking fans to think about the Kennedy family for
a few moments.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
