<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCHULKEN-COLUMN20-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    From the sidelines to the game
 &HT;    By Mary Schulken
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Her glove was meticulously broken in, prepared for use by
wrapping its pocket around a ball, dampening the leather and
leaving it to dry.
</P>
<P>
   Her knees were scabbed as mercilessly as any boy's, scrape upon
scrape earned running down grounders that threatened to slip
between second and third.
</P>
<P>
   Her swing put her on base more times than not.
</P>
<P>
   But when the team took the field, she sat on the sidelines. She
could play, but she couldn't suit up.
</P>
<P>
   Those are the memories of a generation of women. Forty-something
and fifty-something women who once stuffed pigtails inside ball
caps for practice games with brothers and who bought striped
uniforms at the dime store with their allowances. Women who
perfected lay-ups on hoops nailed to barn walls. Women whose
bat-broadened shoulders now bear briefcases, whose muscled arms
lift kids and groceries, and whose knees ? well, whose knees don't
look good in short skirts.
</P>
<P>
   Those memories of the sidelines mingle, bittersweet, with the
images of national adulation for a victorious U.S. women's soccer
team. They are baggage from the days when boys played ball and
girls cheered them on. The days before Title IX, before we as a
nation said women deserve a playing field in high school and
college.
</P>
<P>
   Like other winners, the women's soccer team has captured the
respect and imagination of a culture that attaches enormous
significance to athletic accomplishments. Yet this particular
snapshot of success _ this picture of a nation celebrating talented
and unabashedly competitive women _ takes on a very personal
meaning for those who want to get in the game.
</P>
<P>
   All of us have crazy things, wild things we hold inside our
heart that we want to see. Things that have taken on an almost
unexplained meaning.
</P>
<P>
   For me, it's seeing a woman in a major league uniform. Pitching.
Hitting. Stopping grounders and making a neat toss to second, or a
bullet throw to first for the out.
</P>
<P>
   It won't be me. But I want to see it. I can't really say why,
but it thrills me to think about it.
</P>
<P>
   I don't believe those who say it will never happen. I especially
don't believe them now, while the world claps its hands in glee
over women who can both kick the ball and kick butt.
</P>
<P>
   That's what Title IX and all such measures that aim at
equalizing opportunities in this country have done. They have
opened up the possibilities.
</P>
<P>
   Go back to the sidelines, back 30 years, to the 10-year-old girl
good enough to practice but not play. She might not be able to put
that loss of opportunity into words. This one could not have. But
the forty-something woman can tell you precisely how not being in
the game narrowed her view of the possibilities.
</P>
<P>
   It is no different than the way a staircase makes a person in a
wheelchair feel. No different than when a black child looks around
and sees no black teachers, doctors or police officers.
</P>
<P>
   Now, take a long look at the game film from the World Cup
championship. Take a long look at the young women right in front of
your eyes who in summer whip softballs past batters with the grace
of Cy Young. And take a look at the fans who cheer them, not for
their pretty faces, but for their skill and determination.
</P>
<P>
   How does the world change? In slow, almost unrecognizable
increments.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes that change just happens. But more times than not, it
takes a well-placed kick.
</P>
<P>
   Mary C. Schulken is editorial page editor of The Daily Reflector
in Greenville, N.C.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
