<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-METS-PIAZZA-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BATTING NO. 2 IN NEW YORK: PIAZZA AND THE METS 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 By JASON DIAMOS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ST. PETERSBURG, Fla. _ For one weekend _ last weekend _ New
York's baseball spotlight finally belonged to Mike Piazza, and he
seized it with two three-run home runs as the Mets took two of
three games from the Yankees.
</P>
<P>
   But now reality has returned, and the reality is that Piazza and
the Mets will once again assume their status as second-class
citizens in the New York sports caste system.
</P>
<P>
   How does Piazza, a seven-time All-Star who signed a seven-year,
$91 million contract during the off-season, feel about playing _ in
his own words _ ``second fiddle'' to the Yankees?
</P>
<P>
   ``I really don't think we care about that,'' Piazza said. ``It's
inevitable that the Yankees are going to be covered more or given
more exposure in New York, and that's fine. I think they've earned
it. It's nice not to worry about it. We can play our game and
hopefully get to the point where they are.''
</P>
<P>
   That is exactly what Piazza is supposed to say. But how does
Piazza, who was the undisputed hero in Los Angeles while playing
for the Dodgers from 1993 to 1998, feel about being treated like
the embers compared to the inferno set off by Derek Jeter's star
turn as the Yankees' Most Valuable Player candidate? After all, the
competition for the city's buzz began early as Piazza and Jeter
shared many preseason magazine covers this spring. But Piazza
clearly likes the personable Yankee shortstop and he insists he's
not counting _ or courting _ headlines.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think anybody who knows me knows I don't really thrive on
things like that,'' Piazza said. ``That's not what I'm all about. I
really don't think I'm an ego-driven athlete. I don't have any
problem with it. I kind of enjoy it. That's the way I've always
been. That wave of attention kind of comes and goes and I don't
mind it.''
</P>
<P>
   Which is one reason why Piazza chose to buy a home in Bergen
County, N.J., across the George Washington Bridge from Manhattan.
It's close enough to the intensity that fuels the city. But far
enough removed from it, too.
</P>
<P>
   The Mets care about the attention, however. Or lack of it.
Especially compared to the coverage the Yankees receive in the
local news media. The main reason, in fact, that the Mets' co-owner
Nelson Doubleday and General Manager Steve Phillips traded for
Piazza last May was to address the glaring void of a so-called
marquee player in the Mets' lineup and fill all those empty seats
at Shea Stadium in the process.
</P>
<P>
   And what did Piazza's re-signing with the Mets do to the overall
perception of Manager Bobby Valentine's team?
</P>
<P>
   ``It changed it,'' Valentine said. ``By signing back with us, he
got other people to sign with us. It bolstered our image. It made
us credible. It made us star-studded. And he's made us a very good
team.''
</P>
<P>
   Before Piazza re-signed, Shea Stadium had pretty much belonged
to Valentine for much of the last two seasons. Valentine craves the
spotlight and has a dominant personality. But he has become more
subdued this season, while the club has aggressively signed and
promoted its star players, Piazza in particular.
</P>
<P>
   The money the Mets spent in the off-season to upgrade their team
showed a clear commitment to building their first postseason
qualifier in 11 years. But even with Piazza and a creditable
second-place showing in the National League East, the Mets still
lag far behind the Yankees _ who have won the World Series two of
the last three seasons _ in terms of popularity and news coverage.
</P>
<P>
   That is inevitable, said John Franco, who has been with the Mets
since 1990, who grew up in Brooklyn and who played in Cincinnati
when the Mets of the 1980s captivated New York.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nothing's going to change unless you win,'' Franco said. ``And
when the Mets were winning in the '80s, they were the talk of the
town.''
</P>
<P>
   By the mid-'90s, the Mets were more like the laughingstocks.
Their owners significantly slashed expenditures after the 72-90 and
59-103 debacles of 1992 and 1993. Only now is that perception
starting to change.
</P>
<P>
   But perception and reality are two different things, especially
in the hard currency of the baseball marketplace.
</P>
<P>
   For example, it has been rumored recently that Alex Rodriguez,
the gifted shortstop of the Seattle Mariners whose contract is up
after next season, has cooled on the idea of coming to the Mets
because not only would he be on the second team in town, he would
be the second shortstop in town (to Jeter) and the second player on
his own team (to Piazza).
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's kind of funny,'' Piazza said when told about the
Rodriguez rumor. ``For me, it's enough to do my job every day. I
realize I do have a tremendous amount of the workload on this team.
And maybe if I played another position, I would stand around a lot
more and have the time to think about it a lot more. But I don't
care if I'm put on a cover of some magazine.''
</P>
<P>
   Maybe not. But the people who pay his salary most certainly do.
Which is OK with Piazza, too.
</P>
<P>
   ``If someone wants to promote me, fine,'' Piazza said. ``But I'm
not a self-promoter. I don't have the energy for it. I'll let my
play speak for itself.''
</P>
</TEXT>
