A3935 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-OUTDOORS-DRUM-NYT &LR;      07-17 0932
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OUTDOORS-DRUM-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMBING A BIG BAY FOR A BIG FISH 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By KEN SCHULTZ   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANNAPOLIS, Md. _ My taste buds have never met a softshelled crab
they didn't like. To me, this molting blue crab is especially
likable when cooked on a grill after having been marinated in a
mixture of ranch dressing, olive oil, fresh garlic and lemon juice.
</P>
<P>
   So, at 7 o'clock on a recent morning, when Lenny Rudow opened a
package of 10 fresh softshells and said that this was what we would
be putting on our fishhooks to catch black drum, my eyes opened
wide. Pound for pound, softshells are two to three times the price
of lobster, another delicacy better suited to my taste buds than
those of some fish.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just had two of these for dinner last night,'' I said as
Lenny cut a fresh, soft crab in half and threaded it on the hook.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is how the drum are caught here,'' he answered. ``We have
to find them and drop the crab right on their noses.''
</P>
<P>
   That is a bare-bones explanation of the process, but there's
nothing simple about it. Though relatively shallow, Chesapeake Bay,
at 180 miles long, is the greatest bay on the East Coast, and not
without a lot of places to seek these fish. Finding them is not as
simple as, say, walking up to a deep pool on a trout stream.
</P>
<P>
   Black drum are powerful, stocky fish with deep bodies and an
arched back; they are capable of growing to more than 100 pounds.
They are bottom feeders that use whiskerlike chin barbells on their
lower jaw to find clams and crabs, which they crush with large
teeth in their throat.
</P>
<P>
   Black drum are not aggressive predators that see or hear their
prey and chase it, like many popular sportfish. Add to this the
fact that angling is done in 20 to 30 feet of water where there is
often significant tidal current, blowing wind and rolling waves,
and black drum fishing becomes a semicomplicated hunt bearing
little resemblance to many tightly focused angling activities.
</P>
<P>
   The major payoff is that Chesapeake drum are large and provide a
powerful tussle; it can take 15 to 20 minutes to land one on
medium-strength tackle. An amazing aspect of the Chesapeake Bay
black drum sportfishery is that angler-caught specimens weigh on
average about 40 pounds, which often makes them the largest or
near-largest fish most people have ever caught.
</P>
<P>
   The second payoff is culinary. All members of the drum family
have food value; the red drum, known as redfish and a more
southerly species, is the fare of blackened redfish fame and a
Creole staple. The black drum, though best in smaller sizes, is
often found in large fillets at market during spring and early
summer. Its flesh is tender and delicately flavored; the texture,
which is coarse rather than flaky, draws comparisons to a thick
slice of roast pork and supports diverse cooking methods,
especially grilling. Two nights earlier, a group of us had enjoyed
drum that came from a fish market and that we had broiled with a
simple lemon-pepper garnish.
</P>
<P>
   Lenny and I began our drum hunt 20 miles south of Annapolis, in
about 30 feet of water over an oyster reef. Two charter boats were
cruising the site when we arrived. Five or six anglers stood in the
stern of each boat, both classic low-slung 40-foot Chesapeake Bay
boats with wide-open cockpits and low gunwales, bracing their knees
against the gunwale with rod in hand.
</P>
<P>
   It took 2 ounces of sinker to get half a crab down to the
bottom. We searched the area, concentrating on the deep edge where
the bottom dropped off, watching for fish on the sonar. After
spotting them on the bay bottom, we immediately stopped the boat
and lowered the bait to the bottom, drifting it along. Usually
black drum travel in schools, so there could have been a number of
fish to entice at any time.
</P>
<P>
   The reef showed little on the sonar, and after an hour we picked
up and moved 6 miles south, where a cluster of five charter boats
was working another reef. We drifted close to one boat and asked
the anglers if they'd caught anything. ``Only one,'' said a burly,
shirtless fellow with his cap on backward, braced against the
transom. ``About 70 pounds.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Only one,'' I said to Lenny, with a hint of sarcasm, but he
had spotted something on the sonar and was putting the throttle in
neutral. ``Drop here.'' Down went our softshells, and we waited for
the anticipated strike of a very big fish. After drifting for
several minutes we reeled up and moved on along the oyster reef,
hunting for something else on the sonar.
</P>
<P>
   This we did for hours on end. Periodically, we saw someone on
one of the charter boats hook up, then noticed a net or gaff come
out to lift a big-bodied fish over the gunwale. But we couldn't
manage anything more than the incidental catch of one weakfish, an
undersized striped bass, and two foul-hooked menhaden, a prominent
schooling baitfish.
</P>
<P>
   Late in the afternoon we turned the boat for home. Lenny, a
writer for Boating magazine, was testing a 20-foot Nautico
catamaran-hulled boat powered by two 70-horsepower Suzuki outboard
motors. Catamaran hulls are becoming more popular on American power
boats, and this wide-beamed one was impressively stable en route
home in the bay's choppy water.
</P>
<P>
   Equally impressive was that after running nonstop all day and
covering more than 60 miles of water, the motors consumed just 22
gallons of gas. The cost of the gas, it occurred to me, was less
than the cost of the 10 delicious-looking softshell crabs that we
wasted on unappreciative drum. We should have eaten the bait
ourselves.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
