<HEADER>
A3936 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KENNEDY-MISSING-PLANE     07-17 1062
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KENNEDY-MISSING-PLANE-ART-1STLD-WRITETHRU-950(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PLANE FLYING JOHN KENNEDY, HIS WIFE AND HER SISTER IS MISSING 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (SUBS for complete update; inserts throughout.)  (See also: KENNEDY-PILOT, KENNEDY-TRAGEDY, KENNEDY-SEARCH,
KENNEDY-NY-SCENE, KENNEDY-MASS-SCENE) 
(ART ADV: Photo of John Kennedy Jr. with his staff at George
magazine is being sent to NYT photo clients. Map is being sent to
NYT graphic clients. Non-subscribers can make individual purchase
by calling (888) 603-1036.) 
(lh) 
 By DAVID BARSTOW    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ A small plane carrying John F. Kennedy Jr., his wife,
Carolyn Bessette Kennedy, and her sister, Lauren Bessette,
disappeared late Friday, and by Saturday afternoon, the authorities
had recovered debris off Martha's Vineyard, Mass., that they said
may have come from the plane.
</P>
<P>
   A Coast Guard spokesman said that debris, found about 100 yards
off Gay Head, included luggage, carpeting and a headrest.
</P>
<P>
   Kennedy, who was believed to be piloting the plane, was flying
to the wedding of a cousin, Rory, the youngest daughter of Sen.
Robert F. Kennedy, in Hyannisport, Mass. Ms. Kennedy was to be
married Saturday before 275 guests in a private ceremony. The
wedding was postponed indefinitely.
</P>
<P>
   Lt. Martha LaGuardia, a Coast Guard spokeswoman, said the plane,
a Piper Saratoga owned by Kennedy, left from Fairfield, N.J., at
8:38 p.m. on Friday and was scheduled to land on Martha's Vineyard
about 10 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   The Federal Aviation Administration reported that the last
contact with the plane came at 9:39 p.m. when it was 17 miles from
Martha's Vineyard, the Coast Guard said in a statement. When the
plane did not arrive, the Kennedy family notified the FAA, which
began trying to track the plane, a staff member for Sen. Edward M.
Kennedy said.
</P>
<P>
   At the Kennedy compound in Hyannisport Saturday, a white tent
stood by the sea, and a flag at full staff billowed in the breeze.
A Mass was held on the porch of the house of Rory's mother, Ethel
Kennedy, with about 50 family members and three priests praying
``for the safety of the loved ones, as well as for Rory'' and her
fiance, Mark Bailey, said a family spokesman, Brian O'Connor.
</P>
<P>
   Kennedy, 38, is the only surviving son of John F. Kennedy, the
35th president. He was born on Nov. 25, 1960, weeks after his
father's election and was known to the nation as ``John-John,'' a
childhood nickname.
</P>
<P>
   After his father's assassination, the enduring image from the
funeral came when Kennedy, then a little boy in a blue coat and
shorts, saluted his father's casket outside St. Matthew's
Cathedral.
</P>
<P>
   It was his third birthday.
</P>
<P>
   Given his celebrity and political pedigree, word of Kennedy's
disappearance touched off an extraordinary reaction, from the
corridors of the White House, to the major networks, which broke
into their schedules for live reports from their anchors.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton, spending the weekend at Camp David, was told
about the plane's disappearance by John Podesta, his chief of
staff, shortly after 7 a.m. Saturday, the White House said.
</P>
<P>
   The president called several members of the Kennedy family,
including Kennedy's sister, Caroline Kennedy Schlossberg; Sen.
Edward M. Kennedy, D-Mass.; and Housing Secretary Andrew Cuomo,
husband of Kerry Kennedy, daughter of Robert F. Kennedy.
</P>
<P>
   ``All our prayers and thoughts are with the families of those on
board,'' Clinton said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
   Former New York Gov. Mario Cuomo, the father of Andrew Cuomo,
was among many whose response Saturday was shaped by the family's
seemingly unending dance with tragedy.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think,'' said Cuomo, ``there are just two reactions that
most people share: The almost inexplicable concentration of
tragedy, the reiteration of it in the Kennedy family, which,
perhaps because of their celebrity, seems almost unique. And the
second more important impression is the way they react to their
tragedy over time.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is not by becoming bitter and cursing the gods who did this
to them. It is by becoming more generous and turning to works of
commitment, especially for those people most in need.''
</P>
<P>
   The White House said search efforts were being coordinated by
the Coast Guard, the U.S. Department of Transportation and the
Department of Defense.
</P>
<P>
   The Air Force Rescue Coordination Center out of Langley Air
Force Base in Virginia was leading the search, with help from Coast
Guard vessels dispatched from Cape Cod and Montauk, N.Y.
</P>
<P>
   The search was being conducted along the presumed flight path of
Kennedy's plane.
</P>
<P>
   The Coast Guard said that in addition to a number of vessels, it
had deployed two H-60s, or Jayhawk, helicopters and a Falcon
fixed-wing jet. They were searching off Cape Code, in Block Island
Sound, in Long Island Sound, and along the South Shore of Long
Island.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've set up search areas that would cover any possible area
the plane would have flown over,'' Ms. LaGuardia said. ``We would
hope that if there was a distress signal we would be able to pick
up on it.'' But, she said, ``I have not been able to confirm any
kind of signal.''
</P>
<P>
   Other agencies joined the search. The Air National Guard of
Gabreski, New York, dispatched a C-130 cargo plane. Fifteen
airplanes from the Civil Air Patrol were searching, too.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have three marine boats searching the North Shore area,
from Huntington out east,'' said Officer Robert Harris of the
Suffolk County (N.Y.) Police Department.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. LaGuardia said she did not know who was piloting the plane.
Some news reports said Kennedy, who obtained his pilot's license
last year, was at the controls. Other reports said a flight
instructor was on board.
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman for the National Transportation Safety Board, Ted
Lopatkiewicz, said his agency, which investigates all plane
crashes, was standing by. ``We wouldn't know where to go at this
stage,'' he said. The Safety Board got the report of an overdue
plane at about 5 a.m., he said.
</P>
<P>
   The National Transportation Safety Board early Saturday morning
sent investigators to the airport in Caldwell to gather records and
speak to ground personnel, according to a person answering the
phone at the airport operations center. The Safety Board's regional
office is nearby, in Parsippany, N.J.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't believe that something like this could happen _ again
_ to the Kennedy family,'' said Mayor Rudolph Giuliani of New York,
speaking at the city's Office of Emergency Management on the 23rd
floor of the World Trade Center. ``Let's hope and pray that it's a
successful effort,'' he said of the search.
</P>
<P>
   Police Commissioner Howard Safir said the New York Police
Department, acting on a request from the Kennedy family early
Saturday, had dispatched officers to Kennedy's Manhattan apartment
to make sure he was not there.
</P>
<P>
   The family also asked the police to make sure Kennedy's car was
the airport.
</P>
<P>
   Kyle Bailey, 25, a merchandising analyst from Cedar Grove, N.J.,
and a pilot flying from this airport for 13 years, said he saw
Kennedy and his wife at about 8 p.m. Friday as they walked toward
Kennedy's plane parked at Essex Airport in Caldwell. In the
airport, a group of teen-age girls caught sight of him and gushed
about how they could not believe he had a plane at Essex Airport.
</P>
<P>
   Bailey said he watched as Kennedy walked around the outside of
the airplane and then went through a routine series of preflight
checks. Bailey said he noticed one unusual thing about Kennedy's
preflight check. Usually pilots take their planes down the runway a
bit to do their engine `rev-ups,' to avoid creating too much noise
in the parking area. But he said Kennedy did his rev-ups in the
parking space.
</P>
<P>
   ``The impression I got was maybe there was something wrong with
the plane. It just caught my attention, like, `Why is he doing this
here?''' he said.
</P>
<P>
   He said Kennedy's plane took off heading south, then turned west
and then headed northwest, toward Martha's Vineyard. Bailey, who
flew to Martha's Vineyard two weeks ago, said the ocean route can
be hazardous, especially at night.
</P>
<P>
   ``Flying over the ocean at night isn't the safest feeling. I
know that route and at night with fog it can become dangerous,'' he
said. ``I went home to my family and said, `He's going to kill
himself one day in that airplane.' I mean, it was really a hazy
night,'' Bailey.
</P>
<P>
   Aircraft such as the Piper do not carry flight data recorders or
cockpit voice recorders, the ``black boxes'' that investigators use
to piece together the details of airliner crashes.
</P>
<P>
   The plane was flying under visual flight rules, meaning that the
pilot took responsibility for picking his route and avoiding other
traffic, rather than relying on air traffic controllers.
</P>
<P>
   Thus the FAA's air traffic control system did not assign it a
specific beacon code; it would have showed up on controllers' radar
screens with a generic symbol denoting general aviation.
</P>
<P>
   Investigators could pick it out, though, if they knew its hour
of departure and general route. That might help locate the wreckage
or, if could give a clue if the plane broke up in flight, officials
said.
</P>
<P>
   Though wind conditions were mild on Friday night, visibility in
the area was poor, pilots said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was very hazy, and it was very dark, and it was very hard
to see the horizon,'' said Michael C. Bard, a private pilot, who
left Martha's Vineyard about 9:15 p.m. on Friday and flew back to
his home in Danbury, Conn.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you're not instrument rated, it could be difficult
maintaining the airplane in an upright condition.''
</P>
<P>
   Larry Lorenzo, the owner of Caldwell Flight Academy, which
operates at Essex County Airport, said he believed Kennedy was in
the process of getting his instrument license, which allows pilots
to fly in cloudy or bad weather, using only instruments.
</P>
<P>
   After graduating from Brown University, Kennedy went to law
school and joined the Manhattan district attorney's office.
</P>
<P>
   In 1995 he started the magazine George _ subtitled ``not just
politics as usual.'' A year later, Kennedy _ once dubbed ``the
sexiest man alive'' by People magazine _ married Ms. Bessette, the
whispy blond daughter of a Greenwich, Conn., doctor.
</P>
<P>
   But in Hyannisport Saturday, another Kennedy wedding was turned
into an anxious vigil. Christina Rivers of Hyannis was to dress the
hair of the bridal party before attending the wedding as a guest.
Friday night, she designed Rory's hair for the rehearsal dinner.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was just wonderful over there last night, just exciting,''
Ms. Rivers said. ``It's just not fair. I don't know what it is, but
it's not fair.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
