<SLUG> BC-TOURDEFRANCE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A WEARY POSTAL SERVICE PROCEEDING ON SCHEDULE 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 By SAMUEL ABT   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBI, France _ Defending the yellow jersey of its and the Tour
de France's leader, the U.S. Postal Service team spent another
uneventful day Saturday, but even on quiet days the psychological
and physical toll is high on a team trying to control the race.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm weary,'' said Frankie Andreu, of Dearborn, Mich., who is
in his eighth Tour and has never failed to finish one yet.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't wait for the rest day,'' he added. That will come
Monday, at the foot of the Pyrenees.
</P>
<P>
   A teammate, Tyler Hamilton, of Brookline, Mass., agreed with him
before the day's stage. ``Feeling pretty tired,'' he said. ``It's a
lot of work at the front of the pack. Of course, it's all worth it.
This team is dedicated to keeping Lance in the yellow jersey,
whatever it takes.''
</P>
<P>
   It did not take much Saturday. Sixteen riders were allowed to
break away at Kilometer 8 (Mile 5) of the 236.5-kilometer
(147-mile) 13th stage from St. Flour to Albi. As in the first two
of four days' passage from the Alps to the Pyrenees, the 16 riders
were all far behind in the overall time standing and no threat to
Lance Armstrong, the Texan in the yellow jersey. The attack went
according to the Postal Service plan.
</P>
<P>
   ``The first day we chased down a lot of breaks,'' Andreu said.
</P>
<P>
   When Armstrong's rivals were either caught or discouraged, a
bunch of lesser lights was granted free passage. ``Yesterday,''
Andreu continued Saturday morning, ``we were too spent to chase
much, so we just let them go. Same thing today, I expect.''
</P>
<P>
   It was. The 16, who quickly shrunk to 15 when one rider could
not keep pace, were mainly Italians and Spaniards far down in the
ranking for the Tour, which ends July 25.
</P>
<P>
   The 15 passed over seven testing hills, up and down all day,
until they sighted the red roofs that testify to Albi's
Mediterranean orientation. For the last 50 kilometers (31 miles)
there was scarcely a house along the race's roads that did not have
its shutters closed against the sun.
</P>
<P>
   After 5 hours 52 minutes 45 seconds, the winner was Salvatore
Commesso, the Italian national champion and a rider for Saeco, who
outsprinted Marco Serpellini, an Italian with Lampre, by two
seconds after the group of 15 came together. Third, 2:07 behind,
was Mariano Piccolli, another Italian with Lampre. The winner's
average time of 40 kilometers an hour (25 miles an hour) was
startling in the first heavy heat of the race.
</P>
<P>
   The leaders' pack finished 22:24 later. Armstrong remained in
the lead by 7:44 over Abraham Olano, a Spaniard with ONCE, and by
7:47 over Alex Zuelle.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike most of his teammates, Armstrong was saucy Saturday
morning, for at least three reasons. For one, he usually is. For
another, he is comfortable and confident as the Tour's leader and
possibly the first American since Greg LeMond in 1990, and only the
second in history, to win the sport's most prestigious race, which
began in 1903.
</P>
<P>
   For a third, he does not ride at the very front of the pack,
like Hamilton, setting the pace. The Texan races instead in his
teammates' slipstream, saving about 20 percent of the energy that
the rider up ahead is expending.
</P>
<P>
   Until Armstrong joined the team last year, the U.S. Postal
Service had little experience in controlling a race for a leader.
``We did it for Eki in the Dauphine two years ago,'' Hamilton said.
``Then we did it for Jonathan in the same race last month.'' He
referred to Slava Ekimov, a Russian who was the former team leader,
and Jonathan Vaughters, who led the Dauphine for three days before
he finished second.
</P>
<P>
   Vaughters, of Englewood, Colo., quit the Tour de France after he
crashed and injured himself during the second of 20 stages. Postal
Service lost another of its nine men Saturday when Peter
Meinert-Nielsen of Denmark had to abandon competition because of a
damaged knee.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, the overall plan is working. Neither Olano nor
Zuelle has tried to attack in the four transitional stages,
preferring instead to await the mountains. Even when a rider not so
low-placed has infiltrated a breakaway and gained time, the
American team has stayed the course. An example is Stephane Heulot,
a Frenchman with La Francaise des Jeux, who ranked 21st, more than
20 minutes behind Armstrong, on Friday morning. He rose to sixth
after he was part of an escape and gained more than 11 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Heulot doesn't worry us,'' Andreu said. ``He's still nine
minutes back, and the way Lance is climbing, he'll take a bundle
out of him in the Pyrenees.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
