u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-HEAT-WAVE-450&AMP;ADD-     07-17 1099
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-HEAT-WAVE-450&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HEAT TAKES ANOTHER SHOT AT THE CITY'S WEATHERED POPULACE 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By RANDY KENNEDY    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ First the good news: the temperatures actually were
cooler Saturday than those that seared the metropolitan region over
the Fourth of July weekend. But most people, until they looked at a
thermometer, refused to believe it.
</P>
<P>
   ``It feels like it's 99 degrees,'' said Rosell Stone, a
68-year-old woman who was the first person to seek refuge Saturday
at the East River Community Center on East 105th Street, where the
city has set up an emergency cooling center for those without
air-conditioning.
</P>
<P>
   As Ms. Stone spoke, it was, in fact, only in the high 80s. And
forecasters said the temperatures were expected to climb to no more
than 98, just shy of the 101-degree highs during the last heat
wave. The heat index, the combination of temperature and relative
humidity that gives a better indication of how hot the day feels,
was expected to reach 105 to 110, also a little cooler than the
last hot spell, which the city medical examiner's office said was
responsible for 31 deaths.
</P>
<P>
   ``But that's really little comfort,'' said Paul Knight, a
meteorologist at Pennsylvania State University, who added that the
high temperatures were expected to last at least until Friday.
``For those susceptible to the heat, it's probably going to feel
pretty much the same.''
</P>
<P>
   And around the city, those who contend directly with the results
of the heat _ workers for Consolidated Edison, city emergency
officials, police officers and hospitals _ braced for exactly that.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a very, very difficult day,'' said Mayor Rudolph W.
Giuliani, who joined Jerome M. Hauer, the city's director of
emergency services, and other officials Saturday at the city's
Emergency Command Center at the World Trade Center.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're hopeful we can get through the day without a blackout, a
brownout or some kind of significant problem,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Con Edison officials said they were much better prepared heading
into this stretch of hot days than during the last heat wave, when
several cables feeding electricity to the northern part of
Manhattan were out of service even before the hot weekend began. As
of Saturday morning, said Joseph Petta, a spokesman for the power
company, seven of 1,150 feeder cables were out of service
throughout the 604 square miles of the company's service area. On
July 2, before the last heat wave, 13 cables were not working.
</P>
<P>
   Those kinds of problems are not uncommon even during mild
summers, Petta said. ``It's unfortunate that we're so much under
the microscope here,'' he added. ``On any given day, we take
feeders out for general maintenance all the time, and there could
easily be seven down. But during a heat wave, those numbers get a
lot of attention.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Petta said that all the cables in northern Manhattan that were
damaged during the last heat wave had been repaired and that those
down Saturday _ five in Westchester, one in the Bronx and one in
Queens _ had left only nine customers without power as of Saturday
morning. On July 6, to prevent more damage to the system, Con Ed
shut down power to about 200,000 people north of 155th Street. The
blackout lasted 18 hours.
</P>
<P>
   Con Edison engineers said that by 11 a.m. Saturday, the power
drain on the system was 8,500 megawatts and was expected to rise to
9,500, less than Friday's total of 10,800 and far less than that
used during the last heat wave, which set a record with 11,800
megawatts used. Nonetheless, the company had deployed crews to
monitor the system ``at a level we usually employ only during
extreme emergency conditions,'' Petta said.
</P>
<P>
   And the test will be whether the system can hold up after the
weekend, when workers return to offices and power use typically
increases dramatically. Knight said that more clouds Sunday would
probably bring the temperatures down to about 95, but that the
unusual heat would likely continue at least to the end of the week.
</P>
<P>
   Normally, he said, the third week in July is the hottest of the
summer in the metropolitan region. By the end of this week, he
said, the forecast is for temperatures ``much above normal,''
though he did not predict a high.
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani _ who has strongly criticized Con Edison's preparedness
for heat waves and prompted the city to sue the company last week
for damage caused by the blackout _ did not take the company to
task Saturday. He said that since the failures of the last heat
wave, the company had been in closer touch with city officials, and
most Con Edison officials believed there would not be another
widespread blackout.
</P>
<P>
   ``At this point,'' Giuliani said, ``I think they believe they're
going to get through Saturday OK I think their concern is more
focused toward Monday.''
</P>
<P>
   Water usage _ which was also a serious issue during the last
heat wave as illegally opened hydrants reduced water pressure in
northern Manhattan _ appeared to be within safe limits Saturday,
said Joel A. Miele, the commissioner of the Department of
Environmental Protection.
</P>
<P>
   Only about 23 hydrants were opened illegally overnight Friday,
he said, and New York's water system has remained the only one in
the state not to be placed on a drought watch. ``The pressure is
good and strong,'' Miele said, ``and we'd like to keep it that
way.''
</P>
<P>
   While uncomfortably above average, the high temperatures
Saturday were not expected to break any records.
</P>
<P>
   They were expected to edge very close, though.
</P>
<P>
   The record high for July 17 in the city was 100 degrees, set in
1953, and the record for July 18 was 101, set in the same year. But
Knight said that because of the heavy humidity _ about 49 percent
just after noon _ the heat index for the weekend was solidly in
``that dangerous zone.''
</P>
<P>
   He did not have to tell Ricardo Villarine, a 38-year-old Bronx
man who carried his 1{-year-old daughter, Lisette, from her
grandmother's apartment on East 105th Street to a wildly spouting
hydrant on the corner.
</P>
<P>
   Villarine said he suffers from asthma, which is made worse by
heat and humidity. ``I hang around places where I know the
hospitals are close,'' he said. Saturday, after walking several
blocks with his daughter, he stepped happily right into the spray
of the hydrant.
</P>
<P>
   Near him, Niky Zapata, 8, was busy filling up water balloons and
wished he could douse himself, too. ``But my mother said I couldn't
get wet,'' he said, ``because I already took a bath.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
