<HEADLINE>
STANLEY SOBLE, 59, CASTING DIRECTOR 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Calif.)  (js) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Stanley Soble, casting director for the Center Theater
Group/Ahmanson Theater and the Mark Taper Forum in Los Angeles,
died on July 6 at Cedars-Sinai Medical Center in Los Angeles. He
was 59.
</P>
<P>
   The cause was complications after surgery, said a spokeswoman
for the Mark Taper Forum.
</P>
<P>
   Soble was casting director at the Mark Taper for the world
premiere productions of Tony Kushner's ``Angels in America'' and
Robert Schenkkan's ``Kentucky Cycle,'' both of which went on to
Broadway. His Broadway credits include ``Jelly's Last Jam,'' ``Big
River,'' ``Moon for the Misbegotten'' and ``The Pirates of
Penzance.''
</P>
<P>
   Born in Richmond, Soble studied theater at the College of
William and Mary. His first job as a casting director was for the
NBC soap opera ``Search for Tomorrow'' in 1978.
</P>
<P>
   He is survived by a sister, Sarah Coyne, and a brother, Paul.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
