<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-17 16:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3953 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-COOPER-UNION-580&AMP;A     07-17 0934
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-COOPER-UNION-580&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOTEL DEVELOPER AND COLLEGE DRAFTING BIG PLANS 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By DAVID W. DUNLAP    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Not too long ago, overnight accommodations around
Astor Place consisted of a curbside or a door stoop. No more.
</P>
<P>
   Ian Schrager, the hotelier behind such stylish spots as the
Royalton and Morgan's in Manhattan and the Delano in Miami Beach,
is planning a new hotel on the site of a parking lot at Astor Place
and Lafayette Street, near the Joseph Papp Public Theater. He is to
develop it with Related Cos. on a 99-year lease from the Cooper
Union for the Advancement of Science and Art, which owns the lot.
</P>
<P>
   The college has even bigger plans to transform the bubbling
Astor Place-Cooper Square crossroads in lower Manhattan from a
rough-and-tumble vortex into a grand public plaza.
</P>
<P>
   To do so, it will work closely with Schrager and Related Cos. on
the design of the new hotel. In a highly unusual competition
devised by the college, the developers will submit designs by two
renowned architects, yet to be named, for review by a Cooper Union
selection committee, in concert with Schrager and Related.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are not a stranger to the process,'' said Jeff Blau,
executive vice president of Related, which sponsored a competition
of its own for public artwork at a new apartment tower on East 14th
Street, overlooking Union Square.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that the outcome will be a fantastic building,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   But it will not be easy. Under the terms of the competition, the
new structure must be an ``original artistic invention'' while
harmonizing with Cooper Union's original home, the 140-year-old
Foundation Building, which is undergoing an $11 million exterior
renovation. The hotel would also set the tone for the future plaza.
</P>
<P>
   ``We hope that the building will dictate a great space, a human
space, of appealing and mesmerizing dimension,'' said John Jay
Iselin, the president of Cooper Union. ``This is the beginning of a
process that, in its own way, would be as dramatic as Rockefeller
Center.''
</P>
<P>
   The Astor Place hotel will be the first that Schrager has built
from the ground up rather than renovated, Blau said. It will have
about 100 rooms, with about 150,000 square feet of space, and may
rise 12 stories _ the height has not been determined. Completion is
expected in 2002. To fulfill Cooper Union's requirement of a
cultural tenant, there will be an art-house cinema in the basement.
</P>
<P>
   Depending on city approval and support from the community,
Cooper Union envisions closing or narrowing some stretches of
street to create a circular plaza at the hub of the jumbled
seven-way intersection where the Astor Place subway kiosk stands
and Tony Rosenthal's 10-foot steel cube, ``Alamo,'' balances on its
tip.
</P>
<P>
   Cooper Union might also redevelop the site of its bland and
outdated Engineering Building on the north side of Astor Place.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to do what we can with the assets we have to ensure
the long-term vitality of the school,'' said Robert Hawks, the
treasurer and vice president for business affairs.
</P>
<P>
   Cooper Union is one of a handful of private American colleges
offering a free education _ its officials prefer the term ``full
scholarship'' _ to every student. It costs about $23,000 a year to
put each of its 950 students through school, and Cooper Union is
currently running a $5 million deficit.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can't do what every other college does in the United
States: raise tuition,'' said Anthony Tung, a member of the Cooper
Union board who played a central role in drafting the hotel
competition guidelines.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Schrager and Related will pay an annual rent for the
18,000-square-foot parking-lot site, as well as an amount
equivalent to the real-estate taxes on the property, from which the
college is exempt. Neither the developers nor school officials
would divulge the figures.
</P>
<P>
   But Tung said the tax exemption, as well as Cooper Union's
reputation for excellence in architecture, heightened the sense of
civic responsibility in developing the site. ``It became crucial
here, as a moral issue, that we build well in every sense,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   The architects will have 75 days to prepare their proposals.
College officials and developers will take two weeks to choose. The
Cooper Union selection committee includes the architects Charles
Gwathmey and Francois de Menil and the designer Milton Glaser.
</P>
<P>
   Iselin said the competition represented ``a new chapter in
colleges claiming the future for the benefit of the citizens.''
</P>
<P>
   It is less clear how it will benefit the alumni or faculty.
Schrager is winnowing his list of architects, which includes Sir
Norman Foster of Britain and Herzog &AMP; de Meuron of Switzerland but
apparently no one connected with the Irwin S. Chanin School of
Architecture at Cooper Union. A spokeswoman said late Friday
afternoon that Schrager could not be reached for comment.
</P>
<P>
   Peter Eisenman, the Chanin distinguished professor at Cooper
Union, won a competition last month for his plan to redevelop the
area of the West 30s between Eighth Avenue and the Hudson River. He
said he knew nothing of the Astor Place contest until a reporter
telephoned him on Friday for his reaction.
</P>
<P>
   Eisenman relayed a request for an interview to John Hejduk, the
dean of the architecture school, who was responsible 25 years ago
for renovating the Foundation Building. Dean Hejduk, whose
telephone number is unlisted, replied through Eisenman that he did
not want to discuss the matter.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
