<HEADER>
A3954 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BALTIMORE-APTS-REAL-7     07-17 0807
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BALTIMORE-APTS-REAL-770(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OLD BUILDINGS, NEW HOUSING IN BALTIMORE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Va.)  (js) 
 By CHARLES BELFOURE    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   BALTIMORE _ With the help of a recently enacted state loan
program and city property tax abatements, the conversion of
outdated commercial buildings into downtown apartments here is
gathering momentum.
</P>
<P>
   The Downtown Housing Initiative, a public-private program to
develop new housing, is expected to have 414 units under
construction by the end of 1999 in four buildings, including a 1903
hotel and an 1878 warehouse.
</P>
<P>
   Conversion of those buildings will begin in the next few months.
The most prominent is the Hecht Co. Building, a former department
store on the corner of Lexington and Howard streets, once
Baltimore's premier shopping district. The $10-million project will
convert the eight-story building into 173 apartments.
</P>
<P>
   Others include the Congress Hotel, which will be transformed
into 36 luxury apartments; the Abell Building, a landmark warehouse
that will be converted into 40 apartments, and the Stanbalt
Building, built by John D. Rockefeller's Standard Oil Trust in
1922, which will have 143 apartments. The buildings are all
considered inappropriate for commercial use.
</P>
<P>
   The first major conversion will be the Hecht venture by Southern
Management of Tyson's Corner, Va., the largest apartment owner in
the Baltimore metropolitan area with 25 percent of all rental
units.
</P>
<P>
   Over a year ago, the Downtown Housing Initiative told David
Hillman, chief executive of Southern Management, about the vacant
department store. He entered into negotiations with Merchant Equity
Financial Group, a real-estate investment company based in New York
City that had purchased the building from the Rite Aid drugstore
chain. Southern Management bought the building in late June for
$4.7 million, with Rite Aid retaining the first floor in a
sale-leaseback agreement with Merchant Equity. The seven floors
above Rite Aid will become one- and two-bedroom apartments, some
with an additional loft level.
</P>
<P>
   The Hecht Building, one of four former flagship department
stores still standing on Howard Street, was constructed in 1924 in
a Classical Revival style for the Bernheimer-Leader Store. It was
sold in the late 1920s to May Co., which eventually merged with
Hecht's in 1958. The store was closed in the late '80s. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Southern Management's decision to purchase the department store
was spurred in part by the success of their Gallery Tower project,
a renovation of a long-vacant apartment building six blocks to the
north.
</P>
<P>
   Six weeks after Gallery Tower opened, two-thirds of the 144
one-bedroom units were leased. With the exception of one person,
all the tenants who had moved into the city were from out of town.
``It was a market I didn't expect,'' said Hillman. ``We're seeing a
whole new segment of people moving downtown.''
</P>
<P>
   Some would say Hillman is taking a risk in buying Hecht's and
converting it to a residential use. For Howard Street, once filled
with shoppers, is now lined with vacant storefronts along with
scattered beeper and stereo stores. The other former department
store buildings, Stewart's, Hochilds-Kohn and Hutzler's have, or
eventually will have, commercial tenants. ``David's definitely
doing frontier stuff,'' Tracy Durkin, the director of the Downtown
Housing Initiative, said of Hillman. ``He's the first to go in.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Hillman is quite confident in his strategy, ``If you were in a
helicopter over the city,'' he said, ``you'd see the Howard-Eutaw
Street corridor is the next place for development.'' The corridor
is eight blocks northwest of the Inner Harbor and adjacent to the
University of Maryland's Baltimore campus. It plays an important
role in the conversion program, acting as a kind of spine along
which other projects are planned.
</P>
<P>
   Five blocks up from Hillman's project, near the corner of Howard
and Franklin streets, is the Congress Hotel, the next major project
to go forward, probably by the fall, according to David Beecher,
senior project manager for Streuver Brothers Eccles and Rouse, the
developer.
</P>
<P>
   The ornate Second Empire building, developed by James Kernan, a
theater impresario after whom the $4.4-million project will be
named, will become an upscale apartment complex with retail space
on the ground floor. Along with the now demolished Maryland Theater
and the Auditorium, the Congress was originally part of an
entertainment and hotel complex built by Kernan called the Triple
Million Dollar Enterprise, which showcased some of the country's
top performers. A basement space with a 50-foot-long marble bar
upon which Ginger Rogers and Fred Astaire danced will be rented as
a bar and restaurant.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   The plan to create downtown apartments in obsolete buildings
originated in late 1997, when the Downtown Partnership _ a business
improvement organization that works with the city to make its
downtown attractive to commercial enterprises _ looked for new ways
to fill vacant buildings. A task force was set up to study the
feasibility of an office-conversion program.
</P>
<P>
   A market study found that all existing downtown residential
units were fully rented with waiting lists. While a strong demand
existed, there were still economic obstacles as well as a lack of
commitment on the part of the city.
</P>
<P>
   As a result of the task force's recommendations, financial
incentives were introduced. For the 1998-99 fiscal year, the
Maryland General Assembly passed legislation to add $3 million to
the state's Department of Housing and Community Development budget,
specifically for below-market-interest-rate short-term financing
for the conversion of commercial buildings to rental housing in
downtown Baltimore. About $2 million is available for projects in
fiscal year 1999-2000.
</P>
<P>
   Another key financial incentive passed was the Pilot (payment in
lieu of taxes) Program, under which a building's property taxes
would either be deferred or abated for a certain time period.
</P>
<P>
   Almost all the proposed buildings qualify as historic structures
and can raise additional equity through the federal and state
historic tax credit programs. This is the key component of the
Hecht Co. financing, said Hillman, who is opposed to the gap
financing for the conversions. ``The historic tax credit program
and the property tax abatements are OK, but a project must be able
to stand on its own instead of relying on public financing,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   The task force also recommended that the city give more support
to the conversion program, which led to the creation of the
Downtown Housing Council.
</P>
<P>
   ``By setting up a Downtown Housing Council that facilitates the
entire effort and is headed by the housing commissioner, Daniel P.
Henson III, the city brings all the players to the table, making it
easier for developers to do projects in an expedient manner,'' said
Laurie Schwartz, president of the Downtown Partnership. In
addition, Ms. Durkin was hired as full-time coordinator to help
developers and identify possible future projects. She has
pinpointed 75 potential buildings for conversion.
</P>
<P>
   Developers, however, cite the recent Westside Plan as the real
catalyst for the conversion program. The city is planning a
$350-million redevelopment of an area that includes many of the
proposed conversions in the Howard-Eutaw Street corridor. ``We
wouldn't be doing this unless the city was committed to the west
side,'' said Beecher, the Congress Hotel project manager.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Durkin, who foresees the completion of 1,000 apartments over
the next two years, has high hopes for the program. ``The early
conversions will first attract downtown employees, students and
young professionals and once they go in, others will follow, along
with retail,'' she said. ``In two years, you're going to see a lot
of changes around here.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
