<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-17 16:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3956 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-OLY-RECORDS-OPEN18-CO     07-17 0789
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-RECORDS-OPEN18-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Atlanta Olympic Games records to be opened
 &HT;    By Melissa Turner
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Atlanta Olympic officials plan to unlock the doors Monday on a
vast and historic record of the city's Olympic experience and
invite everyone in to take a look.
</P>
<P>
   In making available for the first time some 5,700 boxes of
documents and artifacts, the officials are loosening their
long-held grip on privacy and opening the 1996 Centennial Games to
microscopic scrutiny.
</P>
<P>
   Inside the treasure trove, the public, researchers and
journalists likely will find much of the behind-the-scenes story on
the staging and organization of Atlanta's biggest organized event
ever.
</P>
<P>
   It may be the most complete history of an Olympic Games ever
compiled.
</P>
<P>
   Historians are eager to pull off the lids on everything from
fence-mending correspondence between the Atlanta organizers and
despondent Athens bidders, to memos documenting the animosity
between Billy Payne and IOC President Juan Antonio Samaranch, and
the real story behind Coca-Cola's involvement in Atlanta's bid
effort.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need this kind of information for a whole lot of
purposes,'' said Penn State professor John Lucas, a historian who
has written four books on the Olympics.
</P>
<P>
   ``Journalists and historians are far apart in a number of
things, but they are both investigators seeking the truth.''
</P>
<P>
   The unseen material might even conclude sponsorship contracts
and television rights negotiations, which have long been
top-secret.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to weigh the affect of it vs. the good that would
come from disclosure,'' said a seemingly unconcerned International
Olympic Committee vice president Dick Pound, whose organization has
thrown back the curtain on its own inner workings. ``If it is just
disclosure for prurient interest, there is no good that comes of
that.''
</P>
<P>
   Initially, historians and journalists will find a slightly
censored truth. The Olympic bid team, headed by attorney Payne and
former Mayor Andrew Young, is holding back eight legal-size boxes
that they claim contain personal and sensitive papers. Copies of
those documents and others have been handed over to federal
investigators looking for any signs of corruption in the Atlanta
bid.
</P>
<P>
   Payne's decision to release the lion's share of records is an
attempt to calm the controversy over his group's campaign for the
Games. The Salt Lake City bribery scandal _ in which that city's
ambitious bid team showered IOC members with more than $1 million
in gifts and favors _ turned the spotlight on Olympic candidate
cities everywhere.
</P>
<P>
   Investigations into the Olympic city selection process were
conducted by four bodies _ the IOC, the U.S. Olympic Committee,
Congress and the Justice Department. The results haven't been
pretty. The IOC has been painted as a club of corrupt and greedy
prima donnas, the bid cities as pawns willing to grease the
members' outstretched palms for a chance at the golden ring.
</P>
<P>
   Payne and his team of lawyers have denied wrongdoing and
expressed indignation toward any questions about the gifts and
entertainment they bestowed upon visiting IOC members.
</P>
<P>
   ``We did not bribe anyone,'' Payne said in February as he
prepared a response to an IOC inquiry. ``We were not extorted by
IOC members. We did not make cash payments. We did not give
outrageous gifts.''
</P>
<P>
   And in a formal report in March, Payne argued that his bid was
above reproach: Any excessive gifts were tokens of friendship, not
bribes; excessive visits to the city were extensions of Southern
hospitality, not an attempt to win favors.
</P>
<P>
   ``Atlanta won the games `fair and square' in an honorable
manner,'' Payne wrote in a letter to Samaranch.
</P>
<P>
   Even as the IOC was ousting 10 members accused of taking bribes
from Salt Lake bidders, Payne promised that the exiled members were
on good behavior in Atlanta. ``They were nice people,'' Payne said.
``They were our friends.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, Payne for months refused to allow the media access to the
bid team records that could verify his claims. Everything of
historical significance would be cataloged and archived at the
Atlanta History Center and released in due time. The remainder _
donor lists, personal correspondence and memos that might prove
embarassing to the authors _ would be boxed up and kept from public
view forever, he hoped.
</P>
<P>
   The cloak of secrecy was warranted, Payne's lawyers contend. The
non-profit Georgia Amateur Athletics Foundation (GAAF), formed to
seek the bid, was a group of private, civic-minded volunteers
acting without authority from the city and state in their effort to
win the Games.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
