<SLUG> BC-GLF-BRITISH-OPEN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A FRENCH TWIST FOR FINAL AT CARNOUSTIE 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By CLIFTON BROWN    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   CARNOUSTIE, Scotland _ It was a spectacular round of golf,
almost stunning considering the difficulty of the golf course, the
magnitude of the tournament, and the player who did it. Jean Van de
Velde, a 33-year-old Frenchman who has not won on the European Tour
since 1993, played the round of his life at Carnoustie Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Nothing rattled Van de Velde, not the pressure of leading a
major, not the marquee names on the leader board like Tiger Woods,
Greg Norman and Justin Leonard, and not the intimidating aura of
one of the world's most difficult golf courses. When he hit into
trouble, Van de Velde escaped with the smoothness of a magician.
Whenever someone threatened his lead, Van de Velde counterpunched
with a timely shot. And when the day was over, Van de Velde was on
the brink of glory.
</P>
<P>
   Shooting a one-under-par 70, and taking a five-stroke lead into
the final round, Van de Velde stood at even par for the tournament
(213), five strokes ahead of Leonard, who shot a 71 Saturday, and
Craig Parry, who shot a 67, the best round of the tournament.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Woods made a costly double-bogey at No. 17 and was
seven strokes behind, tied with Andrew Coltart and David Frost.
Norman, who bogeyed the final two holes, was eight strokes behind
after Saturday's 75, tied with Angel Cabrera, who started the day
in second place but struggled to a 77. But the man of the moment
was Van de Velde, who has the largest third-round lead at any major
since Woods led the 1997 Masters by nine strokes after three
rounds.
</P>
<P>
   Can Van de Velde avoid a Sunday collapse? And what thoughts
would be going through his mind Saturday night?
</P>
<P>
   ``I have about 24 hours to think, which is too many,'' admitted
Van de Velde, who held the biggest third-round lead at the British
Open since 1996, when Tom Lehman went on to win after leading by
six strokes. ``I know many golfers greater than me have been in
this position and lost. I am going to enjoy it, play the golf
course, and see what happens.''
</P>
<P>
   And when it was pointed out that Van de Velde had not won since
1993, he smiled and said, ``Maybe it's time I won one.''
</P>
<P>
   Van de Velde played with remarkable poise, making extraordinary
recovering shots and long-distance putts. He ended the round in
glorious fashion, making a 45-foot putt for birdie at No. 18 that
brought a deafening roar from the grandstand, as he took off his
hat and acknowledged the ovation.
</P>
<P>
   That was the last sparkling moment of a day filled with them.
Van de Velde also made a 70-foot birdie putt at No. 14, and a
25-foot birdie putt at No. 7. As athletes say, Van de Velde was in
the zone, and almost everything he did turned out right.
</P>
<P>
   Carnoustie rarely allows any golfer to miss fairways
consistently yet shoot under par. But in the calmest weather
conditions of the tournament, Van de Velde found a way, hitting
aggressively and sometimes wildly off the tee, yet relying on his
short game to get up and down. Van de Velde made unlikely par saves
at No. 10 and No. 11 that kept his momentum going. After he hit his
drive on No. 10 into a bunker, Van de Velde blasted out short of
the green, hit a wedge shot to 18 feet, then made another key put.
</P>
<P>
   And his save at No. 11 was more remarkable. After hitting a
terrible drive far right into the rough, Van de Velde feared he had
hit out of bounds, and actually teed up another ball for another
tee shot. But a spotter waved to Van de Velde from the fairway that
his ball was playable, so Van de Velde walked to his ball, where a
television tower blocked his path back the fairway. Van de Velde
asked an official for relief, and he was allowed to move his ball
several feet to the right.
</P>
<P>
   ``I asked, `What happens if I kill a cameraman?''' said Van de
Velde, showing the sense of humor that has helped him calm his
nerves. Then after hitting back into the fairway, Van de Velde hit
his approach shot to around 14 feet, then made still another putt.
</P>
<P>
   And while Van de Velde consistently made great things happen,
his pursuers could not. Woods shot a three-over par 74, and two
holes badly hurt him. At the par-5 No. 14, Woods reached the green
in two shots and had a 35-foot putt for eagle. At that point, Woods
was only three strokes behind. But he left the eagle attempt 6 feet
short, then missed the 6-foot birdie attempt as well, settling for
par. Then at the par-4 No. 17, Woods drove into the right rough,
hacked out short of the fairway and hit his approach shot over the
green. He left his next chip short of the green, then finally
chipped onto the green and made a putt for a double-bogey six.
</P>
<P>
   Woods believed he could still win, but he also knew that seven
strokes was a huge deficit, even at Carnoustie.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's going to be awfully tough to catch him,'' Woods said of
Van de Velde. ``Myself and others who are in the hunt need to play
a great round. If I can post a good number early, you never know
what could happen.''
</P>
<P>
   Parry and Leonard had the same thoughts. And Leonard, the 1997
British Open champion, is definitely someone to watch. Leonard has
won three tournaments after trailing by five strokes entering the
final round _ the 1997 British Open, the 1997 Kemper Open and the
Players Championship last year. Instead of complaining about
Carnoustie's conditions, Leonard has concentrated on overcoming
them.
</P>
<P>
   ``Go out there and deal with it,'' said Leonard, who planned to
take that same approach Sunday. ``The goal tomorrow is to go out
and give myself chances.''
</P>
<P>
   But Saturday belonged to Van de Velde. And on Sunday, he would
find out if the British Open championship would belong to him as
well.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the biggest tournament in the world,'' he said. ``What
can happen? I can win it. I can lose it. Either way, I'm having a
good time.''
</P>
</TEXT>
