<SLUG> BC-BBO-FEATURE18-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    By Thomas Stinson
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Petite Pedro Martinez takes his next step today in his 30-win
quest, with his first start of the second half, against Florida. A
remarkable year raises two questions: How did he get here and what
lies before him?
</P>
<P>
   From a Los Angeles operating room to a New York state jail cell,
the answers to those two items have been clarified. L.A. orthopedic
surgeon Frank Jobe confirmed last week that he advised the Los
Angeles Dodgers that Martinez was an injury waiting to happen,
which expedited his trade to Montreal and subsequent stardom.
</P>
<P>
   And from jail, where he is serving an eight-year sentence for
embezzlement, Denny McLain, the game's last 30-game winner, is
wondering if the five-man rotation provides the contemporary
pitcher any real opportunity to reach 30.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's so difficult to win 30 now because you don't pitch
enough,'' McLain said. ``I made 41 or 42 starts. A few of those
came on two days' rest.''
</P>
<P>
   No one said it was going to be easy.
</P>
<P>
   For years, Dodgers general manager Fred Claire quietly bore the
responsibility for dealing Martinez in 1994, for second baseman
Delino DeShields, in what became one of the stupidest deals the
Dodgers ever made. Manager Tommy Lasorda would trust him only as a
reliever, and, even though he made 65 appearances in his last
Dodger season, the club never could convince itself that Martinez's
slim build allowed for a starter's durability.
</P>
<P>
   But now Jobe, one of sports' pre-eminent surgeons, told the Los
Angeles Times that he was advising Claire all along that the little
Dominican was destined for ruin. Martinez separated his left,
non-throwing shoulder while swinging a bat in the on-deck circle in
Albuquerque in 1992, and after Jobe repaired it he became dubious.
</P>
<P>
   ``The circumstances kind of spoke for themselves,'' he said.
``His shoulder had come out once, and once an injury of that type
occurs, you can't say it won't reoccur. He had kind of a delicate
stature to start with, and there were already questions about his
stamina. It's a judgment call, but you had to kind of wonder,
`Golly, is this kid going to break down?'''
</P>
<P>
   Shipped to the Expos, he became a starter, made 117 starts in a
row, won the 1997 Cy Young and is producing one of the best seasons
of the latter half of the century in Boston.
</P>
<P>
   ``All those people who put all those labels on me must be out
there now banging their heads against the wall,'' Martinez said.
``You're talking about some of the biggest people in baseball, but
they obviously didn't know anything about the game. They were still
saying I was too small, too weak, certain to break down. I think
about it all the time. It's still my motivation.''
</P>
<P>
   McLain has no doubts about Martinez's ability, saying he ``has
as good of stuff as anybody who has played this game.'' But while
the starter of the 1990s works 35-36 games a year _ and Martinez
might start just 33 games _ anyone chasing a 30-win year now is at
a disadvantage. McLain started 41 games in 1968, winning 31 times.
He threw a career-high 336 innings that season.
</P>
<P>
   Martinez's career high is 241, in his final season in Montreal.
While he long ago answered the durability questions, the Red Sox
nevertheless are trying to protect him by moving him to the back of
the rotation, which is giving him an 11-day break around the
All-Star Game.
</P>
<P>
   McLain was having so much fun in 1968, no one ever stopped to
count the pitches. He became a celebrity and rubbed elbows with
Hollywood. He still recalls the day Ed Sullivan walked into the
Tigers clubhouse when they were in Anaheim.
</P>
<P>
   McLain said, ``We almost all fell off our chairs.''
</P>
<P>
   Ed Sullivan. Another thing Martinez doesn't have to contend
with.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
