<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-17 17:07 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3968 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KENNEDY-TOWN18-COX     07-17 0666
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KENNEDY-TOWN18-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    HYANNISPORT STUNNED BY NEWS OF MISSING PLANE
 &HT;    With KENNEDY-SEARCH.
 &HT;    By BOB DART
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   HYANNISPORT, Mass. _ On a sparkling summer Saturday, with
breezes beckoning on the bay and white beaches glistening in the
sunshine, shock and sorrow beset this Cape Cod village as tragedy
again struck its most famous family.
</P>
<P>
   Gathering outside the Kennedy family compound, neighbors and
tourists alike whispered, ``no, not again,'' as they exchanged
increasingly gloomy tidbits of news about the missing plane
carrying John F. Kennedy Jr., his wife, Carolyn, and her sister,
Lauren Bessette.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was in the post office picking up my mail when I heard what
happened,'' said Phyllis Kahn, who has a summer home near the
cluster of white clapboard houses where the Kennedy clan gathers in
times of joy and sorrow.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is along my usual walk and I was going home, but you get
transfixed,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Beyond the barricades, a tent could be seen where the wedding of
his cousin, Rory Kennedy, was to have been celebrated Saturday
evening. Family members instead planned to attend a Catholic mass.
</P>
<P>
   Neither grief nor gladness are strangers to this picturesque
neighborhood.
</P>
<P>
   ``You know Ethel Kennedy was pregnant with Rory when Robert
Kennedy (Rory's father) was killed,'' said Helene Schechter, who
was visiting the Kahns. ``And you know this weekend was the 30th
anniversary of Chappaquiddick,'' the incident in which a young
campaign worker drowned in a car driven by Sen. Edward M. Kennedy,
D-Mass.
</P>
<P>
   In the Kennedy compound, there are at least three houses. One,
called the Ambassador's House, was owned originally by Joseph
Kennedy Sr., the family patriarch, passed to his widow, Rose, and
is now owned by Edward Kennedy.
</P>
<P>
   Another, owned by the late Robert F. Kennedy, is now owned by
his widow. A third was owned by President John F. Kennedy and was
passed on to John Kennedy Jr. and his sister, Caroline.
</P>
<P>
   Throughout the town, the news of another seeming Kennedy tragedy
cast a pall on the pleasures of a summer weekend.
</P>
<P>
   At the Four Seas ice cream shop, where three generations of
Kennedy children have charged double cones, the tragedy was the
center of conversation among customers in shorts, T-shirts and
bathing suits.
</P>
<P>
   ``People come in, sit down, and immediately ask if we know
anything,'' said employee Pat McEvoy.
</P>
<P>
   At the Four Seas, John Jr. inherited his mother's fondness for
the homemade peach ice cream. Jacqueline Kennedy would order the
flavor delivered to the compound when her husband was president and
served it at a prenuptial dinner for her daughter Caroline.
</P>
<P>
   Family members have come into the store since before John
Kennedy was president and always charge their purchases, because
they rarely carry cash, said manager Jahni(cq) Clarke.
</P>
<P>
   At the John F. Kennedy Memorial, a grassy park where a stone
wall bearing a bronze relief of the late president overlooks the
sparkling blue Hyannis harbor, visitors spoke quietly of a family
besieged by sorrow.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe it's just because they're in the news, and other large
families have many tragedies, too, but I just feel so sorry for
them,'' said Terri Wirtz, visiting with her husband, Joe, from
Epsom, N.H.
</P>
<P>
   ``We grew up during the Kennedy era,'' she said. ``I just wanted
to say a prayer for their family.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We hadn't planned to come, but it was like the car just took
us here,'' said Diane Seiter, who was at the memorial with her
husband, Tom, and their three children. ``We had to come out of
respect and for a quick prayer.''
</P>
<P>
   Visiting from Florence, Ky., the Seiters heard the report of the
missing plane on their car radio. ``It sent a chill up my spine,''
said Mrs. Seiter, 35. ``We've been giving our children a history of
the Kennedy family going back to Joe Sr. _ who they are and all
they've done.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
