</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    News and notes from the American League
 &HT;    By By Thomas Stinson
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AL EAST
</P>
<P>
   Nearly every Oriole trade bait
</P>
<P>
   The Baltimore Orioles will listen to inquiries about anyone,
except Cal Ripken and Mike Mussina, but with two motivations.
General manager Frank Wren, back on owner Peter Angelos' good side,
has persuaded the owner to dismantle the O's calcified roster.
</P>
<P>
   However, the team needs to dump some of the players just to get
rid of the contracts. Long-term deals granted to six players are
worth about $150 million through 2003, tying up the club's ability
to maneuver in the free-agent market. Those O's Wren will take
offers for are Scott Erickson, B.J. Surhoff, Brady Anderson, Harold
Baines, Mike Bordick, Juan Guzman, Arthur Rhodes and Jesse Orosco.
Albert Belle would be in there, too, but he has a no-trade clause,
as well as dubious appeal.
</P>
<P>
   ``One thing to remember,'' Wren said, ``is that we don't have to
trade anyone right now, even if we decide to begin building for our
future. That can be done after the season, also.''...
</P>
<P>
   Doctors tell designated hitter Jose Canseco he can return Sept.
1, but a second back operation in three years has driven the
slugger to the brink of retirement, even though Tampa Bay has an
option year at $3 million for next season. ``I compare it to a
high-speed performance car. One spark plug is loose, and the whole
thing can't function,'' Canseco said. ``I've had the worst luck. I
keep myself in tremendous condition, but I've been jinxed no matter
what I do.''
</P>
<P>
   AL CENTRAL
</P>
<P>
   Coomer, Fisk complete circle
</P>
<P>
   While growing up in Lockport, Ill., Ron Coomer was a schoolmate
of the Fisk boys, but it was their father, Carlton Fisk, then
catching his final seasons with the White Sox, who had a more
lasting effect. Coomer met the future Hall of Famer at his
graduation party, was tutored by Fisk on how to hit with a wooden
bat and so impressed the catcher that seven years later, after
Coomer was released by Oakland, Fisk got the White Sox to pick him
up.
</P>
<P>
   Coomer moved on twice before settling with Minnesota, but the
circle was closed Tuesday when Coomer came to the plate in his
first All-Star Game and Fisk, the honorary captain, was down in the
AL first base coaching box, yelling at him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wouldn't have had a job without Carlton,'' Coomer said.
``Now we're golfing buddies, and he's always trying to get into my
pocket.''...
</P>
<P>
   Kansas City's old guard is on the way out. The club will move
Kevin Appier this month, and Jeff Montgomery is in the Gulf Coast
League trying to rehab from tendinitis in his pelvis. He is three
saves away from 300, but Mongomery said, ``Right now, that's the
furthest thing from my mind. I'm assuming it will never
happen.''... Cleveland manager Mike Hargrove has reconsidered using
Jim Thome at third base until Travis Fryman gets back. Sub third
baseman Enrique Wilson recently hit .405 over 22 games, making
Hargrove's decision less urgent.
</P>
<P>
   AL WEST
</P>
<P>
   Brawl still hurting Mariners
</P>
<P>
   It will be weeks before the Seattle Mariners get over their
brawl in Los Angeles in the final game before the break. Outfielder
Brian Hunter is on the disabled list with a wrenched knee sustained
that day, and outfielder Charles Gipson dislocated his shoulder
when the pile he was in shifted.
</P>
<P>
   To fill out the roster, the club had to take Jay Buhner off the
disabled list before it would like to. Buhner has been out since
May 19 with a bad hamstring and he jeopardizes the rest of the
season if he pulls it again. But then again, Buhner might have to
sit for a while longer, because he is subject to suspension for
joining the brawl. Players on the disabled list are restricted from
entering the field during a game.
</P>
<P>
   Buhner waded in to rescue Gipson and wound up putting ex-Brave
Pedro Borbon in a headlock. ``That wasn't me out there,'' he said.
``That was (pro wrestler) Steve Austin coming off the
turnbuckle.''...
</P>
<P>
   Oakland continues to listen to offers for left-hander Kenny
Rogers, but given the close quarters in the division standings, the
A's can't trade their No. 1 starter while still in contention.
``Kenny ain't going nowhere unless we really stink,'' right fielder
Matt Stairs said.... Texas' Ivan Rodriguez, who caught all but 66
2/3 of the Rangers' 767 2/3 innings _ 91 percent _ in the first
half, continues to overwork himself. His career batting average
before the All-Star break is .317; after the break, it's .272.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
