 &HT;    News and notes from the National League
 &HT;    By Thomas Stinson
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   NL EAST
</P>
<P>
   Mets eye Marlins' Hernandez
</P>
<P>
   The New York Mets' shopping list includes Seattle's Jeff Fassero
and Oakland's Kenny Rogers as the club tries to shore up its
rotation. But the first name is Livan Hernandez, for whom Florida
is entertaining offers. He comes cheap ($1.575 million this year,
ineligible for arbitration for another season), he's pitched in big
games before and foremost, he works into the late innings, which
the Mets overtaxed bullpen loves.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not like we need rest in the bullpen,'' said reliever
Turk Wendell, ``but if the starters went a little deeper, it would
give the bullpen some breathing room.''
</P>
<P>
   Injuries prompted the Mets to use eight starters in the first
half. In their first 89 games, those starters lasted five or fewer
innings 30 times.... Mike Schmidt, the former Phillies third
baseman named to game's greatest 100 players list, fears what havoc
the game's offensive boom will make of the game's history book.
``When I'm 70, 80 years old, I'm going to be ashamed to admit I'm
in that pitiful, little 500-home run club when there are 30 guys in
the 800-home run club,'' Schmidt said.... Asked if he was
disappointed he didn't get to pitch in the All-Star Game, Phillie
Paul Byrd shook his head and said, ``I would have been the batboy
if they asked me to be.''
</P>
<P>
   NLCENTRAL
</P>
<P>
   Mum to mom on Gooden tiff
</P>
<P>
   Don't tell Pokey Reese's mother what happenend the other night
when Cincinnati was playing Cleveland. Doc Gooden struck out Reese
and the two glared each other down before Reese went to the dugout
and all the Reds second baseman could hope was his mom wasn't
watching back in Columbia, S.C.
</P>
<P>
   ``Big deal, he struck me out.... yeah,'' Reese said. ``But I
ain't gonna fight with a Hall of Famer. Besides, my mom might kill
me. Gooden is her favorite player. She used to live in Flushing and
had season tickets at Shea in 1986. When Cleveland was at our place
this year, I got him to sign a ball for her.''
</P>
<P>
   Gooden later called the Reds clubhouse to apologize to Reese and
said the incident was a heat-of-battle deal. Reese later asked if
the game had been televised anywhere near South Carolina and
informed it wasn't, said, ``Good, I'm not going to tell her about
this.''...
</P>
<P>
   Milwaukee's Jeromy Burnitz may have opened some eyes during the
All-Star Game but not for Chicago manager Jim Riggleman, who
bubbled over the guy. ``People just don't know how good he is,''
said Riggleman. ``He's a good outfielder, he plays hard, he's
aggressive. And it looks like he enjoys the game.''... To reach 90
wins, Riggleman's Cubs need a 49-28 (.630) record in the second
half.... Kent Bottenfield is averaging just over six innings a
start and has a shot at being the first St. Louis pitcher to win 20
games with less than 200 innings.
</P>
<P>
   NLWEST
</P>
<P>
   Giants slow rousing from break
</P>
<P>
   For the 10th time since leaving the Polo Grounds in 1957, the
San Francisco Giants opened the second half in first place. History
says the struggle has just begun. In just four of those 10 seasons
did the Giants finish in first, and lately, late July has almost
killed the season.
</P>
<P>
   In 1997, the Giants lost seven of their first 10 post-break
games but managed to win the division by two games. Last year, a
2-11 start presaged the loss of the one-game playoff with Chicago.
How the next two weeks go should dictate how aggressively general
manager Brian Sabean adjusts his roster. A healthy Barry Bonds
might define the difference of the two halves.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we start the second half like we have in the past, God
forbid, we might have more necessity,'' Sabean said. ``We're all
hoping we don't have to make any moves, and if we do it'd be a
tweak here and there.''...
</P>
<P>
   Painful note: within Arizona's Randy Johnson's winless streak,
he has struck out 60 batters in 41 innings, posted an 0.87 ERA and
not won.... Brian Bohanon's crunchy left elbow has forced
Colorado's Jim Leyland to revert to a five-man rotation. Bohanon's
workload is limited by bone chips
</P>
<P>
   in the elbow, good news for rookie Roberto Ramirez, who joins
the rotation full time. He is in for hazardous duty. Over the first
half, Rockies starters were 27-35 with a 6.42 ERA.
</P>
