 &HT;    Odds and ends from Major League Baseball
 &HT;    By Thomas Stinson
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   U-S-A, U-S-A
</P>
<P>
   Not everywhere has women's sport made inroads. When the score of
the U.S.-China World Cup championship game was posted on the
scoreboard at 3Com Park last Sunday, San Francisco's Jeff Kent
stepped out of the batter's box while the crowd cheered and began
the obligatory ``U-S-A'' chant. Out on the mound, St. Louis's Ricky
Bottalico got chafed. ``Why didn't they wait until the end of the
inning?'' Bottalico asked. ``We've got a baseball game going on.
That's fine and dandy to put it on the board, but get in the box
and play baseball.''
</P>
<P>
   ``To hell with Bottalico. It's my at-bat,'' Kent replied. ``I
was pondering the victory of girls soccer. He should be thinking
the same thing. He must not be very USA-proud.''
</P>
<P>
   MANNY AND HACK
</P>
<P>
   Manny Ramirez's 96 RBIs at the break is not the highest
first-half total, but it's close. He has to drive in 98 more runs
in his final 75 game to catch Hack Wilson, who drove in 191 RBIs in
1930. The biggest RBI totals at the All-Star break.
</P>
<P>
   CHILL OUT
</P>
<P>
   Tim Flannery, third-base coach for San Diego who was invited by
Bruce Bochy to Boston to help coach the National League All-Stars,
had thrown batting practice Monday and was ready to call it a
night.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm in there after batting practice, icing down, eating about
two dozen clams and sippin' on a Guinness,'' Flannery said. ``Mark
McGwire comes up to me before the Home Run Derby and says he
doesn't have a guy to pitch to him. I don't know what happened to
the guy who was supposed to throw, but I start thinking: `Irish guy
hitting, Irish guy throwing, Irish beer, Irish city. Gotta be.
Gotta do it.'''
</P>
<P>
   Did it maybe too well. After McGwire's cannonade in the first
round _ 16 swings, 13 home runs _ the two Irishmen could not keep
up the pace. McGwire was eliminated by Milwaukee's Jeromy Burnitz
in the second round. But for all the marveling going on at Fenway
Park that night, Flannery led both leagues. ``I stopped after six
and looked out into center field,'' Flannery said. ``My son (Danny)
was out there shagging balls. I felt so proud, and it made me think
of my father.''
</P>
<P>
   Ragon Flannery, his father, had died five days earlier after a
long fight with Alzheimer's disease.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
