</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KENNEDY-TRAGEDY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TRAGEDY HAS STALKED THE KENNEDYS 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also: KENNEDY-MISSING-PLANE, KENNEDY-PILOT, KENNEDY-SEARCH,
KENNEDY-NY-SCENE, KENNEDY-MASS-SCENE) 
(lh) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Tragedy has struck the Kennedy family many times since the
1940s.
</P>
<P>
   _ Rosemary, the eldest daughter of Joseph P. Kennedy and Rose
Fitzgerald Kennedy, was mentally retarded and underwent a failed
lobotomy in 1941. After the operation, she no longer recognized her
father. She lived privately at a Catholic institution in Wisconsin.
</P>
<P>
   _ Joseph P. Kennedy, Jr., the eldest child of Joe and Rose
Kennedy, a Navy pilot stationed in Great Britain in 1944, died on a
dangerous secret mission, flying a plane full of explosives in an
attempt to destroy a Nazi missile site. The plane exploded in
midair before its crew could jump to safety.
</P>
<P>
   _ In 1948, Kathleen Kennedy, the fourth Kennedy child, was
flying from Paris to Cannes with Lord Peter Fitzwilliam, whom she
intended to marry, when their De Havilland crashed in severe
weather. Both were killed.
</P>
<P>
   _ Joseph P. Kennedy, the family patriarch, suffered a
debilitating stroke in 1961, just a few months after his son, John
F. Kennedy, was inaugurated as president. He lived until 1969 but
never recovered.
</P>
<P>
   _ John F. Kennedy, the second Kennedy child and the 35th
president of the United States, was assassinated by Lee Harvey
Oswald on Nov. 22, 1963.
</P>
<P>
   _ Edward M. Kennedy, the youngest Kennedy son, broke his back in
a plane accident in 1964, seven months after his brother was
killed. He recovered.
</P>
<P>
   _ On June 6, 1968, Robert F. Kennedy, the third Kennedy son, who
was running for president, was shot by Sirhan Sirhan, just after
claiming victory in the California primary. He died 20 hours later.
</P>
<P>
   _ On the night of July 18-19, 1969, Edward M. Kennedy flew to
Martha's Vineyard to sail in a regatta and to attend a party with
several women who had been Robert's campaign aides. He left with
one of them, Mary Jo Kopechne. He drove off a bridge on
Chappaquiddick Island and she drowned. The episode has shadowed his
political career.
</P>
<P>
   _ Edward Kennedy Jr., the son of Edward and Joan Kennedy, had
his leg amputated for cancer on Nov. 18, 1973. He recovered and is
now a lawyer in New Haven, Conn.
</P>
<P>
   _ David Kennedy, the troubled 28-year-old son of Robert and
Ethel Kennedy, died of a drug overdose in Palm Beach, Fla., on
April 25, 1984. He had been watching his father on television in
1968 when Robert Kennedy was shot.
</P>
<P>
   _ Michael Kennedy, another of Robert and Ethel's children, was
killed on Dec. 31, 1997, in a bizarre skiing accident. The
39-year-old skied into a tree in Aspen, Colo., while playing a game
of ski football. His youngest sister, Rory, who had planned to
marry Saturday, unsuccessfully gave him mouth-to-mouth
resuscitation.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-17-99 1726EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990717.0170 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-17 17:27 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3980 &Cx1f; taf-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EDIT-INDIA-PAKISTAN-N     07-17 0846
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-INDIA-PAKISTAN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL OBSERVER: A STORY OF `BLOWBACK' IN PARADISE 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By STEVEN R. WEISMAN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Under pressure from the United States and some of its own close
allies, Pakistan has apparently brought about the withdrawal of the
insurgents who infiltrated into India last spring to support the
uprising in the disputed region of Kashmir.
</P>
<P>
   What no doubt must have initially seemed like a good idea to
Pakistan's military turned into an embarrassing blunder. Last year,
India looked like the neighborhood bully when it tested a nuclear
weapon. Now it is Pakistan that is seen as the aggressor.
</P>
<P>
   The Pakistani prime minister, Nawaz Sharif, has relearned an old
lesson in South Asia: encouraging insurgencies in a neighboring
country can backfire. By intervening in India, Pakistan was widely
condemned. By retreating, Pakistan has invited internal instability
as religious fundamentalists, army dissidents and others mobilize
against Sharif's regime.
</P>
<P>
   It is an old story. Back in the 1970s, Pakistan first began
encouraging Islamic fundamentalist guerrillas in Afghanistan in
retaliation for Afghan support for insurgents in the Pakistani
province of Baluchistan.
</P>
<P>
   After the Russian invasion of Afghanistan in 1980, the CIA and
Saudi Arabia joined with Pakistan to support the rebels, eventually
pushing the Russians out. The Afghan war helped bring down the
Soviet Union. It also led Osama bin Laden, who fought with the
Afghan rebels, and his allies to use Afghanistan as a base from
which to wage terrorism around the world. Some of these rebels are
said to be operating in Kashmir, India's only Muslim-dominated
state.
</P>
<P>
   Another case of ``blowback'' from an insurgency occurred after
Prime Minister Indira Gandhi of India secretly aided Tamil rebels
in the island nation of Sri Lanka, off India's southern coast. In
the 1980s, when her son, Prime Minister Rajiv Gandhi, tried to
suppress the rebels, they turned on him. He was murdered by a Tamil
explosive in 1991.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, Kashmir is in a class by itself because of its
emotional links to India and Pakistan. As India's founding prime
minister, Jawaharlal Nehru, who was descended from Kashmiri
Brahmins, once declared:
</P>
<P>
   ``Like some supremely beautiful woman, whose beauty is almost
impersonal and above human desire, such was Kashmir in all its
feminine beauty of river and valley and lake and graceful trees.
And then another aspect of this magic beauty would come to view, a
masculine one, of hard mountains and precipices, and snow-capped
peaks and glaciers, and cruel and fierce torrents rushing down to
the valleys below.''
</P>
<P>
   Nehru's desire to keep Kashmir went beyond ancestral, aesthetic
or strategic considerations. It was rooted in his vision of India
as a pluralistic nation, a vision that remains at India's core
today. Among those opposing an independent Muslim nation of
Kashmir, for example, are many of India's 140 million Muslims, who
also fear a Hindu backlash if the rebellion succeeds.
</P>
<P>
   But for Pakistanis, Kashmir also represents a powerful idea of
self-determination. To them, Kashmiris have suffered a bitter life
of poverty and subjugation since the British left the region in
1947. Indeed, in the early 1950s, a U.N. diplomat involved in
mediating the dispute was struck, as many are today, by the
contrast between a sublime landscape and lofty ideas and that
misery.
</P>
<P>
   ``Only those who have visited Kashmir can see this cruel
contrast between the nostalgic beauty and power of its scenery and
the frightened dark eyes of its countless poor,'' wrote Josef
Korbel, in his book ``Danger of Kashmir.'' Korbel was the father of
Secretary of State Madeleine Albright, the latest outsider to get
involved in the conflict.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever the merits of self-determination, one reason for the
recent global pressure on Sharif to force the withdrawal of
insurgents from Kashmir is that too many countries do not like the
idea of other countries, even their friends, making mischief on
their neighbors' soil.
</P>
<P>
   Pakistan was responding not simply to American pressure, for
example, but to pressure from two close allies, China and Saudi
Arabia. After meeting with President Clinton earlier this month,
Sharif flew to London with the Saudi ambassador to Washington,
Prince Bandar bin Sultan, on a Saudi plane. The Saudis feel too
vulnerable to internal unrest to encourage rebellions in nearby
countries.
</P>
<P>
   As for the Chinese, who rebuffed Sharif after the intervention
in Kashmir this spring, they know that if they encourage an
insurgency in India, India could encourage its many Tibetan
refugees to make trouble for them.
</P>
<P>
   The withdrawal of the insurgents is likely to serve only as one
more chapter in the Kashmir struggle. Decades ago, Josef Korbel saw
Kashmir as a Cold War arena in danger of becoming a communist
outpost. Today the fear is that without some resolution of the
conflicting ideas, Kashmir could engulf a region in more war and
deprivation, which no amount of beauty could redeem.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-17-99 1727EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
