<SLUG> BC-GLF-LPGA-IMAGE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LPGA SEEKS SOME OF THE GLAMOUR OF WOMEN'S SOCCER 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk ) 
By STEVE POPPER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW ROCHELLE, N.Y. _ Ty Votaw stepped up to the first tee at
Wykagyl Country Club on Wednesday afternoon and eyed the huge crowd
surrounding the tee box, feeling the pressure to strike a solid
drive before the fans that had gathered, a larger group by
multiples than any other gallery that day.
</P>
<P>
   The crowd, interspersed with young girls, was not there to see
Votaw play; for that matter, most of the fans in it were not there
to see any of the professional golfers. Votaw, the Ladies
Professional Golf Association commissioner, was seeing close up the
mesmerizing effect of the U.S. Women's soccer team, as he joined
Mia Hamm and Julie Foudy in his foursome at Wednesday's Pro-Am at
the Japan Airlines Big Apple Classic.
</P>
<P>
   While the LPGA will celebrate its 50th anniversary next year,
the soccer team was involved in a whirlwind week that dwarfed the
attention that the venerable golf circuit has drawn. All the hard
work that Votaw and the LPGA players put in to try to increase the
visibility of the tour seemed lost as the soccer players drew far
more interest than the golfers, with even the golfers waiting
patiently for autographs of Hamm, Foudy and Brandi Chastain.
</P>
<P>
   But Votaw is confident that what was good for women's soccer
last Saturday will be good for all women's sports. Votaw, in his
first year as commissioner after 10 years with the organization,
said he believes that the good fortune that women have enjoyed in
recent years in soccer, basketball and tennis will help the LPGA,
just as the LPGA carved inroads for the other sports.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have huge gratification and happiness for them,'' Votaw said
of the soccer team's success. ``One of the great things about
women's sports is the sisterhood that goes on. The fact that a
women's sport is on the cover of Time, People and Newsweek in one
week, it's wonderful. One of the best things that happened to the
LPGA was when the University of Connecticut with Rebecca Lobo went
undefeated and it showed broadcasters that women's sports telecasts
could be successful.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe a rising tide lifts all ships. Do I have a jealousy
of the soccer team? No. Envy? Perhaps. Would I love that exposure?
Absolutely.''
</P>
<P>
   Exposure has been part of the battle that the LPGA fights, as it
has to buy airtime to broadcast its tournaments on the networks,
and lacks a marquee player like Mia Hamm. The soccer team was
planted in the public consciousness by advertising campaigns by
Nike, something the LPGA has yet to have.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's one code we need to crack,'' Votaw said. ``You look at
Juli Inkster and her sponsors, Snackwells, Subaru and Izod _ all
took out full-page ads congratulating her. But there are things
that would fit in televised ads. That's the next step. We have to
ride the wings of other people's spending. David Stern of the NBA
is the most brilliant commissioner in sports, but he benefited from
Nike using Michael Jordan.''
</P>
<P>
   The LPGA, with its players taking turns at the top, has had no
clear-cut star to market. Inkster has had a spectacular season
after a long period during which she raised two children, but that
story does not draw young girls to the sport as the soccer team's
success has. Last year's rookie of the year, Se Ri- pak, has become
a huge star in Korea, but has not blossomed here, struggling with
her game and success early this season before recovering in the
last month.
</P>
<P>
   Karrie Webb, Annika Sorenstam and Meg Mallon, some of the other
top players on the tour, have yet to be lifted onto the magic
carpet of television ads. The LPGA awaits the advertising bonanza,
while still earning its way into the hearts and minds of television
executives.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think when it comes to the networks, they take the path of
least resistance and the path of least resistance is for us to buy
time,'' Votaw said. ``When I came to the LPGA, all events were time
buys, and some still are today. However, now some are shared risks,
like with ESPN. And with the Golf Channel, they pay us and pay the
production costs. That is progress.''
</P>
</TEXT>
