<HEADER>
A3983 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TEN-A&AMP;P-CAPRIATI-NYT &LR;      07-17 0415
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEN-A&AMP;P-CAPRIATI-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
(ATTN: N.J.)  
 WHO'S THAT IN THE FINAL? IT'S CAPRIATI 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By FRANK LITSKY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MAHWAH, N.J. _ In 1990, when she was 14, Jennifer Capriati
became the sensation of tennis. That year, she became the youngest
player to be ranked in the world's top 10, the youngest to be
seeded in a Grand Slam tournament (12th at Wimbledon), the youngest
to win a match at Wimbledon (she got to the fourth round). At 16,
she became the youngest player to reach $1 million in career
earnings. She counted Martina Navratilova, Monica Seles and
Gabriela Sabatini in her victory column.
</P>
<P>
   Then, in a sport in which teen-aged prodigies sometimes flame up
and flame out, she flamed out. She was picked up on charges of
substance abuse and shoplifting. She dropped off the tour for more
than two years.
</P>
<P>
   In 1996, she returned and is just getting back into form. On
Saturday, she took another small step forward by beating Erika
deLone, 7-5, 6-2, in the semifinals of the A&AMP;P Tennis Classic.
</P>
<P>
   Capriati has always been a crowd favorite in this exhibition
tournament, which she won in 1991 and 1993. Her victory put her in
Sunday afternoon's final against the winner of the semifinal
between Amanda Coetzer and Chanda Rubin.
</P>
<P>
   During the sunny, muggy afternoon Saturday, the court
temperature at the Crossroads Corporate Center reached 105 degrees.
The sellout crowd of 7,100 sat through the heat and watched
Capriati, now 23, win in 1 hour 25 minutes. She was the clear
favorite over deLone, who became a semifinalist by winning the
Challengers tournament for lower-ranked players earlier in the
week. Capriati is ranked 43rd, deLone 128th.
</P>
<P>
   In the first set, Capriati fell behind by 4-2 and made too many
unforced errors. As she said later, ``Maybe I just underestimated
her.''
</P>
<P>
   But leading at 6-5, Capriati served out the game and set, helped
by three big first serves. The second set was routine.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought I played well the whole match,'' Capriati said. ``I
want to get back to where I was. Mainly, I want to get better, hit
the ball harder, be more mature, that kind of stuff. I need
consistency.''
</P>
<P>
   Capriati is getting closer. She has won seven career tournament
titles, including one this year in Strasbourg, France. In this
year's French Open, she reached the round of 16 before losing to
Lindsay Davenport. In a six-month span in 1993, she reached the
Australian Open, French Open and Wimbledon quarterfinals.  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
