<DOCNO> NYT19990717.0180 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-17 17:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3990 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KENNEDY-TV18-COX     07-17 0495
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KENNEDY-TV18-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Television coverage goes into high gear
 &HT;    By Robbyn Footlick
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ It began, as most unfolding stories do, with few facts
and the opportunity for much speculation _ a potentially dangerous
combination when it comes to live television coverage.
</P>
<P>
   And as the day went on, the best coverage came from the
broadcasters who tempered their reports with repeated warnings that
nothing had been confirmed other than the fact that John F. Kennedy
Jr.'s plane _ with Kennedy, wife Carolyn Bessette Kennedy and
sister-in-law Lauren Bessette _ had disappeared en route to
Martha's Vineyard.
</P>
<P>
   With no footage to show for much of the time, the networks that
broke into regular programming and stayed with the story all day _
CNN, ABC, CBS and NBC _ resorted to graphics of the Piper Saratoga
that Kennedy had been piloting and reports from the Kennedy family
compound in Hyannisport and from the New Jersey airport where
Kennedy had taken off.
</P>
<P>
   Eventually, there were helicopters filming helicopters hovering
over the choppy waters and sunbathers on the beaches of Martha's
Vineyard.
</P>
<P>
   Some did it better than others. CNN, whose Martin Savidge went
on the air with the story at 8:29 a.m., went into its usual high
gear, bringing in Frank Sesno later to anchor from Washington and
Daryn Kagan from Atlanta. Sesno brought in correspondent Carl
Rochelle, who usually covers politics but is also a private pilot,
as an expert and CNN producers Peter Dykstra and Michael McManus,
who were vacationing in the Martha's Vineyard area, as reporters.
</P>
<P>
   On all the networks there were phone calls from Kennedy family
friends, contributors to Kennedy's magazine, George, and, of
course, file footage of the glamorous Kennedy couple entering and
exiting buildings and cars, shaking hands with President Clinton
and British Prime Minister Tony Blair.
</P>
<P>
   On CBS, anchor Dan Rather was doing what he does best _ or
worst, depending on preferences _ emoting. He spent more than a few
moments getting visibly misty-eyed as he recounted his meetings
with Kennedy, including a recent exchange in an Upper East Side
cafe in Manhattan.
</P>
<P>
   As Kennedy was leaving, Rather said, he walked by Rather's table
and greeted him with a ``smashing smile that could light up a room
or, for that matter, an area code.'' Then, said Rather, his voice
breaking and eyes tearing, ``he went away...That's what (Kennedy)
was like.''
</P>
<P>
   Surprisingly, Peter Jennings didn't join the ABC coverage until
early in the afternoon; Tom Brokaw began anchoring on NBC just
before.
</P>
<P>
   As coverage continued through the afternoon, the networks made
announcements of programming changes later Saturday night. CNN was
gathering guests for a planned ``Larry King Live'' at 9 p.m., and
Rather announced that ``48 Hours'' planned a special edition
Saturday at 8 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
