news. (Katz, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   APOLLO _ Thirty years since the first humans blasted off for the
moon, America is about to land on the moon again _ hard. On July
31, a 354-pound spacecraft named Lunar Prospector will slam into a
crater at the moon's south pole, destroying itself for the sake of
science. Alan Binder, the man who conceived Lunar Prospector and
the program's lead scientist, hopes the impact will kick up traces
of water from frozen pockets, proving the existence of ice that
Lunar Prospector's data has strongly indicated. Binder and others
believe the moon's poles contain up to six billion tons of ice,
plenty to support a moon base that Binder thinks should be our next
goal in space exploration. (Gaffney, Dayton Daily News). 38. MOVED
</P>
<P>
   WITH: With glance box on Lunar Prospector.
</P>
<P>
   APOLLO-LANDING _ In the infinite vastness of deep space, two
gleaming spaceships drifted apart 69 miles above the forbidding
landscape of the moon. Four days earlier, Armstrong, Aldrin and
Collins had blasted off to make the first human landing on the
moon. Now it was time. But problems cropped up as soon as the lunar
module Eagle emerged from behind the moon. Radio communication was
spotty, and an overloaded computer signaled alarms. As they neared
the surface, Armstrong steered the lunar module away from a crater,
hunting for a safe spot among a jumble of boulders. Seconds of fuel
remained when he set Eagle down so gently that neither man felt a
bump. ``The Eagle has landed,'' Armstrong said. (Gaffney, Dayton
Daily News). 38. MOVED
</P>
<P>
   OLY-RECORDS-OPEN _ ATLANTA _ In a dramatic gesture of openness,
Atlanta Olympic officials Monday will unlock the doors on a vast
and historic record of the city's Olympic experience and invite the
public in to take a look. In making available for the first time
some 5,700 boxes of documents and artifacts, Olympic officials are
releasing their longheld grip on privacy and opening the 1996
Centennial Games to microscopic scrutiny. Inside the public and
researchers likely will find the blow-by-blow, behind-the-scenes
story of the staging and organization of Atlanta's biggest event
this century, from the excruciating negotiations over the Olympic
stadium to the controversial decision to reroute the Olympic torch
around Cobb County. (Turner, Atlanta Journal-Constitution). 50.
MOVED
</P>
<P>
   EDs: Moving in (a) general news and (s) sports categories.
</P>
<P>
   HURRICANE-BIGONE _ NEW ORLEANS _They call it the Big One, the
dreaded hurricane that would hit New Orleans in just the right
place and with just the right force to turn this city into a giant
lake.The Big One hasn't hit in modern times, but last September, it
came so close, you could almost smell it. That close call, combined
with predictions of a busy 1999 hurricane season, has given many
residents the jitters. (Konigsmark, Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
25.
</P>
<P>
   HOSPITAL-WASTE _ DAYTON, Ohio _ During a routine inspection of a
truck hauling trash this month, workers at BFI's recycling transfer
station outside of Cincinnati discovered what looked like blood
coming from one of the bags. They found that some of the bags
contained hazardous medical wastes _ bloody gauze, surgical gowns
and other operating room equipment. When on July 8 biomedical
wastes were found a second time, it prompted a review by the Ohio
Environmental Protection Agency and the Middletown Health
Department of the Middletown hospital's waste handling, a crucial
procedure that a recent study says needs to be improved at many
hospitals around the country. (Dempsey/Mong, Dayton Daily News)
MOVED
</P>
<P>
   BORDER-PROTECTORS _ MATAMOROS, Tamaulipas _ In a narrow ravine
on the Mexican side of the Rio Grande, four would-be illegal
immigrants huddled together, waiting for opportunity. That's when
the flashlight beam from above found them. ``Come on out,
muchachos, don't be scared,'' said the man in the faded jeans with
the pistol on his hip. After the group reluctantly climbed up into
the warm night air, Erazmo Antonio Alaniz tried to ease their
fears. Alaniz, a 27-year-old Matamoros police officer, is part of
Mexico's own small but growing border patrol, a collection of
police and immigration officers assigned to protect the hundreds of
thousands of migrants who cross the border into the United States
every year. (Harmon, Austin American-Statesman) MOVED
</P>
<P>
   AIRPARK-OHIO _ SPRINGFIELD, Ohio _ A sign declaring ``Going
fast! Airpark Ohio space now available!'' greets visitors at the
entrance to the industrial park four miles south of Springfield.
But the only thing waiting inside the park in Ohio's first Joint
Economic Development District is a road leading to a cornfield and
two dead ends littered with broken beer bottles, fast food
containers and condom wrappers. (Staff, Springfield (Ohio)
News-Sun)
</P>
