<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-YANKS-BRAVES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PETTITTE, YANKEES AVOID SWEEP BY BRAVES, 11-4 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By BUSTER OLNEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Andy Pettitte's future with the Yankees is on the
line every time he takes the field now, and he needs to pitch well
to stay. Facing the Atlanta Braves Saturday, Pettitte pitched well
enough to beat Atlanta, 11-4, and prevent the Yankees from getting
swept.
</P>
<P>
   Chuck Knoblauch banged a two-run homer, scored three runs and
made an important defensive play as the Yankees (53-36) and Braves
and 55,785 fans at Yankee Stadium sweated and sweltered.
</P>
<P>
   There is deep sentiment in some quarters of the organization
that the Yankees should keep Pettitte; some fret that it is far too
soon to give up on a 27-year-old left-hander with such a tremendous
history of success. But according to a baseball executive who has
had recent contact with the Yankees, general manager Brian Cashman
is under orders to solicit and field offers for Pettitte over the
next two weeks leading to the July 31 trade deadline, and then
forward them to George Steinbrenner, the principal owner, for
consideration.
</P>
<P>
   On Friday, Steinbrenner would not comment directly about whether
Pettitte was going to be traded, but he acknowledged that the next
two weeks were important to Pettitte's future. ``He's got to show
us the old Pettitte,'' Steinbrenner said.
</P>
<P>
   Scouts from at least two teams _ the Houston Astros and the
Seattle Mariners _ attended Saturday's game to watch Pettitte, and
the reports they will file on the left-hander will probably be
mixed. For the first three innings, he pitched to both sides of the
plate aggressively and accurately, and the Braves counterattacked
by swinging early in the count, without success. Pettitte allowed a
single hit in the first three innings, needing a total of 16
pitches. Steinbrenner watched from his box, and if he had closed
his eyes, he might have confused the Pettitte of the first three
innings Saturday with the image of Pettitte beating Atlanta in Game
5 of the 1996 World Series.
</P>
<P>
   But Pettitte's final two and two-thirds innings of work Saturday
were completely different. The Braves worked the count a little
more, fouled off pitches and punched hits and sometimes drove the
ball. Only one Atlanta batter saw more than two pitches the first
time through the order, but in the second go-round, only one saw
fewer than three.
</P>
<P>
   It was stifling in the Stadium, and Pettitte had to work hard to
get through the fourth inning. With runners at first and second and
two out, Brian Jordan forced Pettitte to throw nine pitches before
the left-hander struck him out, and Pettitte threw 10 pitches to
the next batter, Andruw Jones, and then walked Jones to load the
bases. Pettitte struck out Javy Lopez to end the inning, pumping a
fist. Scoreless inning or not, however, the Braves exacted a heavy
toll: Pettitte threw 31 pitches in that inning.
</P>
<P>
   Bernie Williams smacked his 14th home run of the season in the
bottom of the fourth, increasing the Yankees' advantage to 3-0.
Then Brian Hunter and Eddie Perez, the No. 7 and No. 8 batters in
the Atlanta lineup, hit back-to-back singles to start the fifth.
</P>
<P>
   After Ozzie Guillen advanced both with a bunt, Pettitte threw a
high fastball to Gerald Williams, and Williams bashed it, high and
down the left-field line; it was only a question of whether the
ball would stay fair. Williams edged down the first-base line,
cajoling his drive with body language, begging it to stay fair, and
sure enough, it slammed off the foul pole for a three-run homer.
Tie game. As the runners circled the bases, a new ball was thrown
to Pettitte, and he snapped his glove at it in frustration.
</P>
<P>
   A nifty play by Chuck Knoblauch saved another run for Pettitte.
Bret Boone singled and broke for second on a pitch to Chipper
Jones, who smashed a line drive to left-center, an extra-base hit.
But Knoblauch faked Boone into sliding into second base, and Boone
was unable to recover quickly enough to score, stopping at third.
Pettitte retired the next two batters.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees finished Atlanta's Odalis Perez with a five-run
outburst in the bottom of the fifth. Knoblauch walked, Jeter
singled and O'Neill singled home Knoblauch. Chili Davis doubled,
Bernie Williams was walked intentionally, and both Scott Brosius
and Ricky Ledee had run-scoring singles. Yankees 8, Braves 3.
</P>
<P>
   Pettitte threw 65 pitches in the fourth and fifth, however, and
he faded for good in the sixth, giving up a double and single;
after he struck out Ozzie Guillen for the second out on his 96th
pitch, he was relieved by Jason Grimsley. Pettitte's final line:
three runs on nine hits and two walks in five and two-thirds
innings, for his first sixth victory _ more for Steinbrenner to
consider.
</P>
</TEXT>
