u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-YUGO-OPPOSITION-530&AMP;A     07-17 1013
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-YUGO-OPPOSITION-530&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KEY OPPOSITION LEADER JOINS RALLY AGAINST MILOSEVIC 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By STEVEN ERLANGER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   KRAGUJEVAC, Yugoslavia _ A leading opposition politician, Vuk
Draskovic, appeared Saturday for the first time at a rally calling
for the resignation of the Yugoslav president, Slobodan Milosevic,
and the formation of a transitional government leading to new
elections.
</P>
<P>
   Draskovic urged a festive crowd of some 20,000 people not to
seek revenge or pursue a violent path that could lead to ``civil
war.'' While he spoke of the need for Serbs ``to discuss and accept
the shame for what was done in Kosovo,'' he also criticized NATO
for allowing the Albanians after its air campaign to force Serbs
from the province and asked, ``Why does someone not threaten the
Albanians with bombing?''
</P>
<P>
   By pulling a crowd twice as large as his rivals did on Thursday
here, some 80 miles south of Belgrade, Draskovic attempted to
assert leadership over the democratic opposition to Milosevic and
his government.
</P>
<P>
   But the crowd, although enthusiastic enough, fell short of party
hopes for 30,000 to 50,000 people, and Draskovic delivered a
passionate but wandering address. He gave his supporters little
more direction than to keep demonstrating, in the hope that
Milosevic would somehow agree to resign and call early elections.
</P>
<P>
   Senior Draskovic aides said, however, that they had little hope
that rallies alone, without evidence of serious cracks in
Milosevic's police and armed forces, would bring any quick change
in Belgrade.
</P>
<P>
   Draskovic, who had been a part of Milosevic's government for
most of the war over Kosovo, had resisted the idea of street
demonstrations until 10 days ago. But his rivals among the
opposition, gathered as the Alliance for Change, were collecting
thousands of ordinary Serbs in towns outside Belgrade for their own
rallies calling for Milosevic to resign after the disastrous war
with NATO.
</P>
<P>
   Draskovic also was urged by a senior U.S. diplomat, Robert
Gelbard, in a recent meeting outside Serbia, to join his rivals in
a common platform, to enhance the chances for a more unified
opposition to Milosevic, who retains a strong grip over most
national news media.
</P>
<P>
   Draskovic is a bitter rival of Zoran Djindjic, the president of
the Democratic Party and a leader of the Alliance. While the two
men led the large anti-Milosevic street demonstrations of the
winter of 1996-97, which forced Milosevic to recognize opposition
victories in local elections, the two men quickly parted amid
mutual charges of egotism and hypocrisy.
</P>
<P>
   That rivalry worsened when Draskovic entered the Milosevic
government in January and Djindjic then fled to Montenegro during
the bombing, saying his life was at risk from the police. Even on
Saturday, Draskovic criticized party leaders ``who left the country
to hide or refused a call-up notice'' to fight during the war, as
Djindjic also did, saying that the draft was a form of harassment
from Belgrade.
</P>
<P>
   Some senior Draskovic aides admitted that this rally in
Kragujevac, which is controlled by Draskovic's party and where he
began his failed bid for the Serbian presidency in 1997, was as
much aimed at asserting priority over Djindjic as at hastening
Milosevic's departure.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Draskovic has called for another rally next Saturday in Nis, to
try to increase the pressure on Milosevic. But he has criticized
Djindjic's call for large marches on Belgrade from Serbian cities
as both risky and likely to fail, and his aides are quietly pushing
the Democratic Party to replace Djindjic as president, possibly
with Zoran Zivkovic, the popular mayor of Nis.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday here, other Alliance leaders called on Draskovic to
join them, with his Serbian Renewal Party leading the Alliance.
</P>
<P>
   But Draskovic said Saturday that his party ``will resist
pressure to join anyone,'' and said that all parties should compete
on their own in any new elections. But pressed by the Americans, he
has allowed other opposition parties to have more access to Studio
B, the Belgrade television station his party runs, and he has
provided a radio frequency for the independent journalists of B92,
a station taken over during the war by Milosevic allies.
</P>
<P>
   The split between the parties of Draskovic and Djindjic, so
visible in Belgrade, did not disrupt the ruling coalition here,
said Vesna Pajevic, who is the deputy director of the city's
executive and a member of Draskovic's party.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview on Saturday, she criticized Draskovic for paying
too little attention to the regions and their problems and too much
attention to his personal position. She said, ``We need unity and a
concrete program to tell people exactly what you will do for them
if they vote for you _ what you will do for the 60,000 unemployed
here in Kragujevac,'' whose biggest employer, the car factory
Zastava, was destroyed by NATO bombs.
</P>
<P>
   On this question, Draskovic was silent on Saturday, although
state television on Friday night led with a government plan to
employ 20,000 Zastava workers immediately and start making 50,000
cars a year again ``soon.'' However fantastic the report, said Mrs.
Pajevic's husband, Velimir, ``it will give people hope and buy
Milosevic more time.''
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Pajevic said she urged Draskovic on Saturday in a meeting
to worry less about winning over supporters of Milosevic and to
seize the moment when the government appears at its weakest.
</P>
<P>
   But she admitted that the system the president created had
deprived Serbs of self-confidence and made them unwilling to risk
``what little they have.''
</P>
<P>
   Pajevic, a pediatric surgeon, said sadly: ``There can be
hundreds of meetings like this, but there is not a critical mass.
People come and get it off their chests, and then they go home more
quietly.''
</P>
<P>
   He laughed sourly. ``Serbia has 178 parties and every party
leader is an egomaniac,'' he said. ``We have been very unlucky in
both our government and our opposition.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
