</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-BRITISH-PARNEVIK-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE FINISHING TOUCH IS ELUSIVE FOR PARNEVIK 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By CLIFTON BROWN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   CARNOUSTIE, Scotland _ Jesper Parnevik has a love-hate
relationship with the British Open. He loves the tournament. He
loves that he has often been in contention. But he hates the fact
that he has never been the winner.
</P>
<P>
   Three times since 1994, Parnevik has entered the final round of
the British Open with a chance to win, but something always went
wrong for him.
</P>
<P>
   In 1994 at Turnberry in Scotland, Parnevik reached the final
hole tied with Nick Price. But Parnevik neglected to read the
scoreboard and thought he needed a birdie to tie. After a good
drive, Parnevik tried a risky approach shot at the pin, rather than
playing a safer shot toward the middle of the green. His shot
missed the green, Parnevik bogeyed the final hole, and he lost to
Price by one stroke.
</P>
<P>
   In 1997 at Royal Troon, Parnevik shot a third-round 66 to take a
2-stroke lead over Darren Clarke and a 5-stroke lead over Justin
Leonard heading into the final round. But Parnevik stumbled to a
final-round 73, while Leonard shot a sensational 65 to win by three
strokes.
</P>
<P>
   Last year at Royal Birkdale, Parnevik entered the final round
trailing Brian Watts by just two strokes, but Parnevik's
final-round 72 was not enough to beat Mark O'Meara, who overtook
Parnevik, then outlasted Watts in a four-hole playoff.
</P>
<P>
   Parnevik entered Saturday's third round of the British Open in
contention again, alone in third place (3 over par at 145), two
strokes behind Jean Van de Velde of France, the second-round leader
at 1 under par, but shot a 78, putting him 10-over for the
tournament and seemingly out of contention in a tie for 14th.
</P>
<P>
   Disappointments like the ones Parnevik has endured can either
make you bitter or make you stronger. Parnevik has chosen to stay
strong and optimistic.
</P>
<P>
   ``To be the winner, I think you have to have luck, get the right
breaks at the right time, and hole a few putts,'' said Parnevik, a
34-year-old Swede. ``At Troon, I have to admit I thought I was
going to win. The night before, coming to the golf course, and then
on the first tee, I was pretty much sure I was going to win. Then
Justin just came out and shot a 65, which was very impressive. But
I still feel very good about my game, so I'm not going to change
much.''
</P>
<P>
   Parnevik should not change much, considering his track record at
the British Open. Why does Parnevik believe his game suits the
British Open?
</P>
<P>
   ``I love the type of shots you have to hit here, the low
drilling punch type of golf shots,'' Parnevik said. ``And I love
the turf. I grew up in Sweden playing on wet, muddy ground. The
club gets stuck in the ground when you hit a ball. I don't think
there's a better feeling or sound when you hit a golf ball anywhere
else in the world than links golf courses. I love the high shots
downwind. You don't hit 9-irons 225 yards very often.''
</P>
<P>
   But Parnevik did not enjoy Friday's second-round 71 as much as
he would have liked. Bothered by a fever and allergies, Parnevik
was not 100 percent, and he played Friday's round with tissue
packed in one nostril to keep his nose from running. After the
fifth hole, Parnevik felt so ill he thought about withdrawing.
</P>
<P>
   ``I haven't felt this bad for five, 10 years,'' said Parnevik.
``Hopefully, I can get some medication of some sort. I felt
terrible. I was sneezing constantly. I had to time putts between
sneezes. I thought I was going to shoot 90 or something.''
</P>
<P>
   Fortunately for Parnevik, he remained in the tournament and
remained in contention. And he continued his history of playing
well when he does not feel well. Parnevik won the Phoenix Open in
1998 while playing with a cold, and he was hoping that a good
night's rest coupled with medication would allow him to play
Sunday's round feeling much improved.
</P>
<P>
   Most players learn to handle the pressure at majors better as
they get older and gain more experience. With players like Norman
and Woods in pursuit, Parnevik will be tested again, but he sounded
confident.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel a lot more comfortable in the situation now,'' Parnevik
said. ``Turnberry was the second time I played in the British and
the second time I played in a major. Standing on the first tee
Sunday, my goal was not to win the tournament, it was pretty much
to break 90 or 100, especially playing with Tom Watson on the last
day. Now, I feel more comfortable.''
</P>
<P>
   Parnevik still doesn't seem to be comfortable enough to win, but
win or lose, Parnevik will still love the British Open.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
