u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HURRICANE-BIGONE18-CO     07-17 0863
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HURRICANE-BIGONE18-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    New Orleans uneasy about `Big One'
 &HT;    By Anne Rochell Konigsmark
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW OREANS _ They call it the ``Big One,'' the dreaded hurricane
that could hit New Orleans in just the right place and with just
the right force to turn this city into a giant lake.
</P>
<P>
   The Big One hasn't hit in modern times, but last September it
came so close you could almost smell it. That close call, combined
with predictions of a busy 1999 hurricane season, has given many
residents the jitters.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm more scared now, because of Hurricane Georges,'' said
Martha Arroyave, a beautician who lives on the West Bank of New
Orleans. Georges headed straight for New Orleans on Sept. 26.
Arroyave and her husband evacuated, along with record numbers of
New Orleanians.
</P>
<P>
   Georges turned east and hit Mississippi, but not before it
scared the daylights out of some residents.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were crazy to stay,'' said Michelle Kirtley, an assistant
professor at Loyola University. She holed up with her fiance and
their two dogs at his Uptown home, a typical one-story ``double
shotgun'' house that has withstood storms for more than 100 years.
Uptown, near Audubon Park, is considered high ground here, as is
the French Quarter.
</P>
<P>
   ``Last year, we thought we would move to the attic if the city
flooded,'' Kirtley said. ``But I saw a town meeting on television
about hurricanes, and it said the water would be up to the roof on
that style house. New Orleans will be a toilet bowl, and that's
what it will smell like too. If it comes close this year, I'm outta
here.''
</P>
<P>
   The toilet bowl image is apt, said Frank Hijuelos, director of
the New Orleans Office of Emergency Preparedness. New Orleans _
which is as much as 3 feet below sea level in many areas, lower
than any other major U.S. city _ is like a bowl, whose rim is
defined by the Mississippi River levees and Lake Pontchartrain to
the north. If a hurricane pushes water over the 17-foot levees,
which could happen only under very specific circumstances, the city
would be submerged.
</P>
<P>
   ``The water would have nowhere to go,'' Hijuelos said. ``It
would take weeks before we could pump it out. And if you were
planning to live in your attic, there will probably be lots of
snakes and critters living up there with you.''
</P>
<P>
   That's why Hijuelos and other city officials have been repeating
a single message as often as they can: When we ask you to leave,
please go.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't want to sound like Chicken Little, and I don't want to
scare people, but then again, I do,'' Hijuelos said.
</P>
<P>
   The city will have no shelters if there is a threat of what
Hijuelos calls ``total inundation.'' By having no shelters, city
officials hope to encourage more people to leave. There will be
shelters outside the areas of highest risk. And there will be a
``refuge of last resort'' for residents who simply can't leave _
probably the Superdome.
</P>
<P>
   ``We got more people evacuated last year than ever in our
history,'' Hijuelos said. ``My one message is that we live in a
bowl and the only way you are safe is out of here.''
</P>
<P>
   Although New Orleans is 100 miles from the Gulf of Mexico, its
position below sea level makes it one of the most vulnerable spots
in the country when it comes to hurricanes. And Georges left
residents feeling that vulnerability.
</P>
<P>
   At crawfish boils and cocktail parties this summer, residents
compare neighborhoods, boasting if they are on high ground and
fretting if they are in a low-lying area. They talk of favorite
``hurricane foods'' _ Pop Tarts top most lists _ and they debate
the benefits of staying put or evacuating.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone is talking about it, and I think that's good,''
Hijuelos said.
</P>
<P>
   All these predictions and worries seem premature to Nash
Roberts, the 81-year-old weatherman who has gained a reputation for
never missing in his forecasts of where hurricanes will hit.
</P>
<P>
   ``I see no unusual situation here,'' he said. ``You could have
an active season and it's conceivable the storms never strike any
mainland, or you could have an inactive season and have one hit
you. I don't see any particular reason for any stretch of the
coastline to be more worried than any other one.''
</P>
<P>
   And New Orleans is well-protected for most hurricane situations,
Hijuelos said.
</P>
<P>
   ``But a Category 4 or 5, or a slow-moving Category 3, coming
over the city with the eye touching the western side _ that's the
threat we fear the most,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Hurricanes come in five categories with five being the
strongest.
</P>
<P>
   Since that specific scenario hasn't happened yet, some residents
aren't holding their breath. David Perkins, a lifelong resident who
works at Home Depot, said he didn't evacuate last year, and he
won't this year.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll stay, unless Mom wants to go,'' he said. ``But she
stayed last year.''
</P>
<P>
   And for all the talk, residents haven't rushed in for hurricane
supplies, such as plywood for windows and doors, Perkins said.
</P>
<P>
   ``People wait until they see a hurricane in the Gulf of
Mexico,'' he said. ``That's when we see a lot of action.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
