<SLUG> BC-GLF-BROPEN-ROUND3-18-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Montgomerie says he's OK with the pressure
 &HT;    By Glenn Sheeley
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   CARNOUSTIE, Scotland _ Colin Montgomerie has resorted to some
questionable mental gymnastics at the 128th British Open.
</P>
<P>
   On one hand, the Scot is questioning the fortitude of leader
Jean Van de Velde, wondering whether he can handle the pressure of
a major championship today. At the same time Montgomerie, after
trying to publicly write himself off at the halfway point to
relieve pressure, bristled at a reporter asking whether he could
handle the Sunday tension.
</P>
<P>
   Neither player, by the way, has won a major championship.
</P>
<P>
   After shooting a 72 Saturday that provided an outside chance of
contending today from 9-over, Montgomerie tried to clarify an
opinion from Friday that he was out of the tournament at 8-over.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew I wasn't out of it,'' Montgomerie said after a Saturday
72. ``I just wanted to try to deflect the situation (Friday) away
from myself and on to other people. The way things were going today
after 14 holes (until bogeys at 15, 16 and 17), it was working.''
</P>
<P>
   After indicating that the Frenchman has not yet seen the Open
Championship's genuine pressure, Monty was asked if he ``can cope
with the pressure.''
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no pressure from (you), OK,'' Montgomerie said,
glaring. ``I can cope with the pressure. I think I proved myself a
number of times now that I can cope with the pressure.''
</P>
<P>
   Duval not a factor
</P>
<P>
   David Duval, with four PGA Tour wins this year and the world's
No. 2 ranking, continued his invisible performance at the Open
Championship, where he has fought with both the local tabloids
about course criticism and the course itself. Duval shot a
third-round 75 to stand at 17 shots off the lead. ``I never said I
didn't like the golf course,'' he said Saturday. ``It's a great
golf course, but like the U.S. Open when it's set up, the smallest
mistake costs you.'' Duval does not think the course set-up
necessarily will identify the best player in the field, but that
can be said for just about any major championship. Didn't Andy
North win two U.S. Opens?
</P>
<P>
   Love drops out of sight
</P>
<P>
   Sea Island's Davis Love III turned the front nine in 40 Saturday
en route to a 77, dropping to 12-over 225 and 12 shots off the
lead. . . . U.S. Open champion Payne Stewart's 74 placed him at
13-over 226, finishing with two bogeys. ``My attitude hasn't
changed to the Open,'' Stewart said. ``I am disappointed in the
course setup, but my view of the British Open hasn't changed. I
love the tournament and I think it's the foremost golf tournament
in the world. . . . .Even being an American and having two U.S.
Opens, I've always held the British Open dear to my heart and it
would really complete my career if I could win one.'' . . .Lee
Janzen five-putted the 15th hole for an eight and shot 79 . .
.Alpharetta resident Scott Dunlap took a triple-bogey eight on the
par-5, 578-yard 6th hole, turning the front nine in 40 for an
eventual 76 and 12-over 225 . . .Nobody bogeyed the 515-yard 14th.
There were 43 birdies, 29 pars and an eagle at the 14th. . . One of
the nastiest photos in recent memory appeared in the Scottish
edition of the London Daily Mail Saturday. Sweden's Jesper Parnevik
was the cover shot, with pieces of tissue paper stuck up his nose
to fight a hayfever drip. The headline: ``Sneezy Does It.'' . .
Parnevik triple-bogeyed the 11th hole Saturday from the middle of
the fairway, shooting 78 to drop 10 strokes off the lead at 223.
``It's not my tournament, this one,'' said Parnevik, a two-time
runnerup at the Open Championship. ``It's gone now for this year.
Oh yeah, again.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
