</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Y2K-PREPARE-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSINESSES ZERO IN ON CALMING Y2K FEARS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY DEBORAH ADAMSON  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES -- Businesses have been gearing up for the Y2K
millennium bug problem for years. Many corporations say they're
ready.
</P>
<P>
   But do their customers know?
</P>
<P>
   In the final stages of preparing for Y2K, companies realize that
it's not enough to get their systems in order. Due to heightened
media attention to this problem, they also have to allay a growing
concern among their customers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Two years ago, they were more focused on communicating to
their own employees because it was an issue internally,'' said
Roger Rittner, a senior vice president at Sheppard Associates, a
Y2K communication consultant. ``In the last six months, when the
press latched on to the Y2K as an issue, companies found that they
have to talk to customers as well.''
</P>
<P>
   The Y2K problem, of course, is that at the advent of the year
2000, computers programmed in old languages that only use two
digits for years won't be able to differentiate between 1900 and
2000. It could cause widespread havoc since computer functions will
be disrupted.
</P>
<P>
   San Fernando Valley businesses are aware of the issue and those
that think they'll be affected by it have made preparations, said
Bob Scott, vice chairman at the Valley Industry and Commerce
Association in Woodland Hills.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody thinks they're ready,'' he said. ``People who think
they might have a problem are dealing with it.''
</P>
<P>
   But the real test to see if preparations have been adequate will
come on Jan. 1, Scott added.
</P>
<P>
   The companies most at risk are those using technology dated
between the early 1960s and mid-1980s, Scott said.
</P>
<P>
   In mid-June, a Y2K test at the Donald C. Tillman reclamation
plant in Van Nuys led to 4 million gallons of raw sewage spilling
into Woodley Avenue Park.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this year, a government study of U.S. industries
concluded that all segments of the economy are vulnerable to the
Y2K problem. Hospitals, doctors' offices, utilities, airports and
the government are less prepared than companies in banking,
insurance, telecommunications and finance.
</P>
<P>
   Among the best prepared, financial institutions are rushing to
get the message out to their customers not to panic and withdraw
massive amounts of cash.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're going to see a lot more communication,'' said John
Stafford, a spokesman at the California Bankers Association in San
Francisco. ``There's an increasing awareness that banks need to
communicate directly with the customer. Consumers are not getting
it yet.''
</P>
<P>
   This week, Union Bank of California customers started seeing
friendly red-and-black stickers on the ATM machines saying ``Y2K
OK.'' The San Francisco-based bank also is sending mailers
informing customers of its preparations.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's designed to reassure customers,'' said spokeswoman Joanne
Kurran, who declined to say how much money the bank has spent
fixing the Y2K bug.
</P>
<P>
   Bank of America, which shelled out $500 million for Y2K, has
launched a toll-free number -- (888) 960-1111 -- to answer customer
concerns in six languages: English, Spanish, Mandarin, Cantonese,
Vietnamese and Korean.
</P>
<P>
   BofA branches have Y2K brochures on display racks, informational
inserts are included with account statements, and the bank's Web
site also addresses the issue.
</P>
<P>
   Washington Mutual said it completed Y2K testing in 1998. The
thrift is communicating its Y2K compliance to customers through
brochures, monthly statements to customers and its Web site.
</P>
<P>
   Other forms of communication include screen savers, wallet cards
and reports to employees, Rittner said. Y2K isn't going to cripple
America, but it will be a problem elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   ``It looks like in the U.S. there will be very little
disruption,'' he said. ``The big worry is outside the U.S. Will
they bring down international systems? The focus of concern has
shifted overseas.''
</P>
<P>
   X X X
</P>
</TEXT>
