<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDITORIAL-JFKJR-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE HOPE AND SORROW OF THE KENNEDYS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Another call late in the night. Another stab of bad news,
striking, once again, in a time of celebration.
</P>
<P>
   The lives and deaths of the Kennedy family, which have so deeply
colored the latter half of the American century, embodied an
extraordinary blend of tragedy and hope. Joseph Kennedy Jr.'s plane
went down in August 1944, when World War II was being won. Kathleen
Kennedy died in 1948, also in a plane crash, on her way to tell her
father of her new love. John Kennedy was killed in 1963 as he
prepared confidently for his reelection campaign. Robert Kennedy
was shot on the night he won the 1968 California primary. Michael
Kennedy was said to have been rebounding from personal difficulties
when he died in a ski accident in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Even after so many dark days in years past, the word out of the
Kennedy compound Saturday was one of optimism. The family was
determined, until there was proof to the contrary, to believe that
some miracle might deliver the occupants of the small plane to
safety.
</P>
<P>
   Optimism against heavy odds was a characteristic of this Kennedy
in particular. Weaned on the nation's nightmare _ he was two days
short of his third birthday when his father was killed _ John Jr.
focused as an adult on communicating to others the joy he said he
found in politics.
</P>
<P>
   His magazine George showed it was possible to be lively and
irreverent but still largely positive. His last editor's letter
praised Senators John McCain and Russell Feingold not so much for
the substance of their campaign reform bill as for their courage in
pushing it against heavy opposition.
</P>
<P>
   ``We do have heroes among us,'' Kennedy wrote. ``While we at
George share your skepticism about many in Washington, we've always
believed that political leaders can inspire a sense of pride and
possibility.''
</P>
<P>
   Pride there can be for the Kennedy family, that the president's
son and namesake navigated a most difficult course with good humor,
a measure of dignity _ and optimism. But the great sense of
possibility that John F. Kennedy Jr. carried within him is
apparently lost in the warm waters off Martha's Vineyard and will
not see a new millennium.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-17-99 1933EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990717.0209 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> MISCELLANEOUS TEXT (slug-filter) </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-17 19:36 </DATE_TIME>
