A4028 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ATL-GLF-BROPEN-NOTES3     07-17 0853
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ATL-GLF-BROPEN-NOTES3-18 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Van de Velde stays step ahead at British
 &HT;    By Glenn Sheeley
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   CARNOUSTIE, Scotland _ Everything logical vanished Saturday at
the Carnoustie Golf Links. The world's No. 1 player stumbled at the
finish and a Frenchman whom no one can describe without a search
engine made a birdie putt from somewhere out on the North Sea.
</P>
<P>
   With one round to play in the 128th British Open, Jean Van de
Velde, 33, is managing what seemed highly unlikely. Instead of
collapsing under the pressure of a major championship, Van de Velde
is gaining in strength. He expanded his lead to five shots Saturday
with a 1-under-par 70 to assume a commanding position at even-par
213.
</P>
<P>
   It's the largest 54-hole lead in the British Open since Tom
Lehman led by six shots entering the final round at Royal Lytham in
1996. Lehman won by two shots. The big question is: Can Van de
Velde, a newcomer to such lofty status and 18 holes from a
life-changing experience, hang in there?
</P>
<P>
   ``You know, many people have asked me that,'' said Van de Velde,
who was a Sunday-Monday qualifier. ``I'm just going to go out there
and do my best to enjoy it. I know that there's a lot better
players than me who had an even more commanding lead and who have
lost. I'm just going to try and focus on my game and try not to
beat myself.''
</P>
<P>
   Just when common sense indicated a back-up by Van de Velde
seemed in order Saturday _ what does the guy think this is, the
Paris Four-Ball? _ he drained a 70-foot putt for birdie at the 14th
hole, then made a 45-footer at the 18th. The ghost of Tom Watson
couldn't have done it any better. Everytime you looked up, the
Frenchman was getting up and down or draining a putt for birdie.
</P>
<P>
   Tied for second place at 5-over 218 are American Justin Leonard,
the 1997 British Open champion, who had a 71; and Australian Craig
Parry, whose 5-under 67 is the lowest of the tournament.
</P>
<P>
   American Tiger Woods, meanwhile, double-bogeyed the 17th to
finish at 74 for 7-over 220, increasing the size of his final-round
task. Also at 220 are South African David Frost (71) and Scotland's
Andrew Coltart (72). Australian Greg Norman, the 44-year-old twice
winner of the Open Championship, bogeyed his final two holes for 75
and is at 221 with Argentina's Angel Cabrera (77).
</P>
<P>
   Conditions that remain difficult, despite a warming trend late
Saturday afternoon and some lessened wind that dropped the stroke
average to 75.6, undoubtedly increase the chance of wide stroke
swings today. Woods is counting on a low number and some trouble
finding its way to the thus far unscathed Van de Velde.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no way I can go out and shoot a number where he stays
at even par and I can beat him,'' Woods said. ``It's that hard a
golf course. I need to rely on him, hopefully, coming back at me a
little bit, and we'll see what happens.''
</P>
<P>
   If things continue in this manner, today Van de Velde, who
stands 40th on the European Order of Merit, will become the first
Frenchman to win the Open Championship since Arnaud Massy in 1907
at Hoylake, England.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe since Van de Velde had not secured a spot until he
qualified Monday with scores of 67-67, there is no real pressure at
all. Using 23 putts Saturday, he played as though a veteran to such
major championship wars. His closest thing to legitimate attention
was a second-place finish at Loch Lomond three years ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know the most pressure (is) playing with my friends sometime
when I've got a 3-footer to win,'' he said. ``What kind of pressure
can you get here? It is the biggest tournament ever in the world
and I'm in there and I'm a bit ahead of everybody. So what can
happen? I can lose it or I can win it. Either way, I'm having a
good time. That's the main thing.''
</P>
<P>
   Scotland's Colin Montgomerie, while respectful of the leader's
game, said his inner strength has not yet been fully examined.
</P>
<P>
   ``The one thing we don't know, and he doesn't know until he has
been there, is how he can cope with the situation now,''
Montgomerie said. ``Now it's not about swinging the golf club for
Jean. It's nothing to do with technique and it's nothing to do with
golf. It's all about what's in his head right now. And if he can
cope with that situation, he can remain up there.''
</P>
<P>
   Even Norman, at eight shots back after a 75, called himself
``absolutely'' in contention. Unfortunately, he knows all too well
about a big lead vanishing in a major, having squandered a 6-shot
lead after 54 holes of the 1996 Masters.
</P>
<P>
   ``Anybody 8, 7 or 6-over has a definite shot,'' said Norman, who
made a miraculous bogey at the 17th, almost holing out from a
greenside bunker after driving into the burn. ``You've just got to
make the putts and get some breaks.''
</P>
<P>
   The man to watch closely could be Leonard, who started the final
round at Royal Troon two years ago also five shots back.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm just pleased to have a chance to win the tournament,''
Leonard said. ``That was my goal at the beginning of the week.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
