<SLUG> BC-KENNEDY-NET18-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    By Frances Katz
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ There was scant information on the Web early Saturday
morning, when the news broke that John F. Kennedy Jr.'s plane was
missing. CNN, ABCNews.com and MSNBC all had stories reporting the
plane missing, but didn't elaborate
</P>
<P>
   much beyond that. The local Massachusetts newspapers, The Boston
Globe (www.boston.com) and the Boston Herald (www.bostonherald.com)
also lacked early original reporting and relied on wire stories.
The early lack of coverage from local news outlets was odd,
particularly in light of the wedding of Rory Kennedy in
Hyannisport, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   Later in the day, as more information became known, the major
news organizations began posting additional information and
background stories. However, they were careful not to make any
definitive statements other than that Kennedy and his family were
missing.
</P>
<P>
   The Boston Herald, which has zealously followed the Kennedy
family's each and every move for years, had a variety of stories
posted by 5 p.m. A chilling AP story titled ``Dressed for a
Wedding, a Compound Braces for Trouble,'' was filled with tragic
details. One poignant scene depicts 50 family members and three
priests huddled on the porch of the Kennedy family compound saying
Mass and praying for the safety of the loved ones as well as the
bride and her fiancee.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
