<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-17 19:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4034 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u p &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BUSH-2000-2TAKES-HNS &LR;      07-17 1083
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSH-2000-2TAKES-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSH'S SEEMINGLY SPONTANEOUS RACE HAS BEEN WELL PLANNED 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By R.G. RATCLIFFE 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ The overflow crowds that turned out in June for
Gov. George W. Bush's California presidential fund-raising swing
surpassed his campaign staff's wildest imaginations.
</P>
<P>
   Almost 2,000 Californians packed into some of the $1,000-a-plate
dinners, requiring extra tables to be set up in a hall in
traditionally Democratic San Francisco. A scalper tried to sell a
ticket to one event for $3,000.
</P>
<P>
   It was not always that way.
</P>
<P>
   ``When Governor Bush first ran for (Texas) governor in 1994, we
had a very exclusive event for him in Los Angeles. Only 25 people.
The reason it was so exclusive was we couldn't get any more people
to attend,'' said Bush's Golden State finance chairman, Brad
Freeman.
</P>
<P>
   On the surface, it appears that Bush's bid for the Republican
presidential nomination _ unprecedented in its early popularity _
ignited spontaneously in the eight months after his landslide
re-election as Texas governor.
</P>
<P>
   But Bush's campaign success is actually based on more than two
years of strategic planning and preparation as his aides and allies
built a network of potential supporters and financiers.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of work went into it. It didn't just happen,'' said
Heinz Prechter, a fund-raiser for Bush in Michigan.
</P>
<P>
   The result of all that planning was the creation of a seemingly
unbeatable front-runner six months before the first primary vote is
cast and a full year before the nominating conventions.
</P>
<P>
   Bush leads every poll. Politicians and political financiers
journeyed to Austin earlier this year to meet Bush as if on a quest
for a political grail. When Bush finally ventured out of Texas last
month to Iowa and New Hamphsire, masses surrounded him.
</P>
<P>
   Then the money poured in, a record $37 million that has allowed
Bush to forgo federal matching funds and their spending limits.
</P>
<P>
   A major source of the success was a program called the Pioneers,
which recruited people willing to raise $100,000 to earn the right
to adopt that frontier moniker. More than 350 people volunteered
for the program and almost 120 had reached their goal by June 30.
</P>
<P>
   Interviews with more than a dozen Bush insiders across the
country produced a picture of a campaign that ``evolved,'' as they
liked to say, from a network of Bush friends from Yale and Harvard,
as well as his father's political campaigns.
</P>
<P>
   At the center was a small group led by political consultant Karl
Rove. Others in the inner circle included longtime friend and
finance chairman Don Evans, administrative aide Joe Allbaugh and
press secretary Karen Hughes. Even within that circle, many secrets
are known only by Bush and Rove, they said.
</P>
<P>
   With Rove serving as the point man, the group built a national
network that would allow Bush's presidential campaign to burst onto
the scene fully developed when he announced the formation of an
exploratory committee in March.
</P>
<P>
   Bush, the insiders said, encouraged everyone he met _ including
his own staff _ to view him as a potential presidential contender
without ever committing to a race. Bush did not want to get too far
out front with his presidential bid, fearing it might hurt his
state re-election campaign.
</P>
<P>
   He also wanted to defer a final decision on running because of
what friends described as the ``gulp factor,'' the gasp before
making a giant step that could change his personal life forever.
But underneath, few ever doubted that he would run.
</P>
<P>
   Hughes tells the story of Bush not making a final decision to
run until after his inaugural church service this past January.
</P>
<P>
   ``The minister had a very compelling call to make the most of
your life. Afterward, the governor said, `I think he was talking to
me,''' Hughes said.
</P>
<P>
   There has been a tendency to portray Bush as almost an
accidental candidate, someone whom the tide of history has swept
toward greatness and the presidency. But Bush has been a meticulous
personal strategist, planning his future for a decade.
</P>
<P>
   Two months after becoming the managing general partner of the
Texas Rangers in 1989, he admitted to a Time reporter that his role
in the team was part of a plan to someday run for Texas governor.
</P>
<P>
   ``My biggest liability in Texas is the question, `What's the boy
ever done?''' Bush said. ```So he's got a famous father and a ran a
small oil company. He could be riding on daddy's name if he ran for
office.' Now I can say, `I've done something _ here it is.'''
</P>
<P>
   While Bush and his friends say there was never a grand scheme
for his political career, part of Bush's success this year came
from taking the tested tactics and themes of his two governor's
races to a national stage.
</P>
<P>
   For instance, as Bush prepared for his first governor's race in
1993, Rove tried to build an aura of a draft-Bush movement. He
announced that 10 of 13 Republican state senators had signed a
letter urging Bush to run for governor in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   Rove similarly this year started a drumbeat for Bush's
presidential bid by encouraging elected officials in various states
to write letters urging Bush to seek the presidency. Bush insiders
say the initial effort was so successful that many of the later
letter-writing campaigns occurred spontaneously.
</P>
<P>
   Bush's friends said there was never any talk of him running for
president during his first two years as governor, but that quickly
changed after 1996.
</P>
<P>
   Bush had gained a great deal of national exposure as co-chairman
of the 1996 Republican National Convention in San Diego. The
convention's host committee chairman, Gerald Parsky, is now Bush's
California campaign chairman.
</P>
<P>
   Then Sen. Bob Dole's presidential defeat, following that of
Bush's father in 1992, had Republican activists looking for a
winner for 2000.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bush had the advantage of being from a big state, having a
presidential name and, at the same time, being a fresh new face,''
said one Bush associate.
</P>
<P>
   During the first half of 1997, Bush started gingerly testing the
waters with political trips to California, South Carolina, Florida
and Tennessee.
</P>
<P>
   Then-South Carolina Gov. David Beasley set off the first hard
speculation about a Bush presidential run during Bush's visit in
March 1997.
</P>
<P>
   ``People here expect him to be a top contender for the
presidential nomination,'' Beasley declared. ``He's just a natural
fit.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(More) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Bush &UR;  &LR; dismissed Beasley's comments when he returned to Austin:
``This is all a bunch of national people, who obviously have got a
lot of time on their hands, trying to put words and thoughts in my
head.''
</P>
<P>
   But the following month, Bush encouraged speculation again when
he spoke before the staunchly conservative California Republican
Assembly. In accepting the Ronald Reagan Freedom Fighter Award,
Bush talked of the need to help ``godless children.''
</P>
<P>
   While Bush was wooing the California conservatives, former
Republican National Committee Chairman Rich Bond was traveling
through Iowa making contacts on the governor's behalf for a 2000
bid. When word got out, Rove quickly distanced Bush from the
effort.
</P>
<P>
   Then, in June 1997, the Zogby American poll came out with a
report that 21 percent of the Republicans surveyed supported Bush
as their 2000 presidential nominee. Not only were Bush's numbers
up, but the poll marked the first time that he had become a popular
name, ahead of such party names as Colin Powell and Jack Kemp.
</P>
<P>
   Hughes said Bush's lead in the June 1997 poll was the first
indication Bush had that he could be a serious presidential
contender.
</P>
<P>
   ``He looked at me and said, `You've got to be kidding me,'''
Hughes recalled.
</P>
<P>
   Even if he was now thinking of running, Bush still demurred in
public, calling the 2000 race the ``famous future question.'' He
insisted that the only thing on his mind was re-election in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   But by August, one of Bush's friends from the graduate business
school at Harvard, Al Hubbard of Indiana, had talked Bush into
participating in the Midwest Republican Leadership Conference. Rove
privately touted the event to national political reporters as
Bush's presidential coming out.
</P>
<P>
   The speech was poorly received, leading Bush again to lower
expectations about himself as a potential presidential candidate.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was invited to go to a fund-raiser,'' Bush told Austin
reporters afterward. ``I hadn't thought through the ramifications
of some national beauty contest.''
</P>
<P>
   In October 1997, Bush declared that he had ``not made a decision
to run for president,'' and said his only concern was Texas and
re-election.
</P>
<P>
   But behind the scenes, Bush's operatives were already planning.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had some early meetings to talk about (running for
president) in generic terms,'' Prechter said. ``I wanted to make
sure after 1996 that we could get behind a leader in our party who
could unite people.''
</P>
<P>
   Prechter said Bush ``wasn't all convinced early on that this is
what he wanted to do.''
</P>
<P>
   Michigan Gov. John Engler, a past chairman of the Republican
Governor's Association, was building support for Bush among other
governors while also trying to get Bush to commit to a run.
</P>
<P>
   ``People in the party, governors like me, wanted somebody who
could both win the campaign and then govern according to a set of
principles that we need to move power out of Washington to the
local communities,'' Engler said.
</P>
<P>
   As part of his early field tests, Bush often traveled across the
country to help Republican gubernatorial candidates raise money for
races in their states.
</P>
<P>
   Bush finance chairman Evans said the trips were not part of a
specific network-building effort, but added, ``It didn't hurt. It
was a chance for him to deliver his positive, hopeful message.''
</P>
<P>
   In June 1998, a re-election planning meeting turned into a
presidential strategy session, as former Republican U.S. Rep. Tom
Tauke urged Bush to go ahead and form a presidential exploratory
committee. Tauke, who was secretly slated to become Bush's
presidential campaign manager, thought Bush was waiting too long to
announce, insiders said.
</P>
<P>
   But when Bush found out about the tone of the meeting, he
brought it to a halt. Some said Bush thought such presidential talk
was premature in the midst of his re-election campaign.
</P>
<P>
   However, Bush began to interview potential policy advisers that
summer. Hubbard set up a meeting with domestic policy adviser
Lawrence Lindsey at the Governor's Mansion, and Bush met his future
foreign policy adviser, Condoleezza Rice, at his father's home.
Rice had been an adviser to the Bush White House.
</P>
<P>
   If the gun for Bush's presidential bullet was back-to-back GOP
defeats in previous elections, the trigger was his 1998 victory
over Democrat Garry Mauro.
</P>
<P>
   Although he won in a landslide, the appearances of President
Clinton, his wife Hillary and Vice President Al Gore at Mauro
fund-raisers enhanced the image nationally that Bush's victory was
gigantic rather than a a political cakewalk.
</P>
<P>
   ``The thing that really made a difference was those re-election
numbers that showed his support was not only deep, but very
broad,'' Freeman said.
</P>
<P>
   During the second week of December, a small group of Bush's
Texas advisers and Tauke met in the private quarters of the
Governor's Mansion. They decided to take public steps toward a run.
</P>
<P>
   If the support was there, they decided, the newly elected
governor should announce an exploratory committee in March, as Bush
eventually did.
</P>
<P>
   (Tauke left Bush's campaign before his role was ever formalized
or made public. One insider said Bush and Tauke just could not
agree on how to run the campaign.)
</P>
<P>
   Probably the most important decision that was made was to create
the Pioneers fund-raising organization. It was a method of raising
a lot of money without holding traditional events. The hope was to
make Bush the financial front-runner by the end of June.
</P>
<P>
   More than 350 people around the country pledged to become
Pioneers. As of the end of June, almost 120 had made it.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Pioneers have raised well over $10 million. So it has been
a significant part of the success story,'' said Pioneers program
chairman Jim Francis of Dallas. ``This is a political movement that
is for real and very enthusiastic for Governor Bush.''
</P>
<P>
   Chuck Nash, a San Marcos auto dealer and a Pioneer, said the
$100,000 goal seemed difficult but was not because the candidate
was Bush.
</P>
<P>
   ``I sell cars for a living. I wish all my products were as easy
to sell as George Bush,'' Nash said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
