<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-17 19:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4037 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KENNEDY-PILOT-1STLEAD     07-17 0963
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KENNEDY-PILOT-1STLEAD-WRITETHRU-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A NEW, CAUTIOUS FLIER, WHO OFTEN WENT WITH HIS INSTRUCTOR 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (SUBS for rewrite, new info)  (ART ADV:  Graphic  is being sent to NYT graphics clients.
Non-subscribers may make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(See also: KENNEDY-MISSING-PLANE, KENNEDY-TRAGEDY, KENNEDY-SEARCH,
KENNEDY-NY-SCENE, KENNEDY-MASS-SCENE) 
 (HLW)  
 By MATTHEW L. WALD   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ John F. Kennedy Jr. was a relatively new pilot,
apparently rather cautious, flying a well-equipped and relatively
new single-engine plane.
</P>
<P>
   Kennedy earned his private pilot's license on April 22, 1998,
officials of the Federal Aviation Administration said. His license
allowed him to fly single-engine planes and to carry passengers,
but not for compensation.
</P>
<P>
   He was not qualified to fly if he had to rely on instruments,
though he had been working on getting that rating. When he, his
wife, Carolyn Bessette Kennedy, and his sister-in-law, Lauren
Bessette, took off from Essex County Airport in Fairfield, N.J., on
Friday night, flying to Martha's Vineyard, the winds were light and
there were no thunderstorms, weather he was qualified to fly in.
</P>
<P>
   Pilots said that haze on the flight path could be a challenge,
because it could make a pilot lose sight of the horizon. In a turn,
a pilot who does not use instruments and who cannot see out the
windows may bank so steeply that he loses control. When making
over-water flights, most private pilots fly at a relatively high
altitude, 7,500 to 9,500 feet, so that if the engine quits, they
can glide far enough to reach land.
</P>
<P>
   Kennedy was known as a cautious flyer. ``If the weather was bad,
he would charter,'' said Chuck McKenna, the operations manager at
Mac Dan Aviation, a maintenance shop and charter service at the
Essex airport, where Kennedy kept the plane, a four-year-old Piper
Saratoga.
</P>
<P>
   ``There were times when if he was at the Vineyard or Hyannis, we
would go up there and pick him up,'' McKenna said, even if that
meant leaving his own plane behind. ``If you're asking me what I
know of his flying and decision-making, I would say he'd err on the
side of caution,'' McKenna said.
</P>
<P>
   Five or six weeks ago, he said, Kennedy had hurt an ankle while
on Martha's Vineyard, and called Mac Dan to pick him up.
</P>
<P>
   A pilot who also flies from the Essex airfield said Kennedy
frequently flew with a flight instructor to Martha's Vineyard on
Friday nights, returning on Sunday nights or Monday mornings. The
instructor, the pilot said, was not aboard the Saratoga on Friday
night; he was in Europe.
</P>
<P>
   The pilot, who asked not to be identified by name, said he saw
the Kennedy party preparing to depart Friday night about 8:15.
Kennedy was dressed in white slacks and T-shirt; his wife wore
black pants and a black T-shirt; her sister was wearing a beige
dress, he said.
</P>
<P>
   One of Kennedy's feet appeared to be injured, the pilot said,
adding that he was ``pivoting around on one spot.'' He had what
appeared from a distance to be a crutch but was not using it and
was wearing ordinary shoes on both feet, the other pilot said.
</P>
<P>
   The plane's rudder is controlled with foot pedals. It was not
clear on Saturday whether Kennedy's apparent injury might have
affected his ability to control the plane.
</P>
<P>
   ``He always said he had an instructor fly with him a lot in the
Saratoga,'' the pilot said. ``He may have been getting accustomed
to a new plane, and trying to enhance his skills, even though he
had the license.''
</P>
<P>
   An air traffic controller, also speaking on the condition of
anonymity, said Kennedy had been given clearance by the airport
tower to take off.
</P>
<P>
   Private planes commonly do not fly under air traffic control,
and Kennedy did not contact the New York Terminal Radar Approach
Control, which would be the first air traffic control office with
jurisdiction over a plane flying under instrument rules. But since
he was flying under visual flight rules, he was not required to do
so.
</P>
<P>
   Under visual flight rules, he was under no obligation to check
in if he chose to take responsibility for spotting other air
traffic and for keeping a safe distance, and if he did not need to
ask about weather conditions ahead.
</P>
<P>
   His plane carried a transponder, a device that automatically
responds to a query from FAA radar, identifying the airplane and
altitude. But for private flights like this one, the transponder
would be responding with a generic code meaning it was a general
aviation flight and not giving its precise identity. FAA
technicians Saturday were sorting through all such flights the
previous night, trying to determine which one was Kennedy's.
</P>
<P>
   Kennedy's Saratoga was built in June 1995, according to the
manufacturer. The model can carry six people, and there are more
than 7,500 in service, according to Chuck Suma, president of the
company. Suma said at a news conference that Kennedy had trained on
two smaller Pipers, a Warrior and an Arrow.
</P>
<P>
   The Saratoga has a single 300-horsepower, six-cylinder engine, a
little bigger than an engine in a large car. It can carry about
1,100 pounds, including people, baggage and fuel. It carries about
100 gallons. The one Kennedy was flying had a market value of
$325,000 to $350,000, Suma said.
</P>
<P>
   The previous owner of the plane Kennedy was flying, Munir
Hussain, of Hasbrouck Heights, N.J., said it was equipped with a
storm scope, which spots thunderstorms, as well as radios for
tuning in two ground-based navigation beacons simultaneously.
Hussain, a furniture manufacturer who used the Saratoga in his
business, said it had leather seats, a compact disc player and air
conditioning. It also had a ground approach warning system.
</P>
</TEXT>
