<DOCNO> NYT19990717.0218 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-17 19:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4038 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SERIAL-KILLER-HNS &LR;      07-17 1439
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SERIAL-KILLER-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RELATIVE WHO PERSUADED SUSPECT TO SURRENDER KNOWS HIM AS `GENTLE,
KIND, LOVING' 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By PATTY REINERT 
and ARMANDO VILLAFRANCA 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBUQUERQUE, N.M. _ Growing up in western Mexico, Manuela
Maturino and her siblings had only sporadic contact with their
gentle, older half-brother, Angel. As adults, they heard from him
occasionally as he drifted back and forth across the Rio Grande, in
and out of their lives.
</P>
<P>
   They knew nothing of his common-law wife. When he became a
father last spring, they had no idea.
</P>
<P>
   Yet in the end, the most important thing that accused serial
killer Angel Maturino Resendez wanted in order to give himself up
was the assurance that his family could cross the Texas border with
him.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday morning, Manuela Maturino, a nurse's aide and mother
of two who had immigrated to the United States years earlier, stood
a few steps behind Texas Rangers Sgt. Drew Carter on an
international bridge near El Paso. Carter's white cowboy hat and
the presence of Manuela were the signal to one of the most-wanted
men in the United States that it was safe to surrender.
</P>
<P>
   He stepped out of his brother's pickup and ended a six-week
manhunt by shaking the ranger's hand. Known to authorities as
Rafael Resendez-Ramirez before he gave a judge the new name last
week, he now sits in a Houston jail cell, a suspect in at least
nine slayings in Texas, Kentucky and Illinois.
</P>
<P>
   Maturino Resendez has been charged with capital murder in the
slaying of 87-year-old Leafie Mason of the East Texas town of
Hughes Springs, and could face more capital charges in the near
future. If convicted, he could face death by injection, a
punishment he likely could have avoided by giving himself up in
Mexico, which does not have the death penalty and does not
extradite citizens who could face the punishment.
</P>
<P>
   ``Manuela and the whole family have been emotionally
traumatized. She hadn't seen him or heard from him in several
years,'' said her pastor, Troy Robinson, who sat with her during
the negotiations at her Albuquerque home and accompanied her to
Texas. ``They all remember him as a gentle, kind, loving person,
and they just couldn't believe this.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it was in the back of their minds that this wasn't the
right man.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet the surrender drama was not the first time Maturino had come
before authorities because of her brother's involvement in a
criminal matter.
</P>
<P>
   In 1989, she was subpoenaed to testify at her brother's trial in
federal court in St. Louis. He was charged with 16 counts of
immigration violations and weapons charges. He had elected to act
as his own attorney.
</P>
<P>
   In questioning his sister, then known by her married name,
Manuela Karkiewicz, Maturino Resendez did not ask any questions
that would help in his defense. Instead, he dwelled on family
secrets and how his sister, whom he called the ``perfect
Christian,'' was kept in the dark.
</P>
<P>
   ``But many of the truths were being hidden (about) the
defendant, isn't that true?'' Maturino Resendez asked.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah,'' his sister answered.
</P>
<P>
   ``Many things you (have) not been told about the defendant?'' he
asked.
</P>
<P>
   ``Uh-huh.''
</P>
<P>
   The family secrets centered on how the identity of Maturino
Resendez's father was hidden from other siblings. He had a
different father than the others.
</P>
<P>
   Maturino said she had asked her grandmother and mother about her
half-brother's father, but was never told.
</P>
<P>
   Maturino Resendez ended with rambling questions about how he was
trusted with family secrets while his siblings were left in the
dark.
</P>
<P>
   In his closing arguments, he praised and apologized to his
sister for having to endure the embarrassment of testifying at her
brother's trial.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's only one witness that I feel bad about ... Manuela
Karkiewicz,'' he said, adding that it was ``a situation that she
was not even supposed to be put in'' and that she ``didn't deserve
to be here.''
</P>
<P>
   ``(She is) married to a good man,'' Maturino Resendez continued.
``He works Sunday, and that's not allowed. A very good lady, she
doesn't ask questions. She does what she is supposed to do to be a
good homemaker. She has trained to be what I consider to be a
perfect lady, a perfect woman.
</P>
<P>
   ``I never was told that I was supposed to try to hurt somebody,
especially like Manuela Karkiewicz. I was supposed to protect her.
If I had to, I was supposed to lie to her.''
</P>
<P>
   Maturino Resendez was convicted and sentenced to 30 months in
prison.
</P>
<P>
   Sounding a theme she would repeat 10 years later, Manuela
Maturino also said at the 1989 trial that she barely knew her
half-brother.
</P>
<P>
   She testified that she first met him when he came to live with
the family in Rodeo, in Mexico's Durango state, when he was about
15. She said her half-brother had been reared before that in the
state of Puebla by an aunt and uncle.
</P>
<P>
   She said Maturino Resendez stayed with the family for less than
a year, then left on his own, and she did not see him again for 10
or 12 years. Four years before the St. Louis trial, she saw him in
El Reno, Okla., where he was serving an 18-month sentence for
immigration violations.
</P>
<P>
   ``They did not see each other very regularly as adults, I
think,'' said Carter, the ranger who befriended Maturino. ``There's
no doubt that they loved one another and cared for one another, but
the frequency of their visits was very minimal.''
</P>
<P>
   Robinson has known Maturino since she joined the Hope Chapel
Foursquare Gospel Church, a Pentecostal congregation, seven years
ago.
</P>
<P>
   Robinson said Maturino, who was divorced from her husband last
year, showed up at his home one day in mid-June. She told him
authorities had contacted her, looking for her half-brother.
Robinson and his wife, Jeanne, prayed with her. He agreed to sit in
on meetings between Maturino and officials from the FBI, U.S.
Marshals Service and the Texas Rangers.
</P>
<P>
   Last Sunday, Maturino received a phone call from her brother,
Florentino Maturino, a minister who lives near Ciudad Juarez,
Mexico. He told her that their brother, Angel, tired of hiding, had
phoned him for help. Maturino then contacted Carter. The ranger cut
short a fishing trip in the Gulf of Mexico and headed to
Albuquerque.
</P>
<P>
   ``She really didn't know where Angel was, or whether he would
actually turn himself in,'' Robinson said. ``It was very important
to the family that Angel make the decision himself. They didn't
turn him in, but they encouraged him to do the right thing.''
</P>
<P>
   The pastor met Maturino at her home Sunday evening. Carter, an
FBI agent and a U.S. marshal arrived a short time later.
</P>
<P>
   ``There were several phone calls back and forth between Manuela
and Florentino on Sunday night and on Monday,'' Robinson said. ``By
10:30 Monday night, I went home and went to bed. My wife woke me up
at 12:30, saying I should get up and get dressed. I was going to El
Paso.''
</P>
<P>
   On the three-hour drive, Maturino slept off and on as the pastor
and the lawmen kept each other awake, speaking of everything but
the purpose of their overnight ride.
</P>
<P>
   ``We talked about how bright the stars were, and the marshal
said he had hoped to see the mountains, but it was still too
dark,'' Robinson said. ``It was Drew Carter's birthday, so we
talked about that. We talked about our families.''
</P>
<P>
   When they arrived in El Paso and checked into a motel, Robinson
slept for a few hours as Maturino made several more calls to her
brother in Mexico. By dawn, the group was on its way to the bridge,
still not sure what would happen.
</P>
<P>
   ``No one was really sure he was actually going to make it
across,'' Robinson said. ``Manuela was on the phone, and I did what
my job was: I went into a corner out of the way and I prayed.''
</P>
<P>
   From a building at the port of entry about 30 feet away,
Robinson watched as Florentino Maturino drove up with his
half-brother, who opened the passenger door and walked toward the
ranger about 10 a.m. Houston time. Carter offered the accused
killer his hand.
</P>
<P>
   ``He accepted it. There were a few words of conversation, and
then Angel turned and let Carter put the handcuffs on him,''
Robinson said. ``It was very calm, very peaceful. No one around
knew what was going on.''
</P>
<P>
   As promised, the suspect's Mexican family _ two brothers and two
sisters _ crossed the border behind him. The lawmen stepped back so
they and Manuela Maturino could approach Maturino Resendez.
</P>
<P>
   ``They hugged him. They cried,'' Robinson said. ``He's accused
of some horrible things, but he's family. He's their brother.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
