<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-17 20:05 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4042 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KENNEDY-CAMELOT18-COX     07-17 0819
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KENNEDY-CAMELOT18-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    By Scott Eyman
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla _ He seemed normal.
</P>
<P>
   God knows, there was no reason he should be, born famous and
then ascending to legend by saluting his father's coffin on the day
he turned 3 years old.
</P>
<P>
   John Fitzgerald Kennedy Jr. combined the best of his father _
the charm, the smile, the ease with people _ with the best of his
mother: the bedrock sense of self, the chiseled, perfect looks that
had more than a touch of Black Jack Bouvier in them, and the
essential reserve that makes a man a mystery _ usually catnip to
women, and always, always to the media.
</P>
<P>
   He bore the burden of a horribly intrusive name, of expectations
that no one could live up to, with a shrug and a shy smile.
</P>
<P>
   There was always a sense of anticipation with JFK Jr. He carried
himself like a young prince, and we took him at that valuation.
Occasionally, he'd even play with those anticipations by stepping
gingerly into the public arena _ delivering a strong speech to the
Democratic convention in 1988.
</P>
<P>
   He was his mother's son in so many ways, for he had her way of
getting on and leading his life.
</P>
<P>
   After her marriage to Aristotle Onassis, Jackie set herself and
her children up in New York and stayed there for the rest of her
life. She stressed responsibility and impeccable manners; she
picked her children up from school every day, and her example took
hold.
</P>
<P>
   She trained Caroline and John Jr. to face real life and the real
world. Once, when John Jr. was mugged in Central Park, his mother
told bodyguards she thought it would be good for him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was really able to lead a normal life from about the age of
5,'' he said in 1997. Asked whether his mother had taught him about
handling fame, John Jr. said: ``We didn't actually sit down and
have a tutorial session. But you pick things up.''
</P>
<P>
   Through John Jr.'s days at college and law school and a
start-and-stop career as a lawyer, the media cheapened themselves,
but they never cheapened him; his aloofness shamed the jokers who
tailed him.
</P>
<P>
   That aloofness was not a pose. He was friendly with his cousins,
but also competitive with them, about doing worthwhile and
interesting things. His (gratuitous) reference to his late cousin
Michael's sexual goings-on in the pages of George was at least as
much about Michael's failure to justify his privileged life as it
was about sex.
</P>
<P>
   He chose to be representative of the best aspects of his family,
not the worst.
</P>
<P>
   ``One day, his mother realized that she was going to use all the
publicity,'' says Laurence Leamer, author of The Kennedy Women and
a forthcoming volume on the Kennedy Men. ``The auction of her
effects was her joke; all those years she'd been exploited, and
this was her chance to exploit. And her son knew that.
</P>
<P>
   ``So if he was going to be named The Sexiest Man Alive by People
magazine and be dogged every time he set foot outside his house, he
had to figure out a way to use it to his own advantage. And he
finally figured it out: George.''
</P>
<P>
   It was politics, yes, but John Jr. could be part of the game
while at the same time being above the game. Anybody else with his
background wanting to start a magazine requiring millions of
dollars would have been shown the door. But because of who he was,
John Jr. got his money and his magazine.
</P>
<P>
   That he was so incredibly normal came to be the most abnormal
thing about him. He shopped at thrift shops in Palm Beach as well
as tony stores along Fifth Avenue. When he flunked the New York bar
for the second time, he told reporters, ``Clearly, I'm not a major
legal genius.'' He took the subway to work.
</P>
<P>
   He may have been born into the closest thing America has ever
had to a Royal Family, but he had the lucky gift of having no
illusions. His friends weren't politicians _ friendship is a luxury
for such creatures of expedience _ and they didn't talk to the
media.
</P>
<P>
   John Jr. had moved smoothly through his first act, had
established the premise for the second act. But now the play _ and
the audience _ is left without the third act we'd been expecting.
</P>
<P>
   There was a saying among the early 20th-century aristocracy, a
means of explaining their often-compulsive philanthropies: To those
whom much is given, much is expected. It was a mantra for the
Kennedys, encompassing their public crusades and private ambitions.
</P>
<P>
   But there is an unspoken codicil to that mantra, and surveying
the vast amount of destroyed and damaged lives that litter the
family history, beginning with Joseph Kennedy Jr. and extending
through sisters Kathleen and Rosemary, brothers John and Robert,
Robert's sons, and now John F. Kennedy Jr., it needs to be read
slightly differently: To those whom much is given, much is
expected, and much is demanded.
</P>
<P>
   Too much.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
