<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-17 20:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4044 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NASA-CHANDRA-HNS &LR;      07-17 1579
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NASA-CHANDRA-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMMANDING PRESENCE: STELLAR ACHIEVEMENTS LAND COLLINS LEADING
ROLE 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By MARK CARREAU 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   If it was only a matter of time before a woman assumed command
of an American space mission, then it was likely a foregone
conclusion that the job would go to astronaut Eileen Collins.
</P>
<P>
   Driven by a lifelong love of flying, the 42-year-old Air Force
colonel and test pilot spent the last 20 years overcoming a series
of obstacles and professional challenges to position herself for a
spot in aviation history.
</P>
<P>
   Monday, on the eve of the 30th anniversary of man's first walk
on the moon, Collins will scramble aboard the space shuttle
Columbia to set a milestone of her own and prepare her crew to
blast off from the Kennedy Space Center in Florida with NASA's
Chandra X-ray Observatory.
</P>
<P>
   With the exception of Russian cosmonaut Valentina Tereshkova's
71-hour solo voyage in a small Vostok capsule in 1963, no woman has
ever claimed dominion over a spacecraft. None has ever assumed
command responsibility for the safety of an entire crew of space
travelers, nor for the success of a mission as complex as
Columbia's.
</P>
<P>
   Collins' crew will deploy the $1.55 billion Chandra X-ray
Observatory, a large space telescope designed for the study of
stellar explosions, galactic collisions and black holes. Together
with its propulsion system, the Chandra observatory is the largest
payload ever delivered to space by a shuttle.
</P>
<P>
   Also, as chief pilot, Collins is responsible for Columbia's
orbital maneuvers and, most importantly, for manually flying the
ship's final approach and landing. As on all missions, Columbia's
high velocity ascent and re-entry are flown by software commands
stored in the cockpit flight computers.
</P>
<P>
   Coming nearly four decades after the first Russian and American
spaceflights, the role of commander has, in Collins' estimation,
been denied women far too long _ particularly in a culture that has
for many years embraced women as U.S. Supreme Court justices, as
leading politicians, as heart surgeons, as college presidents and
as captains of industry.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wish it could have happened before,'' laments Collins, who
is careful to note that she is simply building on the
accomplishments of women who preceded her in the cockpit _ pilots
in World War II who flew transport, not combat, missions because of
their gender, and the scrappy candidates who vied unsuccessfully
two decades later to become Mercury astronauts.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't come here because I wanted to be the first in any
position,'' insists Collins, a willowy combination of grace and
grit, molded more by her blue-collar upbringing in small town
Elmira, N.Y., than feminine stridency. ``But if it's happening now,
and I'm the one that will be flying as the first woman commander,
then I really consider it an honor.''
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, it seems it was an inevitability for which both
NASA and Collins have prepared themselves ever since the young Air
Force officer applied to become an astronaut in 1989.
</P>
<P>
   ``We knew that potentially she would be the first woman to
command a space shuttle, and we had that in mind when she was
selected,'' said Steve Hawley, who at the time was deputy chief of
NASA's astronaut corps and a member of the agency's astronaut
selection committee. Ironically, Hawley will fly with Collins as
Columbia's flight engineer.
</P>
<P>
   Under public pressure to diversify its all-male, predominantly
military fighter pilot Apollo-era astronaut corps, the space agency
selected a half-dozen medical doctors, scientists and engineers as
the first American woman astronauts in 1978. But by 1989, it had
yet to select a woman with the credentials to pilot and perhaps
command a spacecraft.
</P>
<P>
   Collins blames the shortcoming on a now redundant military
policy that denied women the opportunities to fly high-performance
combat aircraft. It was an obstacle that Collins had to overcome,
and when she did, the young pilot proved too attractive an
astronaut candidate for NASA to pass up.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of the things we look for when we interview applicants is
whether this person is someone we would like to represent NASA,
someone we want the world to think of when they think of the space
program,'' said Hawley. ``Another thing we look for is whether this
is somebody who is in it for what he or she can get out of it
personally, or just somebody who wants to contribute to the success
of the program.
</P>
<P>
   ``Clearly, she is not in this for herself. In all of these
things she impressed all of us. She ended up ranking very high, not
just among women applicants, but in terms of all the pilot
applicants.''
</P>
<P>
   With only modest fanfare, Collins arrived at the Johnson Space
Center to begin her astronaut training in 1990.
</P>
<P>
   Like most astronauts, Collins developed a love for flying in her
youth and an interest in spaceflight as her education exposed her
to math and the sciences.
</P>
<P>
   ``I always knew I wanted to fly,'' she said in a 1994 profile.
``I think it was something I was born with.''
</P>
<P>
   The infatuation was nurtured by visits to the National Soaring
Museum near her hometown. Her father, a surveyor, often took his
four children there to watch gliders ride the thermals.
</P>
<P>
   Pursuing her interest would prove difficult. Her parents, James
and Rose Marie Collins, separated and for a time, the Collinses
relied on public housing and food stamps to make ends meet.
</P>
<P>
   Higher education was something she would have to earn herself.
At 17, Collins had saved enough from a retail sales job to begin
private flying lessons. She studied math, first, at a New York
community college.
</P>
<P>
   At Syracuse University, she joined the Air Force Reserve
Officers' Training Corps and earned a degree in math, the
qualifications she needed to begin military pilot training.
</P>
<P>
   Trained by 1979, she was denied by the Air Force, along with its
other women pilots, the opportunity to fly combat jets. Collins was
forced to scrape together the high-performance aircraft hours that
would make her eligible to become a shuttle pilot. Because of
military restrictions on women flying fighters, she had to log her
high-performance hours by instructing other Air Force pilots in the
T-38, a nimble, two-engine jet trainer used by the military to
teach its aviators the basics of supersonic flight.
</P>
<P>
   Later, Collins moved to the much larger C-141, a four-engine,
military jet transport. Based in California, she attained the hours
to earn an aircraft command, and even flirt with combat as she led
a rescue flight to Grenada as part of Operation Urgent Fury in
1983.
</P>
<P>
   She enriched her education with graduate degrees from Stanford
University in operations research, and from Webster University in
space systems management. She also did a stint as a professor of
mathematics at the U.S. Air Force Academy.
</P>
<P>
   There would be one more stop on her way to NASA _ the Air Force
Test Pilot School at Edwards Air Force Base, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   Shuttle commanders are selected from a larger pool of pilot
astronauts. Typically, pilot astronauts fly twice, and sometimes
three times, functioning essentially as co-pilots to a more
seasoned commander before they are eligible for promotion.
</P>
<P>
   Collins served her apprenticeship ably in 1995 as the first
woman shuttle pilot, repeating the experience in 1997. The
missions, to Russia's Mir space station, featured delicate orbital
rendezvous maneuvers, satellite retrieval operations as well as
spacewalks by other crew members.
</P>
<P>
   In between, Collins and her husband, Pat Youngs, a Delta Air
Lines pilot and former Air Force officer, had their first child,
Bridget, now 3.
</P>
<P>
   Collins credits a supportive husband and a talented nanny with
making it possible to juggle a demanding job with the needs of a
young family. She also credits Rhea Seddon, Kathy Thornton and
other women astronauts who interrupted their careers to have
children with making it possible for her to do so.
</P>
<P>
   ``Eileen is just a tremendous person to work for,'' said Jeff
Ashby, the 45-year-old naval aviator who will serve as Collin's
co-pilot. ``She started from very humble beginnings and worked her
way up. For that I respect her tremendously. She's earned the title
of commander of the space shuttle. It's not been given to her.''
</P>
<P>
   Collins' command will bring something extra that not all of her
male counterparts have to contend with _ the public spotlight. She
was summoned to the White House in March 1998 so first lady Hillary
Rodham Clinton could announce the promotion. NASA would normally
handle announcement of a commander with a brief press release.
</P>
<P>
   Collins joined the first lady and President Clinton again last
October at the Kennedy Space Center for the launch of the shuttle
carrying aging Mercury astronaut John Glenn.
</P>
<P>
   She accepts the added attention, without embracing it, hopeful
it will help to spare those who follow her. Waiting in the wings
are Navy Lt. Cdr. Susan Still Kilrain, 37, who has also flown twice
as the shuttle's co-pilot, and Air Force Lt. Col. Pam Melroy, 37,
who is slated to fly as co-pilot for the first time early next
year.
</P>
<P>
   ``NASA is very serious about giving Americans opportunities to
fly in space,'' said Collins. ``But to become an astronaut, you
can't just walk into the job. You have to prepare yourself. You
have to study. You have to have the right technical background.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
