   ATTENTION EDITORS: The following photos are part of tonight's
New York Times Photo Package, moving Saturday, 07/17/99. Photo
clients will automatically receive these photos via AP's
PhotoExpress or may download them from either the Wieck Photo
Database in Dallas at 972-392-0888 or from NYTPhotos on Newscom at
305-448-8411. Non-clients can make individual purchases by calling
(888) 603-1036 or 212-556-4204.
</P>
<P>
   (NYT20) BIRMINGHAM, Ala. -- July 17, 1999 -- ALA-MAYOR-RETIRE,
7-17 -- After 20 years, Mayor Richard Arrington Jr. of Birmingham,
Ala., has resigned, having helped the city become placid and
prosperous. When Arrington took office in 1979 as the city's first
black mayor, Birmingham was still struggling to shed its national
reputation as ``Bombingham,'' the city where racial divisions
became explosive in the 1960s and where any police shooting
threatened to turn into a confrontation. (Alan S. Weiner/New York
Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT19) NEW YORK -- July 17, 1999 -- NY-SUMMER-SCHOOL, 7-17 --
Tommy Carmona, 9, left, and Colin Bunbury, 8, at summer school in
Brooklyn. Lessons are tightly structured. This year, in the most
ambitious and structured mandatory program since the 1980s, 58,000
third-, sixth- and eighth-graders are back in class for extra
reading and writing, and to a lesser extent mathematics, to prepare
them for the promotion test in early August. Mandatory summer
school is expected to grow much larger next year. (Librado
Romero/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT18) KAYENTA, Ariz. -- July 17, 1999 -- NAVAJO-MINE-DISPUTE,
7-17 -- Kelsey A. Begaye, president of the Navajo Nation, says the
tribe was unaware of efforts by the Peabody Coal Co. to influence
the government. A Navajo lawsuit, like several other actions
brought by tribes in recent years, alleges that the Interior
Department and the Bureau of Indian Affairs failed to fulfill their
unique mandate -- to act as trustees working to get tribes the best
possible return on valuable assets like natural resources and land
leases. (Cary Herz/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT17) HYANNISPORT, Mass. -- July 17, 1999 --
KENNEDY-MISSING-PLANE-12, 7-17 -- Terri Wirtz of Epson, New
Hampshire reacts to hearing the news that the small plane carrying
John F. Kennedy Jr., his wife, Carolyn Bessette Kennedy, and her
sister was reported missing. Searchers swept the waters off
Martha's Vineyard, pressing a desperate hunt for those aboard the
plane. A piece of luggage from the plane was found off a Vineyard
beach. (Rick McKay/Cox News Servie Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT16) HYANNISPORT, Mass. -- July 17, 1999 --
KENNEDY-MISSING-PLANE-11, 7-17 -- Members of the news media gather
outside the Kennedy compound in Hyannisport on Saturday after news
of the small plane carrying John F. Kennedy Jr., his wife, Carolyn
Bessette Kennedy, and her sister was reported missing. Searchers
swept the waters off Martha's Vineyard, pressing a desperate hunt
for those aboard the plane. A piece of luggage from the plane was
found off a Vineyard beach. (Rick McKay/Cox News Servie Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT15) NEW YORK -- July 17, 1999 -- KENNEDY-MISSING-PLANE-10,
07-17 -- Michael Berman, George magazine's executive publisher,
left, and John F. Kennedy Jr., the magazine's editor-in-chief, in a
January 1996 file photo. Searchers swept the waters off Martha's
Vineyard on Saturday, pressing a desperate hunt for John F. Kennedy
Jr., his wife and her sister, whose plane had vanished in the
night. A piece of luggage from the plane was found off a Vineyard
beach. (James Estrin/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT14) (NYT14) DJAKOVICA, Yugoslavia -- July 17, 1999 --
KOSOVO-DEATH-TOLL, 7-17 -- Markers, some without names, on graves
near Djakovica. In the chaotic events in Kosovo, bodies are being
buried often without full documentation. At least 10,000 people
were slaughtered by Serbian forces during their three-month
campaign to drive the Albanians from Kosovo, according to war
crimes investigators, NATO peacekeeping troops and humanitarian
agencies. (Stephen Crowley/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT13) YEKATERINBURG, Russia _ July 17, 1999
--RUSSIA-CHURCH-SCHISM-2, 7-17 -- At the monastery of St. Nicholas
in Verkhoturye, where clergymen have protested the actions of the
local Bishop, a family receives a blessing. Short of priests,
strapped for money and facing an overwhelmingly secular society,
the Russian Orthodox Church is already involved in a difficult
struggle to establish itself as a moral voice in post-communist
Russia and attract a new generation of believers. (Jacqueline Mia
Foster/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT12) ALAPAYEVSK, Russia _ July 17, 1999 --
RUSSIA-CHURCH-SCHISM-1, 7-17 -- Visitors to a Russian Orthodox
church in Alapayevsk, which stayed open even in Soviet times, are
mostly elderly. Short of priests, strapped for money and facing an
overwhelmingly secular society, the Russian Orthodox Church is
already involved in a difficult struggle to establish itself as a
moral voice in post-communist Russia and attract a new generation
of believers. (Jacqueline Mia Foster/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT11) MOKHRA, India -- July 17, 1999 -- INDIA-TV-WAR-2, 7-17
-- Television cameras record the funeral ceremony of Indian soldier
Suresh Kumar, as Kumar's father, Mir Singh, gives his son a final
salute. When he died in the fighting with Pakistan over Kashmir,
Suresh Kumar became the first Indian soldier from Mokhra to be
killed in war since India gained independence in 1947. Television
has rallied people from all over India behind the war. (Celia W.
Dugger/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT10) MOKHRA, India -- July 17, 1999 -- INDIA-TV-WAR-1, 7-17
-- A crowd outside the house of Indian soldier Suresh Kumar,
attempts to see his body before cremation. When he died, Kumar
became the first Indian soldier from Mokhra to be killed in war
since India gained independence in 1947. The people of this north
Indian town, have vicariously experienced India's small undeclared
war over Kashmir by watching television and they wanted to share
their part in the drama with the rest of the nation, even as the
fighting draws to a close. (Celia W. Dugger/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT9) MARTHA'S VINEYARD, Mass. -- July 17, 1999 --
KENNEDY-MISSING-PLANE-9, 07-17 -- An aerial view of people walking
along the beach in Gay's Head, the area on the island where debris
from John F. Kennedy, Jr.'s aircraft was reportedly found on
Saturday. A small plane carrying Kennedy Jr., his wife Carolyn
Bessette Kennedy, and her sister Lauren Bessette, disappeared late
Friday. By Saturday afternoon authorities said they had recovered
debris which may have come from the aircraft. (Andrea Mohin/New
York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT8) MARTHA'S VINEYARD, Mass. -- July 17, 1999 --
KENNEDY-MISSING-PLANE-8, 07-17 -- An aerial view of Martha's
Vineyard airport on Saturday where the missing plane belonging to
John F. Kennedy, Jr. was to land Friday night. A small plane
carrying Kennedy Jr., his wife Carolyn Bessette Kennedy, and her
sister Lauren Bessette, disappeared late Friday just south of the
island. By Saturday afternoon, authorities had recovered debris off
Martha's Vineyard that they said may have come from the aircraft.
(Andrea Mohin/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT7) NEW YORK -- July 17, 1999 -- KENNEDY-MISSING-PLANE-7,
07-17 -- A police officer stands next to the entrance to the
apartment building where John F. Kennedy, Jr. and his wife Carolyn
Bessette lived in New York on Saturday. Though a search and rescue
operation was continuing in the hopes of finding survivors, John F.
Kennedy Jr., his wife and and her sister were still missing on
Saturday after their private plane vanished off the North Atlantic
seaboard Friday night while they were on their way to a family
wedding in Massachusetts. A passerby had left flowers at the
building's entrance. (Nicole Bengiveno/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT6) FAIRFIELD, N.J. -- July 17, 1999
--KENNEDY-MISSING-PLANE-6, 07-17 --Kyle Bailey, 25, of Cedar Grove,
N.J., talks with reporters at Essex County Airport, also known as
Caldwell, about seeing John F. Kennedy Jr., and his wife Carolyn
Bessette at this small airport before their flight to Martha's
Vineyard on Friday. A small plane carrying Kennedy Jr., his wife
Carolyn Bessette Kennedy, and her sister Lauren Bessette,
disappeared late Friday. By Saturday afternoon authorities had
recovered debris off Martha's Vineyard that they said may have come
from the aircraft. (Norman Y. Lono/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT5) FAIRFIELD, N.J. -- July 17, 1999
--KENNEDY-MISSING-PLANE-5, 07-17 -- The Airbound Hangar on Saturday
at Essex County Airport, also known as Caldwell, where John F.
Kennedy, Jr., kept his aircraft. A small plane carrying Kennedy
Jr., his wife Carolyn Bessette Kennedy, and her sister Lauren
Bessette, disappeared late Friday. By Saturday afternoon
authorities had recovered debris off Martha's Vineyard that they
said may have come from the aircraft. (Norman Y. Lono/New York
Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT4) MARTHA'S VINEYARD, Mass. -- July 17, 1999 --
KENNEDY-MISSING-PLANE-4, 07-17 -- An aerial view of Gay's Head, the
area on the island where debris from John F. Kennedy, Jr.'s
aircraft was reportedly found on Saturday. A small plane carrying
Kennedy Jr., his wife Carolyn Bessette Kennedy, and her sister
Lauren Bessette, disappeared late Friday. By Saturday afternoon
authorities had recovered debris off Martha's Vineyard that they
said may have come from the aircraft. (Andrea Mohin/New York Times
Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT3) OFF MARTHA'S VINEYARD, Mass. -- July 17, 1999 --
KENNEDY-MISSING-PLANE-3, 07-17 -- A Coast Guard boat, part of the
search and rescue operation looking for John F. Kennedy, Jr.'s
plane off the southwestern coast off of Martha's Vineyard, Mass.,
on Saturday. A small plane carrying Kennedy Jr., his wife Carolyn
Bessette Kennedy, and her sister Lauren Bessette, disappeared late
Friday. By Saturday afternoon authorities had recovered debris off
Martha's Vineyard that they said may have come from the aircraft.
(Andrea Mohin/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT2) WASHINGTON -- July 17, 1999 -- KENNEDY-MISSING-PLANE-2,
07-17 --Deputy Assistant Secretary of Defense for Public Affairs
Rear Adm. Craig Quigley, calls on reporters at the Pentagon during
a news conference about the search for John F. Kennedy, Jr.'s
aircraft on Saturday. A small plane carrying Kennedy Jr., his wife
Carolyn Bessette Kennedy, and her sister, Lauren Bessette,
disappeared late Friday, and by Saturday afternoon, the authorities
had recovered debris off Martha's Vineyard, Mass., that they said
may have come from the plane. (Justin Lane/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT1) NEW YORK -- July 17, 1999 -- KENNEDY-MISSING-PLANE, 7-17
-- John F. Kennedy Jr., with his staff at George magazine. A small
plane carrying John F. Kennedy Jr., his wife, Carolyn Bessette
Kennedy, and her sister was reported missing on Friday, and a huge
search was under way Saturday off Long Island, N.Y., and Cape Cod,
Mass. Kennedy had obtained his pilot's license in just the past
year and acquired the aircraft recently. (Monica Almeida/New York
Times Photo)
</P>
