<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-17 20:14 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4046 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-BASECOL-COLUMN-LA     07-17 0745
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-BASECOL-COLUMN-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THESE DODGERS MORE WOEFUL THAN '92 EDITION
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MATT McHALE  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Remember back in 1992 when the Dodgers lost 99 games and you
didn't think it could get any worse?
</P>
<P>
   Well, 1992 was a golden age for the Dodgers compared to now.
</P>
<P>
   Back then, Mike Piazza and Raul Mondesi were in the minor-league
pipeline ready to win back-to-back Rookie of the Year awards. So
were Ismael Valdes and Todd Hollandsworth.
</P>
<P>
   Now, they have no farm system. If they did, they wouldn't be
baseball's only team with three players making $9 million or more.
And it is a rare night when Kevin Brown, Gary Sheffield or Mondesi
look like they are worth the money.
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers never won a playoff game with that bunch, but they
did win National League West titles in 1994 and '95. Given this
season and last, that doesn't seem so bad.
</P>
<P>
   Piazza lacked the leadership to move the Dodgers beyond the
first round, but since he was traded, the club hasn't even been
competitive. Sheffield and Brown are the leaders now. Two Saturdays
ago, they started a bonfire in the Dodger bullpen to purge demons
and still lost. Even though they have won six of seven, they are in
last place and no closer to first than they were July 1.
</P>
<P>
   If the season ended today, the Dodgers wouldn't even fare that
well in next June's amateur draft. In 1992, they picked second,
which was good enough for Darren Dreifort but sadly not good enough
to get Alex Rodriguez.
</P>
<P>
   Management seems just as inept. It has money to spend, but
spending it on pitcher Carlos Perez and center fielder Devon White
has been a dreadful mistake.
</P>
<P>
   Last winter, GM Kevin Malone and President Bob Graziano went to
the Dominican Republic to hire Felipe Alou as their manager and
only helped him leverage a better contract out of the Montreal
Expos.
</P>
<P>
   Graziano thought he held all the power when playing an Arizona
Indian tribe against Vero Beach, Fla., for the club's future
spring-training home. The club hired a lobbyist to make sure the
state of Florida approved government dollars to improve Dodgertown.
It didn't work. Then the Indian tribe said it needed the Dodgers to
kick in some money. Instead of holding two states hostage as is
customary in these matters, the Dodgers wound up looking weak and
vulnerable.
</P>
<P>
   Both cases must have come out of the new book, ``The Dodger Way
to Play Baseball _ the Lost Chapters.''
</P>
<P>
   Two weeks ago, Fox hired former NBA marketing whiz Rick Welts to
oversee the operation _ ahead of Graziano _ but they have made
plenty of mistakes of their own. They had the right to trade Piazza
but not on some Steinbrenner-esque whim by Chase Carey that has
brought nothing in return.
</P>
<P>
   Signing Brown was fine, but they were negotiating against
themselves when they added a seventh year, threw in six flights
home and a $100,000 bonus for making the All-Star team.
</P>
<P>
   Vin Scully, whose broadcasts have become increasingly critical,
said on air a few weeks back, ``You'd think with all the millions
the players make, they'd pay the teams bonuses if they didn't make
the All-Star team. Just a thought.''
</P>
<P>
   Living through 1992 was not pleasant. Before the season, general
manager Fred Claire traded Tim Belcher and John Wetteland for Eric
Davis. Claire wanted to team Davis with childhood buddy Darryl
Strawberry and Brett Butler to form what he thought would be one of
the greatest Dodgers outfields of all time.
</P>
<P>
   Strawberry ruptured a disc in his back in May and was never the
same. Davis arrived hurt and continued to get injured. He needed
three operations, three teams and four years to turn his career
around.
</P>
<P>
   It also was during that summer that the Dodgers played a series
of doubleheaders against Montreal because of games lost to the
riots in South Central L.A. During those games, Delino DeShields
played so brilliantly for the Expos that Claire saw him as the heir
to Butler's spot at the time of the order.
</P>
<P>
   He traded an underachieving, oft-injured right-hander named
Pedro Martinez to get DeShields.
</P>
<P>
   Toward the end of the season, there were rumors that manager Tom
Lasorda was headed to Tampa Bay to manage the Devil Rays before
turning the job over to Bobby Valentine and becoming GM. But unlike
the 1970s, when reports of Lasorda leaving was big news, no one
seemed to care this time.
</P>
<P>
   Who would have thought the worst was yet to come.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
