<P>
   ATTENTION EDITORS: The following photos are part of tonight's
New York Times Photo Package, moving Saturday, 07/17/99. Photo
clients will automatically receive these photos via AP's
PhotoExpress or may download them from either the Wieck Photo
Database in Dallas at 972-392-0888 or from NYTPhotos on Newscom at
305-448-8411. Non-clients can make individual purchases by calling
(888) 603-1036 or 212-556-4204.
</P>
<P>
   (NYT20) BIRMINGHAM, Ala. -- July 17, 1999 -- ALA-MAYOR-RETIRE,
7-17 -- After 20 years, Mayor Richard Arrington Jr. of Birmingham,
Ala., has resigned, having helped the city become placid and
prosperous. When Arrington took office in 1979 as the city's first
black mayor, Birmingham was still struggling to shed its national
reputation as ``Bombingham,'' the city where racial divisions
became explosive in the 1960s and where any police shooting
threatened to turn into a confrontation. (Alan S. Weiner/New York
Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT19) NEW YORK -- July 17, 1999 -- NY-SUMMER-SCHOOL, 7-17 --
Tommy Carmona, 9, left, and Colin Bunbury, 8, at summer school in
Brooklyn. Lessons are tightly structured. This year, in the most
ambitious and structured mandatory program since the 1980s, 58,000
third-, sixth- and eighth-graders are back in class for extra
reading and writing, and to a lesser extent mathematics, to prepare
them for the promotion test in early August. Mandatory summer
school is expected to grow much larger next year. (Librado
Romero/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT18) KAYENTA, Ariz. -- July 17, 1999 -- NAVAJO-MINE-DISPUTE,
7-17 -- Kelsey A. Begaye, president of the Navajo Nation, says the
tribe was unaware of efforts by the Peabody Coal Co. to influence
the government. A Navajo lawsuit, like several other actions
brought by tribes in recent years, alleges that the Interior
Department and the Bureau of Indian Affairs failed to fulfill their
unique mandate -- to act as trustees working to get tribes the best
possible return on valuable assets like natural resources and land
leases. (Cary Herz/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT17) HYANNISPORT, Mass. -- July 17, 1999 --
KENNEDY-MISSING-PLANE-12, 7-17 -- Terri Wirtz of Epson, New
Hampshire reacts to hearing the news that the small plane carrying
John F. Kennedy Jr., his wife, Carolyn Bessette Kennedy, and her
sister was reported missing. Searchers swept the waters off
Martha's Vineyard, pressing a desperate hunt for those aboard the
plane. A piece of luggage from the plane was found off a Vineyard
beach. (Rick McKay/Cox News Servie Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT16) HYANNISPORT, Mass. -- July 17, 1999 --
KENNEDY-MISSING-PLANE-11, 7-17 -- Members of the news media gather
