<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-17 20:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4053 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KENNEDY-MASS-SCENE-AR     07-17 1026
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KENNEDY-MASS-SCENE-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SORROW INTRUDES ON JOYOUS DAY AS MISFORTUNE CONTINUES TO STALK
KENNEDY FAMILY 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV:  Photos  contributed by Cox News Service are being sent
to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers may make individual purchase
by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(Eds., this story contains material from previously-filed
KENNEDY-TRAGEDY) 
(See also: KENNEDY-MISSING-PLANE, KENNEDY-PILOT, KENNEDY-TRAGEDY,
KENNEDY-SEARCH, KENNEDY-NY-SCENE) 
 (HLW)  
 By FOX BUTTERFIELD   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   HYANNIS PORT, Mass. _ The big white tent was still set on the
lawn between the Kennedy family compound here and Nantucket Sound,
for the planned wedding reception Saturday afternoon for Rory
Kennedy, the youngest of the late Sen. Robert F. Kennedy's
children.
</P>
<P>
   But there were no Kennedys in sight, and the wedding was
postponed. The hazy summer day lengthened, and joy turned into
sorrow once again for the Kennedy clan, as word came that a small
plane carrying John F. Kennedy Jr., his wife, Carolyn Bessette
Kennedy, and her sister, Lauren Bessette, had apparently crashed
into the ocean on Friday night while approaching nearby Martha's
Vineyard.
</P>
<P>
   As has happened so often in the past _ when President John F.
Kennedy was assassinated, when Senator Robert F. Kennedy was shot,
when Rory Kennedy's older brother, Michael, was killed last year in
a skiing accident _ the roads around the Kennedy compound were
closed by the police, leaving the family secluded inside and a
throng of reporters and camera crews outside.
</P>
<P>
   Word of the accident spread slowly in nearby Hyannis Saturday
morning, so that some of the 275 guests for the wedding came to the
John F. Kennedy Museum on Main Street unaware of what had happened.
They were viewing old photographs of a young John Jr. greeting his
father on an airport tarmac in 1963 when a museum official had to
tell them what happened.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were preparing to go to the wedding, some of them from
Ireland, and they were totally shocked when we told them what
happened,'' said Pearl Guba, the museum manager.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a good thing that John's mother, Jackie, died first, she
was so fond of her son,'' Ms. Guba said.
</P>
<P>
   Rebecca Pierce, the chairwoman of the museum, said that as the
day went on other people began arriving at the museum as a way to
commemorate John F. Kennedy Jr. ``We've seen that too many times
when people are drawn here when there is a Kennedy tragedy,'' she
said.
</P>
<P>
   Neighbors at the Kennedy compound, a cluster of white clapboard
cottages with green shutters set near the beach, said all of Sen.
Robert Kennedy's surviving children were inside the house of their
mother, Ethel, on Saturday: Kathleen Kennedy Townsend, the
lieutenant governor of Maryland; Joseph P. Kennedy III, the former
Massachusetts congressman; Robert F. Kennedy Jr.; Courtney Kennedy;
Kerry Kennedy; Christopher Kennedy; Max Kennedy and Douglas
Kennedy; along with Rory Kennedy, a film maker, who was scheduled
to be married to Mark Bailey, a fellow film maker.
</P>
<P>
   John F. Kennedy Jr.'s sister, Caroline Kennedy Schlossberg, was
not here, neighbors said.
</P>
<P>
   A Kennedy family spokesman described the family's mood as
``somber'' Saturday afternoon. ``There are a lot of children
running around,'' the spokesman, Brian O'Connor, said. ``That tends
to lighten the mood, but obviously there is a great deal of concern
today.''
</P>
<P>
   The family has gathered at the compound to mourn almost as often
as to celebrate.
</P>
<P>
   Two of John F. Kennedy Jr.,'s cousins, David and Michael, both
sons of Robert Kennedy, died young, the latter of a drug overdose
in 1984, as did four Kennedys of the preceding generation. Sen.
Edward M. Kennedy, 67, the youngest of the nine children of Joseph
P. and Rose Fitzgerald Kennedy, is the only familiar Kennedy face
to survive middle age.
</P>
<P>
   The nation and the world were shocked when President Kennedy was
murdered by Lee Harvey Oswald on Nov. 22, 1963.
</P>
<P>
   The nation was jolted again on June 6, 1968, when Robert Kennedy
was shot, just after claiming victory in the California
presidential primary in a year roiled by the war in Vietnam and
urban turmoil.
</P>
<P>
   But misfortune ran in the family long before then.
</P>
<P>
   Joseph P. Kennedy, Roosevelt's ambassador to Great Britain
before World War II, had envisioned his eldest son, Joe Jr., as the
nation's first Catholic president after his own hopes had faded.
Joe, a Navy pilot stationed in Great Britain in 1944, was killed on
a secret mission.
</P>
<P>
   Kathleen Kennedy, the fourth Kennedy child, was flying from
Paris to Cannes with her fiance, Lord Peter Fitzwilliam, when their
De Havilland crashed in severe weather, killing them both, on May
13, 1948.
</P>
<P>
   While Joseph Kennedy savored his son Jack's inauguration and the
first few months of the presidency, he suffered a debilitating
stroke in 1961. He lived until 1969. The family's matriarch, Rose,
died on Jan. 22, 1995.
</P>
<P>
   After the assassinations, came the disaster known simply as
Chappaquiddick, on the night of July 18, 1969, 30 years ago this
weekend.
</P>
<P>
   Edward Kennedy flew to Martha's Vineyard to sail his brother
Jack's boat in a regatta and to attend a party with several young
women who had been Robert's campaign aides. He left with one of
them, Mary Jo Kopechne. He testified later that he had been tired
and she was feeling ill and he was returning to their motels when
he drove off a bridge on Chappaquiddick Island and she drowned. The
episode shadowed his political career, although he remains a
leading Democratic senator.
</P>
<P>
   Edward Kennedy, talking with a reporter in Washington on Friday,
had been looking forward to Rory's wedding. He recalled that a year
ago he had brought all the family's generations together on Cape
Cod for an event that was neither a wedding nor a funeral but a
reunion.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had 105 Kennedys,'' Senator Kennedy said.
</P>
<P>
   John F. Kennedy Jr. observed in 1995 on ``Larry King Live'' that
he did not fear for his life. ``It's sort of like walking around
wondering if you are going to be struck by lightning. It's not
something you really keep in the forefront of your mind.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
