<SLUG> BC-ISRAEL-DISCOVERY-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WEST BANK EXCAVATION MAY REVEAL RELICS FROM ABRAHAM'S TIME 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By DEBORAH HORAN 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HEBRON, West Bank _ Archaeologists on a ``rescue dig'' believe
they have discovered the remains of structures dated to about the
time that biblical scholars say the patriarch Abraham was here.
</P>
<P>
   Jagged stone walls, some as high as 20 feet, and a maze of
primitive rooms and ramparts were uncovered during a routine
excavation to prepare for permanent housing for Israeli settlers
claiming the site.
</P>
<P>
   Israeli law requires what it calls ``rescue digs'' before
construction to prevent the accidental destruction of any precious
finds that may be hidden underground.
</P>
<P>
   Archaeologists said the artifacts reveal the city was inhabited
almost without interruption for nearly 3,000 years _ from the early
Bronze Age, or about 2500 B.C., to the early part of the Byzantine
Empire, roughly A.D. 500.
</P>
<P>
   The outer wall of the city dates to 1600 B.C., corresponding to
the time biblical experts calculate Abraham went to Hebron to buy
land for a burial place for his wife, Sarah. The excavation is less
than a mile from the site where both Jews and Muslims believe that
Sarah, Abraham and other biblical figures are buried.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the biblical city, the ancient site of Hebron,'' said
the lead archaeologist, Emanuel Eisenberg of the Israel Antiquities
Authority, which is sponsoring the rescue dig.
</P>
<P>
   ``And this,'' he said, pointing to the outer city wall, ``is
more or less the wall that Abraham could have seen when he dealt
with the ruler of this place to buy the burial ground for his
family, where the Tomb of the Patriarchs is today.''
</P>
<P>
   Archaeologists began digging last May _ ahead of plans by seven
Jewish families to build there _ because they suspected the site,
called Tel Rumeida, was built on top of ancient Hebron. The
settlers have been living in temporary housing in the area,
squeezed between Palestinians and military posts.
</P>
<P>
   Two of the settlers' mobile homes were hoisted on top of other
mobile homes to make way for the dig. The excavation slowly
uncovered exactly what the archaeologists suspected might be there
_ extraordinarily well-preserved fortification walls of an ancient
city with alleyways and the remains of small stone houses.
</P>
<P>
   Eisenberg said the oldest part of the excavation has been dated
to the time the Egyptians built the pyramids, or about 2500 B.C.
</P>
<P>
   The city's builders managed to drag huge stone blocks, some
weighing as much as 2 tons, to make thick walls, using only
primitive tools. Archaeologists found tools and weapons made out of
bronze and bone on site.
</P>
<P>
   Archaeologists dated another section of the ancient city to
about 1000 B.C., the time of the reign of King David, though no
evidence has yet been found to link this first Israelite king to
the site. According to the Bible, Hebron was King David's seat of
power before he moved the capital to Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
   But Eisenberg said he is holding out hope.``What we have here is
(the site of) the ancestors and descendents of his dynasty,'' said
Eisenberg. ``But we still hope to find something that could
identify him with the city.''
</P>
<P>
   Pottery shards and other finds show that this part of the city
was continuously inhabited until as late as 700 B.C., when King
Hezekiah ruled the ancient kingdom of Judah. Evidence also shows
that during this period the city was ravaged by fire.
</P>
<P>
   Charred rock and broken pottery still sit where the fire once
raged.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's nicely preserved,'' said Eisenberg. ``This in our eyes is
a beautiful picture of a destruction.''
</P>
<P>
   Then, though the Bible doesn't mention that Hebron was ever
destroyed, Eisenberg said evidence shows that for some reason
people stopped living here for nearly 500 years, until roughly 200
B.C.
</P>
<P>
   When people returned to the city, they used some of the old
stones to make new structures and left other buildings intact,
including a public grain silo from the time of the Israelite kings.
</P>
<P>
   In roughly A.D. 500, during the Byzantine Empire, the
inhabitants were making wine.
</P>
<P>
   The archaeologists uncovered what Eisenberg called a ``very
developed'' wine press made from stone and wood. And by this
period, much of the ancient city had been covered with dirt and
used to grow olives and grapes.
</P>
<P>
   In 1983, Israeli settlers moved mobile homes to the area, which
by then had become nothing more than an empty lot of dirt and weeds
tucked between sandstone houses belonging to Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
   With the Bible as their guide, settlers say they moved mobile
homes here because they believed it was the site of ancient Hebron.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, after a settler was killed by Palestinians,
then-Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu promised other settlers
permanent housing. It is not known yet whether Prime Minister Ehud
Barak's government will honor that pledge.
</P>
<P>
   With the discovery, construction of permanent housing for the
settlers has been put on hold. They say the find has strengthened
their conviction to stay.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is our heritage sitting right in front of our eyes, the
beginnings of Judaism and monotheism,'' said David Wilder, a
spokesman for the Hebron settlers.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're hoping that Barak will honor the agreement made by
Netanyahu to let us build,'' he said. ``What we'd like to do is
build above the area, so that people can see the finds below, but
we can still live in houses above.''
</P>
<P>
   Eisenberg said he hopes to see the ancient city protected, but
that the decision was not in his hands.
</P>
<P>
   ``In my opinion, the finds are important and worth
preservation,'' he said. ``But it's a political issue, and it's
very sensitive.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
