<SLUG> BC-FBC-MODESTI-COLUMN-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CSUN'S BRADLEY FIGHTS FOR FOOTBALL
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KEVIN MODESTI  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ The realist in me says Cal State Northridge
administrators just destroyed their football team.
</P>
<P>
   The bright young man in front of me says not so fast.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're still the team that everybody said has so much
potential,'' says Jaumal Bradley, the senior fullback and team
captain, with confidence and determination in his voice.
</P>
<P>
   He's standing outside Ron and Lisa Ponciano's house on a sunny
side street in Northridge, a house with a pickup and camper shell
in the driveway and a ``Love Lives Here'' sign in the kitchen. It's
a few hours after CSUN fired Ponciano on Friday, pronouncing the
second-year head coach guilty of recruiting violations that he
denies.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley has come to stand up for Ponciano, who is holding a
press conference to state as much of his side of the story as he
can with a lawsuit looming.
</P>
<P>
   ``I came down here to give him a handshake and a hug,'' Bradley
says.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley loves Ponciano, believes his forceful denials, thinks
the firing is the real crime.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a father figure to me,'' he says. ``This is more than
a football coach. This is a relative, a family member.''
</P>
<P>
   But something Ponciano tells the reporters rubs Bradley the
wrong way.
</P>
<P>
   The coach alludes to ``the general consensus'' that the latest
controversy will be the death of the sport on the San Fernando
Valley campus, and says the 1999 season could be ``a death march''
for the embittered players.
</P>
<P>
   No doubt some of Bradley's young teammates will agree and will
utter rash vows to transfer away.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley says he'll try to talk them out of it.
</P>
<P>
   There will be a dinner this weekend with Marcus Brady, the
sophomore quarterback who is the Big Sky Conference's rising star
and could cripple the team by leaving. There will be a players'
meeting Tuesday. At each, Bradley plans to sound a defiant message.
</P>
<P>
   He'll remind them how Ponciano taught the team to keep fighting,
that one reason the coach refused to resign his job is that he
wouldn't defy his own message.
</P>
<P>
   He'll remind them of the times they'd played angry and won, the
times they'd fought through distractions, the times the players'
spirit was all that held the red and black together.
</P>
<P>
   He'll remind them of last year's CSUN women's basketball team,
which lost its head coach to a drug-trafficking bust, yet earned
the university's first conference title and trip to the NCAA
tournament.
</P>
<P>
   ``For some people, adversity is a reason to quit,'' he says.
``For some, it's a reason to fight harder.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going to go out,'' he promises, ``and prove this team is
worthy of the support of the school and the community.''
</P>
<P>
   Bradley is a tough-looking 25-year-old with a tattoo on his left
biceps and a little silver football on a chain around his neck.
He's one of the few married men on the team.
</P>
<P>
   He's in college at 25 because he lost a few years to juvenile
misbehavior. He doesn't have time to skip a season and start fresh
at another school.
</P>
<P>
   Brady is one teammate who would have time. The quarterback who
passed for more than 2,000 yards in his freshman season was said to
be upset by Ponciano's firing, so emotional that friends urged him
to collect himself before submitting to interviews on the topic.
</P>
<P>
   ``Marcus is 18, 19. A young man might say something he
regrets,'' Bradley says. ``I'm going to tell him, `Think about
this. This is your career, this is your education, your livelihood,
your future.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Bradley believes Brady will listen to him.
</P>
<P>
   ``He wants to hear from me, from other (seniors) on the team,
that we're going to take charge.''
</P>
<P>
   Sounds as if Bradley just did.
</P>
<P>
   What happens next will depend on whether the administration
appoints the right assistant coach to Ponciano's job, keeping key
players happy, or goes with the wrong assistant or an outsider,
driving them away.
</P>
<P>
   What happens in the end will depend on whether the players take
the firing as a cue to abandon the funny little football program
with the box of splinters for a stadium, or dedicate themselves to
making this promising season a success in Ponciano's honor.
</P>
<P>
   If the young Matadors make the latest crisis a rallying cry,
they'll have given us a reason at long last to root for CSUN
football.
</P>
<P>
   Feeling sorry for themselves won't help.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley refuses to let his team feel sorry for itself.
</P>
<P>
   He's saving his pity for the team that will have to feel the
Matadors' anger in their Sept. 4 season opener in Northridge.
</P>
<P>
   ``I pity Western Oregon,'' Bradley says with the slightest hint
of a smile.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-17-99 2047EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990717.0238 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-17 20:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4063 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KENNEDY-PLANE-1STLEDE     07-17 1050
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KENNEDY-PLANE-1ST </SLUG>
 LEDE--2ND   TAKE-ART-BOS  
 BOSTON: ... to the day.  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   For nearly 10 hours, the search focused on a nearly
1,000-square-mile area between the two airports, though much of it
was focused around Montauk, Coast Guard officials said.
</P>
<P>
   Asked whether a rescue effort might have been more effective if
begun sooner, Air Force Lieutenant Colonel Steve Roark said: ``I
don't think so, because it was nighttime, and because of our
standard search procedures.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked how long the search would continue, Coast Guard commander
Mike Lapinski said: ``A lot of things come into play. The Coast
Guard is searching for survivors, and any indications there might
have been a chance of getting out and surviving and potentially
being in the water would lead them to continue. The more signs
there are, the longer we search.''
</P>
<P>
   Coast Guard Rear Admiral Richard Larrabee said Kennedy's
celebrity status had no bearing on the intensity of the search.
``Our efforts are consistent with the way we would search for
anyone who was lost,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Shortly before 1 p.m., the search shifted almost exclusively to
the waters off Martha's Vineyard when beachgoers found items linked
to Kennedy's plane.
</P>
<P>
   Erin McCarthy, 31, of Boston, was sitting on the beach with her
friends when she spotted something in the water. Thinking it might
be debris from the crash, her friend Damon Seligson, 30, a Boston
lawyer, swam out to get it.
</P>
<P>
   It was a black canvas bag packed with clothes, a bathing suit,
cosmetics, and a hair dryer. The bag had an ID tag with Lauren
Bessette's business cards from Morgan Stanley.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a terrible sinking feeling,'' said Seligson. ``I felt
my heart burst out of my chest. It was just terrible.''
</P>
<P>
   Gordon Campbell, 34, a private pilot from Greenwich, Conn., said
he saw the nose wheel and a part called a ``wheel pant'' from a
single-engine plane washed up on the beach. A short time later,
searchers turned up a headrest and part of a plane support called a
strut, said Coast Guard Lieutenant Craig Jaramillo.
</P>
<P>
   The plane Kennedy was flying was built in June 1995. He
purchased it used from Minir Hussain, a 39-year-old native of
Pakistan who runs a furniture factory in New Jersey. Hussain sold
it through a broker and said he believed Kennedy paid about
$300,000.
</P>
<P>
   Hussain said he was at the Essex County Airport on Friday night
and noticed the plane was out of its hangar. He said he immediately
became worried when he was told Kennedy was going to be flying on
his own.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a risky situation for him to be flying without an
instructor because he was not instrument-rated to fly on his own,''
Hussain said in a telephone interview. ``I know that John was a
very good pilot. Everyone knew that. But I immediately began to
worry because the conditions were not that good.''
</P>
<P>
   Hussain said he had just landed his own plane at the airport and
believed that the visibility was not ideal, around 6 miles. While
it was still clear enough to take off without instruments, he felt
that it was ``too risky'' for someone without instrument
certification to do so.
</P>
<P>
   An FAA source said Kennedy had completed just 46 hours of flight
time.
</P>
<P>
   A high-ranking federal transportation offical said the National
Transportation Safety Board had pulled the maintenance records of
the plane and found it to be well cared for.
</P>
<P>
   Apparently Kennedy did not fill his tanks prior to departure,
but fuel records obtained by the safety board indicate there were
at least 90 gallons on board, plenty of fuel for a single-engine
plane to make that trip. However, the plane has two fuel tanks, one
in each wing, and a pilot must remember to switch from one to the
other before fuel runs out.
</P>
<P>
   Noting the proximity of the wreckage to Jacqueline Onassis'
former Vineyard home, the official speculated that Kennedy may have
been ``buzzing'' the property that he and his sister now own and
was caught in a thermal updraft by the Gay Head cliffs.
</P>
<P>
   A thermal updraft would cause the plane to rise suddenly, and
the normal response of the pilot would be to push the yoke down to
lower the nose. Once the plane cleared the updraft, the plane could
suddenly dive. At low altitudes, such a move could be catastrophic.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't count the number of times I have seen low-time pilots,
with family or friends on board, showing off by buzzing their house
and get into trouble,'' the source said. ``It is a mistake many
low-time pilots make.''
</P>
<P>
   The plane itself was not considered particularly difficult to
control.
</P>
<P>
   ``The handling characteristics are very benign,'' said Warrent
Morningstar, director of media relations for the Aircraft Owners
and Pilots Association, a general aviation lobbying group. ``It is
not the sort of plane you would want to learn to fly in, but it
should not be a handful for a low-time pilot who had proper
training in the aircraft.''
</P>
<P>
   Phone calls began flooding into the Kennedy compound around 7
a.m. Saturday. President Clinton, who was spending the weekend at
Camp David, learned of the disappearance from his chief of staff,
John Podesta, and telephoned Senator Edward M. Kennedy and Andrew
Cuomo, the head of Housing and Urban Development, who is married to
Kerry Kennedy, a daughter of RFK.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton also called JFK Jr.'s sister, Caroline Kennedy
Schlossberg, who was reportedly on vacation out West. She was
expected to join the family.
</P>
<P>
   ``All our prayers and thoughts are with the families of those on
board,'' White House spokesman Joe Lockhart said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
   The plane's disappearance came one day before the 30th
anniversary of the day Edward Kennedy's car went off a dirt road at
Chappaquiddick, killing passenger Mary Jo Kopechne on the tiny
island adjacent to Martha's Vineyard.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview in May 1998, three weeks after he received his
pilot's license, Kennedy told USA Today that none of his relatives
could be persuaded to fly with him.
</P>
<P>
   ``The only person I've been able to get to go up with me, who
looks forward to it as much as I do, is my wife,'' he said.
``Whenever we want to get away, we can just get in a plane and fly
off.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Stephen Kurkjian, Tatsha Robertson, Anne E. Kornblut, Beth Carney,
and Joanna Weiss of the Globe staff contributed to this report.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
