<DOCNO> NYT19990717.0239 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-17 20:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4065 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-COLOMBIA-ECONOMY-HNS &LR;      07-17 1370
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COLOMBIA-ECONOMY-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GUERRILLA WAR RAVAGES ECONOMY IN COLOMBIA 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By JOHN OTIS 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOGOTA, Colombia _ Despite the huge body count from the recent
offensive by Marxist rebels, the economic carnage was almost as
shocking.
</P>
<P>
   The fighting began July 8 when guerrillas attacked the mountain
hamlet of Gutierrez, located just 25 miles south of Bogota. Army
generals erroneously portrayed the assault as a rebel push toward
the Colombian capital. Investors panicked and pulled millions of
dollars from the country. The Colombian peso lost 4 percent of its
value.
</P>
<P>
   ``From the headlines, you'd think it was Vietnam all over
again,'' says one New York-based financial analyst, referring to
the fall of Saigon to Communist rebels in 1975.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, the Revolutionary Armed Forces of Colombia, or FARC,
rebels lack the wherewithal to seize major cities and steered clear
of Bogota. But the offensive, which left a combined death toll of
more than 300, illustrates how the combat and Colombia's image as a
chaotic nation on the brink can rattle the markets.
</P>
<P>
   Concern over the slumping economy has put more pressure on the
Colombian government to achieve a breakthrough in long-awaited
peace talks with the FARC, which are scheduled to begin on Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Negotiating teams will meet in Uribe, a village 100 miles south
of Bogota, to explore ways to end the 35-year-old conflict. The
last round of peace talks broke off in 1992.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm convinced that if they don't make progress in the peace
process, Colombia is not going to be able to return to the levels
of economic growth that it needs,'' said Joel Korn, a country
analyst with the Inter-American Development Bank in Bogota.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think I've ever sensed so much concern and pessimism
about the way things are going,'' he said. ``People who have the
money to invest and are quite committed to being here are now
saying that it's just not worth it.''
</P>
<P>
   In the past, it was easier for business people to ignore the
fighting since it was confined to remote jungle areas and had
limited economic impact.
</P>
<P>
   But the FARC now has 17,000 fighters spread across much of the
country. The government spends vast sums to maintain its
146,000-man army and to rebuild wrecked infrastructure. Businesses
shell out millions for armored cars, security guards and kidnapping
insurance, since the guerrillas abduct hundreds of wealthy
Colombians and foreigners every year.
</P>
<P>
   Experts believe that the fighting and related security costs
shave between three and five points off Colombia's annual gross
domestic product, the sum of all goods and services produced within
the country's borders. After decades of robust growth, the economy
is expected to shrink this year by as much as 2 percent _ which
would be Colombia's worst performance since the Great Depression.
In the first quarter of this year, the economy contracted by 5.8
percent, compared to the first quarter of 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, Finance Minister Juan Camilo Restrepo announced that,
for the first time in the country's history, Colombia was turning
to the International Monetary Fund for help. Colombia will receive
a $3 billion line of credit from the IMF.
</P>
<P>
   Everyone from business tycoons to the corner grocer feels the
heat.
</P>
<P>
   For Andres Sierra, a butcher in Bogota, the war means higher
meat prices because the FARC collects ``war taxes'' from ranchers
who, in turn, charge more for their cattle at the slaughterhouse.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's come to the extreme where the simple farmer who grows a
plot of potatoes has to pay the rebels,'' Sierra said.
</P>
<P>
   At Alcimotores, a Bogota auto dealership, demand for luxury cars
and sport utility vehicles has plunged. A salesman explained that
buyers prefer stripped-down models to avoid the appearance of
wealth and the risk of being kidnapped at guerrilla roadblocks.
</P>
<P>
   The conflict has touched off an international commercial
dispute. Venezuelan President Hugo Chavez banned Colombian truck
drivers from entering his country last week in retaliation for the
threat of assaults, kidnappings and shakedowns that Venezuelan
truck drivers face on Colombian highways.
</P>
<P>
   Colombia truck drivers ``can go all the way to Caracas and
nothing happens to them,'' Chavez said. ``Venezuelan truck drivers
who go over there have to enter in war tanks to protect
themselves.''
</P>
<P>
   Colombians who can afford it are emigrating in droves. In the
first four months of this year, 65,000 Colombians left the country
and didn't return.
</P>
<P>
   At the U.S. Embassy in Bogota, applications for visas have
increased by 30 percent. In a recent Gallup poll of Colombians, 54
percent of the respondents said they have considered moving abroad
while 32 percent said they would marry a foreigner to facilitate
their departure.
</P>
<P>
   ``People don't want their kids to grow up this way, so if they
have a chance to leave, they go. It makes sense,'' said Roberto
Steiner, an economist at the University of the Andes in Bogota. He
warns that this ``brain drain'' will take years to overcome.
</P>
<P>
   But many Colombians believe that if negotiations with the
guerrillas are successful, the country would reap a substantial
``peace dividend.''
</P>
<P>
   Steiner points out that neighboring Peru suffered through 12
years of terror by Shining Path guerrillas. But after Shining Path
leader Abimael Guzman was captured in 1992, foreign investment
flowed and Peru's economy took off.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of people hope that something similar happens here,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts point out, however, that the FARC has the upper hand in
the war and say that the demoralized Colombian army lacks the
manpower, weapons and commitment to defeat them. Meanwhile, it's
unclear whether the FARC really wants peace.
</P>
<P>
   Negotiations were originally scheduled to begin in January, but
FARC leader Manuel ``Sure Shot'' Marulanda skipped the inaugural
ceremony. Since then, the rebels have delayed the start-up date
while carrying out a wave of spectacular assaults on army and
police units. All along, they have refused pleas for a cease-fire.
</P>
<P>
   Because the rebels are stronger than ever, the government may
have to offer major concessions to forge a truce.
</P>
<P>
   Just to persuade the FARC to come to the table, the government
withdrew troops from five municipalities in southern Colombia and
proclaimed the region a demilitarized zone. The rebels launched
raids from bases inside the zone during their latest offensive.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we have to prepare ourselves for the idea that peace
will be very costly. In the short and medium term, it will have
more costs than benefits,'' said Juan Jose Echavarria, director of
Fedesarollo, a private Bogota think tank.
</P>
<P>
   Others believe that the talks could quickly break down because
the two sides have little in common. On economic issues, for
example, the government has pursued an aggressive free-market
approach while the guerrillas are dogmatic Marxists.
</P>
<P>
   The FARC wants half of the national budget dedicated to health
and education and has called for state management of
telecommunications, ports and natural resources, such as oil.
Marulanda, the FARC leader, has reportedly said that even
Colombia's newspapers should be run by the government.
</P>
<P>
   ``Any economic idea that comes from the guerrillas is bad,''
said Steiner, the University of the Andes economist. ``They are
communists. They have spent 30 years studying a model that doesn't
work. And the model that does work, they don't understand.''
</P>
<P>
   Few economists believe that the government will consider deep
structural changes.
</P>
<P>
   But the two sides do share common ground on points like agrarian
reform and the need for sustained development in rural areas. From
the beginning, poverty in the countryside and distorted ratios of
land distribution have helped fueled the war.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's where you should make the biggest concessions,'' said
Juan Pablo Gonzalez, vice president of the Bogota Stock Exchange.
``But if profitability in the countryside is negative, you don't
solve anything by distributing the land among many people.
</P>
<P>
   ``The only thing you get is a larger number of bankrupt
people.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
