<DOCNO> NYT19990717.0240 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-17 20:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4066 &Cx1f; tad-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KENNEDY-BAXTER-COLUMN     07-17 0578
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KENNEDY-BAXTER-COLUMN18-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    It feels like our pain, but grief is personal
 &HT;    By Thomas Baxter
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ There is little point in regretting the avalanche of
media attention that greeted the news of yet another Kennedy
tragedy, when you are a part of it.
</P>
<P>
   The Bessettes faced Saturday the loss of two of their daughters,
with no preparation for such a tragedy, while the Kennedys, grimly
conditioned to the public rituals of grief, were confronted with
the loss of yet another son. That isn't the point either: All
families sooner or later confront the loss of those who were young
and full of promise, and are gone too soon.
</P>
<P>
   The Kennedys, on the other hand, are a family fused into the
American psyche in a unique way.
</P>
<P>
   With the news of a plane lost off the Atlantic coast, the memory
of the boy, who was too young to really know heartache, bravely
saluting as his father's coffin passed by, comes effortlessly to
mind. The tender smiles of 1963 are recalled and the news of 1999
brings us back, with a somber sense of completion, to what we
mourned so long ago.
</P>
<P>
   In the media's mad rush to tell every part of the story, to
pinpoint precisely how the plane went down and locate, again, those
with some association with the family, Americans feel the illusion
of personal connection.
</P>
<P>
   So it is inescapable that we will tell this story in an outsize
way, and add to the Pharaonic tradition in which every turn of bad
luck in a family's history becomes an integral part of ours. But to
be decent to John F. Kennedy Jr. and the two women with him, we
still ought to try to make a distinction between public fascination
and private grief.
</P>
<P>
   It was said of JFK Jr. that he wanted to be an actor when he was
younger, which should come as no surprise. He had movie star looks,
but more than that, he had spent his entire life in the
presentation of a public image that had to vary from the emotions
of the private self.
</P>
<P>
   It was not possible, however, for the president's son to pursue
roles very different from those for which he had been born. He had
an indifferent career as a lawyer and seemed averse to the family
business, which, of course, was politics. Ultimately he found his
calling as the publisher of a magazine, George, which treats
politics with the sensibilities of an actor.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe it was the best accommodation he could have made. George
is not a great magazine for those who truly love the sweaty push
and pull of politics, but on its pages Kennedy was able to approach
the world in the same way it had treated him. He gave us
politicians wrapped in the scented gloss of celebrity, political
events gussied up as media myth.
</P>
<P>
   How much, in the execution of a glamorous lifestyle, Kennedy was
haunted by the obligations of the myth that made him, we can never
know. His decision to turn away from the life of a candidate hints
at a certain uneasiness.
</P>
<P>
   He tried to strike another bargain with fame, but the loss of
his plane was too dramatic a story for him to escape becoming
another Kennedy, offered up on the Aztec altar of American
celebrity.
</P>
<P>
   His family faced the news this weekend in a way no others can,
no matter how much we think we know them. The true end of the
Kennedy curse will come when they can mourn their dead and deal
with their tragedies in just the way the rest of us do.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
