<DOCNO> NYT19990717.0242 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-17 20:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4070 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HEMINGWAY18-COX     07-17 1614
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HEMINGWAY18-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Nobody knows Hemingway like his fightin' friends
 &HT;    By Tom Archdeacon
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   I wanted to hear the ear story, but the first thing I got were
the feet.
</P>
<P>
   As soon as I showed up, unannounced, at Shine Forbes' little
bungalow at the corner of Fort and Geraldine in a side pocket of
Key West, I began to see why the guy had been a favorite of Ernest
Hemingway.
</P>
<P>
   This guy was a character. The outside of his house _ designated
by a homemade ``Shine's Ponderosa'' sign _ shows a puckish bent on
life. There are mounted steer horns, a trombone, pictures of Howdy
Doody and Hemingway and a hodge-podge of other kitsch and corn.
</P>
<P>
   After a couple of knocks at the door, a young woman answered and
let me inside the cramped quarters, where the walls were covered
with hundreds of pictures and cards. She told me Shine wasn't home
and asked why I wanted him.
</P>
<P>
   I told her I wanted to talk about Hemingway and boxing. I told
her that Shine's lifelong friend _ Iron Baby Roberts _ had told me
Shine once had been the best boxer on the island.
</P>
<P>
   As I talked, my eyes happened to settle on the faded blue
curtain that hung over a doorway to the back room. Jutting from the
bottom of the curtain was a pair of bare feet. Someone was there
and I figured I knew who it was. I kept talking about Shine _ how
Hemingway had singled him out, how Iron Baby said he rarely was
beaten.
</P>
<P>
   And with that, the curtain was flung back and out stepped Shine
Forbes, who, with a gleaming, gold-toothed grin, announced: ``I'm
here!''
</P>
<P>
   At the time Shine was close to 70, though his trim, well-muscled
body and neatly clipped beard and moustache made him look 20 years
younger. In fact, he didn't look much different than he did in
those two pictures on the wall of Hemingway and him _from the late
1930s.
</P>
<P>
   No mention was made of the curtain trick. I figured Shine just
wanted to see who he was dealing with before he got involved. That
wasn't always the case _ which was why I was there that afternoon
almost 15 years ago. And it's why we spoke by phone again a few
days ago and why today I'm yelling you this story.
</P>
<P>
   With the centennial of the Nobel laureate's birth on Wednesday,
it seems as if everyone is remembering Hemingway. Celebrations are
underway today in Hemingway's hometown of Oak Park, Ill., as well
as Paris, Havana, Pamplona, Spain, Washington, D.C., Petroskey,
Mich., Ketchum, Idaho, Dania, Fla., Piggott, Ark., and, of course,
Key West, with its annual Hemingway Days.
</P>
<P>
   Yet nobody has Hemingway stories quite as sweaty, bruising and
real as do Kermit ``Shine'' Forbes and James ``Iron Baby'' Roberts
_ Papa's pugs, Papa's pals
</P>
<P>
   Back in the 1930s, they used to put on gritty club fights in Key
West at an outdoor ring next to the Blue Heaven bar, pool hall _
and some say, bordello _ at the corner of Thomas and Petronia.
Today, the place is a popular faux, funk restaurant, but there are
reminders of the past. The rooster graveyard in the courtyard is
from the days when cock fights were as popular as the boxing shows.
</P>
<P>
   The place is only a few blocks from that fabled, coral rock
mansion on Whitehead Street where Hemingway lived from 1928-1939.
While in Key West, he produced more than two-thirds of his life's
work, including Death in the Afternoon, To Have and Have Not, For
Whom the Bell Tolls, as well as classic short stories like The
Snows of Kilimanjaro.
</P>
<P>
   Away from the literati scene, Hemingway found Key West energized
him. It kept him in fighting form. He rose at dawn every morning,
slipped back into his second floor study in the coach house, eased
into his old cigar maker's chair and wrote until noon. Afternoons
were for fishing and the night for carousing. Often, he made his
way to the Blue Heaven.
</P>
<P>
   He was fascinated by the fight shows put on by a Cuban boxer and
barkeep named Josey Mills. He had a lifetime passion for boxing and
already at 16, he had turned his mother's music room into a
makeshift gym so he could box with schoolmates, most of whom were
smaller and subject to his bullying tactics. Later, he took boxing
lessons and had his nose broken at a Chicago gym.
</P>
<P>
   As a young expatriate in Paris, he sparred with poet Ezra Pound
and had many spirited sessions with Canadian novelist _ and
one-time fighter _ Morley Callagan. Once he got to the tropics, the
battles got tougher. He knocked out publisher Joseph Knapp on the
docks in Bimini, then boasted he'd give $100 to any local who could
stay in the ring with him for four rounds. No one did. There also
was a brawling exhibition with heavyweight contender Tom Heeney and
a much-celebrated duke-out of poet Wallace Stevens at Sloppy Joe's
Bar in Key West.
</P>
<P>
   Hemingway believed sports gave man his best chance to make the
transition from coward to courage. He often wrote about the sport -
from his powerful short story ``Fifty Grand,'' about a boxer who
would not take a dive, to ``The Sun Also Rises,'' where the chief
character was once a middleweight champ.
</P>
<P>
   As for Hemingway's participation, he once wrote: ``My only
approach to truth was to have the experience directly and try to
write as well as I can about what happened while I was there.''
</P>
<P>
   And what better place to immerse himself than the Blue Heaven.
He was there the night Mills took on an overmatched Alfred ``Black
Pie'' Colebrooks, who asked Iron Baby and Shine to work his corner.
</P>
<P>
   Shine _ who'd left town as a teenager on a freight train loaded
with Cuban pineapples and had just returned after six years on the
road _ didn't recognize the burly, sun baked man who agreed to ref
the bout.
</P>
<P>
   ``He had a bunch of beard, long hair and old khaki shorts held
up by a rope,'' Shine said. ``I thought he was a bum trying to earn
money for a drink.''
</P>
<P>
   As Iron Baby once remembered the fight: ``Black Pie musta got
knocked down four of five times. Finally, Shine got tired of it, so
he threw a white towel in the ring. The ref tossed it back, so
Shine throwed it in a second time. Then a third and a fourth, but
the ref would have none of it.''
</P>
<P>
   Shine picked up the story: ``I was on the ring apron when the
towel hit me in the face. I jumped over the ropes and took a poke
at the ref. I missed and kinda landed in his arms and that's when
he grabbed me by the ears and started shaking me.''
</P>
<P>
   Hemingway stood 6-foot and weighed some 210 pounds. Shine _ who
often fought under the name ``The Battlin' Geech'' _ was 5-foot-6
and 135 pounds. Shine's buddies couldn't believe his brashness and
local cops poured into the ring to arrest him.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody was saying to Shine, 'you know who you swung at?'''
Iron Baby said. ``He said he didn't give a damn, but they said he
better 'cause that was the great writer, Ernest Hemingway.''
</P>
<P>
   Hemingway studied the fiery little man he held in his paws and
refused to press charges. ``The next day people told me I should go
beg Mr. Hemingway's pardon,'' Shine said. ``I did, but Hemingway
just laughed. He said that glory and spunk had made me do that
'cause most men wouldn't of had the guts to jump in the ring with
him.''
</P>
<P>
   Hemingway had a ring set up in his yard, two speed bags, a heavy
bag and various sets of gloves. He invited Shine, Iron Baby and a
few other boxers to spar with him each day. He paid 50 cents a
round, but Iron Baby claimed after the most vigorous sessions he'd
``shower $20 bills on us.''
</P>
<P>
   As Shine remembered: ``I can still see Ernest Hemingway in the
ring. He was big and didn't move real well, but he could take it.
He held his fists up jabbing, old -time style.''
</P>
<P>
   With the difference in size and noticing Shine's drooping eyelid
and milky left eye, you asked Iron Baby if Hemingway had done that
to his partner? Iron Baby looked surprised and shook his head. He
explained that it happened long ago when Shine was having trouble
with his wife. He followed her to another woman's home and that
woman opened the door and flung a jar filled with potash and
molasses in his face. The molasses made the solution stick and the
potash severely burned the eye.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nobody hurt Shine in the ring,'' Baby said. ``He was a hell of
a fighter. Only lost a couple fights in his career. He was born to
be a boxer.''
</P>
<P>
   Iron Baby was, too: ``My daddy was a boxer. In them days he was
one of the strongest men in the city. No one could whip him. Pretty
soon they called him Iron Daddy. As for me, well, I was his baby.''
</P>
<P>
   Today, both are old men. Shine is 83, Iron Baby, a few years
older, and according to Shine a couple days ago, ``real sick and
close to dying.''
</P>
<P>
   But this week _ as centennial celebrations fill the land _ no
stories have more life than those of Shine and Iron Baby
</P>
<P>
   ``One of the last times we saw Hemingway was a Christmas Eve,''
Shine said. ``These were poor times in Key West. I mean we didn't
have change for a quarter. Then all of a sudden here comes
Hemingway walking through the neighborhood. He had some guests over
to the house and wanted to know if we'd put on a boxing show.
</P>
<P>
   ``We went and there with the big shots was Gene Tunney. He had
been the heavyweight champ and Ernest wanted him to see us box. And
we put on a hell of a show. Baby got so worked up he tried to knock
me out. Afterward Hemingway passed a hat and got over $200 for us.
It was the best Christmas ever.''
</P>
<P>
   With that came another golden-toothed laugh: ``That big poke I
took at Ernest Hemingway? Oh man, that was the greatest thing that
ever happened to me in my life! It kinda got me famous.''
</P>
<P>
   ...Famous enough that sometimes you even recognize him by his
feet.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
