<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEN-DAVISCUP18-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    U.S. regains a step in doubles
 &HT;    By Todd Holcomb
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   BROOKLINE, Mass. _ The U.S. Davis Cup team, desperate to escape
a 2-0 hole for the first time in 64 years, beat and teased the
Australians on Saturday by breaking their 12-match winning streak
in doubles and hinting that Pete Sampras will be inserted into the
singles lineup today to face Patrick Rafter.
</P>
<P>
   Sampras, playing with Alex O'Brien, served out the 6-4, 6-3,
3-6, 4-6, 6-3 victory over Mark Woodforde and Sandon Stolle to
close the Aussies' lead to 2-1. A classic doubles match, it took
three hours, 27 minutes as the temperature reached a record 98 at
the Longwood Cricket Club.
</P>
<P>
   Afterward, U.S. captain Tom Gullikson boosted American hopes
further by saying Sampras may play singles after all.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wouldn't rule it out,'' Gullikson said. ``Our backs are
still to the wall, and we've got to throw everything into the
matches tomorrow.''
</P>
<P>
   Davis Cup rules prevent substituting singles players unless
there is an injury. Todd Martin, scheduled to play Rafter in the
opening match at 1 p.m., has a right elbow injury that's chronic,
and he recieved treatment for an unspecified complaint after
Friday's match, a four-set loss to Lleyton Hewitt.
</P>
<P>
   ``Todd has been a medical marvel this whole year,'' Gullikson
said. ``He's been in two states since Jan. 1 _ playing competitive
matches or rehabbing. He's really not been healthy all year, and he
manages to win matches, so he has an assortment of problems.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet Martin appeared healthy Saturday when he was found
practicing after the doubles match, executing overheads with ease.
Asked if he was fit, he said, ``Don't ask me stupid questions.''
</P>
<P>
   And following Friday's singles, Martin said he'd be willing to
play doubles if needed.
</P>
<P>
   Sampras has maintained since joining the team that he'd play
singles only if there was an injury to Martin or Jim Courier.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's something we're going to talk about,'' Sampras said. ``We
will keep everyone posted.''
</P>
<P>
   In Saturday's doubles, Sampras and O'Brien weren't broken until
the eighth game of the third set. O'Brien was the first to falter,
a loose game lost at love, and then Sampras was broken to open the
fourth set.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the fourth, (Gullikson) was like, 'What are you guys doing
out there, you look like a bunch of plumbers,' `` Sampras said.
``There is not a ton of strategy involved at that point. It's more
insiration.''
</P>
<P>
   The decisive moment came in the fifth set at 3-4 with Woodbridge
serving. The former world No. 1 in doubles led 30-love and hadn't
faced a service break in six games, but he double-faulted twice for
30-all. After a netcord helped give Sampras and O'Brien another
break point, the Aussies saved it with the point of the match, one
that required five overheads to finish.
</P>
<P>
   ``The ones where the boys were smashing and the Americans
retrieved, I thought this is as good as it gets in sport,''
Australian captain John Newcombe said. ``That last half hour was a
sporting spectacle.''
</P>
<P>
   But it was O'Brien who won the game with quick defensive lob
that got over Stolle's head for a winner.
</P>
<P>
   Sampras ran out to a 30-love lead in the deciding game but ran
into O'Brien trying to hit an overhead to make it 30-all. Sampras
then broke a string serving at 30-all and missed the first volley.
</P>
<P>
   The Australians hadn't lost a doubles match in Newcombe's four
years as captain. Ten of their 12 straight wins were registered by
Woodforde and Todd Woodbridge, but Woodbridge pulled out last week
because of an arm injury. Stolle is ranked No. 4 in doubles but was
making his Davis Cup doubles debut.
</P>
<P>
   The Americans are 1-28 after trailing 2-0 in Davis Cup, winning
only in a 1934 semifinal against Australia, but they've won 21
straight Davis Cup ties when winning the doubles point.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
