<HEADER>
A4074 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TEN-DAVISNOTES18-COX     07-17 0572
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEN-DAVISNOTES18-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    U.S. still no shoo-in in doubles
 &HT;    By Todd Holcomb
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   BROOKLINE, Mass. _ Pete Sampras is in and Todd Woodbridge is
out, but it doesn't mean that the United States is favored to win
the doubles point today.
</P>
<P>
   Sampras has played doubles four times in Davis Cup, winning
twice with John McEnroe in 1992 and once with Todd Martin in 1995,
but Sampras and Martin were beaten by Woodbridge and Mark Woodforde
in the 1997 semifinal against Australia.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can play good doubles,'' Sampras said. ``It's still the same
sport out there _ keep it in the lines and serve big and return
well.''
</P>
<P>
   The Aussies were weakened when Woodbridge took himself off the
team last week, citing a sore arm and poor confidence. He was
replaced by Sandon Stolle, ranked No. 4 in the world in doubles and
winner of the U.S. Open with Cyril Suk.
</P>
<P>
   Sampras' partner, Alex O'Brien, has lost both of his Davis Cup
doubles matches, including a five-set defeat against England's Tim
Henman and Greg Rusedski in the first round.
</P>
<P>
   Davis Cup rules allow captains to change their doubles pairings
as close as an hour before the scheduled match, which would be 1
p.m. today.
</P>
<P>
   The legends of Longwood
</P>
<P>
   The Longwood Cricket Club is known as the oldest tennis club in
the country and the site of the first Davis Cup competition, but
neither claim is precisely correct. Bud Collins calls Longwood
``the oldest significant tennis club in the U.S.,'' which probably
doesn't appease the New Orleans Lawn Tennis Club, established a
year before Longwood in 1876. The first Davis Cup competition,
between the United States and a British Isles team, was played at
Longwood's original location in 1900. The club was moved a few
blocks to its present site in 1922 and still provides lawn tennis
to its members.
</P>
<P>
   Winning on principle
</P>
<P>
   Tom Gullikson's decision to adhere to Sampras' wishes to play
only doubles opens the way for criticism if the U.S. team doesn't
win. It is reminiscent of another sporting but unusual move by the
1971 U.S. captain, Ed Turville. The United States was going to play
Romania in the final in Charlotte, and Turville didn't think it was
fair to put the Romanians on hardcourts, which favored the
Americans. So he ordered clay to make it ``entertaining for the
fans.'' Cliff Richey quit the team in protest, but his replacement,
Frank Froehling, defeated Ion Tiriac in five sets, and Stan Smith
upset Ilie Nastase, and the U.S. prevailed.
</P>
<P>
   Briefly
</P>
<P>
   The United States leads the Davis Cup series with Australia
25-19, although the Aussies lead in finals 15-14. ... The U.S. team
is 9-3 when Sampras plays, 9-3 when he doesn't. ... The 362 media
credentials issued represent a record for a U.S. Davis Cup match,
which was sold out in 81 minutes and attracted scalpers asking for
$250 a ticket. ... Former President George Bush attended Friday's
matches. Bush's uncle, Joseph Ware, was captain of the 1928 and '35
U.S. teams. Other celebrities in attendance included Jason
Alexander, Matt Damon, Gwyneth Paltrow and Orlando Cepeda. ...
ESPN2 is televising a six-hour Davis Cup commemorative today,
beginning at 10 a.m. and will feature the 1982 McEnroe-Mats
Wilander match, won by McEnroe in five sets, and the 1987
McEnroe-Boris Becker match, won by Becker in five.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
