<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KENNEDY-PROFILE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR A NATION, HE WILL ALWAYS BE `JOHN-JOHN' 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By GREG McDONALD 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ He'll be remembered always as that little boy who
stood at attention and saluted his father's flag-draped coffin as
it passed in front of him on a dark November day some 36 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   That image was burned forever into the nation's psyche.
</P>
<P>
   So it was with some disbelief that Americans awoke Saturday
morning to learn that young ``John-John,'' the toddler who used to
romp beneath his father's desk in the Oval Office, was missing at
age 38 off the Massachusetts island of Martha's Vineyard along with
the plane he was piloting and his wife and sister-in-law who were
aboard.
</P>
<P>
   John F. Kennedy Jr. turned 3 on the day his assassinated father
was buried, and his life has been anything but normal ever since.
</P>
<P>
   But the only surviving son of the nation's 35th president
struggled to live normally as best he could, despite the so-called
``curse'' of the Kennedy family mystique.
</P>
<P>
   He worked hard to shun the spotlight most of his life _ through
college at Brown University, law school, and then later as a junior
prosecutor in the Manhattan district attorney's office, where he
won six cases.
</P>
<P>
   Still, those were trying times for him. He flunked his New York
bar exam twice and was hounded by the media after being linked
romantically to Madonna and dubbed by People magazine as ``the
sexiest man in America.''
</P>
<P>
   It was about that time that friends revealed that Kennedy had
decided that law was not necessarily his calling, and he gave up
his job in the district attorney's office .
</P>
<P>
   Although he was not always clear about where he was going with
his life, he always seemed to be amazingly grounded for a member of
the nation's most pre-eminent and tragic family, and for a young
man who was often referred to in profiles of the Kennedys as
``America's prince.''
</P>
<P>
   In his early 30s, however, he seemed to find his calling as a
New York magazine publisher and journalist. Finally embracing the
media limelight, he used his celebrity status in 1995 to help
launch George Magazine, which pokes fun at American politics with a
combination of substance and fluff. The venture seemed to make him
happy.
</P>
<P>
   Putting out the magazine, he told a reporter two years ago, ``is
the most fun I've ever had,'' and he agreed with those who observed
that George was a way for him to be involved in politics like his
father and other famous Kennedy family members without really
having to run for office.
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, Kennedy never ruled out the possibility of a career
in politics and joked that his magazine might be useful as ``a
launching pad'' should he ever decide to seek elected office.
</P>
<P>
   ``I haven't ruled out going into politics in the future,''
Kennedy told a group of European reporters last November. ``I don't
have any specific plans. I don't have any clear ideas. It's more of
a prospect.''
</P>
<P>
   But ``right now,'' he added, ``I'm a journalist and I like that
a lot.''
</P>
<P>
   As news of the missing plane spread Saturday, old Kennedy family
friends and even average Americans who didn't know much about him
said they had always hoped that one day he might eventually follow
in his father's footsteps and run for national office.
</P>
<P>
   ``Who knows what the future would have held,'' John
Seigenthaler, a friend and former adviser to Robert F. Kennedy,
told NBC News.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's just a real tragedy if its true,'' said Grover
Sands, a 41-year old tourist from Maryland who brought his family
Saturday to see the White House. ``I think he might have run for
office, and I think it would have been real interesting ... I think
a lot of Americans love the idea that another Kennedy could be
president one day.''
</P>
<P>
   Vice President Al Gore also paid tribute to Kennedy at an
appearance in Los Angeles, noting that he had set a remarkable
example for all Americans during his life given the tragedies that
have dogged his family.
</P>
<P>
   ``At the age of 3, he was the most famous person in the world
because with his innocent and brave young heart he helped the
nation and the world endure some of the hardest hours of our
history,'' Gore said.
</P>
<P>
   ``He has carried his legend with enormous grace and with a
commitment to live up to his father's legacy, his mother's love.''
</P>
<P>
   Kennedy was born Nov. 25, 1960, the second child of former
President Kennedy and his wife Jacqueline. Another son, Patrick
Bouvier Kennedy, was born premature Aug. 7, 1963, and died two days
later. John Kennedy's older sister, Caroline, was born in 1957.
</P>
<P>
   Along with his sister, Kennedy sought throughout his life to
dedicate himself to public service even though both continued to
shy away from political office. Together the two sought to help the
poor and disadvantaged, not only by volunteering their services but
with considerable money as well. The two founded a number of
charities and public service organizations together aimed at
helping children and the elderly.
</P>
<P>
   The two also dedicated themselves to upholding their father and
mother's legacies. When Jacqueline Kennedy died in 1994, Caroline
took over the Profiles in Courage awards program at the Kennedy
Library and John began overseeing the Kennedy School of Government.
John had also just been appointed as chairman of the school's
Institute of Politics.
</P>
<P>
   But away from his magazine and public service duties, Kennedy, a
natural athlete, also pursued a number of challenging sports,
including kayaking, in-line skating, climbing and parasailing. He
received his pilots license just a little over a year ago, and he
was reportedly at the controls of the single-engine plane when it
went missing late Friday night with his wife, Carolyn Bessette
Kennedy, and her sister Lauren Bessette on board.
</P>
<P>
   Although he was rumored to be engaged to a number of women
during his early 30s, including actress Daryl Hannah, Kennedy met
Carolyn Bessette, a former Calvin Klein publicist, in 1993. After
nearly three years of on-again off-again dating, they married in
1996 at a small, secluded church on Cumberland Island, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
