<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-GALLOWAY-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GONZALEZ'S ALL-STAR ABSENCE A BIG NOTHING
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RANDY GALLOWAY 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   What Juan Gonzalez should have done is miss a third of the
regular season with a mystery ailment, then show up for last week's
All-Star Game and play the full nine innings.
</P>
<P>
   A certain cornerback pulled a similar stunt but still had a
loving local media licking up to him.
</P>
<P>
   Or what Gonzalez could have done is accept an invite to Boston,
but then decline the All-Star spot due to personal business.
</P>
<P>
   A certain bullpen ace for Joe Torre's Yankees did exactly that.
Mariano Rivera's ``personal business?'' He went home to Panama to
check on the construction of a new house.
</P>
<P>
   Did anyone harpoon Rivera as a disgrace to the game for
insulting baseball fans of all ages? Did Torre, the All-Star
manager, question Rivera's motives as he did Juan's? Of course not.
</P>
<P>
   Based on what has happened the last couple of weeks, Gonzalez
might as well change his name to Casey Jones. He's been railroaded
in a national and local frenzy of criticism.
</P>
<P>
   Suddenly, Juan is being portrayed as the evil poster child for
everything that ails millionaire members of the jock kingdom. He
has been called a disgrace to the game and to the Rangers'
organization. But the disgrace is actually elsewhere. It rests in
the laps of those guilty of overreaction and overkill.
</P>
<P>
   Gonzalez didn't attempt to strangle Johnny Oates, or he didn't
flunk a drug test for the fourth time, or he didn't get drunked up
and slam his Mercedes into a concrete wall. Nor was there any ``why
don't you run the laps'' backtalk to a coach, and no cops were
knocking on a hotel-room door.
</P>
<P>
   This amounted to nothing more than Gonzalez saying he wasn't
going to last week's All-Star Game unless he was voted in as a
starter. Big deal.
</P>
<P>
   Should he have gone anyway? Sure. And if he wasn't going, could
Gonzalez have handled it a bit different? Sure.
</P>
<P>
   But this isn't high crimes against humanity. Some ego obviously
became involved, and Juan maybe pushed himself out there on a
ledge. I don't know about you, but I happen to live on the same
ledge. Stuff happens. People get mad. I'm sorry if you're offended.
</P>
<P>
   More than anything else, however, Gonzalez simply spoke the
truth on why he wasn't going to the All-Star Game.
</P>
<P>
   And yes, the system was flawed. Cleveland fans went nuts on us,
voting in undeserving characters just because their ballcaps had
the insignia of a weird looking Native American, which hisses off
the Native Americans something fierce.
</P>
<P>
   Plus, in the strangest bit of scheduling in Rangers history, The
Ballpark in Arlington basically sat empty the entire month of June,
prime voting month for the All-Star Game. Local fans didn't get the
opportunity to ballot-box stuff, while the Indians lived at home in
June.
</P>
<P>
   The system was flawed.
</P>
<P>
   But speaking the truth turned Gonzalez into a human dartboard,
not only for media types but also many in baseball.
</P>
<P>
   Juan did not deserve the trashing. No, he's never been Cal
Ripken or Sammy Sosa in creating positive P.R. for himself. But
Juan is an OK guy and the best player ever in Arlington and one of
the best in the game today.
</P>
<P>
   ``I never said anything negative about the fans, other players,
or the manager,'' said Gonzalez. ``I did feel like, based on my
performance this season, and being the MVP from last season, I
deserved to start.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I understood what was happening with the voting system,
and how the schedule was unfair to the Rangers. And then I said
what I said because I believed strongly I was right.''
</P>
<P>
   It would be best now if Juan, looking back at his decision,
would retreat a bit and admit he was wrong. But he won't. I respect
him for that.
</P>
<P>
   In his original comments to T.R. Sullivan of this sports staff,
Gonzalez did note some personal displeasure about Joe Torre. Two
years ago, when Juan was also coming off an MVP season and also
putting up large numbers, Torre snubbed him and selected two
Yankees outfielders as All-Star reserves. Torre was wrong. Juan had
a right to still be miffed.
</P>
<P>
   But Juan quickly and wisely backed off any criticism of Torre.
Juan centered everything around the flawed system.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have eyes and ears _ I read and hear what's been said about
me,'' noted Gonzalez. ``But I will stay strong. I believe what I
believe. People wonder about next season _ would I do the same
thing? But this was about this year. Every season is different.
Maybe I don't deserve to go next season, who knows.''
</P>
<P>
   One of the many media rip jobs on Gonzalez suggested he had
``embarrassed'' the Rangers with this ``controversy.''
</P>
<P>
   I laughed. Then I thought of Jerry Jones. Jerry is praying hard
the Cowboys' next embarrassment and controversy will be as big a
nothing as this whole affair.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
