<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FORBES-DEFECT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CONGRESSMAN QUITS REPUBLICAN PARTY, BLAMING EXTREMISTS 
</HEADLINE>
   (Eds., this story has been added to NYT Page 1, as 2X reefer,
bottom of page)  
 (HLW)  
 By JAMES DAO   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   QUOGUE, N.Y. _ Rep. Michael P. Forbes, a mercurial Republican
who has frequently butted heads with House Republican leaders,
announced Saturday that he was becoming a Democrat because his own
party had been captured by ``extremists.''
</P>
<P>
   He accused the Republican leadership of being ``tone deaf'' to
the concerns of average Americans on issues from health care to
education to the environment.
</P>
<P>
   Sweating profusely in the blistering sunshine during a news
conference outside his gray-shingled home, Forbes repeatedly
slammed his former party's leadership with the kind of harsh
oratory that Democrats once used against him.
</P>
<P>
   ``With no communist menace to rail against, and with an American
economy that is the strongest to be sustained in our lifetime, the
national Republican Party over the last four and a half years has
allowed itself to become defined through the actions of extremists
in the House of Representatives,'' said Forbes, who is in his third
term.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's become angry, narrow-minded, intolerant, uncaring,
incapable of governing at all, much less from the center.''
</P>
<P>
   Democratic officials said Forbes, 47, is the first congressional
Republican to switch to the Democratic Party in nearly a
quarter-century _ a period in which they said at least 10 Democrats
in Congress flipped to the Republican side.
</P>
<P>
   Forbes, who once did the unthinkable by voting against Newt
Gingrich, when Gingrich was running for re-election as speaker of
the House in 1997, has for years been an outcast in the Republican
Party, and his defection is not expected to draw other Republicans
into the Democratic fold.
</P>
<P>
   But the move still seems like an important psychological victory
for the Democrats as they seek to capture the House next year. With
Forbes' defection the Democrats now need to win just five
additional seats to be in the majority.
</P>
<P>
   `I really think you are seeing a party in a real state of
difficulty,'' Dick Gephardt, the House minority leader, said of the
Republicans. ``You may be seeing a realignment taking place.''
</P>
<P>
   House Republicans played down the significance of the move,
suggesting Forbes was a political loner who could be less than
stable in Congress.
</P>
<P>
   ``Michael's decision to leave the resurgent Republican Party for
the minority party is, like many of his past actions, inconsistent
and erratic,'' said Rep. Thomas M. Davis III of Virginia, chairman
of the National Republican Congressional Committee. ``Last year, he
voted to impeach Democrat Bill Clinton. Last month he endorsed
George W. Bush for president and today, he chooses to side with the
party of higher taxes and bigger government.''
</P>
<P>
   Davis said the Republicans would do ``everything we can'' to
unseat Forbes next year. Among the names of challengers being
circulated in Republican circles are Suffolk County Executive
Robert J. Gaffney, New York Assemblyman Fred W. Thiele Jr. and
state Senator Kenneth P. LaValle.
</P>
<P>
   Forbes, who won re-election last year with 64 percent of the
vote, said he expected to be the target of Republican retribution
not just in next year's election but also in the House, where the
Republican leadership is likely to block his bills and strip him of
his seat on the powerful House Appropriations Committee.
</P>
<P>
   But Gephardt said he would ask Democrats on the Appropriations
Committee, which allocates federal funds, to step aside so that
Forbes can retain his seat. He also vowed to do ``everything I
can'' to get Forbes re-elected, though he said he could not promise
that there would not be a primary.
</P>
<P>
   At least one Democrat, Tony Bullock, chief of staff to New
York's senior Democratic senator, Daniel Patrick Moynihan, has said
that he might challenge Forbes in the primary. But Democratic
officials said Saturday that an effort was already under way by
party officials to urge Bullock to back off.
</P>
<P>
   Forbes has told Democratic officials that he has not yet decided
whether to retract his endorsement of Bush of Texas, who is the
Republican front-runner in the polls. In his news conference
Saturday, the congressman was careful not to attack Bush directly.
</P>
<P>
   Vice President Gore, who is seeking the Democratic nomination to
replace Clinton, issued a statement Saturday praising Forbes as a
man of ``principle and integrity.''
</P>
<P>
   In a sign of the symbolic importance of the defection, leaders
in both parties waged a tug-of-war for his heart and mind in recent
days.
</P>
<P>
   Since Thursday, when the rumors began spreading in Washington
that Forbes might defect, Davis, Alfonse D'Amato and Gov. George
Pataki have called Forbes and asked him to reconsider, Democratic
officials said.
</P>
<P>
   Forbes is not easy to peg ideologically, and he will be somewhat
to the right of House Democrats. He supports Democratic initiatives
to expand federal spending on day care, to protect the environment,
to revamp campaign finance laws and to regulate health maintenance
organizations. But he also opposes abortion rights and often votes
against gun control.
</P>
<P>
   In an indication of the balancing act Forbes may now be forced
into, he was sharply questioned Saturday at his news conference by
an abortion rights advocate, an environmental advocate and a local
Republican leader.
</P>
<P>
   He said changing parties would not cause him to change his
positions on major issues.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
