<DOCNO> NYT19990717.0255 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-17 21:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4084 &Cx1f; kan-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DIVERSITY-WORKPLACE-K     07-17 2452
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DIVERSITY-WORKPLACE-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LOOKING FOR BUSINESS DIVERSITY IN KANSAS CITY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By TED SICKINGER and MARY SANCHEZ  
 c. 1999 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. -- If one defines workplace diversity as taco
day in the company cafeteria, a sensitivity seminar for employees
or a line in a mission statement about respecting cultural
differences, then everything's up to date in Kansas City.
</P>
<P>
   But if a diverse company is one where management, board members
and suppliers mirror the racial makeup of the community, good
hunting.
</P>
<P>
   Beyond cosmetic changes, the complexion of Kansas City's
business community remains overwhelmingly white, with few signs of
impending change.
</P>
<P>
   Blacks, Hispanics and Asians make up 19 percent of the total
population and 19 percent of the work force in the Kansas City
area. But they comprise just 9 percent of the managers and
professionals at area companies -- a statistic that lags national
numbers.
</P>
<P>
   Of 277 directors at the 20 largest public companies and four of
the largest and best-known private firms in Kansas City, only nine
directors, or about 3 percent, are minorities. That is half the
national average.
</P>
<P>
   While most local companies profess a strong commitment to the
principles of diversity -- which extends to gender, disabilities,
sexual orientation and more -- few have specific programs to
recruit and retain minority executives, or to increase the amount
of business they do with minority-owned firms.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, ``when you look at where the large corporations stand,
you can be assured the small and medium-sized companies are not
addressing it,'' said Kirk P. Perucca, president/CEO of Project
Equality, which tracks employment practices at area companies.
</P>
<P>
   It's no wonder, then, that when Jesse Jackson came to Kansas
City last month, he dragged Sprint Corp. into the spotlight,
questioning why the area's largest private employer was not hiring
more minority contractors to work on its $1 billion corporate
campus in Overland Park, Kan., in suburban Kansas City.
</P>
<P>
   But Jackson was quick to note that the problem was not just
Sprint. ``Let's take a look at all of corporate Kansas City,'' he
said. ``Let's challenge them.''
</P>
<P>
   Many here say that challenge is long overdue.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've been in business for 30 years, and we still lack
credibility in our business here,'' said Kelvin Perry, president of
Newspaper Electronics Corp., a minority-owned company that sells
computer hardware to businesses. ``Go down a list of the top 50
businesses in Kansas City. We do no substantive business with those
companies.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you can make it here, you can make it anywhere. And I'm not
singing `New York, New York.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Perry and many others said that the lack of minority managers
and the dearth of minority-owned businesses in the area reflected
the racial attitudes ingrained in corporate culture, the ongoing
segregation and the lack of inclusiveness in the community at
large.
</P>
<P>
   More-charitable observers give credit to a few companies that
have attacked the issue head on, but fault the business community
at large for failing to address it in a meaningful way.
</P>
<P>
   ``Kansas City is a polite town,'' said Colette Holt, an
affirmative-action lawyer. ``People here don't want to be
uncomfortable, and they don't want to make other people
uncomfortable.
</P>
<P>
   ``That makes it harder to talk about race.''
</P>
<P>
   Consultants acknowledge that progress in the inclusion of
minorities as top managers and suppliers is an evolutionary
process. It takes commitment from top management, sensitivity to
the complexities of race and a willingness to work around very real
hurdles.
</P>
<P>
   But they say it is possible, and ultimately profitable.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have the greatest potential here to make a difference,''
said Jim Abbott, executive director of the Minority Supplier
Council in Kansas City, a diversity liaison between minority and
majority businesses.
</P>
<P>
   ``When the leadership here decides to take something on, it gets
done. I can't say that collectively they have taken on this
issue.''
Talking the talk
</P>
<P>
   Corporate attitudes about diversity span the spectrum. Some see
it as an opportunity, others as a problem that needs to be solved,
or even a nonissue.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't distinguish between minority and nonminority
suppliers,'' said Julie Bartels Smith, a spokeswoman for American
Century Investments. Nor, she said, does the company have a
minority hiring program.
</P>
<P>
   Many area companies express a variation on that theme.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our position is that there is no color,'' said Stephen Pope,
vice president of human resources at O'Reilly Automotive.
</P>
<P>
   ``Traditionally this was a white, male-dominated business,'' he
said, noting that there were few women or minorities. ``Over the
years we have brought those people into the company, and over time
and they have progressed quite nicely.''
</P>
<P>
   When contacted by The Kansas City Star, representatives of the
20 largest public companies in the region and four of the largest
private firms almost universally stated that their company embraced
diversity.
</P>
<P>
   Some celebrate a specific diversity day. Commerce Bank has at
least two. When Western Resources had its annual diversity
celebration, Kansas Gov. Bill Graves issued a proclamation naming
Oct. 23 diversity day in the entire state.
</P>
<P>
   Few would criticize those efforts. But when it comes to formal
programs, with measurable goals that are benchmarked, tracked and
prioritized by senior management -- the kinds of programs that
experts say deliver results -- most companies have little to brag
about.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no diversity plan per se,'' said Mark Dirkes, senior
vice president of marketing at Interstate Bakeries. ``That doesn't
mean we aren't using minority suppliers. There's just no plan.''
</P>
<P>
   Some companies may be able to diversify without a formal effort.
But not many, experts say.
</P>
<P>
   ``Once a company sets real, meaningful goals, it tends to
work,'' said Abbott, of the Minority Supplier Council. ``If it's
just an ad hoc thing, the numbers aren't there.''
</P>
<P>
   In the end, most companies' commitment to diversity depends on
whether they see a compelling business reason to do it.
</P>
<P>
   Diversity advocates say there is -- profits.
</P>
<P>
   Twenty-eight percent of Americans are minorities today. By 2050,
half will be. That is an enormous pool of potential customers,
prospective employees and vendors.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, experts insist, diverse work forces are better problem
solvers. They make it easier to recruit and retain staff, tap new
markets, design better products and provide first-class customer
service to a diverse customer base.
</P>
<P>
   ``We kind of approached diversity as the right thing to do,''
said Keith Kennedy, director of corporate diversity at Hallmark
Cards. ``But we have grown to the point that it is also a business
imperative for us.''
Parsing the talk
</P>
<P>
   It is unclear how many local companies think diversity benefits
the bottom line.
</P>
<P>
   Most companies approach recruiting and new markets with a
specific target. They go where they can generate numbers, period.
</P>
<P>
   Banks, for instance, go for neighborhoods and customers with big
loan volume and substantial account balances. Beyond regulatory
requirements, they see few compelling reasons to put branches in
minority neighborhoods, or chase the tiny loans and accounts that
they have found are typically generated there.
</P>
<P>
   Likewise, Sprint is pinning its future to an integrated voice
and data service that will cost more than $100 a month. It is
specifically aiming at high-value, technology-savvy consumers who
already use multiple phone lines and communications services. The
company isn't excluding minorities, but minorities make up a small
part of the target market for a key new product.
</P>
<P>
   Diversity also can be a tough sell to executives who were weaned
on conformity and resent outside advice on how to run their
businesses. Many see aggressive diversity initiatives in the same
light as affirmative action.
</P>
<P>
   Even when executives advocate diversity, the mention of specific
goals elicits concerns about quotas, or being forced to promote
less-qualified employees.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have avoided quotas, because that's opening another bag of
worms in terms of people feeling they're discriminated against
because they're not part of that group,'' said Lloyd Hill, chief
executive of Applebee's International.
</P>
<P>
   Middle managers and line employees also can take a cynical view
of the programs, particularly if they see senior management making
little effort to diversify itself, or using a diversity program as
a legal shield against discrimination complaints and lawsuits.
</P>
<P>
   Some employees feel threatened. Others assume the changes will
be inefficient or unacceptable to shareholders, because they expect
increased costs and reduced profits.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to deal with the tradeoffs,'' said Tim Larson, vice
president of supply at H&AMP;R Block. ``Purchasing from a minority
business might mean paying a significant premium or getting lesser
quality.''
</P>
<P>
   Minority firms frequently do lack the capacity to ramp up a crew
and get a big job done quickly. They may lack adequate staff, cash
flow, bonding or insurance.
</P>
<P>
   Minorities, however, say the issue of nonperformance is a
convenient excuse.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a very real misconception that using minority
suppliers will cost you more money and give you an inferior
performance,'' said Maurice Williams, coordinator of supplier
diversity at Kansas City Power &AMP; Light. ``You may not be able to
put your hands on it, but it's virtually everywhere.''
</P>
<P>
   A. Marie Young, executive director of the Black Chamber of
Commerce, sees a common reaction when she introduces her members to
purchasing representatives at large businesses in the area.
</P>
<P>
   ``It used to shock me,'' she said. ``They don't even attempt to
hide their surprise that these black business leaders exist ...
that we have businesses with the capacity and experience that is
here,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Lack of awareness is only one aspect of what many describe as a
vicious circle in the development of minority businesses.
</P>
<P>
   To a large extent, business always has been a matter of whom you
know. And minorities, by definition, are not part of the old-boys
network.
</P>
<P>
   Minority-owned firms say they often are ignored when companies
request bids from suppliers -- even when they've networked and made
formal presentations to the same companies' purchasers.
</P>
<P>
   ``People feed who they know,'' said Elbert Harris, owner of
Courtney Day Inc., a local construction contractor. ``If I don't
have access, I don't have opportunity.''
</P>
<P>
   Without new opportunities, it is difficult for small firms to
grow, build equity and get the financing they need to increase
capacity and take on successively larger jobs. And businesses that
do not grow often die.
</P>
<P>
   Apart from a few restaurants and funeral homes, relatively few
local minority businesses have endured from one generation to the
next, which bolsters the perception that they are ill-managed and
lack expertise.
</P>
<P>
   It also means the incentive is diminished for young minorities
to return to Kansas City after college. Many don't see compelling
opportunities in the minority business community, competitive
salaries at large companies or enough neighborhoods where upwardly
mobile minorities are comfortable living.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you've got multiple offers and you can go anywhere, and
you've got that kind of potential to grow, why would you come to
Kansas City?'' asked Young, of the Black Chamber.
Walking the talk
</P>
<P>
   What separates token diversity programs from effective ones,
experts say, are those that identify potential barriers up front
and work around them.
</P>
<P>
   On the supply side, some companies restructure their payment
schedules on contracts to help small contractors cover payroll and
equipment leases. Others break large jobs into smaller chunks that
small companies can digest.
</P>
<P>
   Last year area lenders refused to grant one of KCP&AMP;L's
streetlight contractors a line of credit to handle working capital
-- even when KCP&AMP;L offered to guarantee 75 percent of the loan. So
the company paid the contractor out of its own pocket and then
collected from the city once the work was approved.
</P>
<P>
   KCP&AMP;L has three programs designed to further develop its
vendors' businesses. Adopt-A-Vendor, for instance, offers vendors a
12-week evaluation of their financing, management, technical
expertise and marketing, and a comprehensive action plan for
developing the business.
</P>
<P>
   KCP&AMP;L tracks its annual expenditures with minority businesses,
and has a specific goal each year to increase them. Moreover, the
purchasing department is held accountable for those goals at annual
review time.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm proud of the things we've been able to do,'' Williams
said. ``But we've got a long, long way to go.''
</P>
<P>
   Williams' statement is typical of the companies that are
furthest along the diversity curve. They acknowledge that there is
a problem.
</P>
<P>
   NationsBank has taken pains to address diversity issues in
Kansas City, creating a local diversity action council with 45
officers. The group focuses on taking specific measures in four
areas: recruiting and retention; promotion and career development;
education; and community involvement.
</P>
<P>
   This summer the company hired 16 interns in the Midwest. Eleven
are minorities. This year in Kansas City it paired 25 promising
minority professionals in a formal mentoring relationship with
officers who are senior vice presidents and above. The company
tracks how many times the pairs meet each month. And each pair
issues regular progress reports.
</P>
<P>
   NationsBank's overall corporate goal this year is to direct 15
percent of the company's total procurement dollars to minority- and
women-owned businesses.
</P>
<P>
   Hallmark has been setting concrete spending goals with minority
vendors for 30 years. In 1969 the amount was $25,000. This year it
is about $45 million.
</P>
<P>
   The company stays in touch with employees who have left, hoping
to one day woo them back. There are mentoring programs, a program
to help employees chart their career paths and support groups for
racial groups.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's better for us to talk to our employees about their future
rather than to let some headhunter tell them,'' said Hallmark's
Kennedy.
</P>
<P>
   Hallmark is in the third year of a five-year program to increase
the number of minorities and women in senior management. And hiring
and retention of minority and women employees has been made one of
the key priorities senior managers are expected to meet.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you don't make people accountable for it, is it really a
business imperative?'' Kennedy asked.
</P>
</TEXT>
