<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-17 21:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4085 &Cx1f; kan-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-OLDEST-CELEBRATION-KA     07-17 1059
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLDEST-CELEBRATION-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TOWN UNWAVERING IN ITS DEVOTION TO ANNUAL FESTIVAL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JIM FISHER  
 c. 1999 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WAVERLY, Kan. -- Starting at 6 p.m. last Monday, the first of
what would grow to about 2,000 men, women and children began
filling the downtown of this Coffey County community.
</P>
<P>
   The grown-ups toted lawn chairs; the smaller kids, eyes wide
with anticipation, clutched paper and plastic bags. Everybody
waited.
</P>
<P>
   For what?
</P>
<P>
   Why, a parade.
</P>
<P>
   At 7 p.m. the annual Ohio Days procession began rolling south
down Pearson Avenue -- 35 entries, 13 floats, Shriners doing stunts
on their all-terrain three-wheelers, Miss Flint Hills, politicians,
horses with riders, dogs, National Guard vehicles, a Pepsi-Cola
truck, Boy Scouts, the American Legion marching, an 1880s fire
wagon, older kids on bicycles swirling here and there, even an
antique manure spreader.
</P>
<P>
   And that was just part of the parade, which was part of Ohio
Days, a three-day event that for more than a century has riveted
this town in midsummer.
</P>
<P>
   From almost every passing vehicle came a shower of candy, a
tradition akin to the throwing of beads during New Orleans's Mardi
Gras. The little kids with their bags scurried to claim the booty.
Their parents, sitting in the lawn chairs, kept a sharp eye.
</P>
<P>
   The parade took 45 minutes to pass the farm trailer/announcing
stand. Not bad for a town of 600-plus, well off Interstate 35, as
yet untouched by franchisees and long ago abandoned by the Santa Fe
railway.
</P>
<P>
   For a brief moment on a pleasant July evening, Waverly turned
itself into a slice of Americana now mostly relegated to old
photographs and newsreels -- flags, costumes, friends waving at
friends, and children retrieving Tootsie Rolls from the cracks of a
classic brick main street. With minor changes in clothing and
motive power, what took place here Monday could have happened in
1910, 1940 or 1960.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't change,'' said Kenneth L. Combes, an insurance man
who is on the Ohio Days steering committee. ``We just do it year
after year pretty much the same. It gets to be a habit. But then
people here don't want that much change.''
</P>
<P>
   The parade ended at the city park, but not before every float,
every entry, every bike and vehicle went past the Sunset Manor
nursing home, where residents could look out the windows or come
out, some with walkers, some in wheelchairs.
</P>
<P>
   At the city park there was a stage show. And, of course, there
were the carnival and rides provided by the Ottaway Amusement Co.
of Wichita, which has been coming to Waverly just about as long as
anybody can remember.
</P>
<P>
   ``Best parade ever,'' one middle-age woman said afterward. At
her age, though, she couldn't really know. The Ohio Days parade is
103 years old. It is thought to be the oldest continual celebration
of its kind west of the Mississippi River, said Irene Combes,
Kenneth Combes' wife.
</P>
<P>
   The story goes that in 1896 a group of Waverly residents -- all
settlers from Ohio -- decided to have a picnic south and west of
here.
</P>
<P>
   ``They wanted shade, and in those days that was the only grove
of trees around,'' said Opal Kunkel, 84, who's deep into the
history of Waverly.
</P>
<P>
   From the very first, Kunkel said, the people referred to the
celebration as Ohio Days, a time for reminiscing about the Buckeye
State. Kansas had blistering heat in the summer, strange storms
then called cyclones, grasshoppers, blizzards and land that
hereabouts -- because of thin topsoil -- was overly susceptible to
droughts.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps Coffey County wasn't as barren as western Kansas. But it
wasn't -- by any stretch -- Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   Over the years, Kunkel said, Ohio Days outgrew the picnic in the
grove and was moved to town. There always have been church
services, she said. And a parade, entertainment, and even something
as hokey as a baby show.
</P>
<P>
   The oddity about Ohio Days, said Kunkel and the Combes, is that
it has never missed a beat. Rather than fade away as so many
celebrations have in so many small towns, it endured, the only
change over the years being a change of dates from August back to
July.
</P>
<P>
   The Depression and Dust Bowl days, when lots of people didn't
have two nickels to rub together? Ohio Days went on.
</P>
<P>
   The World Wars, when the young men were gone, gas and tires were
rationed, and bad news came by Western Union? Ohio Days survived
those, too.
</P>
<P>
   Or the long twilight of small-town Kansas, where high school
graduating classes seemed to disappear almost overnight as they
left for bigger places? Ohio Days persisted.
</P>
<P>
   ``In all my days, I can't remember anybody even suggesting we
cut back,'' Kunkel said. ``It's just something that's here, that
everybody gets involved in. It's our heritage.''
</P>
<P>
   Kenneth Combes says he thinks that's part of the secret. Fully
20 percent of the population here has some sort of job to do in
relation to the celebration -- floats, the barbecue, games, the
talent contest and a legion of other tasks.
</P>
<P>
   The other part of the secret, Combes said, is that Waverly has
never commercialized Ohio Days and tried to make it an ``event,''
something he knows the tourism people in Topeka would dearly love.
</P>
<P>
   ``We get a lot of pressure from the media for advertising,'' he
said. ``You know, put it in the paper, publicize it on the radio.
And we get vendors calling, wanting to come in and set up booths.''
</P>
<P>
   Instead of the hard sell to tourists -- all the rage now as
rural Kansas tries to diversify its economy away from the old
mainstays of livestock and crops -- Waverly puts out a simple
flier, black print on white paper. That's the extent of publicity
for Ohio Days.
</P>
<P>
   ``Look at our entertainment,'' Combes said. ``All local. Oh, we
could get a big-name act, bring people in from Topeka or Kansas
City.
</P>
<P>
   ``Or we could bring in vendors from outside and their booths.
But that's not what this is all about. Pretty soon it would all be
different. It wouldn't be Ohio Days.''
</P>
<P>
   Happily, said Irene Combes, young people are moving back to
Waverly, primarily those who went away after high school but who
want to return to their roots and raise their children in a bucolic
town.
</P>
<P>
   ``So we're getting new blood,'' she said. ``And they're getting
involved. And one of these days, they'll be running Ohio Days.
Simple.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
