<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-17 21:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4086 &Cx1f; kan-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SPRINT-MOVE-KAN &LR;      07-17 1145
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SPRINT-MOVE-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MOVING DAY -- ONE OF MANY -- IS FINALLY HERE FOR SPRINT CORP. 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARK P. COUCH  
 c. 1999 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. -- The great migration has started.
</P>
<P>
   Sprint Corp. this weekend is rolling out the moving trucks and
beginning a three-year shuffle of 14,500 workers that eventually
will gather the company's scattered masses on its $920 million
corporate campus in Overland Park, Kan., in suburban Kansas City.
</P>
<P>
   Seventy-five workers in Missouri's tallest office tower in
downtown Kansas City will be the first Sprint employees to move
into Kansas' largest office park headquarters.
</P>
<P>
   ``The campus comes to life this weekend,'' said Philippe Dordai
of The Hillier Group of Princeton, N.J., the lead architect on the
project. ``Until now, it's all been bricks and mortar. Now with
people in it, that's when it starts to happen.''
</P>
<P>
   On Saturday morning, the fourth truckload of chairs, boxes and
office equipment was delivered to the first building to open on the
campus.
</P>
<P>
   Two moving specialists in a conference room tracked deliveries
while several movers hauled the equipment into the building. About
45 persons worked on this weekend's moving crew.
</P>
<P>
   The movers tracked their progress with red check marks on lists
taped to the conference room window. Moving trucks were dispatched
with walkie-talkies as unloading crews hustled cartloads of items
into the building.
</P>
<P>
   The move was calculated with military precision. Trucks are
scheduled to arrive every half hour. Computer gurus prowl the
cubicles to connect the equipment.
</P>
<P>
   By Monday, this mission will be accomplished. But the crew has
hundreds of similar missions over the next three years before the
job is down.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is like the marathon, as opposed to the sprint,'' said
Patricia Henriques, president of Management Alternatives Inc., a
Washington moving consultant that has worked with the Pentagon on a
huge renovation of its offices.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday morning, 75 Sprint employees will report to the campus
for the first day of work at a site that's still largely a
construction zone.
</P>
<P>
   That's when already crowded roads and restaurants around the
campus at 119th Street and Nall Avenue will begin the Sprint test.
</P>
<P>
   By the end of the year, the telecommunications company will move
3,500 workers to the campus, spokeswoman Laura Meyer said. The
company expects to haul 10,000 pieces of computer equipment and
35,000 boxes in 500 truckloads for those workers.
</P>
<P>
   The first 75 workers will occupy half a floor, or about 40,000
square feet, in the only campus building near completion. That's
about 1 percent of office space in the Sprint campus.
</P>
<P>
   The entire first building will be completed in three weeks, said
Daniel Euston, project manager for J.E. Dunn Construction Co., the
general contractor.
</P>
<P>
   The Sprint workers will be separated from construction in
progress by barriers, Euston said.
</P>
<P>
   When completed, the 200-acre campus will have 18 office
buildings, 16 parking garages, restaurants, a fitness center, a
child-care center, a 1.7-mile jogging trail and a 3,000-seat
amphitheater.
</P>
<P>
   The Sprint workers moving this weekend are part of a unit that
sells long-distance service to businesses, said Margaret Latshaw, a
Sprint group manager overseeing the move.
</P>
<P>
   Sprint will move an average of 200 workers to the campus each
weekend through October, Meyer said.
</P>
<P>
   The first group was selected because Sprint's lease in One
Kansas City Place at 1200 Main St. expires soon, Latshaw said.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the early moves are dictated by lease issues, Latshaw
said. Sprint now occupies more than 40 leased buildings throughout
the metropolitan area.
</P>
<P>
   Sprint Chief Executive Officer William T. Esrey probably won't
move to the campus until 2001, Meyer said. Sprint owns its
headquarters building in Westwood, and the company is focusing on
moving workers out of leased properties in the first round of
moves.
</P>
<P>
   By early next year, the moves will bring together divisions that
originally were separated to comply with federal rules prohibiting
greater cooperation, Latshaw said. Under current laws, the
divisions -- long-distance and local service -- can work more
closely.
</P>
<P>
   ``This will really be an enabler to get groups to interact in a
way they haven't been able to,'' Latshaw said. ``We now have the
opportunity to bring those walls down.'
</P>
<P>
   While Sprint is knocking down walls between departments, some
Sprint employees are knocking on doors to buy houses near the
campus.
</P>
<P>
   Kathy Larson, an agent with J.C. Nichols Residential, said the
influx of homebuyers into Johnson County was pushing up prices and
causing houses to sell quickly.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's hard to pinpoint whether it's all Sprint, but our market
is booming,'' Larson said. ``There have been a lot of Sprint
employees who have opted to move closer.''
</P>
<P>
   But as Sprint moves in, some residents are moving out.
</P>
<P>
   Judy Meyer, who lives a few blocks from the campus, said her
family was moving this month to a new house a few miles away to
avoid the traffic congestion she expects the 14,500 Sprint workers
to cause in the area.
</P>
<P>
   ``The roads haven't been prepared,'' said Meyer, who isn't
related to Sprint spokeswoman Laura Meyer. ``I feel like this
development thing is just out of control and that people don't
realize the impact to individuals. It's great for the community
because of the new jobs. But it impacts our quality of life, and I
felt like we had to give up our house. That's not replaceable.''
</P>
<P>
   Mark Stuecheli, senior transportation planner for Overland Park,
said widening Nall Avenue from four to six lanes between Interstate
435 and 119th Street would help.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a top-priority project to get done, and it's something
we're pushing for,'' Stuecheli said.
</P>
<P>
   The federal freeze on road expansion projects, however, is a
stumbling block for the Nall project, because officials don't know
whether they can proceed with construction. The project was
supposed be completed by late 2000.
</P>
<P>
   In May the U.S. Department of Transportation ruled that the
area's transportation plans did not meet federal clean-air
requirements. The ruling halted new highway expansion projects and
could affect the Nall plan, officials said.
</P>
<P>
   Not everybody is worried about increased traffic. Nearby
retailers are already seeking ways to attract Sprint employees.
</P>
<P>
   A sign on the Firestone Tire and Service Center at 7050 W. 115th
St. invites Sprint workers to pick up their free employee-discount
card.
</P>
<P>
   Ty Brown, manager of tire sales at Firestone, said the store had
given away 4,000 discount cards since the store opened in April.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sprint employees are an economic force for our business,''
Brown said. He estimated that more than half of the store's
customers were Sprint employees.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
