<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-17 22:04 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4123 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KENNEDY-CURSE-HNS &LR;      07-17 1269
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KENNEDY-CURSE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SORROW ONCE MORE: TRAGEDY STRIKES FAMILY ALL TOO USED TO IT 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By CRAGG HINES 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   A child of tragedy may have become a victim himself.
</P>
<P>
   The disappearance of John F. Kennedy Jr. is just the latest
shock in more than 50 years of sorrow for one of the nation's most
prominent families.
</P>
<P>
   As a toddler, the picture of his snappy salute before the coffin
of his father, the slain president, was etched into the national
conscience.
</P>
<P>
   Over recent years, even with his high media profile and magazine
editor's job, he seemed to be one of the more normal of the Kennedy
cousins _ a brood known as much for public scandal as public
service. JFK Jr. was even moved a few years ago to write that two
cousins, one of whom had an affair with the baby sitter and another
who badgered his wife into a divorce, were ``poster boys for bad
behavior.''
</P>
<P>
   Now, JFK Jr.'s disappearance on a plane he was piloting, and
which carried his wife and her sister, raises anew the question of
a star-crossed family _ and of the ``Kennedy curse.'' That sense
may be heightened by the timing _ the fact that Sunday is the 30th
anniversary of the car accident at Chappaquiddick Island, Mass., in
which Sen. Edward M. Kennedy, D-Mass., swam to safety but a woman
in the car, Mary Jo Kopechne, drowned.
</P>
<P>
   In part, talk of a ``Kennedy curse'' stems from an idea that
patriarch Joseph Kennedy Sr.'s overweening political ambition _
first for himself and then for a succession of sons _ has visited a
heritage of horrors on his offspring.
</P>
<P>
   The debate inevitably becomes ideological as much as emotional.
</P>
<P>
   Liberal commentators focus on the string of tragedies striking a
family that has provided a president, two senators and a host of
other politicians and activists who have risen above their
privileged station to champion the downtrodden. Conservative
analysts see a myth perpetuated by what one called a
``Camelot-clinging'' media.
</P>
<P>
   ``If there's a curse on the Kennedy's, it's pretty much a
self-inflicted wound,'' David Horowitz, author of ``The Kennedys _
An American Drama,'' told television interviewers in 1998 after
cousin Michael Kennedy died in Aspen, Colo. He slammed into a tree
during a game of football on skis.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Kennedy's death emphasized the sometimes reckless, macho
side of the family's exploits _ especially among its men. But it
also revealed an intense bond. An eyewitness to the skiing accident
said sister Rory gave Michael mouth-to-mouth resuscitation,
spitting his blood onto the snow. JFK Jr. was en route to Rory's
wedding when his plane disappeared.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is a clan, and it is tight-knit,'' Horowitz said in the
television interview. ``And it has an almost paranoid stance
against the rest of the world.''
</P>
<P>
   The Kennedy family has a history of heroics and hedonism that
stretches back before World War II, when Joseph Sr. was ambassador
to Britain. He wanted to be the United States' first Roman Catholic
president, but those hopes were dashed not only by religious
intolerance but also by his urging too much caution in the fight
against Hitler and by a longtime and well-known extramarital affair
with actress Gloria Swanson.
</P>
<P>
   He transferred his political aspirations to son Joe Jr., but at
29 the handsome heir was killed as he flew a military mission in
war-torn Europe. Four years later, daughter Kathleen, the adored
``Kick'' who had married into British nobility, also died in an air
crash.
</P>
<P>
   Joseph Sr. quickly refocused his electoral hopes on his second
son, John F. Kennedy, and financed his campaigns for the U.S. House
and Senate from Massachusetts. In 1960, the patriarch's dream was
realized, as JFK narrowly won the White House.
</P>
<P>
   It may have been a charmed administration, but it was also
brushed with sorrow, when in the summer of 1963, son Patrick
Bouvier Kennedy was born premature to first lady Jacqueline Kennedy
and soon died.
</P>
<P>
   Then, 1,000 days into his presidency _ on Nov. 22, 1963 _
Kennedy was assassinated, at age 46, as he rode in an open
limousine through downtown Dallas.
</P>
<P>
   For the family, as well as much of the nation, it was
unbelievable, something more from a Wagnerian plot than history
itself.
</P>
<P>
   By 1968, Joseph Sr.'s third son, Robert F. Kennedy, was seeking
the presidency _ in protest against President Lyndon B. Johnson's
war in southeast Asia and in search of his family's disrupted
legacy. As he left the stage after claiming victory in the
California Democratic primary, RFK, at 43, was gunned down by an
Arab fanatic. His wife, Ethel S. Kennedy, was pregnant with Rory.
</P>
<P>
   What had been tragic for the family would soon become surreal.
</P>
<P>
   In the summer of 1969, as man was landing on the moon, the
fourth Kennedy son, Sen. Edward M. Kennedy, drove off a bridge at
Chappaquiddick, the incident in which Kopechne was killed.
</P>
<P>
   The death and the senator's murky explanations of the events
effectively ended any prospect he would make it to the White House,
although he sought the nomination in 1980 against the incumbent
Democrat, President Carter.
</P>
<P>
   Soon the line of tragedy and scandal shifted to the next
generation of Kennedys, especially RFK's children. In 1973, Joseph
Kennedy III was the driver in an accident that left a woman
passenger paralyzed for life. In 1984, his brother, David, was
found dead of a heroin overdose in a Florida hotel, after he had
been kicked out of the family's Palm Beach estate.
</P>
<P>
   In 1991, a night of partying at the family's seaside compound
resulted in rape charges against another cousin, William Kennedy
Smith. He was acquitted, but testimony at his trial included
details of Sen. Ted Kennedy wandering about in his underwear while
the younger generation sought sex with locals.
</P>
<P>
   Shortly before Michael Kennedy's death, he was implicated in a
sexual affair with the family baby sitter. At about the same time,
his brother, Rep. Joseph Kennedy III, D-Mass., was getting a Roman
Catholic annulment so he could remarry.
</P>
<P>
   As in the Chappaquiddick incident, the more recent cases raised
questions about whether the Kennedys receive special treatment, in
these cases from the law and the church.
</P>
<P>
   Although Michael's baby sitter was a teen-ager, and he could
have faced statutory rape charges, he did not because the girl and
her family would not press charges or cooperate fully in the
investigation.
</P>
<P>
   In the case of Joe's annulment, the archdiocese of Boston had to
come up with some canonical reason to allow dissolution of a
marriage that was long enough and intimate enough it had produced
twin boys.
</P>
<P>
   Joe's ex-wife, Sheila Rauch Kennedy, responded with a book,
Shattered Faith, in which she alleges he treated her like a
``nobody.''
</P>
<P>
   Amid the controversy and his defense of Michael, Joe scrapped
his plan to run for governor of Massachusetts and also did not seek
re-election to the House. At the same time, new accounts emerged of
JFK's extramarital sexual escapades while president, which included
a liaison with a Mafia moll.
</P>
<P>
   Amid the troubled swirl that made up the lives of some of his
cousins, JFK Jr., even with all his glamor and media attention,
seemed extraordinarily sound and sane.
</P>
<P>
   In a recent magazine article, RFK son Christopher said about a
third of his cousins were regulars at Alcoholics Anonymous, ``and
clearly a number of them have spent time in rehabilitation clinics
around the country.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a big family,'' Joe has said. ``There are always going to
be a few little problems along the way.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
