<SLUG> BC-HKN-NHL </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WILL BRUINS PAY PRICE IF KHRISTICH REMAINS 
</HEADLINE>
 NOTEBOOK-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By NANCY L. MARRAPESE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ So, Dmitri Khristich has filed for arbitration again.
</P>
<P>
   Don't get me wrong, it's his right as defined by the collective
bargaining agreement.
</P>
<P>
   He's a Group 2 (restricted) free agent and the Bruins made him
the requisite qualifying offer of 10 percent over his $1.95 million
salary to protect their rights to him.
</P>
<P>
   If the Bruins had their way, they would've traded Khristich a
long time ago. Around the time of the entry draft in Boston at the
end of last month, the club talked to other teams in an effort to
pull off a deal. It was unsuccessful. Too bad. It's only going to
get harder from this point, especially if Khristich pockets a $3
million award from an arbitrator at his hearing next month.
</P>
<P>
   ``We talked to a lot of clubs,'' president/general manager Harry
Sinden said then. ``But they look at Khristich the way we do. He's
a good player who can score 25-30 goals but when you need him, is
he going to be there? We'd like to keep him. He's been here two
years and the longer he stays, I think the more he'll feel some
loyalty to the team. He drives (coach Pat Burns) nuts. To be a
talent like that and then be invisible some nights. It's
frustrating.''
</P>
<P>
   Too bad the Bruins couldn't get the Rangers, who signed away Tim
Taylor and have been throwing money around like it's nothing, to
bite on a deal for Khristich.
</P>
<P>
   For the past two years, Khristich has scored 29 goals. That's
great and all, but for the final quarter of the season and the
entire playoffs, Khristich was flat-out awful. He played with as
much intensity as a game of shinny on a New Hampshire pond during a
mid-morning in January. An empty sweater would have been just as
effective.
</P>
<P>
   It's easy to second-guess the Bruins' stranglehold on the purse
strings, their decision to not lock up Taylor long before free
agency was even an issue, and a multitude of other things. However,
on the subject of Khristich, it's impossible not to share
management's frustration.
</P>
<P>
   At the end of the season, Sinden teed off on center Jason
Allison and Khristich's performances in the second round against
Buffalo. Sinden mitigated his comments a day later on Allison,
saying he didn't get much help with Khristich as a linemate, but
reinforced his comments that Khristich was a bitter disappointment.
</P>
<P>
   ``He wants all this money because he gets a few goals that are
meaningless, really,'' said Sinden after Boston was eliminated by
the Sabres. ``Meaningless goals. I need him in the playoffs.''
</P>
<P>
   The big question is will they endure Khristich's inconsistency
for a third season? The team has the option to walk away from the
award Khristich receives if it decides it doesn't want to pay it,
making him an unrestricted free agent. The downside of that,
however, is they will have lost him for nothing. It's not as if the
Bruins have 29-goal scorers just hanging around, waiting to take
Khristich's place.
</P>
<P>
   Wouldn't you love to be a fly on the wall for that hearing?
Sinden, armed with a case of videotapes defying the arbitrator to
find Khristich in any of the games against the Sabres; Khristich
relying on the numbers to justify his demands.
</P>
<P>
   The Bruins have the better case, not that it always matters, and
in the near future, could have a tough decision to make.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   If you want to find out where and when Bruins goalie Byron Dafoe
will be in your area this offseason, the netminder has an updated
web site that lists his personal appearances as well as other
pertinent information. To access it, go to
www.geocities.com/colosseum/stands/7752 . . . The world became a
poorer place last week with the passing of Philadelphia broadcaster
Gene Hart. Hart had an enthusiastic love of his sport and equal
enthusiasm for life. He was always quick with a greeting, a smile,
and a colorful story. He will be missed . . . It's possible that
former Bruins goalie Bill Ranford, who did two stints in Boston,
could be headed back to Edmonton for his second stint with the
Oilers, with whom he won a Stanley Cup in 1990. Since leaving
Edmonton, his career has been a real mixed bag. After almost nine
seasons in Edmonton, Ranford has been on four teams in four years.
After parts of two seasons with the Bruins, Ranford was traded to
Washington. From there, he was traded to dreadful Tampa Bay and
then to Detroit. The Red Wings bought him out at the end of the
season. ``He's only 32 years old and I'm sure he can recapture his
form,'' said Oilers president/general manager Glen Sather. If he
does, it's likely to be as a backup to probable No. 1 netminder
Tommy Salo. Ranford made nearly $3.1 million last season. If he
signs with Edmonton, the pay day will be, well, less. ``A lot
less,'' said Sather. If there's hope for locking up a backup,
Sather said he was thrown a strong curveball by his No. 1 goalie.
Sather said Salo and his agent, Rich Winter, had an understanding
about not going to arbitration and Sather said he was stunned when
Winter and Salo filed for a hearing. ``I didn't have a written
agreement but I had a verbal agreement,'' Sather said. ``I don't
think it's right that you give somebody your word and go back on
it, but that's his choice.'' Not surprisingly, Winter had a
different version. ``There appears to be a disagreement, a
misunderstanding, or a lack of consensus on the understanding that
preceded the trade (from the Islanders),'' said Winter. ``Tommy and
I made it clear to Glen we will be available to discuss that.
Hopefully, those discussions will lead to an arrangement.'' The
miscommunication or posturing or whatever between management and
goalie isn't the only story coming out of Edmonton. There is a
strong rumor floating that the club is trying to shop center Doug
Weight, who is coming off a serious knee injury. Sather vehemently
denies it. It already has been a long, hot summer for Sather, who
has 15 free agents to sign, with several heavy hitters among them,
including Bill Guerin, Roman Hamrlik, and Mike Grier. With a team
on a tight budget, the Oilers could make several deals before camp.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Sad to see yet another player forced into retirement because of
a concussion problem. The latest is big defenseman Jeff Beukeboom,
who bid farewell to the Rangers at the age of 34. Beukeboom
absorbed significant blows to the head in November when hit by the
Kings' Matt Johnson, was hit again in December, and had another
concussion Feb. 12 in a game against the Carolina Hurricanes. He
still has headaches and has trouble concentrating. ``My situation
over five months, the symptoms have not subsided,'' said Beukeboom,
who won four Stanley Cups in his career. ``It's never an easy
decision to walk away but it's easier to walk away because of
medical problems. I believe physically I could still compete. I
know medically the risk I would put my family in. My body is
healthy. My mind is not healthy right now.'' Maybe it's not
realistic to think this but for heaven's sake, we can send a man to
the moon but we can't come up with a helmet design to protect
people's heads from concussions? There has to be an answer out
there . . . Former Bruins goalie and all-around good guy Craig
Billington has changed addresses again. After three years as a
backup to Patrick Roy in Colorado, the 32-year-old Billington was
dealt to the Washington Capitals for future considerations. He is
slotted to back up Olaf Kolzig . . . Carolina general manager Jim
Rutherford has a real dilemma _ how to honor the late Steve
Chiasson. By all accounts, Chiasson was a wonderful person, great
family man, and first-class teammate. That's how the Hurricanes and
his family want to remember him. The tough part is coming to terms
with the circumstances under which Chiasson died May 3. He was
legally drunk when he rolled his pickup truck over in the wee hours
on the night the Bruins eliminated Carolina from the first round of
the playoffs. ``It is very important to us that we do remember him
and recognize him properly but the question is how to do that,''
said Rutherford. ``We're dealing with some issues when we talk
about this.'' Rutherford said the club has consulted those who deal
with the league's alcohol and substance abuse programs in an effort
to honor Chiasson properly . . . Perhaps carrying the weight of all
those Dallas Stars fans took its toll after all. Whatever the
cause, Stars coach Ken Hitchcock had to endure surgery to repair a
softball-sized hernia. The 47-year-old was supposed to go home to
Edmonton for a golf tournament, with the Stanley Cup in tow, when
the medical procedure intervened, forcing him to remain at his home
in Dallas. ``It was a full-blown hernia and it was awfully big,''
said Hitchcock. ``I'm motoring around like a normal human being and
getting better every day. I'll be fine.'' . . . Only 48 days to
training camp. The real question is will Dafoe be there?
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
