<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KC-SUPERINTENDENT-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DEMPS SAYS HE IS READY TO EASE `BURDEN' OF CHILDREN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PHILLIP O'CONNOR  
 c. 1999 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. -- The simple question stirs a passionate
response from Benjamin Demps Jr. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Why? &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Why would a 65-year-old with no experience in public education
want to leave a comfortable life of semiretirement in Oklahoma City
to take on what many consider the metropolitan area's major puzzle
-- the Kansas City School District? &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``There are some things in life that go beyond comfort,'' said
Demps, a retired Federal Aviation Administration official who
served as director of the Oklahoma Department of Human Services in
the early 1990s. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``I realized that all of those children would be entering into
society in the United States ... without a capacity to perform at a
standard Americans generally would look for,'' Demps said Saturday
to The Kansas City Star. ``That is one heck of a burden for young
people in America to have to deal with. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``We have got to educate our children in America irrespective of
the color of their skin. That's what I feel. Have I felt this
strongly about it? Yes. Have I had an opportunity to voice it? No.
I have never been in a position to do something for an organization
with the duty of educating children. That's what's driving me. To
me, that's pretty doggone exciting and challenging -- to get it
done.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The school board and Demps reached agreement Friday on a
two-year contract that would pay him about $200,000 a year in
salary and benefits. Demps celebrated the deal by taking in a
late-night showing of the latest Star Wars movie. He left midway
through. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``My mind was on other things,'' he said. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Demps' contract still must be approved by the court-appointed
Desegregation Monitoring Committee. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Reached in Florida on Saturday night, committee chairman John
Murphy said approval was assured. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh sure, absolutely, no problem, no question at all,'' Murphy
said. ``I'm pleased. He's a fine man, and maybe now we can all work
together and move things forward rapidly.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Board members expect to introduce Demps to U.S. District Judge
Dean Whipple at a court hearing scheduled for 10 a.m. Monday. He is
scheduled to start work Aug. 1. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Demps on Saturday declined to outline his plan for the first
weeks of his administration. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``I have some very cogent thoughts about that, but I have not
yet put the priorities in order,'' he said. ``I'm not, at this
point, ready to say what those are.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   He said he would move quickly to hire a top educator to oversee
instructional issues. Demps said he already had contacted various
education experts and others, seeking input on candidates. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Demps also met for about two hours Saturday afternoon with
Arthur A. Benson II, attorney for the plaintiff schoolchildren in
the desegregation lawsuit. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``We had a very informative exchange,'' Benson said. ``I'm very
favorably impressed. He had many very perceptive questions, none of
which I feel at liberty to share.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Demps said he was not bothered that the board first offered the
job to two other candidates. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Retired Air Force Maj. Gen. Jay T. Edwards and former U.S.
education commissioner Pascal Forgione both withdrew in the midst
of negotiations. A fourth finalist, John Martin, was never offered
the job but also withdrew. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``The point here is someone decided there were four individuals
who were competent or worthy of looking at and my name came
third,'' Demps said. ``If I were a football player picked in the
third round of the draft, I'd still be playing football. I still
have a chance to prove myself.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Demps said he would develop a positive relationship with the
school board, which voted 7-1, with one abstention, to approve his
contract. But he said he did not consider it his responsibility to
mend any rifts that exist among board members. He said conflict was
to be expected in any public body. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``If all the citizens of a community were of one mind, we
wouldn't need these boards,'' he said. ``I don't see anything here
as adversarial. Reasonable people are going to differ always.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Demps said he would work with the monitoring committee. The
previous superintendent, Henry Williams, frequently complained
about the committee's authority over day-to-day district matters. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``They are a factor I must take into consideration,'' Demps
said. ``I must accept their direction if it's given, and if they
want to have a discourse I am certainly going to be eager to have
that discourse. I see no gain in fighting, fighting, fighting.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Demps said he was not worried about the negative publicity that
has dogged previous superintendents. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``That has nothing to do with me,'' he said. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Nor is he concerned about being in the public eye. Demps is
learning about the notoriety that surrounds the Kansas City school
superintendent. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Returning to his hotel Friday evening just minutes after
reaching agreement on the contract, the doorman congratulated him
by name. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   During a tour of the city Saturday, strangers frequently wished
him luck. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   At his hotel Saturday evening, a man interrupted a conversation
to give Demps a thumbs-up and a word of encouragement. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Demps said he planned to spend today relaxing and thinking about
what lies ahead. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel I have a chance to use my diverse experiences and bring
that together with my firm belief in the concept of America and
democracy and equality,'' he said. ``I can bring that all to bear
in one place. I'm excited about it.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
