<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-NL-COLUMN-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LIEBERTHAL BOOSTS PHILLY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MATT McHALE  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Philadelphia's Mike Lieberthal leads NL catchers in RBI, but
it's his defensive ability that has helped turn the Phillies into a
contender.
</P>
<P>
   Lieberthal, the Westlake High product who played in his first
All-Star game on Tuesday, gives a lot of credit for his defense to
Texas catcher Ivan Rodriguez, eight-time All-Star and eight-time
Gold Glove winner.
</P>
<P>
   ``I try to get as much out of him as I can,'' Lieberthal said.
``He's definitely the one guy I watch more than any other. He's one
of the few catchers who plays 150 games a year. That's something I
want to do.''
</P>
<P>
   Although the Phillies only play the Rangers a couple of times a
year in spring training, Lieberthal always spends time talking to
Rodriguez about how he approaches the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``He talks to me a lot about things behind the plate,''
Rodriguez said. ``I like it when people come up to me and ask what
they should do. That means they want to be a better player.
Lieberthal is the kind of guy who likes to learn. I'm not surprised
he's an All-Star. He's a great hitter.'' &QL; 
__ Trachsel hopes for better
</P>
<P>
   Cubs right-hander Steve Trachsel finally stopped his losing
streak at eight last Sunday, beating the White Sox 6-3. Trachsel, a
15-game winner last year, starts the second half 3-12.
</P>
<P>
   While Trachsel has a 6.53 ERA, don't be surprised if the Cubs
find a way to trade him before the July 31 deadline. His contract
is up after this season and they would love him to have a few more
good starts so they can get something for him.
</P>
<P>
   Trachsel isn't the only struggling pitcher on the staff. Cubs
starters had an 8.97 ERA from June 9 to July 8, but the team
doesn't thipX&AMP;SyTi+$K$XZYHW-[YK,X9
</P>
