</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KENNEDY-CRASH-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOPE DIMS AS SEARCH CONTINUES FOR JFK JR. 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By BENNETT ROTH 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ The prospect grew stronger late Saturday that yet
another deadly tragedy may have befallen the Kennedy family as
searchers in boats and helicopters combed the waters near Martha's
Vineyard, where a plane carrying John F. Kennedy Jr., his wife and
sister-in-law had apparently crashed.
</P>
<P>
   The son of the former president, still known to many Americans
as ``John John,'' was on his way to a cousin's wedding Friday night
when the plane he was piloting failed to show up at the resort
island off of Cape Cod.
</P>
<P>
   By midday Saturday, Coast Guard officials had determined that
the single-engine, six-seat Piper Saratoga, which had embarked from
northern New Jersey, had likely gone down about 17 miles off the
coast of Martha's Vineyard.
</P>
<P>
   Kennedy, 38, had been traveling with his wife, Carolyn Bessette,
33, and her 35-year-old sister Lauren.
</P>
<P>
   While the Coast Guard, aided by the Air Force, had not located
bodies or substantive wreckage by late Saturday, they found
pertinent debris, including luggage belonging to Lauren Bessette, a
prescription drug bottle in the name of Carolyn Bessette Kennedy,
and a cosmetics bag. They also picked up an aircraft seat, a black
pedal cover and landing gear parts belonging to a plane that fit
the description of the aircraft flown by Kennedy.
</P>
<P>
   The Coast Guard temporarily called off the aerial search after
nightfall Saturday, but kept a helicopter with special infrared
heat-seeking equipment aloft through the night to try to detect
material or bodies in the search area.
</P>
<P>
   Also, the Coast Guard will be aided through the night hours by a
research vessel operated by the National Oceanographic and
Atmospheric Administration. The vessel, called Rude, uses sonar to
detect wreckage.
</P>
<P>
   Despite that the chances of finding anyone alive were dimming as
the day wore on, Coast Guard searchers late Saturday were still
classifying their operation as a search-and-rescue effort.
</P>
<P>
   Rear Adm. Richard M. Larrabee, the First District Coast Guard
Commander in Boston, said searchers had not given up hope that the
plane's passengers might be alive.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can tell you miraculous stories about people surviving. I
can tell you in previous cases like this we've searched for as many
as three or four days. We're not ready to give up on this yet, and
we're going to continue to focus on search and rescue,'' said
Larrabee.
</P>
<P>
   Yet the ominous feeling that another member of this famous
family had met a premature death appeared only to grow as the day
wore on. As they have so many times in the past, the Kennedys
secluded themselves at the family compound in Hyannis Port awaiting
the news and comforting one another. Ironically, many family
members had visited for a joyous occasion, the wedding of Rory
Kennedy, the daughter of Robert and Ethel Kennedy.
</P>
<P>
   JFK Jr. was expected to attend the wedding after dropping off
Lauren Bessette in Martha's Vineyard and continuing on to Hyannis
Port. But the wedding was called off, and the white tent that had
been pitched for dining instead became a sanctuary for prayer.
</P>
<P>
   Police on Saturday afternoon cleared the beach on a section of
Martha's Vineyard popularly known as Gay Head as debris from what
appeared to be the Kennedy's plane started washing ashore.
</P>
<P>
   Erin McCarthy, 31, of Boston, who was sun bathing on the beach,
told The Associated Press she saw a black bag with Lauren
Bessette's name on it in the water. A friend, Damon Seligson, waded
in to retrieve it.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was kind of like, `Oh, God.' It seemed like it would be
pretty bad news. Everyone was shaking,'' said McCarthy.
</P>
<P>
   The news of Kennedy's disappearance shocked a nation that for
decades has been transfixed by the towering successes and
astounding tragedies of a family that has come closer than any
other to American royalty.
</P>
<P>
   At airports people stood dumbfounded in front of television sets
while politicians, including Vice President Al Gore, offered words
of support for the family. All of the major television networks
broke into their regular coverage to provide updates on the search
as well as to once again chronicle the Kennedy family saga.
</P>
<P>
   It is a story that includes the assassination of Kennedy's
father in 1963 and his uncle Robert five years later. The weekend
also marked the 30th anniversary of the Chappiquidick incident when
Sen. Edward Kennedy, D-Mass., drove a car into the water near a
tiny island next to Martha's Vineyard, resulting in the drowning of
his passenger, Mary Jo Kopechne.
</P>
<P>
   Kennedy's mother, Jacqueline Kennedy Onassis, died of cancer in
1994. JFK Jr. has one sister, Carolyn, who was rafting out West
when the plane went down.
</P>
<P>
   For the older generation, the image of Kennedy still remains
that of the young ``John John'' frolicking in the Oval Office and
later standing at attention saluting his father's casket as it
rolled down Pennsylvania Avenue in Washington, D.C.
</P>
<P>
   But for those born after his father's death, the younger Kennedy
was America's heartthrob, considered one of the sexiest men in the
nation.
</P>
<P>
   While others mentioned him as a possible political candidate,
the younger Kennedy did not demonstrate the same affinity for
elected office as some of his cousins. After graduating from law
school he found his niche in publishing by launching George
magazine. Three years ago he married Carolyn Bessette, a poised and
beautiful woman who specialized in public relations.
</P>
<P>
   The couple lived in the trendy Manhattan neighborhood of
Tribeca.
</P>
<P>
   A year ago Kennedy obtained his pilot's license. On Friday, he
took off from Essex County Airport in Fairfield , N.J., about 8:30
p.m. EDT with the expectation of landing in Martha's Vineyard about
10 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   When the plane did not arrive, family members alerted the Coast
Guard around 2:15 a.m. About 3:30 a.m. the Air Force received a
signal from Long Island that it initially thought might have come
from the downed plane. But that signal proved to be a false lead.
</P>
<P>
   At 7:30 am, the Coast Guard launched a full-scale search ranging
from New Jersey to the Massachusetts coast. Since Kennedy had not
filed a flight plan, officials could not be sure where the plane
might have gone down.
</P>
<P>
   But by midday, the Coast Guard had narrowed down the likely
crash area to 17 miles off the coast of Martha's Area, the last
place where the FAA had been able to track the plane. Shortly after
that debris from the plane was discovered off of Philbin Beach.
</P>
<P>
   The FAA reported that it had lost contact with the plane while
it was on final approach to the Martha's Vineyard airport about
9:39 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   A Coast Guard official involved in the search said Saturday that
radar signals Friday night showed a plane approaching the airport
at an altitude of 2,500 feet, then descending to 2,200 feet.
</P>
<P>
   Only 12 seconds later, the time it takes the radar to make one
sweep, the device showed the plane at 1,300 feet, indicating a
descent rate of about 4,000 feet per minute that would be reached
only in a steep dive.
</P>
<P>
   Larrabee said that it was not unusual for Kennedy not to file a
flight plan. Nor did he believe there was any equipment problems or
severe weather conditions.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no indication that there was anything out of the
ordinary,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Larrabee said that while it was hot and hazy Saturday ``the
search conditions are good.''
</P>
<P>
   He said the water depths in the area range from 20 to 100 feet.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
