<HEADLINE>
MONDESI'S HOMER A HIT WITH TEAM
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MATT McHALE  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANAHEIM, Calif. _ After Raul Mondesi reached home plate Saturday
after his first home run since June 8, he punched the air. He
smacked Gary Sheffield's hand with a resounding high five and waded
into the Dodgers dugout like a heavyweight coming into the ring.
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt great freedom,'' Mondesi said after the Dodgers 13-3
victory over the Angels at Edison Field. ``I never gave up hope,
never lost confidence. I figured if I worked hard, it would come
back to me.''
</P>
<P>
   Mondesi hit his 20th homer of the season off knuckleballer Steve
Sparks, a two-out, two-run shot in the third that gave the Dodgers
a 4-0 lead. It was just his second since May 28. He had gone 112
at-bats without a homer, including a first-inning strikeout that
made him 1 for 10 in the series.
</P>
<P>
   ``That shot was so important to this team,'' said Eric Karros,
who hit two homers to move within one of Mondesi for the team lead.
``We don't have one guy who can carry the team. Everyone has to
contribute. We've missed him. I hope he's back.''
</P>
<P>
   Mondesi also doubled to right in the ninth and scored the
Dodgers' final run. Manager Davey Johnson said the double was just
as impressive because it showed Mondesi was using the whole field.
</P>
<P>
   ``When players get frustrated, they try to pull everything,''
Johnson said. ``You could see a big load had been lifted from his
shoulders.''
</P>
<P>
   __ More bad news: Antonio Osuna's injury-plagued season could be
over. The Dodgers relief pitcher learned Saturday he has a partial
tear of the ulnar collateral ligament in his right elbow.
</P>
<P>
   Osuna, who underwent an MRI Thursday, is expected to decide
today whether to have season-ending surgery or seek an alternative
method. Early this season he balked at the thought of surgery to
remove bone chips from his elbow but went ahead after attempts to
throw pain-free failed. If Osuna has the surgery, it will be the
third on his right elbow since last August. He underwent the MRI
after experiencing discomfort in the elbow after pitching one
inning Wednesday in a rehab assignment for Class-A San Bernardino.
</P>
<P>
   Osuna made five appearances with the Dodgers this year, going
0-0 with a 7.71 ERA.
</P>
<P>
   __ Crime and punishment: The Dodgers were hoping NL president
Leonard Coleman might reduce the suspensions after requesting he
watch last Sunday's fight with Seattle a second time. It didn't
happen and coach Rick Dempsey began serving his 17-day suspension
that ends Aug. 3. Jamie Arnold, suspended five games and fined
$1,000, and Todd Hundley, suspended three games and fined $1,000,
have filed appeals and were available Saturday. Arnold took over
for Chan Ho Park with one out in the seventh inning and finished
the game.
</P>
<P>
   Dempsey, whose combative nature landed him in many fights during
his 24-year career, was suspended three games and fined $3,500 for
decking Philadelphia's Lenny Dykstra at home plate in 1990. In
perhaps the most famous fight involving the Dodgers, Giants pitcher
Juan Marichal was suspended eight games and fined $1,750 for
striking catcher John Roseboro over the head with a bat in August
1965. Roseboro later sued Marichal for $110,000 and settled for
$7,500.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
