<SLUG> BC-BBA-RANGERS-DIAMONDBACKS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RANGERS' WETTELAND ROUGHED UP AS DIAMONDBACKS WIN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOHNNY PAUL 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
ARLINGTON _ The Rangers' manager says his closer will be fine.
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Rangers' pitching coach says the closer will be fine.
</P>
<P>
   Arizona manager Buck Showalter says the Rangers' John Wetteland
is ``as good as any closer you're going to find.''
</P>
<P>
   Wetteland's right elbow might be saying otherwise.
</P>
<P>
   Wetteland's ninth- and 10th-inning failures during yesterday's
8-6 loss to the Diamondbacks fuel speculation regarding the
closer's health. Wetteland failed to convert his third consecutive
save opportunity and fifth in the past eight chances by
surrendering ninth-inning home runs to Arizona's Kelly Stinnett and
Jay Bell.
</P>
<P>
   The loss belonged to Wetteland, too, after left fielder Rusty
Greer lost a fly ball in the late-afternoon sun. The ball dropped
for a two-run double in the 10th, and that two-out ``hit'' by Tony
Womack scored two of the three runners right-hander Esteban Loaiza
inherited from the closer.
</P>
<P>
   Wetteland (3-4) underwent arthroscopic surgery Oct. 27 to remove
a bone chip and spur from his right elbow, but the hard-throwing
right-hander will not use that as an alibi.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know where to go with that,'' said Wetteland, who
surrendered two home runs during a game for only the second time in
514 major-league appearances. ``You know what I'm going to say.
No.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet, Wetteland will concede that the surgery robbed him of his
best fastball.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah, there's a difference in velocity,'' Wetteland said,
``but if you throw four pitches _ and I'm mixing them all in _ you
should be able to work around that. It's not just fastballs I'm
getting beat on. I'm getting beat on fastballs. I'm getting beat on
curveballs. I'm getting beat on changeups and sliders.''
</P>
<P>
   Stinnett pounded an 0-1 curveball for his home run, while Bell
deposited an 0-1 fastball into The Ballpark in Arlington's
right-field seats for his game-tying blast.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm just not getting it done,'' said Wetteland, who has
surrendered eight home runs after allowing only six during all of
last season. ``There's no excuse for it. I'm just not getting the
job done.''
</P>
<P>
   Wetteland retired center fielder Steve Finley to begin the 10th
inning, but David Delluci lined a single off the pitcher's glove
for an infield single. Wetteland then made matters worse by issuing
consecutive walks to first baseman Travis Lee and shortstop Hanley
Frias to load the bases.
</P>
<P>
   Rangers manager Johnny Oates could watch no more and removed
Wetteland from a game for the first time this season. Loaiza
replaced Wetteland and struck out Stinnett for the inning's second
out and induced what appeared would be an inning-ending fly ball
from Womack.
</P>
<P>
   Left field, though, becomes a nightmare for an outfielder from 5
p.m. to 7:30 p.m., and Greer lost the ball in the bright sun.
</P>
<P>
   ``I backed up to keep the ball from going by me,'' Greer said.
``I had no clue where it was.''
</P>
<P>
   Dellucci and Lee scored, and that would be the decisive blow in
a game that took nearly four hours to complete.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is probably one of the toughest periods of my career,''
said Wetteland, who has failed to convert seven of 33 save
opportunities. ``I honestly don't have a lot of answers for it.''
</P>
<P>
   Oates does not, either, but the manager dismissed the elbow as
the source for Wetteland's recent rash of failures.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's nothing there physically wrong,'' Oates said. ``We'll
sit and talk and figure out the best thing to get him back on
track. John Wetteland is going to fine. The key is patience.'' nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
