<SLUG> BC-DALLAS-REAX-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DEALEY PLAZA VISITORS SHOCKED, SADDENED
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY MARY DOCLAR and KRISTIN N. SULLIVAN 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DALLAS _ Christine Gonzalez wept Saturday as she stood near the
sloping street where President Kennedy was assassinated almost 36
years ago.
</P>
<P>
   At the same spot where thousands of people from around the world
have come to mourn the dead president, Gonzalez came to pray for
Kennedy's son.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm just praying that he's not dead,'' said Gonzalez, 54, of
Grand Prairie. ``I have followed John-John's life. I just pray
against all odds that he's alive.''
</P>
<P>
   Hope mingled with grief Saturday as the crowds that flock to
Dealey Plaza each weekend coped with the news that John F. Kennedy
Jr., his wife and his sister-in-law were missing after their plane
disappeared near Martha's Vineyard.
</P>
<P>
   Memories of President Kennedy's last moments rolling down Elm
Street in his presidential motorcade were intertwined Saturday with
remembrances of his son, especially the unforgettable image of
3-year-old John-John saluting his father's coffin during Kennedy's
funeral procession.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm just horribly sad,'' said Anne Corrow of Plymouth, Minn.,
who visited Dealey Plaza and the Sixth Floor Museum, which is
dedicated to President Kennedy's life and death. ``I think it's
affected people. It's very quiet and people are very somber.''
</P>
<P>
   At the Sixth Floor Museum, visitors scrawled their reflections
about the latest tragedy on pieces of crisp, white paper in
three-ring leather binders. Fresh flowers were to be placed inside
the museum if John Kennedy Jr.'s death is confirmed, officials
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``To be in Dallas at this time, on this day ...'' wrote Judy
Caputo of Cleveland, Ohio. ``My prayers are with the Kennedy
family, and thank you for this experience.''
</P>
<P>
   Jeff West, executive director of the Sixth Floor Museum, said
that Saturday's grief was for the loss not only of the man with the
Hollywood good looks, but for someone with a bright political
future.
</P>
<P>
   ``For me, it's a mourning of what would have been,'' West said.
``At 38 years old, he had years before he had to worry about time
running out.''
</P>
<P>
   Some tourists said that the loss of John Kennedy Jr. would truly
signal the end of the Kennedy dynasty.
</P>
<P>
   ``His life just started ... and then it's over,'' said Johnathan
Walker, 27, of Ontario, Canada. ``He just got married. He didn't
even have a chance to have a family. The Kennedy legacy ends now.
That line is gone.'' David Vershaw of Dallas said that his wife was
so upset by the situation that she stayed in the car while he,
Walker and another friend visited the Kennedy assassination site.
</P>
<P>
   ``There does seem to be a strange sense of irony to it,''
Vershaw said. ``I've heard that the family was cursed. I don't know
if I believe that, but they do have their share of tragedy.''
</P>
<P>
   Some of the expressions of grief Saturday were impromptu. John
Nagel, a tour guide and sales director at The Conspiracy Museum in
downtown Dallas, walked down Elm Street carrying a white cross that
he said has been used to commemorate the anniversary of President
Kennedy's death.
</P>
<P>
   He placed the cross, which was decorated with artificial lilies
and the words ``JFK. Only truth shall keep us free,'' at the place
on Elm where President Kennedy was shot.
</P>
<P>
   Then he urged those around him to pray.
</P>
<P>
   ``We wanted to let the Kennedy family know our prayers are with
them,'' he said, adding later, ``Maybe in a sad way, John-John got
to see his dad again.''
</P>
<P>
   Although the conspiracy theorists who gather at Dealey Plaza
every weekend were doing a brisk business Saturday, most said they
do not suspect foul play in John Kennedy Jr.'s loss.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe in conspiracies, obviously,'' said Robert Groden,
who has written eight publications about his theories on Kennedy's
death. ``But I think this is just a tragic accident.''
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
