<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-17 23:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4320 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-astros-HNS &LR;      07-17 0872
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-astros-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
Astros prevail after Tigers test Bell's patience
<TEXT>
<P>
   By CARLTON THOMPSON &QL; 
Houston Chronicle
</P>
<P>
   The source of just about everyone's frustration with Derek Bell
has centered on the way he has swung the bat this year. Ironically,
he may have won back some fans Saturday simply by not swinging the
bat at all.
</P>
<P>
   Bell's bases-loaded 10th-inning walk forced home the winning run
in the Astros' 3-2 victory over the Detroit Tigers at the
Astrodome. Bell pumped his fist into the air as he made the
obligatory trot to first base, and the crowd of 41,177 erupted as
Craig Biggio crossed the plate for the winning run.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was very satisfying,'' said Bell, who has been a target
of criticism after comments he made about the fans and being
dropped to the sixth spot in the batting order. ``With the game on
the line, my approach was to be patient and get a good pitch to
hit. I never got a good pitch to hit, so I took the walk, and that
was good enough for us to win the game.''
</P>
<P>
   The Astros completed a three-game sweep of the Tigers and
extended their winning streak to a season-high six games. They
remained in sole possession of first place in the National League
Central, one game ahead of Cincinnati, which defeated Colorado on
Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   The Cleveland Indians, owners of the best record in baseball,
open a three-game series at the Astrodome beginning today. Having
swept their last two series _ both against American League
competition _ the Astros might be catching the Indians at a good
time.
</P>
<P>
   ``The way we're feeling right now, everyone is positive,''
Astros shortstop Tim Bogar said. ``We're playing a little better,
and our pitching has been great the last six games.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, the Astros have posted a 3.11 earned run average during
their winning streak, including another solid effort Saturday by
Jose Lima, who allowed two runs in seven innings, and relievers
Doug Henry and Billy Wagner, who combined for three scoreless
innings to close out the Tigers.
</P>
<P>
   Wagner, battling flu symptoms, struck out three batters over the
final two innings to earn his second win. But it was a former
Astros closer _ Wagner's predecessor, Todd Jones _ who contributed
the finishing touches to this victory.
</P>
<P>
   Jones, who entered the game with two outs in the bottom of the
ninth inning, quickly found himself in a mess in the 10th.
</P>
<P>
   After Biggio led off with a single, Bill Spiers reached on a
questionable hit toward the mound that should have been fielded by
Jones. Instead, it was the first of back-to-back infield singles;
Jeff Bagwell followed with the other.
</P>
<P>
   Jones nearly escape the jam, striking out Richard Hidalgo and
pinch hitter Jack Howell, but he fell behind in the count to Bell
and eventually walked the Astros' right fielder, who has received
only 27 free passes this season.
</P>
<P>
   ``Derek doesn't walk much, so it took a lot of restraint,''
Astros manager Larry Dierker said.
</P>
<P>
   And, according to Jones, a little help from home-plate umpire
Greg Bonin. Jones took exception with Bonin's call on his 2-0
delivery to Bell.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought it was (a strike), and so did (catcher) Brad
(Ausmus),'' said Jones, who has allowed nine runs in his last 3
innings against the Astros, dating to last season. ``That changed
the situation obviously, because it's 3-0 instead of 2-1. I got a
break when Hidalgo swung at a 2-0 pitch out of the zone, but I
didn't get a break on Bell.''
</P>
<P>
   But Bagwell said the credit goes to Bell.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was a great at-bat for Derek,'' the Astros' first baseman
said. ``Obviously, he's had some problems lately swinging at bad
pitches. But he waited for a good one this time, and it paid off.
That's what veterans do.''
</P>
<P>
   Lima, who matched a season high with 10 strikeouts, allowed only
two runners to reach scoring position through the first six
innings, but he began to tire in the seventh when the first three
batters he faced reached base.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was disappointed that I didn't beat the Tigers,'' said Lima,
who was groomed in the Detroit organization. ``But I kept the team
in the game, and we won. That's the most important thing.''
</P>
<P>
   Tigers shortstop Devi Cruz singled home a run in the seventh,
and another scored on a groundout by rookie pitcher Dave Borkowski,
who was making his major-league debut.
</P>
<P>
   Borkowski, who was pitching for Class AAA Toledo against
Pawtucket just six days earlier, fared well in his first extensive
exposure to big-league hitters. He held the Astros scoreless until
solo home runs by Biggio and Bagwell tied the game at 2 in the
eighth.
</P>
<P>
   That made it possible for Bell to be a hero two innings later.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been striking out a lot more than what I want,'' said
Bell, who is hitting .245 and has struck out an NL-high 95 times.
``When I pumped my fist in the air, that was for the fans. It was
very satisfying to see the signs and having them cheer for me.
Houston is a great city, and I want to finish my career here, but
that's out of my hands.''
</P>
<P>
   The bat may as well have been out of Bell's hands in the 10th
inning. But as he proved Saturday, sometimes it's not necessary for
a hitter to take his hacks to deliver in the clutch.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
